<HEADER>
A0464 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ETRADE-CEREAL-SFCHRON     07-01 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETRADE-CEREAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-TRADE SERVES NEW AD ON BACK OF BREAKFAST BOX  &HT;     BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
You might call it capital grains.
<P>
   E-Trade Group, a company known for over-the-top advertising
rarely seen in the fusty brokerage business until the Internet came
along, has found an unlikely venue to promote itself _ cereal
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The online broker is teaming up with Kellogg, the venerable
breakfast foodmaker from Battle Creek, Mich. In a campaign now
rolling out, E-Trade is advertising on boxes of Smart Start cereal,
pitching brokerage accounts to the bleary-eyed masses scarfing down
their morning meal.
</P>
<P>
   A promo on Smart Start boxes promises $100 to people who open
accounts through a link on Kellogg's Web site. More than 3 million
packages of cereal with E-Trade ads will be shipped in the
campaign's first round, said Jacqueline Russo, a spokeswoman for
the brokerage. The promotion expires in April.
</P>
<P>
   Menlo Park's E-Trade is a company that feels more kinship with
the Net world than with Wall Street and its tradition of ads filled
with gray-haired men in walnut-paneled rooms. But for Internet
companies, E-Trade's marketing style isn't unique.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ask Jeeves, the Emeryville search engine company,
has plastered stickers with its name, logo and sample search
questions on some 175 million apples, oranges and bananas,
according to spokeswoman Alexa McCann.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade has already set up joint marketing deals with companies
as varied as United Airlines and Blockbuster Video. But cereal
boxes?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the connection between a bowlful of Smart Start and an
E-Trade account isn't as obscure as it might seem.
</P>
<P>
   The low-fat, whole-grain cereal, marketed to health-conscious
25- to 45-year-olds, is good for you, a little like investing money
for the future. But it's also loaded with sugar, a bit sinful, like
the money lust E-Trade promotes in its edgy television and
billboard ads.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, said E-Trade marketing chief Michael Sievert, cereal
boxes are ``one of those kinds of marketing media that people
really read.``
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade, of course, has never walked the straight and narrow in
touting itself. This is the company after all that ran a TV spot
featuring a patient rushed into emergency surgery because he had
money coming ``out the wazoo.``
</P>
<P>
   Ads like that have propelled the company into a solid No. 2 spot
among Internet brokers, gaining on market leader Charles Schwab
Corp., despite a lackluster reputation for customer service.
</P>
<P>
   In the three months ended in March, the company added a
phenomenal 603,000 new accounts, bringing its total to 2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sievert wouldn't discuss financial terms of the Kellogg deal but
stressed the benefits to both companies. Kellogg might sell more
cereal with a $100 bonus offer on the front, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Still, observers presume the broker is paying a tidy sum to get
its pitch on an object that's one of the first things people see
every day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Sam Zuckerman at szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
