<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE METS INSTIGATE THEIR OWN DISTURBANCE
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the end, all the mayhem was in left field, right
about where everyone thought it would be.
</P>
<P>
   But the drama in Friday night's Mets-Braves game had nothing to
do with John Rocker, who was requested three times by the sold-out
crowd of 52,831 at Shea Stadium during the eighth inning but never
dashed from the left field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The game itself was better than an appearance by Rocker, and any
of the jeering and sneering that would accompany one. This was what
the Mets and Braves were talking about when they said they would
play great baseball this weekend. If people focused on one relief
pitcher and his six-month old social commentary, it would be their
loss.
</P>
<P>
   On the first pitch he saw from Terry Mulholland in the eighth
inning, Mike Piazza lined a three-run homer just inside the left
field foul pole to cap an inning that matched the most prolific in
Mets history. It broke a tie, gave the Mets 10 runs in the inning
and lifted them to an 11-8 victory in a game that had been
dominated by the Mets' sloppy play.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are intense games, with all the added issues surround
it,'' said first baseman Todd Zeile. ``You can feel beat up on
after you've made a couple of mistakes, and you can get flat. But
one positive is, we didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets pulled to within two games of first place in the
National League East, and can tie the Braves for first by winning
the final two games of the series, Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was not the kind Piazza usually hits. This was no
scorcher to the opposite field or high-arching parabola into the
left field bleachers. This was the kind of shot that defines the
broadcasters' cry of ``It might be! ... It could be! ... it is!''
</P>
<P>
   When it crashed against the padding a few feet over the fence,
the fans exhaled and screamed and arms shot up all over Shea. The
postgame fireworks seemed redundant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike gets in certain situations where you can feel that the
pitcher is in trouble,'' Zeile said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves starter, Kevin Milwood, never seemed in trouble as
the Braves built an 8-1 lead through seven and a half innings.
Millwood had handcuffed them for seven innings and muted the crowd,
but the presence of journeyman reliever Don Wengert created an
opening for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell opened the inning with a single. Piazza singled with
one out and an error advanced the runner. Robin Ventura's ground
out brought in Bell to make it 8-2.
</P>
<P>
   Then Zeile singled, and Jay Payton did the same. As they had
done when Wengert entered, the fans chanted for Rocker, who had a
callous on his thumb and could not pitch. Bobby Cox called for
Kerry Ligtenberg, and he was a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Benny Agbayani walked to load the bases. A walk to Mark Johnson
walked in a run. A walk to Melvin Mora walked in another.
Mulholland entered _ still no Rocker _ and the control specialist
walked Bell, forcing in another run. Somewhere in Texas, former
Mets pitcher Kenny Rogers, who walked in the run that clinched the
pennant for Atlanta last October, must have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   The score by then was 8-6 Braves, and Edgardo Alfonzo came to
bat. The Mets' second baseman lashed two-run single to left, tying
the game and setting up Piazza's 22nd home run of the season. The
blast also gave Piazza 13 consecutive games with a run batted in,
establishing a new National League record.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Benitez pitched the ninth inning and was credited with a
victory by the official scorer, who ruled that the rookie Eric
Cammack, who had been the last pitcher before the game-turning
outburst but whose outing had been brief and ineffective, did not
deserve the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Until the eighth, the Braves were asserting their dominance over
the team they had beaten in 19 of their last 25 regular-season
meetings, and in the National League Championship Series last
October.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had two singles in the first inning, but a passed
ball, a hit batter and a bases-loaded walk helped them to their
first run. In the third, a bases-loaded single led to three Braves
runs. In the seventh, Melvin Mora threw away an inning-ending
double play ball and the Braves scored again.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton had shut out the Pittsburgh Pirates in his last
start and has been rolling for almost two months. But he allowed
five runs Friday night, the most in any start since his dreadful
month of April, and he walked six (one intentionally) over seven
innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
