<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0469 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-N     07-01 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES, LACKING PEP AND POP, FAIL TO PULL OUT ANOTHER CLOSE ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Maybe the New York Yankees need more than
David Justice, or a couple of pitchers. Maybe what they are missing
is more subtle than that.
</P>
<P>
   There is a dullness to the Yankees these days. They always found
a way to win in 1998 and 1999, and now they are giving away games,
exuding the energy of flagmen on a highway construction site,
hazily guiding opponents to victories.
</P>
<P>
   After Bernie Williams tied Friday night's game against Tampa Bay
with a two-run homer in the top of the eighth, Yankees relievers
walked four batters in the bottom of the eighth, forcing home two
runs in a 6-4 loss to the Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Justice was 0 for 3 in his Yankees debut, reaching base in his
first plate appearance on catcher's interference.
</P>
<P>
   On May 6 the Yankees' record in one-run and two-run decisions
was 13-1. They are 7-19 in one-run and two-run games since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning is contagious, and losing is contagious,'' said Derek
Jeter, the Yankees' shortstop. ``I don't think anyone here lacks
confidence. We're just not getting the breaks we're used to
getting.''
</P>
<P>
   They were in a position to win; they should have won. Jason
Grimsley started in spite of an ear infection, and although he
surrendered nine hits in 2 1/3 innings before he was relieved _
Grimsley was so sick that he had trouble seeing the ball coming off
the bat of hitters _ the Yankees trailed by only 4-2 early. Craig
Dingman, promoted to the majors Thursday, shut out the Devil Rays
for 2 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's Bryan Rekar had a 2-4 record and a 4.80 earned run
average before Friday night's game, but he stifled the Yankees, who
seemed to be overeager against him. Rekar is a sinkerball pitcher
and hitters usually try to drive the ball to the opposite field.
But of the 19 balls the Yankees put in play against Rekar, 14 were
pulled; they kept beating the ball into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to relax and let the game come to us,'' Justice
said later, after pulling three grounders to the right side. ``I
didn't let the game come to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams bailed out the Yankees, however, slamming a two-run
homer off Jim Mecir (6-1) with two out in the Yankees' eighth. The
Yankees have won games like this time and again over the last few
years, coming back in the late innings to tie the game, holding
opponents with their bullpen and then pushing across the winning
run.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelson relieved in the Tampa Bay eighth, retired the first
hitter and got the second hitter, Fred McGriff, to lift a high pop
to the left side. Scott Brosius, the third baseman, backpedaled,
then held his arms out: he couldn't see the ball. Neither could the
shortstop Jeter, and left fielder Shane Spencer could not reach the
pop before it fell to the fake grass at Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I turned my back _ I don't know if it was the backdrop or
the catwalks _ I just couldn't spot it up there,'' Brosius said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson walked the next batter, but struck out Jose Guillen. Two
outs. He had control of the inning. He fell behind in the count to
Mike Difelice, and then disintegrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get down, two balls and no strikes,'' Nelson said,
``you start pressing, and you start aiming the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He walked Difelice, loading the bases. Russ Johnson came to bat.
When the game began, he had drawn a total of two walks for the
season, but he had three in the first seven innings, and Nelson
could not throw strikes. With the fans screaming, Nelson walked
Johnson, as well, forcing home the go-ahead run. Nelson snapped at
the return throw from the catcher Jorge Posada, as teammates looked
on mournfully.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson fell behind the next batter, Felix Martinez, two balls
and no strikes. The Yankees scrambled in their bullpen, rushing to
get Todd Erdos warmed up. Nelson appeared frazzled. Posada went to
the mound to kill time until Erdos was ready.
</P>
<P>
   But after Erdos came on, he completed the walk to Martinez _
another run _ and Erdos slammed a fist into his glove. In all,
Yankees pitchers issued 11 walks and allowed 12 hits. The Devil
Rays stranded 16 runners, a club record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave it away, basically,'' Manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
