<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN AND NORTHWEST CONTINUING MERGER TALKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN REED 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Merger talks between American Airlines and
Northwest Airlines are progressing and could lead to a deal this
month, people close to the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   American ``has a bunch of people working on it, and the goal is
to be ready to do something'' by the middle of July, one source
said.
</P>
<P>
   American officials tacitly acknowledged early last month that
they had met with counterparts from Northwest to discuss a merger.
American also held preliminary talks with Delta Air Lines during
which, sources said, the primary subject was Delta's interest in
acquiring Northwest's 13 percent stake in Continental Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings followed a May 24 announcement by UAL Corp., parent
of United Airlines, that it would buy US Airways, the nation's
sixth-largest carrier, in a deal worth $11.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``American wants to get a deal announced and out on the table by
the time Justice Department gets going on its review of the
United-USAir deal,'' the source said, explaining why the goal is
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing talks were confirmed by several people inside and
outside American who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   American, which is based near Dallas/Fort Worth Airport, and
Northwest, based in Eagan, Minn., declined to comment officially on
the status of any negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chiames, an American spokesman, said airline management
had promised employees and others that it would not initiate a new
round of industry consolidation. Still, American has to consider
the changing dynamics of the industry seriously, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While our employees would prefer internal growth,'' Chiames
said, ``there's probably not one person out of the 100,000 or so
here who would want this company to stand still and put their
futures at risk because of a lack of competitiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior American official was more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, whether we want to buy Northwest or not has nothing to
do with it now,'' the official said. ``Now that United has moved on
USAir, we've got no choice. We're trying to get a deal done.
There's no guarantee that we'll get a deal done, but I think it is
very likely that we will get a deal there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't do a deal at any price,'' the official said. ``But
we'll probably have something soon.''
</P>
<P>
   American employs 27,000 people in North Texas and controls 70
percent of the passenger traffic at D/FW.
</P>
<P>
   Joining American, which is the nation's No. 2 carrier, and
Northwest, the No. 4 carrier, would create an airline about the
size of a combined United and US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest, which has more flights to Asia than any other U.S.
carrier, would also bolster American's domestic system with its
hubs in Minneapolis and Detroit. That would be crucial in competing
with a bigger United, which is based in Chicago and would dominate
the Northeast with US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   But any merger would also present the challenge of meshing
unionized work forces and disparate fleets. It would also be
costly.
</P>
<P>
   American values Northwest at about $56 a share, the sources
said, based on the notion that Northwest shares should fetch what
United is paying for US Airways. But, the sources said, Northwest
Chairman Gary Wilson is seeking at least $65.
</P>
<P>
   Because Northwest has about 100 million shares outstanding, its
price would run from $5.6 billion to $6.5 billion, under the two
scenarios. In addition, American would probably have to assume
Northwest's $3.3 billion in debt, pushing the value of a deal to at
least $8.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Harris, airline analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in New
York, has reached a similar conclusion. In a report issued to
clients three weeks ago, Harris estimated Northwest to be worth $55
a share, or about $5.5 billion. However, Harris said Northwest's
ownership of preferred shares in Continental could inflate the
price.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate that American could recover $2.3 billion to $3
billion of its purchase price for Northwest by selling certain
assets, such as the Continental stock and Northwest's stake in
Worldspan, a computer reservation company.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest's stock closed at $30.44 a share yesterday on the
Nasdaq exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said American does not have an agreement on price with
Wilson and Alfred Checchi, the California financiers who led a $3.6
billion leveraged buyout of Northwest in 1989. Wilson, Checchi and
their associates own a controlling stake in Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``But both sides know what it will take to do a deal, and both
sides really want to do this deal,'' one source said. ``The
negotiations on a final price will be tough, but Gary and Al want a
big payday, and American is the only bidder. I can't imagine that
these two sides wouldn't be able to reach a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   American recently rekindled contract extension talks with its
pilots union in hopes of enlisting its support for a Northwest
deal.
</P>
<P>
   American's desire to announce a deal this month is driven by its
belief that it needs to put a deal before regulators before they
sign off on a United-US Airways combination.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Hopkins, a United spokesman, said his company formally asked
the Justice Department on June 16 to conduct an antitrust review of
its proposed merger under the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act.
</P>
<P>
   That means Justice has until July 16 to decide whether it will
allow the merger, oppose it in court, propose conditions, such as
selling off certain assets, or seek more time for review. Most
observers, including airline executives, expect the Justice
Department to extend the review period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expect the Justice Department to take more time
reviewing the United-US Airways case because it's such a complex
subject and could have such far-reaching implications for
competition in the airline industry and for the consumer,'' said
Julius Maldutis, airline analyst at CIBC Oppenheimer, a New York
investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Although some members of Congress have questioned whether
airline mergers harm consumers, Maldutis said mergers can create
opportunities for new competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my conclusion that mergers are actually beneficial to
new entrants and to consumers,'' Maldutis said. ``They create entry
opportunities for new entrants because the merged entities
consolidate and restructure their operations.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
