<HEADER>
A0474 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-     07-01 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KREUTER TO CONTINUE APPEALS PROCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dodgers catcher Chad Kreuter was prepared to
begin serving his eight-game suspension Friday, but after
consulting with the players association and his agent, Kreuter said
he needed to follow through with the appeal process.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lawyers for the players association continue to
research the viability of appealing the five-game suspensions of
Gary Sheffield, Carlos Perez and F.P. Santangelo. Reliever Mike
Fetters said he is dropping his appeal of a one-game suspension,
only because it's the best thing for the team. Fetters will serve
his suspension July 21.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Courtney, a spokesman for Major League Baseball, said
commissioner Bud Selig would hear this round of appeals. A baseball
official said it was imperative Kreuter gets an opportunity to
speak to Selig during this appeal, and that apparently will happen.
The time being discussed is during the All-Star break in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to follow the appeals process right now,'' Kreuter
said in a rare comment about the suspensions. ``I was ready to bite
the bullet and be a team player and take my suspension, but the
players association and my counsel feel it's in my best interest to
go through the appeals process and take it to a higher jurisdiction
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter said his decision could change, but he's been advised
not to drop the appeal because of the civil lawsuits filed against
him and club, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a big issue and it's still a big issue,'' Kreuter
said. ``For Major League Baseball and fan-relations, there's a lot
of ramifications.''
</P>
<P>
   The players association has seven days to appeal from when Paul
Beeston announced his decision Thursday. Beeston, chief operating
officer for baseball, wiped out the suspensions of 11 players, kept
four players' intact and reduced Fetters' from four games to one.
</P>
<P>
   A baseball official said the players association was looking
primarily at appealing Kreuter's and Sheffield's suspensions. The
players association convinced Fetters to drop his appeal and likely
will talk to Santangelo and Perez about doing the same, an official
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gene Orza, associate general counsel of the players
association, said Kreuter's situation is worth appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this ruling, it still portrays Chad as a monster,'' Orza
said. ``That is the furthest thing from the truth. With the ruling,
it makes it OK for fans to do anything and the player has no
recourse. You couldn't do that to an individual on the street and
get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The suspensions are a result of the May 16 fight at Wrigley
Field in which Kreuter was allegedly struck in the head and had his
cap taken. Kreuter said he only went into the stands to detain the
person when the melee broke out.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers understand litigation must be considered in filing
the appeals, but if the club had their way all but Sheffield would
serve their suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to take it to the highest level and go through the
appeals and exhaust every option,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``The one danger that concerns me is that we're pretty
healthy right now in catching, and in the game of baseball things
can change. There were some other things in there with the way it
was structured where (Kreuter) would miss (catching) Chan Ho (Park)
once, and there's an off-day in there.''
</P>
<P>
   HERSHISER CLEARS WAIVERS: Right-hander Orel Hershiser cleared
waivers Friday, making him a free agent. But the former Cy Young
winner, who can now negotiate with any team, hasn't made a decision
about his future.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hershiser, 41, did release a statement through the
Dodgers about his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``These have certainly been interesting days,'' Hershiser said
in a statement. ``First, my family and I want to thank so many who
have called to wish us well. Your words of encouragement are
sincerely appreciated. As of 11 PDT Friday morning, the waiting
period is over and I have cleared waivers, making me a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Already I have received a number of inquiries, both from
inside and outside of baseball. We're taking the long holiday
weekend to seek the counsel of family and friends, and to pray
about our future.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Dodgers officials believe, given the right opportunity,
Hershiser would continue pitching. He has spoken with several
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   AND FINALLY: Right-hander Gregg Olson faced four batters and
pitched a scoreless inning in a rehab outing with Single-A San
Bernardino against Mudville in the California League. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
