<HEADER>
A0475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     07-01 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: METS COMEBACK IN KNICK OF TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets needed this miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Silly as it may sound on one night of a 162-game season, the
Mets made a major claim on posterity.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were down, 8-1, going into the bottom of the eighth
inning Friday night at Shea Stadium. The Braves were on the verge
of taking the Mets' heart. They had already trounced them on
Thursday, and now they were moving in for the kill. Atlanta
manhandled Mike Hampton, the multimillion-dollar pitcher whose sole
purpose in baseball life was to carry the Mets over the top. Melvin
Mora, the rock-solid everything player, made an error Friday night
and Mike Piazza made his second in three days.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, Atlanta was toying with the Mets. The Atlanta
players were on the bench laughing and guffawing, sitting on the
top step of the dugout, backs turned to the Mets as if the game
were over.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the eighth inning, when the Mets loaded the bases with
two out. In a fitting turnabout for a team that was eliminated from
the National League Championship Series by Atlanta on a
bases-loaded walk, the Mets scored three runs on three consecutive
walks. They tied the game, 8-8, on a two-run single by Edgardo
Alfonzo and then finally won it on a three-run homer by Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's victory did so much to cut through a depressing
funk that was enveloping this franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, a man wearing a jacket and a badge
approached me and asked how he might get the key to Wilpon's suite
and Doubleday's suite. Two other men were holding a pair of dogs by
leashes. The man with the jacket and badge explained that they were
part of the New York City Police Department's bomb detail. ``We
have to sweep Wilpon's suite, but we need the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Why he was asking me how to get the key, I had no idea, but
searching for bombs in the suites of the Mets' co-owners was
unsettling. With walkie-talkies, the police officers left with the
dogs to sweep other parts of Shea Stadium but said they would
return.
</P>
<P>
   Take me out to the ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Shea, waves of New York City police officers lined up
and received instructions for deployment inside the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   All this because a 25-year-old Atlanta Braves relief pitcher
named John Rocker pushed the limits of his constitutional right to
free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs went sniffing and the police officers went to their
posts.
</P>
<P>
   This was Day 2 of a four-game Atlanta-Mets series. But the men
with blue coats and badges and dogs created an atmosphere that
intruded on the hallowed space of a baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day Bobby Valentine, the Mets manager, finished
his pre-game interview with reporters, looked around the stadium
and shook his head. He said the Rocker affair made him feel
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a 17-year-old who just brought three friends up from
Texas,'' he said. ``I gave them free rein, after he spent a month
in the city, battling the subway when he's downtown, taking the No.
7 coming out here, leaving when he wants to leave. Going to Times
Square, going to SoHo on his own, with his buddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now their parents are in Texas going: `What's this idiot doing
with my kids? They took the train home from the game.' And just the
fact that my wife had to say `Are you sure it's OK for them to do
it?' bugs me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freedom is a wonderful thing,'' Valentine added. ``People say
it's not free, but it definitely isn't for anyone to take away from
anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this police state is what we're all about,''
Valentine said. ``I understand protecting the individual, but the
guarded statements, closed clubhouses _ what is all that?''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker made disparaging remarks about Valentine, New York City
and its ethnic groups in a Sports Illustrated article six months
ago. ``I almost think he was saying what he thought was cool,
taking that persona when he runs out of that bullpen, what I think
of as a WWF mentality.`
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has apparently cautioned the Mets and the Braves to
watch what they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're held to a higher standard than everyone else,''
Valentine said. ``Our sport and the rest of society are going in
different directions. We're under more restrictions as the rest of
society becomes more free. What is that? I feel resentment of the
fact that I do feel restrained.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was something unsettling about all the police, the
bomb-sniffing dogs, the layers of cameras. The scene was
depressing. Everyone had been diminished.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night there was some illumination. The Mets needed this
miracle. We all did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
