<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FRUSTRATED' BOTTENFIELD GETS BACK TO WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Pitcher Kent Bottenfield shagged fly balls during
batting practice Friday with the fervor of a wide-eyed rookie.
Bottenfield's motivation, though, wasn't to impress coaches into
giving him playing time.
</P>
<P>
   It was simply part of his between-starts workout regimen, which
is probably the most rigorous of any pitcher on the staff.
Bottenfield can be seen running the stadium steps in the ballpark.
On the road, he can be found running the city streets. When he's
not working out, he's studying videotape.
</P>
<P>
   And that makes it understandable that Bottenfield was so upset
after Thursday's loss to the Mariners. It was probably his biggest
start to date as an Angel, but he was the losing pitcher after
giving up four runs in 5 innings in a 7-2 loss the Mariners. The
normally affable Bottenfield snapped at the Mariners' Mike Cameron
during the game, then waved off reporters after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was frustrated,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``He's put a
lot of weight in the fact he knows he's a big part of the rotation,
a big part of the ballclub. He wants to go out there and lead. And
it's tough to do when you're not throwing the ball as consistently
as you'd like to. But I think Kent's been a little hard on
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield, 4-7 with a 5.60 ERA, and second baseman Adam
Kennedy were acquired from the Cardinals on March 23 in a trade for
Jim Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   MIKE AND OREL: Scioscia said he has tried calling pitcher Orel
Hershiser, who was released this week by the Dodgers. Scioscia, who
was a teammate of Hershiser's with the Dodgers in the 1980s, said
he left a message on Hershiser's answering machine but hasn't heard
back from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a difficult transition,'' Scioscia said. ``You
think you have an ounce of competitiveness left, you want to get it
out of your system.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Angels would consider signing Hershiser, Scioscia
said: ``You'll have to ask (general manager) Bill Stoneman.''
Reminded that he has another former Dodgers pitcher on the staff in
Tim Belcher, Scioscia responded: ``Why don't we get Fernando
(Valenzuela) too?''
</P>
<P>
   NOT READY: Pitcher Scott Schoeneweis is eligible to come off the
disabled list Sunday, but he isn't close to recovering from a
strained muscle in his right side.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis believes he hurt himself initially when batting in a
National League stadium (Bank One Ballpark in Arizona) on June 11,
then aggravated it pitching in Baltimore on June 16, forcing him to
the DL. He has not even begun playing catch and there are no
immediate plans to do so. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
