<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-WHITESOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE SOX BLASTS RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Statistically, this is (thus far) the best Chicago
White Sox team since the 1919 edition that wound up tanking the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, we have a Red Sox ballclub that is doing what
all the others have done since 1918 _ only this time they're free
falling sooner than usual.
</P>
<P>
   The team on the way up met the team on the way down Friday
night, and the result was a predictable 10-4 White Sox victory over
the remnants of a Red Sox team that made New England dare to dream
only a few short weeks ago. 10-4. Over and out?
</P>
<P>
   The erstwhile Princes of Suffolk County surrendered five more
homers (two each for Frank Thomas and Brook Fordyce), lost for the
27th time in their last 40 outings, and Saturday could drop to the
sea level of .500 for the first time since April 14 (5-5). Boston
goes into Saturday's battle with Paxton Crawford, a 22-year-old
righty who'll be making his major league debut. How could it have
come to this so swiftly?
</P>
<P>
   They went 9-18 in June and the clubhouse karma is being tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of looking back,'' catcher Jason Varitek said. ``If
we look back at this damn month, we're never gonna get better.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only riled Boston player. Jeff Frye, who pinch hit
for Mike Stanley in the eighth inning, was furious after striking
out. Frye would not say why he was mad, but he may have been
bothered that manager Jimy Williams was embarrassing Stanley (seven
K's in his last 10 at-bats). Meanwhile, Frye got into an animated
discussion with Carl Everett before the bottom of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't getting into it,'' said Frye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to say,'' said Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad they can't field more than one Nomar Garciaparra. The
incomparable shortstop had three more hits and is at .396 on the
first day of July.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sox' pitching staff is reeling. The immortal Hipolito
Pichardo was followed to the hill by brutal Bryce Florie,
``Virtual'' Rheal Cormier and John ``Way Back'' Wasdin. All four
gave up home runs. Boston pitchers have been taken over the bridge
in a club-record 15 consecutive games, yielding a whopping 36 bombs
in that sorry span.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' answered Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan had an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making really bad pitches,'' said Kerrigan. ``Those
pitches are right down the middle of the plate. You couldn't put it
on a tee any better. We're pitching right into their strength _
right where we tell them not to throw it in our meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   Hipo made his first big league start since he faced the Red Sox
while working for the Kansas City Royals two summers ago. It was
only a matter of time before the ChiSox got to Pichardo. They
scored three in the third with some help from Boston's increasingly
dubious defense.
</P>
<P>
   Fordyce (his sister owns a beauty salon in Newton) led the
three-run third with a bloop to medium right field. Izzy Alcantara
broke in, but stopped and let the easy out fall for a single. After
Jose Valentin hit a one-out double, the Sox intentionally walked
Thomas to load the bases. Magglio Ordonez brought home the first
run with a fielder's choice grounder, then Chris Singleton hit a
first-pitch double to left, scoring two more runs, and it was 3-0.
With two out and nobody aboard in the fourth, Fordyce hit his
second homer of the season, a shot to left off Pichardo.
</P>
<P>
   Facing lefthander Jim Parque (8-2), the Sox had one of their
lineups quilted from Dan Duquette's regular visits to the junkyard.
Morgan Burkhart batted fifth, followed by left fielder Brian
Daubach, Stanley, Alcantara, and Manny Alexander. Stanley, who had
fanned five times in his prior seven at-bats, struck out against
Parque in the second and again in the fourth. He looked like Joe
Hardy in the final scene of ``Damn Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox broke through with three runs in the fifth. Rookie
Alcantara led off the inning and golfed a 414-foot drive over the
fence in center. It was the kid's first big league homer and he
savored the moment, rounding the bases in Jeffrey Leonard fashion.
A member of the Red Sox bullpen crew fetched the souvenir for
Alcantara.
</P>
<P>
   Two outs later, Varitek hit what should have been an
inning-ending grounder to short, but Valentin booted it (error No.
18 this year), and it opened the gates for the Red Sox. Garciaparra
followed with a single to left, Everett got hit by a pitch, then
Burkhart held back on a hanging curve and grounded it into center
for a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Florie came on to start the bottom of the fifth and it was ugly.
Thomas greeted the righthander with a heat-seeking shot into the
left-field seats on a 1-2 pitch. After a double by Ordonez,
Singleton grounded out (he should have been awarded first on
catcher's interference, but Boston caught a break), then Carlos Lee
drove a 1-0 pitch far over the wall in left-center. It was 7-3, and
Cormier got the call. In Florie's last four games, he's given up
eight hits and eight earned runs in 2 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hang one and he hits it 700 feet,'' said Florie. ``There's
nothing tired about that. It's just tired pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Cormier gave up his homer to Thomas in the sixth. Thomas's
second shot of the night gave him 12 for June and brought Wasdin
into the game. The rout was on. Scott Hatteberg hit a pinch homer
for the Sox in the eighth, and Fordyce answered with the obligatory
shot off Wasdin in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   And Saturday Red Sox Nation turns its lonely eyes to Paxton
Crawford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
