<P>
   CHINA-CITRUS (Beijing) _ When China joins the World Trade
Organization, probably later this year, it will be forced to allow
a huge range of foreign goods greater access to its vast markets.
But a few American agricultural items _ including citrus fruit and
pork _ have already gained dramatically improved entry in the last
few months, under of a recent United States-China agricultural
agreement. And, in Beijing, the fate of the invading oranges and
grapefruits is seen as a glimpse of China's future, presaging the
sudden new opportunities and problems that free trade will bring.
By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
