<SLUG> BC-HKN-LINDROS-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS KEEPING EYE ON LINDROS SITUATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dave Taylor had a sense the Philadelphia Flyers would wait until
the last minute to offer a new contract to Eric Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   He also had his cell phone nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, the Kings general manager, is spending the holiday
weekend at his in-laws in upstate New York, where he learned of the
Flyers offer just hours before the deadline for eligible players to
become either restricted or unrestricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have expressed an interest in acquiring Lindros, the
one-time Hart Trophy winner as the league's MVP who is
re-evaluating his hockey future after suffering four concussions in
the last six months and six in his career.
</P>
<P>
   So have the New York Rangers and Toronto Maple Leafs. If the
Flyers hadn't made a qualifying offer to Lindros at $8.5 million,
the list certainly would have grown. Lindros would have become an
unrestricted free agent, with the Flyers receiving no compensation.
Any contract offers were expected to be short on guaranteed money
and filled with incentives based on games played.
</P>
<P>
   For much of Friday it appeared the Flyers, after months of
acrimony over Lindros' medical treatment, might let him leave
without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   When he is playing, Lindros is one of the best. But he also is
suffering from post-concussion symptoms from his last injury, which
occurred in late May during the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Kings, Rangers or Maple Leafs mentioned players in
their talks with the Flyers. All were waiting to see a report on
Lindros' condition from the Chicago-based neurologist James Kelly,
who is treating him. Any team that trades for Lindros would have to
assume the $8.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   There also is a risk the team could not receive insurance on the
contract given Lindros' medical history. The NHL requires that the
top five salaries on each team are covered by insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers were required to tender him a new contract of at
least last year's salary. Lindros has until Aug. 1 to accept or
become a restricted free agent. Teams can still make offers for
Lindros, but if the Flyers do match the offer, it will cost the
offering team five No.1 draft choices.
</P>
<P>
   The list of unrestricted free agents includes:
</P>
<P>
   Forwards Mark Messier, Claude Lemieux, Shayne Corson and Rick
Tocchet.
</P>
<P>
   Defensemen Mathieu Schneider, Paul Coffey and Dave Manson.
</P>
<P>
   Goaltenders Ron Tugnutt, Sean Burke and Tom Barasso.
</P>
<P>
   The only member of the Kings who is an unrestricted free agent
is defenseman Garry Galley, who is not expected back.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Lindros, the list of potential restricted free
agents includes:
</P>
<P>
   Forwards Joe Sakic, Doug Weight, Owen Nolan, Slava Kozlov and
Adam Deadmarsh.
</P>
<P>
   Defensemen Sandis Ozolinsh, Scott Niedermayer and Alexei
Zhitnik.
</P>
<P>
   Goaltenders Felix Potvin, Chris Osgood and Steve Shields.
</P>
<P>
   After teams make a qualifying offer ($8.5 million in Lindros'
case), player have 30 days to accept it or become a restricted free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   NHL general managers will receive a final copy today of the
complete list of restricted and unrestricted free agents. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
