<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT DAY WAS GOOD FOR CLIPPERS' BAYLOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's young-and-the-feckless edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   For a good definition of purgatory, see Elgin Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA Hall of Famer has been the Clippers General Manager for
14 years, meaning he's had maybe a dozen good nights of sleep since
signing on with renown basketball slumlord Donald Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the fact injuries forced Baylor to retire early in
1971, the year the Lakers won their first NBA title, and you have a
man who has without question paid for his sins of this life and
several others.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was a good day for Baylor. He weaved in and out of the
draft and picked up four rookies with promise and two second-year
players who, alongside Lamar Odom, shines a rare ray of hope on the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   But something nags at me nonetheless, and it has to do with
Sterling's attention to his money. Thanks to the NBA's new labor
deal, it now takes five years for a player to become a free agent,
and the draft is subject to salary slotting. Meaning, the best way
for a team to keep a lid on its expenses is to assemble a team of
young players.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor's motive is pure. He aches to build a winning team, and
this may be his best opportunity since Danny Manning was a Clipper.
But let's not lose sight that this works to Sterling's benefit, and
the only losses that bother him are financial. ...
</P>
<P>
   This strategy may also work to Sterling's benefit when he gets
around to hiring a coach. Rather than hiring another NBA coaching
retread with salary history, it may be smarter and cheaper to hire
an ambitious college coach with a reputation for teaching. Because
Odom, Darius Miles and the other members of Boyz II Men will need
instruction. ...
</P>
<P>
   Best one-liner going around about the Clippers: They finally
have a team capable of making it to the Final Four. ...
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's Mark Madsen was ecstatic to be drafted by the Lakers.
But it probably hasn't dawned on him yet that he'll now be dragged,
bludgeoned, minced and squashed on a daily basis in practice by the
NBA's original 800-pound philosopher, Shaquille O'Neal. Madsen may
come to view game days as a day off. ...
</P>
<P>
   Here's one draft development that warmed by heart. With JaRon
Rush not being drafted, his pseudo-agent, sneaker league coach and
all-around misanthrope Myron Piggie, who personally turned Rush's
college career into a nightmare, will receive 10 percent of nothing
for all of his work.
</P>
<P>
   The Rush story should be bound and made mandatory reading for
every high school basketball player with a dream. ...
</P>
<P>
   The people who went to Costa Rica to study the juice factor in
major league baseballs now say there's only a modest difference in
the ball being used in 2000 compared to the ones used in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine, but the ball's liveliness was only part of the
equation. The best hitters say they can pick up the rotation better
because of the blue Major League Baseball logo on each ball. And
the best breaking ball pitchers say the seams are lower and it has
taken some of the bite out of their pitches.
</P>
<P>
   While I don't doubt the tests were thorough, seeing is
believing. Balls are being hit harder and farther by a greater
number of players this year than last. That's all the information I
need to believe the 2K ball is hitter-friendly. ...
</P>
<P>
   All-Star voters in general do a good job selecting the right
starters for the game. But when they miss, they do so like Sammy
Sosa chasing high heat.
</P>
<P>
   The American League scorecard is perfect except for the
predictable sentiment installing Cal Ripken as the starter at
third. It even has Royals outfielder Jermaine Dye atop the outfield
list. With Cal injured, the starting job will likely go to the
Angels' Troy Glaus (23 home runs) or Indians' Travis Fryman.
</P>
<P>
   Picking the reserves won't be easy. Four first baseman deserve
to go -- the A's Jason Giambi (.345, 22 home runs, 75 RBI),
Toronto's Carlos Delgado (.361, 27, 72), Chicago's Frank Thomas (65
RBI) and Kansas City's Mike Sweeney (73 RBI) -- but there may be
room for only three. And Jim Thome, having an off year, is second
in voting behind Giambi and could pass him.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Ramirez currently ranks third in the outfield, but his
lead on Carl Everett (23-68) and Darin Erstad (.373, M.L.-leading
126 hits) is slim and he, too, may skip the game because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there's no logical backup for Roberto Alomar at
second. On the fence: Ex-Dodger catcher Charles Johnson, Yankees
catcher Jose Posada and Orioles shortstop Mike Bordick, stuck
behind The Trilogy (A-Rod, Jeter, Nomar).
</P>
<P>
   The N.L. has two blatant mistakes: Craig Biggio leading at
second base and Ken Griffey Jr. leading all outfielders. Biggio is
having a poor season, and worse, there are six viable alternates
behind him -- the Mets' Edgardo Alfonso (.340), the Braves' Quilvio
Veras, ex-Dodger Eric Young (.321, 54 runs, 23 steals) of the Cubs,
the Marlin's Luis Castillo (.357, 33 steals), Montreal's Jose Vidro
(.370, 50+ runs and RBI), and the Giants' Jeff Kent (.347,
N.L.-leading 75 RBI).
</P>
<P>
   Griffey is hitting just .241 (with 25 HR), the lowest average of
any Reds regular, and both Vladimir Guerrero (.369-22-67) and
ex-Angel Jim Edmonds (72 runs, 22 HR) are more deserving of a
starting spot. Sammy Sosa (.312-20-66) also is a tentative starter.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' Gary Sheffield has the numbers (.350, 25 home runs,
66 RBI), but he's ambivalent about the game and a glut of outfield
candidates -- Brian Giles (67 RBI), Eric Owens, Andrew Jones, Steve
Finley, Geoff Jenkins -- could lead manager Bobby Cox to select
Kevin Brown as the Dodgers' lone representative. ...
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing it took only 30 seconds for ex-Tar Heel Larry Brown
to call his alma mater and inform them he would to take over for
Bill Guthridge. And it took only 35 seconds for Allen Iverson to
call North Carolina with a personal recommendation. ...
</P>
<P>
   A couple more apologies and relief efforts like Thursday and the
New York tabloids will start suggesting the Mets trade for John
Rocker. ...
</P>
<P>
   I know Mike Tyson is hungry for a match against Lennox Lewis,
but he should snack on Evander Holyfield one more time before
moving to the main course, uhh, event. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
