<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ATHLETICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOPER, ANDERSON DO JOB FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Angels pitcher Brian Cooper surely owes center
fielder Garret Anderson a hearty ``Happy Birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Anderson's home run-robbing catch of a deep fly ball by
Oakland's Randy Velarde in the fourth inning that made Cooper's
first major-league shutout possible in the Angels' 7-0 victory in
front of 28,765 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper (3-2) gave up only three hits, walked one and struck out
four while making 124 pitches. Other than Velarde's deep fly,
Cooper was never in danger of giving up a run. No A's baserunner
even reached second base.
</P>
<P>
   With the crowd on its feet, Cooper retired Velarde on a grounder
to third to end the game. Cooper had fallen behind 3-0 in the count
to Velarde and knew if he walked him he would be taken out because
of his high pitch count. But he settled down just enough to finish
it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was jacked up,'' said Cooper, who lowered his ERA to 3.48,
best among the starters on the staff. ``That first pitch (to
Velarde) was as hard as I threw all game. It pumps you up to be out
there like that. I felt tingling down my spine. It was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper went right after the A's hitters. The A's lead the league
in walks, and Cooper didn't want to play their game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the type that strikes people out, I rely on the
defense,'' Cooper said. ``I need them to make plays for me, and
they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly Anderson, who celebrated his 28th birthday with
home run No.22 (a career high). But it was the catch that gave
Cooper an even bigger lift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it would go that far,'' Anderson said. ``But I
knew once I got back to the wall and it was still in the air I had
a shot at it. Those are always hard to judge. You have so much time
and you get back so early, you have to judge it instead of just
react to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's play wasn't the only fine play made by the Angels
defense. In the sixth inning with Terrance Long on first and one
out, A's manager Art Howe called for a hit-and-run with Velarde at
bat. Velarde lined out to Tim Salmon in right center, and Salmon
doubled up Long at first with a one-hop throw. It was Salmon's
seventh outfield assist of the season, second most in the American
League.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was in command throughout the game, his sinker helping
him get 14 outs on ground balls. Between Jason Giambi's two-out
single in the first inning and Matt Stairs' one-out single in the
fifth, Cooper retired 11 consecutive batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in games he's struggled early, he's managed to pitch deep
into ballgames, and that's about as deep as you can pitch into a
ballgame,'' said Angels manager Mike Scioscia. ``You look at his
stuff, a sinker and a slider, and he's not intimidating. But he
executes his pitches in jams. He doesn't scare off and he pitches
inside well. He knows what he has to do and he does it. He's a real
clear thinker out there and that's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels first baseman Mo Vaughn caught third baseman Troy Glaus'
throw for the final out, handed the ball to Cooper and giving him a
hug. Cooper then got hugs from catcher Bengie Molina and Glaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coop, he's a cool cat,'' Vaughn said. ``He doesn't get too
excited about himself. He's always relaxed, always cool.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second complete-game shutout by the Angels this
season. Scott Schoeneweis did it on April 10 vs. Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper nearly threw a shutout earlier this season. On June 14,
Cooper and the Angels held a 2-0 lead after eight innings against
Tampa Bay, but Scioscia went to closer Troy Percival in the ninth,
and Percival gave up three runs in a 3-2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper admitted he was looking over his shoulder after the
eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little worried (about coming out),'' he said.
``Especially when Buddy (Black, pitching coach) came up to me. But
Buddy and Scioscia said `How you doing?' I said fine, then Scioscia
said, 'You've got seven pitches (to finish the ninth).'''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper needed 11 but still got the job done.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had 12 hits, including Anderson's homer and homers by
Molina and Benji Gil.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved the Angels to within five games of first-place
Seattle and 4 of second-place Oakland in the AL West. It was the
first game in a 10-game homestand, which includes seven games
against the A's and Mariners. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
