<HEADLINE>
U.S. FALLS SHORT AGAINST YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMITOS, Calif. _ On Wednesday in the UPS International
Tournament in Los Alamitos, the U.S. National water polo team won a
close game against Croatia thanks in part to several shots bouncing
off the bar and into the goal.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Chris Humbert of the U.S. said those shots, which
are called bar-in when the ball goals in and bar-out when it
doesn't, can be the difference in a close game.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night against powerful Yugoslavia it was a bar-out on a
shot by Tony Azevedo with one second remaining that kept the U.S.
from salvaging a tie, and the Yugoslavians swam away with a 9-8
victory in front of 1,500 at the U.S. National Aquatic Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're showing signs of some good things,'' U.S. coach John
Vargas said after his team played one of the world's best teams to
a near-standstill.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. may get another chance against Yugoslavia, which
improved to 4-0-0 in the tournament and clinched a spot in Sunday's
3 p.m. final. The U.S. (2-1-1) can clinch their spot in the
championship game with a win or tie against Italy in today's 1:30
p.m. game.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. may have already clinched a berth in the final if it
would have done better on man-advantage situations against the
Yugoslavians. They managed to convert only 2 of 10 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia, which converted 15 of 21 man-advantage opportunities
in the first three games of the tournament, remained hot on 6-on-5s
by making 5 of 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the 6-on-5, there are so many subtleties'' said Vargas,
whose team only recently returned to full strength. ``The key is
playing together. The success on the 6-on-5 will come with time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia opened up a 6-3 lead at halftime and scored the first
goal of the second half. But the U.S. stormed back with five
unanswered goals. Humbert began the streak with scores on a
man-advantage and a counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. got to within 7-6 when Gavin Arroyo tipped in a goal
after a nice lob pass by Azevedo with 3:20 left in the third
quarter. They then evened the score at 7-7 with 5:32 left when Sean
Kern fired a goal into the upper-right corner on another
counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two minutes later, the U.S. took the lead when Humbert
drew a four-meter foul and Azevedo converted the penalty shot.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia, which went 11:22 without a goal, tied the score on a
twisting shot by leading scorer Aleksandar Sapic with 3:15 left and
notched the game-winner with 1:46 remaining on a pretty backhand
from the hole by Viktor Jelenic.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavian goalkeeper Aleksandar Sostar smothered Arroyo's
point-blank shot on a 6-on-5 with 1:03 and Azevedo just missed on
the team's other prime late-game opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. goalkeeper Dan Hackett kept his team in the game by making
eight saves, many coming on point-blank opportunities. Humbert,
Kern and Azevedo each had two goals for the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   In other games:
</P>
<P>
   ITALY 10, TEAM UPS 6: Merrill Moses had 15 saves for Team UPS
(0-4-0), but it wasn't good enough to hold off Italy (2-2-0). Layne
Beaubien and Omar Amr had two goals each for Team UPS and Italy was
led by Roberto Calcaterra. Team UPS never led in the game but they
did close within 7-5 with 4:33 left on a goal by Amr.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA 8, CROATIA 7: Australia (1-2-1) won for the first time
in the tournament as they jumped to a 5-2 lead and held on for the
win over Croatia (2-2-0). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
