<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-GIANTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD CAPS BIG MONTH WITH BIG NIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Emotion often got the better of Gary Sheffield
earlier in his career. He admitted that when his five-game
suspension was upheld two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   However, what separates Sheffield's past from his present is how
he channels his emotions, and that can't be illustrated any better
than by what he accomplished Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield capped one of the most explosive months in his career
with a pair of homers and four RBI as the Dodgers pummeled the San
Francisco Giants 9-2 at Pac Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth time this season Sheffield hit two homers in a
game and the third time he did it in June. In batting .383 (38 for
99), Sheffield homered 12 times and drove in 30 runs in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Thursday) was a tough day for me and I tried to suck up
everything and go out there and help my team,'' Sheffield said.
``For me to break down like I did (Thursday), I needed to get that
out of my system. Like it says in the Bible, it's healthy. When you
do that, you can get it behind you and move on, and that's what I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield leads the Dodgers with 27 homers and 70 RBI. He's
seven short of his home run total of last season and has
established a Los Angeles Dodgers record for homers before the
All-Star break. Mike Piazza had 24 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield trails Mark McGwire (29 homers) and Barry Bonds (28)
in the home run race and Todd Helton in RBI (76). The production,
not to mention Sheffield's leadership role, is why the Dodgers are
strongly in favor of him appealing the five-game suspension that
was upheld by Paul Beeston, chief operating officer of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very concerned about the suspension thing and he's
still very concerned about it,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``He's an emotional player. He plays with a lot of emotion.
You may not see it, but it's there. ... ``That (second homer)
against the wind, that might have been the hardest hit ball I've
seen hit this year. That was a bone-crusher.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield's offense gave Dodgers right-hander Kevin Brown some
much-appreciated but rarely seen run support.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (7-2) allowed two runs in seven innings as his mastery
over the Giants continued.
</P>
<P>
   Brown entered the night 7-1 with a 1.20 ERA in nine games
against the Giants, including a no-hitter when he was pitching for
the Florida Marlins. He was even better by the bay. Brown didn't
pitch at Pac Bell Park when the Dodgers played three games here in
April. But at Candlestick, Brown was 5-1 with a 1.29 ERA in six
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brownie was nasty, as usual, but a little wild,'' Johnson
said. ``He threw a few more pitches than you'd like to see, 122 in
seven innings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers gave Brown a 2-0 lead in the first as Eric Karros'
sacrifice fly and Todd Hundley's double qualified as a windfall for
Brown. Or at least it was a premonition of how the evening would
turn out.
</P>
<P>
   In Brown's two losses, the Dodgers failed to score a run. In the
seven no-decisions Brown has had, the Dodgers scored three runs or
less three times.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who walked in the first inning, hit his first homer
when he pulled Russ Ortiz's 2-2 pitch down the left-field line for
a solo homer. It put the Dodgers ahead 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later, Sheffield delivered again, and in a much bigger
way, with a three-run homer into the teeth of a strong wind to give
the Dodgers a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obviously a tough day for (Sheffield) with the
decision, but he uses things like that to motivate him,'' said
Dodgers right fielder Shawn Green, who walked a career-high four
times. ``He's even more intense than he usually is right now. He's
not the type to mope or let things get him down. He uses adversity
to his benefit.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
