<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0561 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-KRUGMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-01 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KRUGMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GOING FOR BROKE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL KRUGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever I start to get blase about today's amazing business
world, I pull out my copy of John Kenneth Galbraith's ``New
Industrial State,'' published in 1967. It's a reminder of how
thoroughly the economy has defied the old conventional wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Galbraith was expressing the consensus of the economics
profession. On the contrary, throughout the book he expressed
contempt for his colleagues, with their naive belief that market
forces still mattered. But his message _ that planning by huge
corporations was increasingly supplanting the chaos of the market
system, that capitalism was becoming indistinguishable from
socialism _ found wide favor. When Galbraith wrote that ``the
entrepreneur no longer exists as an individual in the mature
industrial enterprise,'' when he spoke of the ``euthanasia of
stockholder power,'' many people _ living, let us remember in
Galbraith's defense, in an era when General Motors was the very
model of a major modern manufacturer _ nodded their heads in
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last couple of weeks questions about the prospects for
the world's most visible e-tailer have once again roiled the
markets. An analyst at Lehman Brothers has warned that Amazon may
run out of cash early next year; other analysts have leapt to the
firm's defense. I'm not going to get into the middle of this fight.
Isn't it amazing, though, that Amazon has become a household name,
that last year Time named founder Jeff Bezos Person of the Year _
and that we still don't know whether Amazon, or for that matter any
dot-com, has a viable business model?
</P>
<P>
   But that is actually the point. Amazon's business strategy _ to
lose money for an extended period while building a market position
_ is not all that unusual. In fact, it's exactly what Japanese
companies did in their export markets during the '70s and '80s,
when Japan's economy seemed an unstoppable juggernaut. Information
technology, with its powerful increasing returns _ the more people
who use a product, the more useful it becomes _ may have made it
even more necessary than it used to be to lose money now in order
to make it later. But the strategy per se isn't new.
</P>
<P>
   What is new is the sight of Amazon and other companies pursuing
a full-scale go-for-broke strategy right from the start, losing
hundreds of millions before anyone is even sure that there is money
to be made in their businesses. When Galbraith was writing, it
seemed obvious that only large, well-established companies with
plenty of profits from their existing businesses could afford to
make big bets on the future. When people thought about
private-sector innovation, they had in mind IBM's development of
the 360 series of computers, or Boeing's development of the 747. In
fact, as little as six or seven years ago the common view was that
Japanese companies would steadily gain the technological upper hand
over their American rivals because only the Japanese _ not faced
with annoying pressure to satisfy the financial markets _ could
afford to take the long view, and ignore short-term losses.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few years our stock market has proved willing
and eager to finance brand-new companies with highly speculative
business plans that require years of losses before anyone will know
whether they make sense. In fact, even companies that could afford
to finance their innovations out of profits on older businesses
prefer to spin off the sexiest projects as semi-independent
companies, in order to benefit from that enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   How did this happen? I suspect that the emergence of our
innovation-friendly finance markets was less inevitable than many
people imagine. And it is by no means certain that the new era will
last. For a while almost every IPO was enthusiastically welcomed by
markets willing to imagine that every new company might be the next
Microsoft. That euphoria has faded; but will it eventually be
replaced by cynicism, by the demand that new businesses show an
actual profit before they can raise large sums of money?
</P>
<P>
   Amazon may be the test case. If the company proves the
pessimists wrong, the golden age of the individual entrepreneur
will certainly go on for a while longer. If Amazon really does go
under, we may be headed back to the era when only big companies
could afford to make big innovations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 1053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000701.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-2TAKES     07-01 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO OARS BY SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the start, 66-year-old Bill Lenderking said he wondered
if he had ``the right stuff'' to keep up with the four younger and
more experienced rowers. He felt the old-school dread of letting
the side down and a more recent fear of discovering he really was
as old as his reflection in other people's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Would he shame himself and slump over his oars, unable to
continue, or, even worse, be humiliated by his companions'
indulgence? Of course, they would wait for him to catch up; the
four-day, 100-mile trip from South Street Seaport Museum to Shelter
Island had been his idea.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest and most experienced of the five, the wiry, cool
David Stookey, 57, doubted at the start that Lenderking would make
it. He did not appear especially fit or muscular, and he had not
rowed since childhood. His greatest strength, an almost childlike
enthusiasm, seemed to desert him as the four boats pulled out of
the slip at the foot of John Street into the East River. Lenderking
was already falling behind, jerking his oars in a ragged rhythm.
God help him at Hell Gate.
</P>
<P>
   Three people came to see them off at 10:30 a.m. last Monday.
Chelsea Danburg, 26, one of Louis Mackall's four daughters, brought
her husband, Asher, to support her dad's sustaining passion. For
the past 12 years, Mackall, a 59-year-old architect from Branford,
Conn., has rowed nearly every day, summer and winter, before work.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory is that the body is happy only when it gets a lot of
exercise,'' said Mackall. ``We need much more exercise than we get.
If I was a therapist, I'd tell my patients, `Go run 20 miles, then
come back and we'll talk.'''
</P>
<P>
   The third waver from the shore was Robert Ruenitz, a former
Foreign Service colleague of Lenderking's who had been surprised
when he read about the proposed trip; he knew Lenderking had
trekked and scuba-dived during overseas assignments, but he had
never heard about rowing. No wonder, he agreed, watching him
awkwardly yanking under a boiling sun, trying to get out before The
Beast, a huge tourist boat with a wake as terrifying as a perfect
storm, came churning in. As the four boats turned left and headed
north, Mackall yodeling in the lead, Lenderking already trailing by
several lengths, Ruenitz sighed and said, ``A gallant band.''
</P>
<P>
   They were not a band yet. They barely knew each other.
</P>
<P>
   Lenderking, who had sentimental memories of boyhood rows off
Shelter Island, where he recently bought a house, conceived the
trip as a test. For all his endearing, lanky gawkiness, there is
something steely and calculating about Lenderking. It is not hard
to envision him as a propagandist for the government's Vietnam
pacification program. But ever since he was pensioned off five
years ago at 61, Lenderking has struggled to chart a new course in
a world skewed to the young. He sensed a metaphor in rowing out of
the discard pool.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, he called a longtime friend, Stookey, a
management consultant who also publishes a newsletter, ``Open-Water
Rowing.'' Stookey thought the cruise, as he called it, was
``do-able.'' He called one of his 800 readers, 58-year-old John
Mullen, a Dallas architect and businessman whom he had once met
briefly at a race. Mullen has won a number of masters sculling
championships, but, like the others, had never rowed more than 20
miles in a day, and then for only one day at a time.
</P>
<P>
   But Mullen called his summer rowing partner, Mackall, who
recruited his neighbor, 60-year-old Tom Luckey, an architect who
designs children's playground climbing structures. Luckey had never
rowed before but was in good shape and willing to train for rowing
a two-man boat. The men began an e-mail circle of questions,
training tips and bios. None of the men considered themselves
jocks, although Lenderking ran track at Dartmouth, Mackall played
ice hockey at Yale, Luckey is a swimmer, Mullen, who is 6 feet 7
inches, played freshman basketball at Rice, and Stookey once sailed
solo across the Atlantic in a race. They became cyberbuds.
</P>
<P>
   As the notion became a high concept, Lenderking drove from his
home in Washington to Ontario to buy a 17-foot Loudon fiberglass
boat for $2,200. He named it Up the Creek. And then, in an act that
they all admit raised the ante, Lenderking, without consulting the
others, called to see if I was interested. We had never met. I was
mildly interested, I said, being in their age group.
</P>
<P>
   But after I wrote about the plan-in-progress (``It gives new
meaning to the word `cockamamie,''' Mackall would say later),
thelipsite(at)aol.com received more than 100 e-mails requesting the
trip be covered. The e-mailers tended to be upper-middle class,
middle-aged men engaged by Mullen's reason for rowing _ ``I'm at an
age when I'm looking for stretches.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first two hours, despite unexpectedly smooth conditions
(the East River turned out to be cleaner than much of Long Island
Sound, which was a millpond), it seemed far more than a stretch for
Lenderking. He would say later that he never for a moment doubted
he would finish, but as he frequently rested from his flailing
strokes, the others' concern mounted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' said Luckey, a whimsical man with a spacey
delivery, ``I was hoping Bill would give me an excuse. Mackall has
these annoying bursts of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   But sometime after the surprisingly pacific Hell Gate,
Lenderking found his rhythm. The long, ropy arms on his 6-4 body
became an extension of the oars. Up the Creek began to move
smoothly into the brown waters of the Sound. Stookey stayed with
Lenderking and they pulled into Bayville a half-hour behind the
other two boats. Exhausted, the five men lugged the four boats
across a highway to a motel, ate and fell asleep.
</P>
<P>
   They all felt better in the morning, astonished at their lack of
stiffness. Mullen said his back had ached more in training. On the
second day, they pulled with a favorable tide, screamed and laughed
through a brief thunderstorm that, according to Mackall, turned the
surface of the water into ``vibrating marbles.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackall (``He is a bull,'' said Luckey) was pulling more than
his weight in a 17-foot Monument River wherry he had bought used
for $1,500 last winter. The boat had won a number of races, but
with the two men's gear and food it looked like a floating slum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so exciting,'' Mackall said. ``I feel like a kid again
on an adventure with the guys. I brought Luckey along because he
talks endlessly, but we have run out of interesting things to say.
We are into fantasies now.''
</P>
<P>
   The most do-able and durable of their fantasies revolved around
their designing The Dinner Boat, in which people would work up an
appetite by rowing out while one of them cooked in the stern. Once
in open water, a dining table would slide out for the feast they
deserved.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The fantasists stopped once at a private beach in Sands Point
for a quick swim; the owners of the mansion were not at home and
the workmen didn't care. Mullen did not swim; raised water-skiing
on Texas lakes, he says he is still not used to salt water drying
on his body. With Mullen, they pulled into Mount Sinai Yacht Club
near Port Jefferson at about 4:30 p.m., after seven hours of
rowing. Lenderking and Stookey, caught in a tide shift, arrived
three hours later. They ate pizza and drank beer on the yacht club
deck, then all slept on a sailboat, Daydreamer, courtesy of a
yachtsman they knew only as Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   On the phone that night, Mackall said he was amazed by
Lenderking. He added: ``The guy is smiling. He's getting
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   On the third morning, Stookey took off a half hour ahead of the
others. Because his boat was the slowest, he said. He dismissed
Lenderking's suspicion that he was really trying to avoid another
long day of baby-sitting Up the Creek.
</P>
<P>
   A trim, tightly knit man with curly dark-blond hair, blue eyes
and a sharp, sun-weathered face, Stookey is self-contained, almost
mysterious, genial yet watchful. He has done most of his rowing
alone, often testing boats for his newsletter and Web site
(www.openwater.com). Manufactured by a French firm, Birus, his boat
was a self-bailing, white 14-foot fiberglass yole with a sliding
seat.
</P>
<P>
   Stookey hugged the shore on the third day, stopping several
times to examine geological formations and to bird-watch. Maybe
that's why the others never noticed that they were passing him.
Mullen was Lenderking's ``escort'' that day, and Mullen likes to
row a mile out to sea. The Mackall/Luckey fantasies were
particularly absorbing (``Babes on the beach'' was all they would
reveal later.) At 4:30, when they pulled into the Matt-A-Mar Marina
in Mattituck, which charged them $20 each a night to tie up,
Stookey was nowhere to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he just found people he likes better than us,'' Mackall
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whacked-out side to him,'' Luckey said. ``He's up to
something. We'll see him tomorrow. He'll just row out to meet us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mullen, the tall straight-arrow from Texas, fretted all the
way back to the motel and while the others showered, he called
other marinas on his cell phone. He was faintly annoyed that
Stookey was not carrying a cell phone or a VHF radio or a global
positioning system, as he was.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:45, about to go for dinner, Mullen insisted they all go
down to the dock for one more look. It was Lenderking who shouted,
``The drama is over.''
</P>
<P>
   There was Stookey, cool and smiling, changing his shirt. He had
reached the inlet hours ago, assumed he was still in the lead,
parked the boat and fallen asleep on the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   He was only one who did not drink at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, they hitched a ride on a garbage truck back to
the marina. Mullen had wanted to row around Orient Point as part of
his grand scheme of circling Long Island in stages. But the others
were ``smelling the barn,'' as Mullen put it, and so they
compromised on a portage through Truman Beach near East Marion.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen was amazed at how jaunty everyone was, how much lighter
the boats seemed on the fourth day than the first. They were all so
much stronger, surer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole trip was much easier than I thought it would be,''
he said. ``You wonder how many things in life you don't try because
the idea seems too big, too intimidating. I stayed up nights
worrying about Hell Gate, and it was nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never have tried this without Bill, and I've rowed for
years and he never rowed before. I'm grateful to him and I'm amazed
by his indomitability.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullen seemed to get the most pleasure from his boat, the
fastest of the four, a beautiful, wooden, 18-foot St. Lawrence
River skiff, a copy of a 19th-century boat in Mystic Seaport called
Annie.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you row you blow out your pipes,'' he said. ``There's a
freshness, a different set of ideas out there. Clouds, water, your
body, it's not a place to ponder changes in your life. It's a place
to just plug into the environment we are usually isolated from.''
</P>
<P>
   The last day for the gallant band was the mellowest. They rowed
at their usual 4 knots, but they arrived unusually close together,
atypically on schedule, at about 4:30 p.m. They pulled up onto a
private lawn on Gardiner's Creek in Shelter Island. It was
suspicious that Lenderking was in the lead, but he seemed as fresh
as the rest of them. His grin was certainly the widest. He echoed
the consensus: The trip had been hard and senseless, and more fun
than any of them had had since boyhood.
</P>
<P>
   The welcoming committee was smaller than the bon voyage
entourage. Mullen's wife of 35 years, Anne, and their dog, Lover,
were waiting on the lawn. Plans were made for a victory feast the
next night at Mullen's house in Springs, Easthampton. Stookey was
returning to Manhattan to pick up his car, then drive back to pick
up his boat for the trip home to Rhode Island. It sounded harder
than the row. Mullen, Mackall and Luckey would return in the
morning to row to Springs and Amagansett.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now,'' said Luckey, ``my wife, Ettie, will ask me again to
explain why I am doing this, and I will tell her again I still hope
to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So this is an existential search,'' said Lenderking, as if he
was considering the trip for the very first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about life,'' said Luckey, striking a pose on the
lawn. ``People die because they get out of the stream. The body
senses you are not having a good time and says, `That's it, buddy,
we're out of here.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``And what we just did,'' asked Mullen, ``was in the stream?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' said Luckey, ``this was the stream.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 1100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
