<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      07-01 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, July 2:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION (Mexico City) _ The past hangs heavy over
Mexico's people and politics, but rarely has a moment seemed so
pregnant with history as the presidential balloting scheduled for
Sunday. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-BORDER (Border Post 34, Lebanon) _ The quick deployment
of U. N. peacekeepers and Lebanese forces into the stretch of
southern Lebanon that Israel abandoned in May after 22 years of
occupation has been thrown into doubt with the controversy over a
series of apparent Israeli incursions across a borderline drawn in
1923. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-PASTRANA (Bogota, Colombia) _ He has just received a
vote of confidence from the United States in the form of $1.3
billion in emergency military aid. But as President Andres Pastrana
nears the midpoint of his term, his standing is sinking. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-PEOPLE-TRAFFIC (Dover, England) _ This was once a quiet
port town famous above all for its white cliffs. It is now
notorious for the corpses of 58 Chinese immigrants that lie,
unclaimed and unnamed, in refrigerators normally used for meat
shipments _ and for the likes of Tara Muhammad roaming its streets.
By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PARTY-STRUGGLE (Shenyang, China) _ For more than 40 years,
Zhou Wei found success as a Communist Party cadre. Colleagues and
family say he was a brilliant, if prickly, man who still loves the
party. But today he is in a labor camp, accused of organizing
illegal assemblies and inciting unrest in this depressed industrial
city. Now, a campaign to gain Zhou's release has brought into
public view an extraordinary five-year struggle between the local
party and some of its most senior retired officials _ a bizarre
conflict in which the police tail old men who are heros of the 1949
revolution that brought the party to power. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-FUTURE (Seoul, South Korea) _ While the friendship and
reconciliation that emerged from the Korean summit meeting two
weeks ago was surprising, and sudden, officials in South Korea
insist that actual unification is years, if not decades, away and
can be achieved only gradually. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-JEWS (Shiraz, Iran) _ A judge convicted 10 of 13 Jewish men
accused by the Revolutionary Court of being spies, asserting that
their years of religious piety were a cover for espionage and
illegal aid to Iran's enemy, Israel. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RACE-SPORTS (Baton Rouge, La.) _ In July 1996, Southern
University, a powerhouse among black colleges, desperately needed a
quarterback, and a white player, Marcus Jacoby, badly needed a
place to play quarterback. Southern's head coach, Pete Richardson,
recruited Jacoby. The decision made headlines. So began an odyssey
of triumph and defeat on and off the football field. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   DYING-TOWNS (Mountain, N.D.) _ Like towns of the West that
turned to shells once they were stripped of their gold, new ghost
towns are sprouting over much of the Great Plains. By Peter T.
Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   SC-FLAG (Columbia, S.C.) _ As its reign atop the South Carolina
statehouse finally drew to an end, the Confederate battle flag had
become almost as much a curiosity as an object of division, a
symbol of the state's exhausted recent history even more than of
its distant past. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   VERMONT-GAYS (South Burlington, Vt.) _ From Burlington to
Brattleboro, with hoopla or careful privacy, a scattering of gay
couples across Vermont became the first in the country Saturday to
legally take on all the rights and responsibilities of marriage, in
the first state to let them. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-EXPERIMENT (Youngstown, Ohio) _ Nine convicts were free
to exchange hugs with their children, some of them hesitantly at
first, and to play and advise and gaze upon them for four hours
each morning last week. Sharing thoughts and meals, they tested a
program, as merciful as it is experimental, to let 11 children and
their imprisoned fathers directly repair family ties. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   PRESBYTERIANS-GAY-UNIONS (Long Beach, Calif.) _ After an
emotional debate over one of the most contentious issues embroiling
some Protestant denominations, the top policy-making body of the
Presbyterian Church (USA) has approved an amendment to the church's
constitution forbidding ministers from conducting same-sex unions.
By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BUSH-ASSESS (Washington) _ One breezes past the tough stuff
in an effort to remain forever buoyant, and can come across as
lighter than air. The other fairly bludgeons listeners with all
that he knows, and can come across as aloof. Their campaign
schedules and appearances last week perfectly captured these
contrasting styles, which also happen to tap into their strengths
and especially their weaknesses as candidates, what they must take
advantage of and what they must overcome. By Frank Bruni and
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   TELECOMMUNICATIONS-POLITICS (Philadelphia) _ When the
Republicans gather here this month for their national convention,
to some it might be hard to tell the difference: Is this a
political convention or a telecommunications trade show? While the
main event at the convention here _ and the Democratic convention
to be held in August in Los Angeles _ is, of course, nominating a
presidential candidate, a big corporate sideshow is being planned
as well. And in that effort, no single industry is better
represented than telecommunications companies. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ For some, coattails are less
helpful; A losing candidate helps the other side; Making a point in
cold cash; Bush still ahead, new polls show. By B. Drummond Ayres
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ The significance of Amazon.com. By
Paul Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-BUDGET _ A rundown of sports stories will move by 1 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12 noon.
</P>
