<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5131 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-BLUES-REVIEW-     07-01 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BLUES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOFFS AND MACHIAVELS: THE BRITISH AREN'T GETTING ANY RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In its understated way, Britain is the Ed Koch of
nations, endlessly wondering ``How'm I doing?'' But unlike the
self-congratulating former mayor of New York, Britain rarely
expects a positive answer. And lately, a nation that is always
sensitive about perceived slights to its international status has
found more than usual to be upset about.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did CBS News recently report that some crime in England
is far worse than in the United States, but England's soccer team
ignominiously lost to Romania (Romania!) in the Euro 2000
tournament. Then, the country's No. 2 tennis player, Greg Rusedski,
was blown out of Wimbledon on opening day by Vincent Spadea, an
American known to British newspapers as ``the world's biggest
loser'' because he had lost 22 of his last 22 matches.
</P>
<P>
   And now along comes ``The Patriot,'' a film about the American
Revolution that presents the English as effete war criminals with
snobby accents who herd families of fledgling Americans into barns
and set them on fire, just for fun. To Britons sick of being pushed
around, this obnoxious affront to retrospective pride may be the
last straw.
</P>
<P>
   The film hasn't even opened in Britain yet, but the newspapers
have been full of outrage at what they see as wanton disregard for
the historical record. Maybe the war was dirty and violent at
times, they say, but their soldiers certainly never shot children
or minced around in the creepy manner of Nazi generals. And it's no
accident that Mel Gibson stars in the film, they say _ he's
Australian.
</P>
<P>
   ``As every Hollywood casting agent knows, the devil speaks with
an English accent,'' Neil Norman wrote in The Evening Standard,
deploring how ``to a man, the dastardly English are presented as
heartless toffs and Machiavels, war criminals and child-killers.''
</P>
<P>
   Why do the British persist in casting everything in terms of
national pride? Shouldn't they just lighten up?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a significant pride in what we achieved in the past
with regard to the British empire, and we don't like to see it
unfairly traduced,'' explained the British historian Andrew
Roberts. This puffed-up feeling about the past, he said, is
inextricably linked to a sadly deflated view of the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is there to be proud of?'' he asked, musing crossly about
the European Union. ``What are we doing now? We're getting sucked
into some amorphous European superstate, largely against our will.
As a nation we haven't achieved much since 1945, and the things
that we are rightly proud of are being taken away from us by the
distortions of a foreign entertainment industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriot,'' of course, is just one in a recent series of
Hollywood slights perpetrated on the British _ and more
specifically, the English. There were the Englishmen in
``Titanic,'' who battened down the hatches to prevent the declasse,
mostly Irish, lower-deck passengers from escaping. Then there was
Anthony Hopkins, the repellant hissing villain in ``The Silence of
the Lambs.'' And don't forget Gibson's ``Braveheart,'' in which the
English are shown raping, slaughtering and pillaging their way
through 13th-century Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   More worryingly, Britons don't figure in ``U-571,'' a recent
film starring Matthew McConaughey as the leader of a band of
Americans on a submarine who capture the German Enigma code-making
machine in World War II. In real life, the Americans didn't capture
the code _ the British did.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always this way. Before the communists, when the Nazis
were still the worst villains, World War II movies regularly showed
the British and Americans working together to repel the heinous
Germans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until quite recently, films made in America were on the
whole quite admiring of the British and British history,'' said
Jeffrey Richards, a professor of cultural history at the University
of Lancaster. Since then, he said, the British film market has
virtually disappeared, and Hollywood no longer cares whether it
alienates British viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The British are feeling alienated a lot these days. But no
matter what other people say about them, it's not as bad as what
they say about themselves _ particularly when they lose at sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this absurd obsession with sport,'' Roberts said.
``Even though, since 1967, we've been beaten at all the sports we
invented, after 30 years we still get into great emotional upsets.
The things we should be looking at seriously are things like
Britain's great economy, but instead we get into a huge tussle
about whether Greg Rusedski has a good day at Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   When the unfortunate Rusedski lost to Spadea, the hapless
American who had been touring the world losing one match after
another for eight months, The Times of London just couldn't control
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are on a 22 match, world-record losing streak,'' it
wrote, ``there is only one person capable of ending your misery: a
British sports star.''
</P>
</TEXT>
