<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0597 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-WALTER-MATTHAU-OBITUA     07-01 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALTER-MATTHAU-OBITUARY-900&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALTER MATTHAU: AMERICAN CURMUDGEON 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a 500-word sidebar 
 By GAYDEN WREN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walter Matthau was so unlovable he was irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   The more crotchety and curmudgeonly the characters he played,
the more charming audiences found him. Not since W.C. Fields has
anyone captured the spirit of the aging misanthrope with such comic
glee.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, of course, Matthau managed to conceal his
deepest secret _ that behind the cartoonish glare, perfectly
pitched grumble and impeccably timed shtick lurked one of
Hollywood's best actors.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Oscar-winning actor died on Saturday, July 1, of a
heart attack at 79, he left behind four decades of films to testify
that he was a lot more than a grumpy old man.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York on Oct. 1, 1920, as Walter Matuschanskavasky,
Matthau got his start as a child actor in Manhattan's flourishing
Yiddish theater. After spending three-plus years in Europe with the
Army Air Force, he returned to New York and began to seriously
pursue an acting career.
</P>
<P>
   His Broadway debut came in ``Anne of a Thousand Days'' (1948),
and for the next 15 years he would be a favorite of theater-goers,
earning Tony Awards as Best Actor for ``A Shot in the Dark'' (1961)
and ``The Odd Couple'' (1964).
</P>
<P>
   With his world-weary look even as a young man, Matthau was
rarely called on to play leading roles. However, he created a wide
range of supporting parts, from corrupt officials to sarcastic best
friends, in a variety of plays and live television productions into
the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   When Hollywood called _ his first role was in ``The Kentuckian''
(1955) _ Matthau continued to play straight roles, for the most
part. When he starred, it was usually as a heavy, as in ``Gangster
Story'' (1960), his directing debut, in which he played a mobster
whose girlfriend (Carol Grace, Matthau's newlywed wife) tries to
reform him.
</P>
<P>
   But comedy was clearly his forte, and in 1966 legendary director
Billy Wilder cast Matthau as Jack Lemmon's brother-in-law in ``The
Fortune Cookie.'' Matthau took home a Best Supporting Actor Oscar
as the shyster lawyer ``Whiplash Willie,'' and three patterns were
established: Matthau would be a comic actor, he and Lemmon would
work together frequently and both would become favorites of the
aging Wilder.
</P>
<P>
   The finnicky Lemmon was a natural choice to pair with the
slouchy Matthau when he recreated his Tony-winning role in ``The
Odd Couple'' (1968), and the two would team repeatedly in years to
come, including Wilder's ``The Front Page'' (1974) and ``Buddy
Buddy'' (1981), ``Grumpy Old Men'' (1993), ``Grumpier Old Men''
(1995), ``Out to Sea'' (1996) and ``The Odd Couple II'' (1998).
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 1970s, 1980s and 1990s Matthau etched a series of
comic portrayals which were similar in broad overview but
distinctive in their details. He had a harder-than-usual edge as
the driven newspaper editor Walter Burns in ``The Front Page,''
then aged a couple of decades for an Oscar-nominated turn as a
spiteful, elderly comedian in ``The Sunshine Boys'' (1975) _ 55 at
the time, Matthau played the older half of the team, opposite the
79-year-old George Burns. In 1976, he gave unexpected bite to his
performance as the loser coach of a Little League team in ``The Bad
News Bears.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his other memorable roles, Matthau played a craggy Supreme
Court justice in ``First Monday in October'' (1981), and in 1993
found a perfect role as the harried Mr. Wilson in ``Dennis the
Menace.'' He and Lemmon were better than their material in the
unexpected hit ``Grumpy Old Men,'' while the next year Matthau
delivered perhaps his most charming performance as a whimsical
Albert Einstein in ``I.Q.'' (1994).
</P>
<P>
   He made his money with comedy, but Matthau continued to
demonstrate that he could shine in drama as well. He played a bank
robber in ``Charley Varrick'' (1973) and a cynical Transit
Authority official in the hostage drama ``The Taking of Pelham One
Two Three'' (1974), and had an effective cameo in ``JFK'' (1991).
On the small screen, he played a small-town lawyer in the Emmy
Award-winning television movie ``The Incident'' (1990), whose
success led to a couple of sequels.
</P>
<P>
   In drama or comedy, however, Matthau's assets remained the same
_ a surly curmudgeonliness that suggested he was inwardly laughing
at the world, including himself, and a native intelligence that
expressed itself in cynical asides and occasional moments of
genuine warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Even as a young man, Matthau seemed older than his years, and as
he aged he sometimes let his jowly, baggy-eyed visage and shambling
walk do too much of the work of characterization. He could also
succumb to the temptation to overact, especially when paired with
fellow ham Lemmon.
</P>
<P>
   But to the very end of his career Matthau was capable of
nuanced, interesting performances that lifted second-rate and
first-rate material alike. Behind the facade of the classic grouch
lived a canny, masterful American actor. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-WALTER-MATTHAU-OBIT-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: lived a canny, masterful American actor.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIDEBAR: FOREVER OLD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of Walter Matthau's best films can be found on video
cassette, and a few on laser disk or DVD. A greatest-hits sampling
might include the following eight films:
</P>
<P>
   + `CHARADE' (1963).
</P>
<P>
   It's one of those sophisticated, neo-Hitchcockian thrillers _
this time from musical maven Stanley Donen, of all people. Audrey
Hepburn is an American widow in Paris who's being stalked by a
bunch of killers and protected, she thinks, by Cary Grant. But
Grant has more names than the average man should, and the only
person she can trust is American Embassy official Matthau ... or
can she?
</P>
<P>
   + `THE FORTUNE COOKIE' (1966).
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lemmon is injured at a Cleveland Browns game, and his
ambulance-chasing brother-in-law sees it as their ticket to the big
bucks. Matthau won an Oscar for his role as ``Whiplash Willie,''
and deserved it for the scene with the nuns alone. Nice plus: Some
real-life game footage from the NFL's low-glamour years.
</P>
<P>
   + `THE ODD COUPLE' (1968).
</P>
<P>
   Neil Simon's play gets an impeccable film rendition, with the
tense, obsessive-compulsive Felix (Lemmon) moving in with the
aggressively slobbish Oscar (Matthau, who created the role on
Broadway). With all due respect to Randall and Klugman, Lemmon and
Matthau have this one nailed. Pass on the disappointing 1998
sequel, though.
</P>
<P>
   + `KOTCH' (1971).
</P>
<P>
   Matthau plays an elderly man whose children are trying to shove
him aside _ but, predictably, the crotchety Matthau isn't ready to
go. Heartwarming but rarely saccharine. Matthau's frequent screen
partner, Jack Lemmon, directs in his only stint behind the camera,
and does well.
</P>
<P>
   + `THE FRONT PAGE' (1974).
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wilder's remake, the third go-round for the classic
Hecht-MacArthur play, casts Matthau as tough editor Walter Burns
(previously played by Adolph Menjou in 1931 and Cary Grant in 1940)
and Jack Lemmon as determined-to-quit reporter Hildy Johnson
(previously Pat O'Brien and Rosalind Russell!). Hard-hitting drama
with comic overtones, plus a great supporting cast that includes
Susan Sarandon, Vincent Gardenia, Charles Durning and Carol
Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   + `THE BAD NEWS BEARS' (1976).
</P>
<P>
   Matthau is a sodden, underachieving pool cleaner trapped into
coaching a pathetic Little League team, with Tatum O'Neal as the
girl pitcher who suddenly gives the team a whole new look. Some
raunchy language, but funnier than its many imitators, with Matthau
surprisingly touching in a broadly sketched part. He skipped the
two sequels, incidentally, and so should you.
</P>
<P>
   + `HOUSE CALLS' (1978).
</P>
<P>
   One of the decade's funniest comedies casts Matthau as a
recently widowed doctor who is torn between reveling in his
independence and the charms of Glenda Jackson. Terrific support
from Richard Benjamin and from Art Carney as a dotty chief of
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   + `I.Q.' (1994).
</P>
<P>
   A highly unusual romantic comedy, half Meg Ryan movie and half
philosophical fantasy. Tim Robbins is an auto mechanic in 1950s
Princeton, N.J., who falls in love with the physicist niece (Ryan)
of the famous Professor Albert Einstein. Matthau plays Einstein as
an inspired combination of absent-minded professor, insightful
genius and twinkle-eyed romantic in a performance that deserved the
Oscar it didn't get.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Gayden Wren is the entertainment editor for The New York Times
Syndicate.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 1206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
