<P>
   Even as a young man, Matthau seemed older than his years, and as
he aged he sometimes let his jowly, baggy-eyed visage and shambling
walk do too much of the work of characterization. He could also
succumb to the temptation to overact, especially when paired with
fellow ham Lemmon.
</P>
<P>
   But to the very end of his career Matthau was capable of
nuanced, interesting performances that lifted second-rate and
first-rate material alike. Behind the facade of the classic grouch
lived a canny, masterful American actor. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-WALTER-MATTHAU-OBIT-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: lived a canny, masterful American actor.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIDEBAR: FOREVER OLD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of Walter Matthau's best films can be found on video
cassette, and a few on laser disk or DVD. A greatest-hits sampling
might include the following eight films:
</P>
<P>
   + `CHARADE' (1963).
</P>
<P>
   It's one of those sophisticated, neo-Hitchcockian thrillers _
this time from musical maven Stanley Donen, of all people. Audrey
Hepburn is an American widow in Paris who's being stalked by a
bunch of killers and protected, she thinks, by Cary Grant. But
Grant has more names than the average man should, and the only
person she can trust is American Embassy official Matthau ... or
can she?
</P>
<P>
   + `THE FORTUNE COOKIE' (1966).
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lemmon is injured at a Cleveland Browns game, and his
ambulance-chasing brother-in-law sees it as their ticket to the big
bucks. Matthau won an Oscar for his role as ``Whiplash Willie,''
and deserved it for the scene with the nuns alone. Nice plus: Some
real-life game footage from the NFL's low-glamour years.
</P>
<P>
   + `THE ODD COUPLE' (1968).
</P>
<P>
   Neil Simon's play gets an impeccable film rendition, with the
tense, obsessive-compulsive Felix (Lemmon) moving in with the
aggressively slobbish Oscar (Matthau, who created the role on
Broadway). With all due respect to Randall and Klugman, Lemmon and
Matthau have this one nailed. Pass on the disappointing 1998
sequel, though.
</P>
<P>
   + `KOTCH' (1971).
</P>
<P>
   Matthau plays an elderly man whose children are trying to shove
him aside _ but, predictably, the crotchety Matthau isn't ready to
go. Heartwarming but rarely saccharine. Matthau's frequent screen
partner, Jack Lemmon, directs in his only stint behind the camera,
and does well.
</P>
<P>
   + `THE FRONT PAGE' (1974).
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wilder's remake, the third go-round for the classic
Hecht-MacArthur play, casts Matthau as tough editor Walter Burns
(previously played by Adolph Menjou in 1931 and Cary Grant in 1940)
and Jack Lemmon as determined-to-quit reporter Hildy Johnson
(previously Pat O'Brien and Rosalind Russell!). Hard-hitting drama
with comic overtones, plus a great supporting cast that includes
Susan Sarandon, Vincent Gardenia, Charles Durning and Carol
Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   + `THE BAD NEWS BEARS' (1976).
</P>
<P>
   Matthau is a sodden, underachieving pool cleaner trapped into
coaching a pathetic Little League team, with Tatum O'Neal as the
girl pitcher who suddenly gives the team a whole new look. Some
raunchy language, but funnier than its many imitators, with Matthau
surprisingly touching in a broadly sketched part. He skipped the
two sequels, incidentally, and so should you.
</P>
<P>
   + `HOUSE CALLS' (1978).
</P>
<P>
   One of the decade's funniest comedies casts Matthau as a
recently widowed doctor who is torn between reveling in his
independence and the charms of Glenda Jackson. Terrific support
from Richard Benjamin and from Art Carney as a dotty chief of
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   + `I.Q.' (1994).
</P>
<P>
   A highly unusual romantic comedy, half Meg Ryan movie and half
philosophical fantasy. Tim Robbins is an auto mechanic in 1950s
Princeton, N.J., who falls in love with the physicist niece (Ryan)
of the famous Professor Albert Einstein. Matthau plays Einstein as
an inspired combination of absent-minded professor, insightful
genius and twinkle-eyed romantic in a performance that deserved the
Oscar it didn't get.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Gayden Wren is the entertainment editor for The New York Times
Syndicate.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
