<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     07-01 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLS, STRIKES, AND SOME FIRST AID 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   People ask her why, at 38, she is still out there, on the road,
a different tour stop every night, chasing a dream she has already
lived. Dr. Dot Richardson can answer only that she still has the
passion and she earned the opportunity and because a game not
measured by time is preferable to waiting around for hers to be up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not forever,'' she said. ``Every moment of our lives we
truly need to live.''
</P>
<P>
   What sounded like the inside of a fortune cookie was actually
more the voice of traumatic experience. When she is not winding her
way along the Olympic softball trail, Richardson is a surgeon and
thus not unfamiliar with mortality's terms. She just didn't expect
to be confronting them while warming up recently at second base.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was my favorite Atlanta Olympian in 1996, the
freckled and chatty shortstop who invited the world to come watch
the U.S. women do their thing at the isolated outpost of Columbus,
Ga. She also hit the game-winning home run against China that gave
the Americans the first Olympic gold medal in women's softball, a
splendid game requiring abundant levels of athletic skill.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted to be an ambassador for her sport, which she had
played internationally since 1979 and at UCLA and throughout
medical school and her residency years. And though none of the
Olympic softball games were televised, the buzz from Columbus was
so strong that the network geniuses back in New York finally broke
down. They stole a few moments from the gymnastic pixies, and let
Dr. Dot and teammates rap live with Bob Costas on the night they
struck gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Atlanta, I felt that I never wanted to step on a field
again,'' she said last Thursday when the national team, on the long
road to Sydney, stopped by in Staten Island to play a college
all-star team. ``It was like I never wanted to taint those
memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years is a long time to stick to an emotional decision. By
the following year, Richardson was convincing herself there was no
harm in returning to Columbus for an encore. She wanted to say
thank you to the fans, relive the moments. The plan would have been
perfect had she not tried out for the United States team, and been
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop had become the undisputed territory of Crystl Bustos,
a strapping 23-year-old slugger. Richardson, at 5 feet 5 inches,
felt they were telling her the game had outgrown her, that she was
too old. That made her mad enough to try out again.
</P>
<P>
   She had a 10 a.m. flight to San Diego from Los Angeles, where
she lives, for the next national team auditions. After being up at
the hospital all night, she missed the flight, tending to a
patient. Now she had a choice: give it up for good and go home to
sleep, or drive the two hours and try out, exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember driving and thinking about how they say athletes
never know when to get out,'' she said. ``I was saying, `God, give
me a sign.'''
</P>
<P>
   She got cut again, and decided that wasn't the sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I took from San Diego,'' she said, ``was that while
I was on the field, I was thinking: `I just love this. I want to
play.'''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson kept trying and, finally, last year, she remade the
national team, at second base. The Americans rolled into Staten
Island, not having lost since a 2-1 preliminary round defeat to
Australia at the 1998 world championships. On the current tour,
after 13 of 32 stops, they had outscored the opposition, 154-1.
</P>
<P>
   Before hitting the road, Richardson completed a fellowship with
the Kerlan-Jobe Institute, and she plans to start her own practice
in sports orthopedics next year. Medical duties were on hold, until
the second inning Thursday night at the ASA complex in Staten
Island. When she saw the commotion by the bleachers behind first
base, when she noticed her team manager, Ralph Weekly, frantically
waving her over, she knew why. She dropped her glove and sprinted
off.
</P>
<P>
   She had treated diabetics at games before. She performed a
Heimlich maneuver once. But this time, a 70-year-old man, Sal
Lamendola, had gone into cardiac arrest. He lost consciousness and
Richardson started cardiopulmonary resuscitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to go to a hospital,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In an emergency medical van, she began chest compressions. She
checked for a pulse and found none. Soon, the van was pulling over,
intercepted by an ambulance, which soon sped off with the patient.
Richardson, in uniform, was in the street, in a daze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so stressed, working so hard, and it felt as if we had
driven for miles,'' she said. ``I said to someone, `Where's the
field?' He said, `Right over there.'''
</P>
<P>
   She walked around the corner, into the dugout. The coach, Ralph
Raymond, asked if she wanted to play. Why not? Richardson replied.
She soon grabbed a bat and went up to hit.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Richardson learned that Sal Lamendola had died
at the Sisters of Charity Medical Center. She didn't know the man.
She just tried to save him. She had heard that he often umpired
softball games at the complex and that his life had ended watching
his favorite sport, doing something he loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best we can do while we're here,'' said the good
doctor and softball philosopher. ``Things that we love.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 1213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000701.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0602 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     07-01 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reds Try to Find a Way Back Into the Race
</P>
<P>
   Unable to fix the Cincinnati Reds' primary problem this season,
Jim Bowden has embarked on a do-it-yourself plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have five boys,'' Bowden said. ``I'm trying to make them all
starting pitchers. We have a mound in the backyard and I'm going to
make sure they all become pitchers. How else can we afford
pitchers?''
</P>
<P>
   As a long-range solution, the Bowden plan is commendable. But
what can it do for the Reds in their attempt to get back in the
National League Central race this season? Bowden's sons _ J.B.,
Tyler, Chad and their twin brothers (even younger, not quite 2) _
are not going to replace Steve Parris, Ron Villone and Rob Bell. So
what is a general manager to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night,'' Bowden said, ``I go home and my kids say, `Do
you have a pitcher, do you have a pitcher?' I tell them, `It's not
as easy as your Nintendo game.' They do trades every day on their
video games.''
</P>
<P>
   The inability of Ken Griffey Jr. to hit the Ken Griffey Jr. way
the first two months of the season focused attention on the
newcomer as the culprit in the Reds' disappointing start. A few
days into June and he was hitting a paltry .211.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, Bowden said, Griffey was not the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's hogwash,'' he said. ``This guy is playing Gold Glove
center field, he's on pace to hit 50, 60 home runs and drive in
120. It's not his fault that other guys haven't hit. If they were
on base when he's hitting these bombs, he'd have 180 RBI.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when he was not hitting for average, Griffey was slugging
home runs, 15 in the first two months, 11 more since in 22 games,
in which he has also batted .338 and raised his season average to
.247.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares about the average?'' Bowden asked. ``Greg Vaughn hit
.220 most of last year and he almost got us into the playoffs. He's
producing runs and saving runs every night.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Reds acquired Griffey from Seattle last Feb. 10, the
Reds were immediately viewed as the team most likely to win the
division championship. But just about at the midway point in the
schedule, the Reds languish eight and a half games behind St. Louis
(before Saturday's games).
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, meanwhile, have one of the best records in the
American League, but that is another story.
</P>
<P>
   This one is about the Reds and their failure not only to command
the division race but also to take off in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had told me in spring training that on June 30 we'd
have the same number of wins as the Yankees, I'd probably have been
happy,'' Bowden said. But he is not happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my responsibility that we're not winning,'' Bowden said.
``I haven't been able to make deals for starting pitching. Why do
the Yankees have the same number of wins as we do? Starting
pitching. You don't win without starting pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds have sent one of their starting pitchers, a rookie, Rob
Bell (5.28 earned run average), back to the minor leagues after 15
starts. Parris has a 5.67 ERA and 11 losses, Ron Villone a 5.92
ERA. Only Denny Neagle (3.86) and Osvaldo Fernandez (3.21) have
been consistently effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have guys who get us down 5-0 before we say hello,'' the
usually resourceful Bowden said. ``If we have starting pitching, we
can get back in this thing. There are pitchers out there who I
think will make a difference. We can't afford to add payroll so we
couldn't get Mussina or Radke, that type of guy, but we need
someone to keep us in games for six innings.''
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, Pete Harnisch, the Reds' No. 1 starter, returned
from nearly two months on the disabled list with an ailing shoulder
and pitched six shutout innings against Arizona Friday night. The
Reds won the game for Harnisch's first victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey did not get a hit in 4 times at bat, lowering his
average to .244. In 11 seasons with the Mariners, Griffey was a
.300 hitter seven times. He hit a career-high .323 in the
strike-shortened 1994 season, then followed it with a career-low
.258. He hit .284 and .285 the past two seasons, leaving him at
.299 for his career.
</P>
<P>
   His batting average, then, has never really been an accurate
barometer of his overall contribution. He has averaged 52 home runs
the past four seasons, and his 26 home runs this season have helped
keep the Reds close enough to the Cardinals to be able to make a
run at them if the starting pitching cooperates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's awesome,'' said Bowden, an admittedly shameless admirer,
``one of the best players I've seen in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's Discomfort
</P>
<P>
   Can Sammy Sosa rediscover peace and happiness on the North Side
of Chicago? The Cubs certainly hope so, but the betting in baseball
circles (where no betting is allowed) is that he will not. The
furious love affair that had existed has been shattered, very
likely beyond repair. One friend of Sosa said he was ``dying'' to
get away from the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   But Sosa probably lost his chance to go elsewhere when the Cubs
squandered what appeared to be their best chance to trade him. The
Yankees came within one player of making a deal, but they wouldn't
give the Cubs the extra player they demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of other clubs saw the Cubs' stance as greedy. ``They
let a left-handed `A' ball pitcher stand in the way,'' one general
manager said contemptuously, referring to Alex Graman. ``This might
have been the biggest trade blunder in Cubs history. They had an
opportunity to get four pretty good young players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs may find another team that would be willing to give up
a cache of good young prospects and sign Sosa to a contract
extension worth perhaps $18 million a year, but it's highly
unlikely. As one general manager pointed out, next winter's free
agent crop will feature Alex Rodriguez, Juan Gonzalez, Manny
Ramirez and Chipper Jones. A team that otherwise may be interested
in Sosa could sign one of those players and keep their prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Andy MacPhail, the Cubs' president, does not see the team's
circumstances as dire as others obviously do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you get involved in these type of things,'' he said,
``you have to satisfy yourself that you did your best for the
organization and the player. We made a good faith effort to
accommodate the player, balancing that with what we perceived our
needs to be down the road. The Yankees chose to go a different
road, which is their prerogative.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was obvious their talks with the Yankees had died, the
Cubs quickly took steps to try to repair the schism that had
developed with Sosa. General Manager Ed Lynch spoke with him in
Pittsburgh, and MacPhail contacted one of his agents. There is not
much confidence outside of Wrigley Field that their words will
create the peaceful coexistence the Cubs now desperately need.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Deep on the Disabled List
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians, who reached Saturday alive but a shocking
nine and a half games from first place, have had a fulltime job
shuffling pitchers. Because they have had so many pitchers hurt
this season, they have had to bring pitchers up from the minor
leagues when they hadn't planned to or signed free-agent pitchers
who were available only because other teams had released them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You anticipate that you'll have to go to Triple A and get
three guys during the season,'' Mark Shapiro, the team's assistant
general manager, said. ``You can't do it with seven. We're seven
pitchers deep on the disabled list. No team is equipped to handle
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In order, the Indians have added to their pitching staff this
season: Sean DePaula (now on the disabled list himself), Jim
Brower, Mark Watson (lost on waiver claim), Scott Sanders (released
next day), Paul Rigdon (disabled list, later optioned to minors),
Tim Drew (optioned next day), Justin Speier, Jared Camp (lost on
waiver claim), Jamie Brewington, Kane Davis (optioned, later
recalled), Willie Martinez (optioned three days later), Brian
Williams, Jaime Navarro (designated for assignment after two
starts), Mike Mohler (designated for assignment two days later),
Andrew Lorraine, Alan Newman (designated for assignment two days
later).
</P>
<P>
   Charles Nagy, a veteran starter who has been on the disabled
list since May 18, is expected back just after the All-Star break.
Jaret Wright, on the disabled list for the second time this season,
won't be back until August, if at all this year.
</P>
<P>
   Trading Benefits
</P>
<P>
   On the same day last week, Wednesday, Cal Eldred gained his 10th
victory against 2 defeats for the Chicago White Sox and Jeff
Cirillo hit 3 home runs in a game for the Colorado Rockies. Eldred
and Cirillo were traded to their teams a month apart last winter by
the Milwaukee Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   With Eldred becoming one of two 10-game winners, the White Sox
have grabbed a commanding lead in the American League Central. With
Cirillo hitting .348 and driving in 61 runs, the Rockies are
challenging Arizona for first place in the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Valentin was in the trade with Eldred and is the White Sox
shortstop. Within that same month, the Brewers traded Fernando Vina
to St. Louis, where he was hitting .290 as the regular second
baseman for the first-place Cardinals before going on the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers, at last look, were languishing near the bottom of
the N.L. Central.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
