<P>
   RIORDAN-LEGACY (Los Angeles) _ This is Richard Riordan's final
year as Los Angeles mayor. Left in doubt at this point is how well
the multimillionaire former businessman will have fared with his
vision of a safer city, friendlier to both business and
constituents. By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``a'' national and
``n'' California state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION (Los Angeles) _ Some 10,000 Mexican nationals
living in California are going to Mexico this weekend to vote in a
historic presidential election that could result in the dethroning
of the 71-year ruling party. The caravans and thousands of free
phone cards to call family members to influence their votes is the
result of an unprecedented fight for the Mexican vote abroad,
widely viewed to favor the opposition candidates. By Dominic
Berbeo. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California state
news files.)
</P>
<P>
   ABALONE-ENDANGERED (Port Hueneme, Calif.) _ In its heyday, white
abalone dotted the ocean floor in the prime fishing grounds off the
Ventura County coast and numbered in the millions from Point
Conception to Baja. But with fewer than 2,540 remaining, white
abalone is nearly extinct. The public has until Wednesday to
comment on a National Marine Fisheries Service plan to list the
mollusk as an endangered species, the first time a marine
invertebrate would receive the classification. By Cecilia Chan.
(Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California state news
files.)
</P>
<P>
   ABALONE-RESCUE (Port Hueneme, Calif.) _ At the dead-end of
Hueneme Road, on the edge of Port Hueneme Harbor, a nonprofit
institution is gearing up for its role in breeding a sea snail that
is facing extinction. The Channel Islands Marine Resource Institute
is part of a group of public and private entities that have come
together to form the White Abalone Restoration Consortium. By
Cecilia Chan. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California
state news files.)
</P>
<P>
