<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0609 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-RIORDAN-LEGACY-2Takes     07-01 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIORDAN-LEGACY-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIORDAN IN FINAL YEAR OF OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Twelve months from now, Mayor Richard Riordan
leaves Los Angeles City Hall, ending what will have been a
personally expensive, eight-year experiment in reconfiguring local
government.
</P>
<P>
   Left in doubt at this point is how well the multimillionaire
businessman will have fared with his vision of a safer city,
friendlier to both business and its constituents. What, in essence,
will be his legacy?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you worry about that, then you are unable to do anything,''
the 70-year-old mayor said in a recent interview in his
eighth-floor office at City Hall East, overlooking historic City
Hall, which is undergoing earthquake repairs and might be open by
the time Riordan returns to private life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't worry about legacy. It will be what it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who do gauge legacies say this is Riordan's make-or-break
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that people will remember Richard Riordan for will
take place this summer,'' political analyst Sherry Bebitch Jeffe
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His whole legacy will be based on how the city comes through
the (Democratic National) Convention, how the Rampart scandal
shakes out and how well (new schools superintendent) Roy Romer does
at the school district.''
</P>
<P>
   There is irony in the controversies that surround Riordan and
the nation's second-largest city: The secession drives and the
police corruption scandal at the Los Angeles Police Department's
Rampart Division.
</P>
<P>
   It was Riordan who ran in 1993 on a campaign of making the city
safer after the 1992 rioting that followed the initial acquittal of
four LAPD officers accusing of beating African-American motorist
Rodney King and the promise of increasing the Police Department to
10,000 officers _ a goal that was never reached, and for which the
mayor was not held accountable as crime dropped anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It was Riordan who raised the hopes of neighborhoods by urging
them to demand service from the city.
</P>
<P>
   When that failed and a growing disenchantment settled across the
city, secession drives began _ first in the San Fernando Valley,
then spreading to the Wilmington-San Pedro area and to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   While he adamantly opposes secession, Riordan said he is proud
of the energy he has unleashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one thing I'm proud of, it is empowering
neighborhoods,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, this past year has been the toughest for him even
as others question his commitment to city issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been busier this year than I've ever been,'' Riordan
said. ``I'm spending every day dealing with Rampart and the
convention. And, then there's education and the school board that
takes a lot of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Convention is seen as crucial in
remaking the image of the city from the scenes of rioting and fires
following the Rodney King verdict in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be worth $1 billion in publicity,'' Riordan said. But
that is contingent on a smoothly run convention with few problems
and a police department seen neither as overbearing nor
under-reactive to protests and demonstrations that could turn
violent.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the convention planning has been far from smooth. Fund
raising fell so far short, the Host Committee was forced to ask the
City Council for $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The council reluctantly agreed - although there are moves to
reverse that - but only after it forced Riordan to pay off on a $1
million personal letter of credit he had written for the Host
Committee to cover some of its costs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, Riordan insists his relationship with the City
Council is strong on practical matters affecting the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is only when we get into politics that there is a
problem,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas, who has been both ally and
adversary to the mayor, said it might be too late for Riordan to
forge a relationship with the council after years of ignoring it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regrettably, he continues to refuse to work cooperatively with
the council,'' Ridley-Thomas said. ``It has been one form of combat
after another and we have suffered from that. His administration
has suffered, the people have suffered and local government has
suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that Riordan's lame duck status.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a level of intolerance and impatience by several
members of the council toward the mayor, and that's unfortunate,''
Ridley-Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan worries only about the potential loss of staff during
his final year in office rather than being a lame duck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of having the will to get things done,'' Riordan
said. ``But I have a lot of loyal people who are going to be
looking ahead. A lot of them can make twice the amount of money in
the private sector as they do here.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Much of Riordan's problems with the City Council stem from his
original campaign, which cost him $6 million of his own money. He
ran as an outsider against ``career politicians,'' lambasting city
bureaucrats and criticizing the level of spending.
</P>
<P>
   But he was unsuccessful with many of his original proposals such
as selling off Los Angeles International Airport and privatizing
city services. Others, such as reforming the city business tax
structure, saw partial success but never went as far as Riordan
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan's second election in 1997 was much easier than his first
_ in which he defeated former Councilman Mike Woo in a runoff _ but
still cost millions of dollars. Riordan spent $3 million of his own
funds in the 1997 race against state Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Riordan has used his own money and his contacts with
millionaires to bring them in for a variety of causes, from the
Disney Hall to library and police programs.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the area in which Riordan has been most successful is
one in which he has no direct power: The Los Angeles Unified School
District.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan created a political committee, Coalition for Kids, that
saw the election of three new school board members and the
re-election of a fourth member committed to the mayor's vision of
reform.
</P>
<P>
   That board ousted Superintendent Ruben Zacarias, brought in
interim superintendent Ramon Cortines and recently hired former
Colorado Gov. Romer to oversee the latest restructuring plan of
creating 11 minidistricts.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan, however, said he will continue his efforts in the area
of education. He's already raised $300,000 and is targeting two of
the three board members up for election next year, Julie Korenstein
and Vickie Castro. Riordan said board member Valerie Fields has
embraced his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he has no such plans against any City Council
members, half of whom will be leaving their seats for other
political jobs or because of the term limits approved by voters
after an initiative campaign financed by Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   While a victim of those term limits, Riordan said he has no
regrets over being forced from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while, people forget who they are and begin to define
themselves by their title,'' Riordan said. ``That's when it's time
to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
