<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN VOTERS LIVING IN U.S. PLAN CARAVAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOMINIC BERBEO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Thousands of Californians are in Tijuana this
Fourth of July weekend, not to party but to vote in the most
contested presidential election in Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
   To vote, Mexicans must cross the border, where special booths
have been set up to handle the expected crowds. Fifteen such sites
have been set up in the tourist town of Tijuana, a three-hour drive
from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left Mexico a long time ago,'' said Desiderio Villegas, a
semi-retired Christian pastor who came to Van Nuys from Mexicali,
Mexico, 19 years ago. ``But the struggle for change there is still
my struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   His sentiment is a widespread one, as most of the estimated 4
million Mexican-Americans in the Los Angeles area closely watch the
elections, regarded as a test of true democracy in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those in the mass ballot-box exodus are thought to
support Mexican opposition candidates in an election that has the
first real chance of dethroning the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, since it took power in 1929. The PRI is the
longest-ruling political party in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Only Mexican citizens with voter identification cards qualify to
vote. Mexico estimates there are 1.5 million people in the United
States with valid Mexican voter cards. Mexico recognizes dual
citizenship, allowing people who live in the United States to vote
in Mexican elections if they've received a voter card.
</P>
<P>
   Villegas, who has networked through his extensive ties in the
San Fernando Valley to church groups, unions and grass-roots
community organizations, said he believes at least 5,000 from the
area will travel south to vote.
</P>
<P>
   While Mexicans living in the United States can't vote from
abroad, they are highly influential members of their extended
families across the border. Each year they send home an estimated
$6 billion annually, the country's third-biggest source of foreign
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is a historic moment to bring democracy to
Mexico,'' said Francisco Garciduenas, an opposition supporter
organizing a voting caravan from Los Angeles to Tijuana expected to
draw at least 500. ``It's not a question of, Can we afford to do
this, but rather it's our duty.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that most of those going, like many other
Mexican-Americans, maintain intense cross-border relations with
family members, and even maintain property or businesses in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposition has made great progress in the past decade,''
he said. ``We now have non-PRI governors, mayors and members of
congress. We're moving closer to democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   He has contacted family members in his home state of Michoacan
to influence their vote, just as many others in the United States
have called relatives down south.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the PRI-controlled Mexican congress killed a law that
would have allowed Mexicans abroad to submit absentee ballots
through consul offices. The move was criticized as a political
safeguard against strong opposition support abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition candidate Vicente Fox of the center-right National
Action Party (PAN) and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the center-left
Democratic Revolutionary Party (PRD) each have extensive support
groups in California, where they traveled this year to campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The vote from abroad could have an impact on the close
presidential race, with the most recent voter polls showing Fox in
a dead heat with Francisco Labastida, the PRI candidate. Cardenas
runs a distant third with 15 percent to 20 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a former governor and head of Coca-Cola in Mexico, has set
himself apart by promising to seek a more open border with the
United States and radical tax incentives to lure foreign investment
into the country.
</P>
<P>
   But Labastida, a former governor and three-time federal cabinet
secretary, has criticized Fox for setting unrealistic job-creation
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Fox made an unsuccessful, last-ditch effort last week to seek
Cardenas' support to ensure opposition victory over the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   In California, Fox supporters plan to hand out thousands of
two-minute phone cards so that Mexican-Americans not able to travel
to Mexico to vote can call relatives and influence their choice,
said Carlos Salazar, international relations advisor to Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling throughout Mexico and on this side of the border
is that people want change, and that's what we represent,'' Salazar
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Elections Institute, or IFE, which runs the election
process in Mexico, estimates there are 56 million registered voters
in Mexico, and expects about 40 million to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Created in the aftermath of the 1988 elections, in which
Cardenas claimed he was robbed of victory by a corrupt government,
the IFE is an independent agency put in place to ensure a clean
election.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, a former governor and mayor of Mexico City, held a
strong lead in polls in 1988 but lost by a landslide after a
suspicious computer glitch in the PRI-controlled government offices
on election night.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge for the IFE in this election will be
ensuring the public that a fair vote took place. The agency is
sending out thousands of observers on election day and will begin
releasing early results this afternoon, with the first official
tally expected at 11 p.m. Mexico City time.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. President Jimmy Carter is the key monitor from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the IFE is setting up more than 110 special voting
sites with 750 ballots each along the 2,000-mile U.S. border with
Mexico in expectation of a large number of Mexicans traveling south
to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Tijuana, where there will be 15 sites with 11,250 total ballots,
is the expected destination for many Californians.
</P>
<P>
   Many planned to leave Saturday and spend the night to get in
line before voting sights open at 8 a.m. to ensure they get a
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working on this for years,'' said Juan Jose
Bocanegro, one of 20 Mexicans in a group traveling from Seattle to
Tijuana who plan to ride the last mile across the border on
horseback for dramatic effect. They will be joined by other
horsemen in Los Angeles and Orange counties, and hope to be 100
strong by the time they reach Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Bocanegro has run a job training program aimed at immigrants in
Seattle for the past 13 years, and says his ties to Mexico have
remained strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my family in Guadalajara will be voting for the
opposition, but the votes from up here are important, too,'' he
said. ``What affects my cousins and uncles also affects me.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 1229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
