<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0617 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-ABALONE-RESCUE-LADN     07-01 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABALONE-RESCUE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROJECT SEEKS TO BREED WHITE ABALONE FOR RELEASE
</HEADLINE>
 (With BC-ABALONE-ENDANGERED-LADN, both for use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By CECILIA CHAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT HUENEME, Calif. _ At the dead-end of Hueneme Road, on the
edge of Port Hueneme Harbor, a nonprofit institution is gearing up
for its role in breeding a sea snail that is facing extinction.
</P>
<P>
   The Channel Islands Marine Resource Institute is part of a group
of public and private entities that have come together to form the
White Abalone Restoration Consortium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will use techniques that have been in existence for almost
a half-century to breed abalone,'' institute Director Tom McCormick
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been used successfully on green, pink, red and black, so
we will modify those spawning conditions and rearing for the white
abalone to get them to spawn for us in captivity.''
</P>
<P>
   The institute has built two self-contained systems that mimic
the habitat of the white abalone. The systems each have six tanks
able to house up to 10 abalone.
</P>
<P>
   The white abalone can thrive in shallow water but is typically
found in the deep, where temperatures stay below 60 degrees and
they are sheltered from predators, McCormick said.
</P>
<P>
   Abalone reproduces by releasing millions of eggs or sperm into
the water, where they make contact by chance. After the fertilized
eggs hatch, the larvae spin around for a week - each the size of a
grain of sand, McCormick said. They then settle down and begin to
feed on algae.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love to eat for the first six, eight, 10 months of
life,'' McCormick said. ``These abalone, we hope will be grown up
to the size of three to four inches - adult size - and they they
will be released into the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   McCormick said the goal is to release 10,000 abalone a year back
into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The institute is one of several labs along the California
coastline that will participate in the breeding program.
</P>
<P>
   The first batch of nine white abalone were transported to the
University of California, Santa Barbara, and the next batch is
destined for the institute. McCormick said he expects to hear any
day now that a collection is arriving.
</P>
<P>
   The abalone at UC Santa Barbara are in quarantine, undergoing
treatment with antibiotics in case they have withering syndrome, a
bacterial infection that has decimated the black abalone, said Dan
Richards, marine biologist at the Channel Islands National Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are attempting to collect as many as we can,'' Richards
said. ``The plan is to breed them in captivity like the condors and
eventually raise them up to a reasonable size so they can survive
for the first couple of years''
</P>
<P>
   It will take four years for the abalone to reach adulthood
before they can be released, said Ian Taniguchi, marine biologist
with the California Fish and Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a whole lot that we know about the (white
abalone's) life history,'' he said. ``Part of what we are doing is
figuring out the husbandry, how to keep white abalone in captivity,
and also learn about the reproductive process.''
</P>
<P>
   Taniguchi said another technique is to bring the adults closer
together in the wild - within a meter - on protective reefs so they
can reproduce. Over-consumption in the early 1970s has thinned the
density of the population, making it hard for their released eggs
and sperm to make contact.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCormick said it would take decades to bring the
species back to a sizable number, Richards estimated if all the
facilities are in operation and enough funding is available it
would take $10million over 10 years to get a healthy population
back in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we need to give them that boost or they are not going
to make it,'' Richards said. ``They are too few and far in between
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
