<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0624 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-ART-8     07-01 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-ART-875(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOEVER WINS, VOTE IN MEXICO WILL BE FATEFUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV 13 : A graphic is being sent to NYT 14  graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers 15  can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The past hangs heavy over Mexico's people and
politics, but rarely has a moment seemed so pregnant with history
as the presidential balloting scheduled for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will choose either to bring down the curtain on a dynasty
that has governed since the Mexican revolution or, almost as
extraordinary, to inaugurate a new century by freely electing the
party that dominated most of the last one.
</P>
<P>
   Either result would usher in a period of some uncertainty. The
leading opposition candidate, Vicente Fox, pledged to govern with
caution if elected, but his victory would shatter an elite tied to
the Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI. A new
triumph by the party that has won 13 consecutive presidential
elections would outrage many in the educated and middle classes,
with potentially volatile consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the decades, the PRI created an atmosphere of eternal
victory,'' said Homero Aridjis, a poet and former ambassador. ``But
now the opposition has shown that defeat of the official party is
possible. Mexico has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the rancorous presidential campaign that culminates with
Sunday's balloting, the country abandoned a series of authoritarian
traditions stretching back half a century. And in characteristic
fashion, even as Mexicans lived a thrilling period of democratic
innovation, they often debated their own history as fervently as
their strategies for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weight of the past has sometimes been more present than
the present itself,'' the author Enrique Krauze once wrote of
Mexicans' singular preoccupation with history's legacy, the
crucible of conquest and colonialism, reform and revolution that
forged their modern outlook.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed true during much of the campaign, as the major
candidates and their supporters restaged Mexico's battles and
betrayals. Yet at the end of the grand debate, all Mexico seemed to
grasp the momentous nature of the choice at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is the culmination of struggles, initiatives and
sacrifices stretching throughout our entire history,'' Porfirio
Munoz Ledo, who ended his candidacy in June to endorse Fox,
thundered the week before last. ``Never, since we became an
independent nation, has power passed peacefully from one party to
another through elections. This vote is a watershed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the balloting, voters will elect a president for a six-year
term, 500 congressional deputies, 128 senators, two state governors
and the mayor of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   In a final opinion poll published by the newspaper Reforma on
June 22, the governing party candidate, Francisco Labastida, was
favored by 42 percent of voters, Fox of the center-right National
Action Party by 39 percent, and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a leftist
candidate, by 16 percent. The margin of error was 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those results showed how Mexico's opposition forces have grown
into a broad majority, but their division between two major
candidates could bring a new governing-party triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has a rich tradition of electoral fraud, but safeguards
put in place by the autonomous federal agency organizing the
election have greatly reduced the possibility for chicanery. One or
more opposition parties are expected to be represented at the vast
majority, if not all, of the 113,000 voting places.
</P>
<P>
   The government said it had authorized 860 foreigners to visit
Mexico to observe the voting. Jimmy Carter is here, as are
delegations sent by the U.S. Republican and Democratic parties.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI, founded in 1929 as an alliance of rival factions within
the postrevolutionary army, long monopolized Mexican life. During
its first decades, the party put the nation's finances on a sound
footing, built thousands of schools and clinics, and raised living
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic intellectuals opposed to the land reform and other
policies that they considered socialist formed the National Action
Party, known as the PAN, in 1938, and it has always been the most
important opposition party. But it remained a mere sect during its
first half-century. The governing party has won 13 consecutive
presidential elections, usually by sweeping margins and four times
by alleged fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two decades, amid recurrent economic crises and
revelations of party corruption, opposition strength has grown.
Even in the last presidential balloting in 1994, however, the
party's candidate, Ernesto Zedillo, received nearly twice as many
votes as the National Action Party nominee, who came in second.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox has mounted the opposition's fiercest assault,
galvanizing support among millions of voters beyond his own party.
Announcing his candidacy three years ago, he rewrote the political
calendar in which no campaigning ever began before the sitting
president had handpicked his successor.
</P>
<P>
   His audacity forced Zedillo and his party to organize the PRI's
first presidential primary, holding candidate debates and placing
new emphasis on television campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Win or lose, Fox has changed Mexican politics forever,'' said
Federico Estevez, a political scientist. ``His candidacy forced the
ruling party to open up the process, bringing elite politics down
to the level of the masses. That's a huge change.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But throughout a campaign that moved Mexicans toward a more
modern presidential succession, the candidates frequently invited
them to look over their shoulders, drawing contemporary lessons
from past struggles.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, for instance, often dresses like an American cowboy, and
his mother was born in Spain. In television advertisements,
Labastida stoked Mexicans' lingering bitterness over the Spanish
conquest and an 1847 American invasion in which Mexico lost
territories from Texas to Oregon, and he derided Fox as a man with
foreign roots and treasonous tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida reached back across 65 years of history to portray
himself as an heir to President Lazaro Cardenas del Rio,
Cuauhtemoc's father, who ruled with great popularity during the
1930s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who created our Social Security system?'' Labastida bellowed
during a rally the other day. ``Who expropriated the petroleum? Was
it a Martian, the PAN or was it one of our PRI presidents?''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Labastida cranked up his party's machinery,
enlisting the aid of 21 PRI state governors and a string of his
party's hoariest leaders, men associated with illicit fortunes and
election fraud. They carried out a nationwide campaign to dispense
taxpayer-financed giveaways to poor voters, often in exchange for
written vote pledges.
</P>
<P>
   Those tactics may have helped Fox to persuade some undecided
voters to adopt his view that in recent times the PRI governments
acted as corrupt stewards while workers' real income plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexicans have been the great losers of the 20th century,'' Fox
said in a televised debate in April.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks later, in another broadcast encounter with his rivals, he
portrayed himself as the champion of Mexico's democratic movement,
which has built since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The road has been long and difficult,'' Fox said. ``We're
arriving at our goal, thanks to millions of Mexicans who have
confronted PRI authoritarianism.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's campaign to draw votes from across the political spectrum
seemed to be snowballing until May, when a letter in which Fox
courted the support of the Roman Catholic bishops stirred
anti-clerical animosities dating from the Inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Distrust of the church smolders because of its often exploitive
role during colonial rule; it was the largest banker until
19th-century reform laws expropriated ecclesiastical properties.
Every president since Benito Juarez has come from a party with a
strong anti-clerical streak. Fox, in contrast, is an
unapologetically devout Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Fox wins, it will be the first time a party linked to the
church has assumed power in Mexico since the 1850s,'' said
Friedrich Katz, a historian at the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But the greatest obstacle to Fox's attempt to unite the
opposition against the PRI was Cardenas, who broke with his
father's party in 1987 and lost his own presidential challenge the
next year, many believe through fraud. He finished last among the
major candidates in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent intellectuals sought to negotiate an alliance between
Fox and Cardenas last fall, but the effort collapsed because
neither man would relinquish his own candidacy. Fox has since
insisted that a vote for Cardenas is a vote wasted.
</P>
<P>
   That argument posed a powerful quandary for the left. Some from
Cardenas' party, and even a handful of former Communists, endorsed
Fox, declaring that since the fall of the Berlin Wall their desire
to oust the governing party had come to outweigh ideological
considerations.
</P>
<P>
   But Cardenas and most of his supporters spurned Fox's unity
pleas. Some cited Fox's 1996 proposal to privatize Pemex, the
state-owned oil company, an icon of Mexican nationalism ever since
Lazaro Cardenas expropriated the oil fields from Standard Oil in
1938.
</P>
<P>
   Others looked further back, across centuries, to conclude that
despite their current disgust with corruption, they had more in
common with the PRI than with Fox and his conservative associates.
</P>
<P>
   In a final campaign speech, Amalia Garcia, the historian who is
the president of Cardenas' party, outlined Mexico's national
development as a struggle between conservative traitors like Fox
and a line of heroic, modernizing leaders including Benito Juarez,
Lazaro Cardenas and his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the dawn of our independence, our nation has been in
conflict over two great visions,'' Garcia said. ``We're living the
same historic dispute again today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
