<HEADER>
A0633 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-IRAN-JEWS-775&AMP;ADD-NYT     07-01 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-JEWS-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 JEWS CONVICTED BY IRANIAN COURT IN SPY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHIRAZ, Iran _ A judge on Saturday convicted 10 of 13 Jewish men
accused by the Revolutionary Court of being spies, asserting that
their years of religious piety were a cover for espionage and
illegal aid to Iran's enemy, Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The men _ shopkeepers, Hebrew teachers, a part-time rabbi, an
English professor and an electrical utility official _ were
sentenced to prison terms ranging from four to 13 years. Most were
convicted of being members of an illegal group, recruiting others
to join it and ``cooperating'' with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Two Muslim men convicted of aiding the spy ring were also
convicted and sentenced to two and four years. Two other Muslims,
arrested because they had dealings with some of the Jewish
defendants, were acquitted along with three Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The case has been closely monitored by Western governments as an
indicator of Iran's adherence to international principles of
justice and human rights. Several European countries and the United
States have said that the conduct and outcome of the trial would
affect their future relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The verdicts, seen by Tehran-based diplomats as harsh, drew
immediate condemnation from Jewish groups and from Israel, which
has denied using the Iranians as spies.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
told the Reuters news agency that the outcome was ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a kangaroo proceeding,'' Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights organizations also had criticized the proceedings
as unfair, because the trials were held in secret and the
defendants were held for over 15 months without access to
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Esmail Naseri Mojarrad, the spokesman for the three-lawyer team
representing most defendants, said the court had not proved that
the men passed _ or even had access to _ classified information. He
said he would appeal the convictions if family members wished,
based on the absence of any evidence other than confessions of some
of the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are not guilty of collecting information, exactly what
kind of cooperation are they supposed to have given?'' Naseri
Mojarrad said.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the defendants were paraded before cameras of the state
television channel during the hearings and made confessions that
were broadcast nationally. Defense lawyers complained that the
confessions, both off camera and on, were invalid because of the
length of detention and because their clients had no lawyers
present.
</P>
<P>
   Iranian officials have gone to unusual lengths to defend their
handling of the case, denouncing the international attention as
interference in internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare gesture, court officials read the 72-page decision of
the Revolutionary Court judge, Sadeq Nouri, to reporters and the
foreign diplomats who have monitored the trial since it began in
late April.
</P>
<P>
   The norm for the Revolutionary Court, which handles political
trials as well as drug-smuggling and national security matters, is
not to announce a verdict at all. Trials are secret, defendants
often do not have lawyers until the last minute and evidence is
never made public.
</P>
<P>
   But in the case of the Shiraz Jews, court officials held public
briefings after each week of hearings and insisted that the closed
hearings were justified because national security was involved.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein Ali Amiri, the head of the provincial judiciary in
Shiraz, said each defendant had faced five separate charges
relating to spying, each carrying a possible sentence of 10 years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The men could have also been charged with a special count in
Iran's Islamic penal code _ acting against God _ that carries the
death penalty. But the judge, who also acted as the prosecutor,
decided against that charge, Amiri said.
</P>
<P>
   While the case has traumatized Iran's Jews, a dwindling
population of about 30,000, it has not reverberated through the
country as a whole. Iranians have been absorbed, instead, in the
political battles between reformers allied with President Mohammad
Khatami and religious conservatives who control the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami has not commented on the trial except to assure foreign
visitors that it would be fair and the court would act
independently.
</P>
<P>
   But the convictions may have a tangible impact on Khatami's
attempts to create warmer relations with the West. The week before
last, a visit planned for July 4 by the British foreign minister,
Robin Cook, was abruptly canceled.
</P>
<P>
   In just over a week, Khatami is scheduled to make a long-delayed
trip to Germany. The European Union is expected to make a statement
about the spy trial, and the fate of that visit is not clear.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The decision on Saturday gave few details of the activities that
the convicted men were supposed to have conducted on behalf of
Israel. But it did indicate that Jews in Iran have been monitored
by intelligence agents for many years, even though investigation in
this case was said to have begun only in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's long narrative accused the Jewish men of working for
Israel for over 20 years, since before the Islamic revolution that
overthrew the shah in 1979. It said the espionage group began under
the tutelage of a Shiraz rabbi identified only as Itzhak, who
passed information to Israel's secret service, Mossad, by telephone
and fax and through Iranians traveling outside the country.
</P>
<P>
   Some Shiraz Jews, who said they were afraid now to speak
publicly, said that Itzhak is their former rabbi, Itzhak
Balalaness, who emigrated to the United States in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Balalaness, they said, was a charismatic figure who helped
revitalize Jewish life in Shiraz.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the men convicted in the spy case were quoted in the
judge's report about the rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   One, Farhad Seleh, was reported to have said: ``He created love
for Israel in our hearts. He used to say that serving Israel was
like serving Torah and that in our Jewish books it says that we
should move before others move against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Iranian Jews have relatives in Israel and visit them,
although Iran does not recognize Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the defendants were quoted in the judge's report as
saying that they had collected information about the location of
military bases and information about Iran's politics, culture and
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The group was also accused by the judge of being ``a cause in
the war between Iran and Iraq.'' One of the men convicted of
providing information about the war was only 17 years old when it
ended 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The convicted Jewish men are: Asher Farzadmehr, 51, sentenced to
13 years in prison; Nasser Levi-Haim, 52, sentenced to 11 years;
Seleh, 41, sentenced to eight years; Javid Bent-Yakub, 43,
sentenced to nine years; Shahrok Paknahad, 30, sentenced to eight
years; Hamid ``Dani'' Tefileen, 31, sentenced to 13 years; Farzad
Kashi, 45, sentenced to eight years; Ramin Farzam, 31, sentenced to
10 years; Faramarz Kashi, 39, sentenced to five years; and Ramin
Nematizadeh, 27, sentenced to four years.
</P>
<P>
   The two Muslims convicted were Ali Akbar Safaee, sentenced to
two years for assisting the spy network, and Mehrab Yusefi,
sentenced to four years for assisting the network and cooperating
with Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
