<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0643 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PRISON-EXPERIMENT-ART     07-01 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-EXPERIMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAILED DADS TELL VISITING CHILDREN: DON'T FOLLOW IN OUR FOOTSTEPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)   (EDS: Note that there are 2 girls named Dominique.)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT1,2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio _ Dominique first heard the strange word
directly from her father four years ago, when she was 8 and he was
going away. But she did not grasp the meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy said `incarceration,''' recalled Dominique, who knows
the word well now that she has spent much of a week within the
confines of the prison that has kept her father, convicted of
violent assault, 300 miles from her.
</P>
<P>
   Nine convicts have been free to exchange hugs with their
children, some of them hesitantly at first, and to play and advise
and gaze upon them for four hours each morning last week. Sharing
thoughts and meals, they tested a program, as merciful as it is
experimental, to let 11 children and their imprisoned fathers
directly repair family ties.
</P>
<P>
   Small scenes of joy _ fathers and children making cutouts and
paintings together, laughing, embracing, finally airing difficult
problems, sometimes crying _ are hidden from society here in the
confines of the fathers' home behind bars and razor wire, which
they admitted to their children is known as ``the cage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would cry when he first went away,'' Dominique said. ``But
Daddy would write me letters and tell me always do my homework.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of his 6-year to 18-year sentence, her father,
Alonzo Thompson, found himself lying down hand-in-hand with
Dominique one morning on the floor of the Northeast Ohio
Correctional Center's visitors' room, where each father and child
had their own piece of silhouette paper on which to trace their
outlines for a life-size mural of their reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my heart right there,'' Thompson said of his daughter
as she colored in fanciful details of the two of them and made the
fingers securely overlap.
</P>
<P>
   Their laughter never made it outside to this gray city of
burned-out steel mills. Youngstown is quietly becoming the prison
capital of a nation that, to use Dominique's hard-learned word, is
now the world leader in incarceration. Five prisons operate here
with about 40,000 inmates; two more are on the way. Many of the
prisoners are young fathers with plenty of time to ponder long
lists of regrets, with their children, often little known and less
seen, at the top of those lists.
</P>
<P>
   In this prison, there is even a class on being a parent for
clueless fathers. Jeanette Jenkins, a stalwart mother of six,
grandmother of seven and retired prison guard, fervidly teaches the
convicts that they still have the responsibility, and the power, to
inspire their far-off children along the straight and narrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to hurt when my boy goes back home, and I just may
cry, you know what I'm saying?'' admitted DeWayne Mixon, a hulking
32-year-old convict in his sixth year of a nine-year assault
sentence. His 9-year-old son, Diamond, nudged him as they painted
the record of themselves, together once more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week spoiled me, but it tells me I got to put all the old
nonsense behind me and do the right thing,'' said Mixon, his face a
mask of paternal delight and worry. ``It's time to be a father, you
know what I'm saying?''
</P>
<P>
   The parenting experiment originated with an inmates'-rights
volunteer, Carol Fennelly, who followed 1,300 inmates here when
they were moved three years ago from a condemned prison in Lorton,
Va., a Washington suburb. Now an overnight trip away from their
families, the inmates suffered a severe drop-off in family visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't care about prison inmates; there's not even
a debate any more about rehabilitation,'' said Fennelly, who
settled here and opened Hope House, a one-woman volunteer program
for which she is constantly seeking contributions. ``But people
care about children, so I thought maybe this way society will pay a
little more attention to the problems of prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the pioneering children's programs for convicts at
the women's prison in Bedford Hills, N.Y., Fennelly did some
research and found that criminals behind bars who happened to be
fathers were of no special concern to anyone. She created a
teleconferencing hookup between here and two Washington churches
where fathers could see and talk with their offspring. Then she had
inmates read stories onto cassettes so their voices might soothe
their children back home.
</P>
<P>
   These programs, and the week of children's visits, might have
died as proposals in a typical state-run prison, Fennelly said. The
Northeast center is run by a private company, the Corrections Corp.
of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strong family affection _ what these guys have to live for _
can get lost,'' Brian Gardner, the prison warden, said of the long
distance that discourages many families.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed a lot of her important years,'' Ricky Walker, a
36-year-old father doing seven to 21 years for second-degree
murder, said of his 13-year-old daughter, also named Dominique. ``I
last saw her when she was 9. I remember carrying her around on my
shoulders, and now look: She's a young lady who doesn't disrespect
no one.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominique found the medium-security prison frightening when she
first approached it, but she forged ahead from clanging gate to
steel door, fulfilling her childhood mission. ``I missed him a lot
these years; we were so close before he left,'' she said,
remarking, as other youngsters also did, that the fathers had been
sternly lecturing their children on how to stay out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go back and do the same things I can't expect anyone to
come visit me, not if I forever play the fool,'' said Walker,
finding fresh resolve in his daughter's presence.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Mixon looked up from his painting to beam upon the son
at his side. Lolling and smiling, the two might as well have been
fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderful, first time I've seen Diamond in five years,'' Mixon
said. ``It's taking the frustration out of me. I'm loving him, and
he knows where I'm at and why I'm here. I been telling him
wrongdoing gets you in prison, and don't follow in my footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   But the boy never seemed more than hand-holding distance from
the man. Diamond happily sounded as if he had forgotten nothing
across the lost five years of his father's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have no beard when he left, and he bites his nails
now,'' Diamond said, smiling at his father.
</P>
<P>
   During this day's four-hour visit, the prison carried out its
required head count discreetly, with no lineup to demean the
fathers in front of their children. Their white prison uniforms
were daubed with some of the day's fun when Fennelly gathered the
children to leave. Diamond playfully resisted, even with the
promise of an afternoon swim waiting out in the world of the free.
</P>
<P>
   ``You going back in that cage with me?'' his father gently
growled, grateful for the gesture but surely knowing the answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
