u i BC-COLOMBIA-PASTRANA-NYT     07-01 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-PASTRANA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIAN GETS LIFT FROM U.S., BUT WOES PILE UP AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ He has just received a vote of confidence
from the United States in the form of $1.3 billion in emergency
military aid. But as President Andres Pastrana nears the midpoint
of his term, his standing at home is sinking, and even his
supporters fear that his position will continue to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   Vowing to end decades of guerrilla war, Pastrana took office in
August 1998 with the highest vote total of any candidate in
Colombian history. But he has been steadily hurt by a lack of
progress in peace talks with the Marxist rebels, economic
recession, a crippling feud with Congress and now accusations of
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The result is what Semana, the country's leading news magazine,
has called ``a crisis of governability without precedent.'' A
recent cover showed two rebel leaders with big grins and warned
that ``while the establishment wears itself out in futile clashes,
the country is collapsing and the guerrillas gain ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Congress' approval of an emergency antidrug aid package
this week appears to afford Pastrana only marginal respite. The
plan will do nothing to eliminate the sparring with his own
Congress or the complaints of corruption. Nor will it help to end
the recession, as the bulk of the aid will go to the military, not
into the economy.
</P>
<P>
   For economic relief, Pastrana has been counting on the other
side of what his government calls ``Plan Colombia,'' nearly $2
billion in social aid from European and other donors due to meet
Colombian officials in Madrid, Spain, in coming days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants Pastrana to come home empty-handed, and every
effort will be made to prevent that from happening,'' said a
European diplomat here. ``But there is a feeling that this is a
primarily military plan and that we are being asked to clean up the
mess that the Americans are going to make.''
</P>
<P>
   With few visible signs of progress in ending the war and with
the economy reeling, popular support for the peace effort is now
``precarious,'' Jorge Humberto Botero, head of the country's bank
association, cautioned earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country is sickened by blood,'' he said. ``It is
intimidated and terrorized.''
</P>
<P>
   Botero's warning came after the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia, the main insurgent group, announced a plan to tax all
wealthy Colombians and kidnap those who refuse to pay. Since the
rebels are already taxing businesses and carrying out summary
executions in the sizable demilitarized zone Pastrana handed to
them in late 1998, the new demand has added to the impression they
see themselves as a parallel government.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much longer is our government going to keep treating these
subversive criminals with such deference?'' asked Jose Manuel Tovar
Jimenez, an accountant. ``I'm sick of constantly making concessions
to them and getting nothing in return but new and more outrageous
demands.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana's political problems mounted this spring when he called
for a referendum that would shut down the Congress, widely seen as
corrupt and ineffective, and replace it with a more streamlined and
accountable body. Legislators counterattacked, saying that
Pastrana's own job should also be put to a vote, and the president
was eventually forced to withdraw his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pastrana is in dire straits as a result,'' a diplomat here
said. ``No matter how things turn out, he has poisoned relations
with Congress for the remainder of his term, and is going to have a
hard time getting any legislation passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Charges of corruption in Pastrana's administration have also
emerged, fed by the opposition Liberal Party, whose own image was
tarnished by evidence that drug traffickers contributed to its 1994
presidential campaign. Suspect donations to the Pastrana campaign
from a dredging company seeking government contracts have been the
focal point of the allegations, with key members of Pastrana's
cabinet and staff said to have been involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the certainty that nothing will be found, I'm not going
to slow down to dedicate further time or space to such infamies,''
Pastrana said in a recent speech.
</P>
<P>
   None of the accusations have been proved. But the simple
perception of irregularities has weakened the ``white knight''
image that has been about the only trump card remaining in
Pastrana's deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for him because he seemed sincere, and I am
disappointed at the way things are turning out,'' said Mercedes
Ardila Ochoa, a secretary. ``I wanted a change, and what we are
getting is the same old way of doing things at the time we can
least afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana's declining popularity is also part of a broader
institutional breakdown in Colombian politics. As in neighboring
Venezuela and Peru, the population here is growing increasingly
disgusted with the traditional party system, in which power
alternates between Liberals and Conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people perceive the parties as not representing their
interests,'' said Myles Frechette, who was the U.S. ambassador here
in the late 1990s. ``And they are just not doing what the people
need. They equate the political class with corruption, and they see
a lot of cheap populist talk but nobody really doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, with any progress in fighting either the war or the
recession seemingly a long way off, Pastrana is trying to reverse
his sagging political fortunes by making over his image, which a
diplomat here described as ``slick and cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed casually in a sweater and open-necked shirt and speaking
in an unusually colloquial manner, Pastrana went on television June
21 to urge Colombians to ``adopt a new attitude'' and be more
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of the bad news that does not let us see and
construct a better country for all, the country that we dream about
and need,'' he said. ``I'm tired of pessimism always winning out
over hope, of negativism over the positive, of the bad over the
good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
