u a BC-SC-FLAG-NYT &LR;      07-01 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE FLAG IS LOWERED BUT WAR ISN'T QUITE OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ As its reign atop the South Carolina Statehouse
finally drew to an end Saturday, the Confederate battle flag had
become almost as much a curiosity as an object of division, a
symbol of the state's exhausted recent history even more than of
its distant past.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments over the flag might have grown familiar over its
38-year presence, but they were often riveting, and no issue has
delineated the state's racial chasm more clearly. Many of the
people, black and white, who have streamed by the Capitol over the
last few days before the flag's removal at noon Saturday seemed
wistful not so much for the flag itself but for the emotional
charge it injected into public life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember when it wasn't up there,'' said Dwight Enroe,
a 32-year-old diesel mechanic who drove his family of four down
from Spartanburg for a last glimpse, even though he favors its
removal. ``For a while it seemed like that was all anybody talked
about, that and video poker. What are we going to fight about
now?''
</P>
<P>
   By a strange and resonant coincidence, the other issue that has
obsessed the state for the last decade _ the insistent spread of
video gambling machines _ also came to an end this weekend. Thanks
to a state Supreme Court decision last October, the 34,000 machines
that had noisily overtaken most of the state's gas stations and
convenience stores were illegal as of midnight Friday, the largest
shutdown of a state's gambling industry in a century.
</P>
<P>
   These two issues were related principally by the intensity of
the passions they created among citizens and elected officials, and
by their ability to eclipse any other substantive discussion during
legislative sessions and statewide elections. Partisans on the
various sides grumbled or exulted at the demise of the two
leviathans, but many South Carolinians saw the holiday concurrence
as a signal of relief and renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a momentous weekend,'' said Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr.
of Charleston, who has campaigned prominently against both video
poker and the flag. ``After all these years of paralysis, the
people of South Carolina finally rose up at the grass roots and got
their representatives to respect their wishes. This state really
can control its own destiny, and now we can get to education and
everything else we put aside.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote to remove the Confederate battle flag from the dome and
the Senate and House chambers came in May, after legislators
finally tired of years of pressure from business and religious
leaders, as well as a statewide tourism boycott imposed by the
NAACP. The moral argument against the flag as a banner of slavery
was ultimately unpersuasive; many suburban legislators who had
previously supported the flag as a benign symbol of Southern
heritage said the weariness of their constituents and the damage to
the state's economy finally changed their minds.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision came only after flag supporters insisted on a
compromise: placing a smaller, square version of the flag on a pole
at the main entrance to the Capitol, adjacent to a monument to
Confederate soldiers. The prominence of the new flag, which was to
go up Saturday after the old flag was retired, has infuriated some
black leaders, who said the entire disposition of the flag was
arranged by the state's white leadership. (Actually, most black
senators voted for the compromise, while most black House members
did not.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that the movement to another flagpole was intended
not to resolve the issue, but to continue the reign of the flag,''
said Dwight James, executive director of the state NAACP
Conference, which conducted a silent protest march to the Capitol
Saturday morning. ``They're trying to distract those who have
called for economic sanctions against the state, but it won't
work.'' The boycott has already shown some signs of weakening, but
the organization plans to maintain it as long as the flag flies in
its new location.
</P>
<P>
   The end of video poker was likewise the result of a middle-class
revolt against the enormous size and power of the gambling
industry, which at its peak in 1999 was generating $3 billion in
yearly revenue. Some 3,000 people will lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   A referendum against the machines was on the verge of passage
last year, riding an enormous tide of revulsion generated by
religious and business leaders, when the state's high court beat
the voters to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same group that ultimately came together against
the flag, too,'' said Richard Gergel, a prominent Columbia lawyer
who brought a racketeering lawsuit against the video industry.
``They saw the social cost to the people who were gambling, and the
economic cost to the state. And they finally made the political
system respond.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
