<HEADER>
A0653 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOREA-FUTURE-NYT &LR;      07-01 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE SPEEDY ACCORD, LONG ROAD AHEAD TO KOREAN UNIFICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ While the friendship and reconciliation
that emerged from the Korean summit meeting two weeks ago was
surprising, and sudden, officials here insist that actual
unification is years, if not decades, away and can be achieved only
gradually.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials have paid close attention to Germany's
unification _ in which an economically stronger country swiftly
absorbed its weaker brother _ and have determined, in the words of
Park Jie-won, minister of culture and tourism, ``that it will not
work on the Korean peninsula.''
</P>
<P>
   ``North Korea would never agree to it, and South Korea's economy
would not survive the high costs,'' Park said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   However, if there is another thing to be learned from Germany's
unification, it is that such processes are unpredictable and can
happen faster than almost anybody expects. The leaders of East and
West Germany did not plan to rush their reunification, but as
thousands of East Germans overwhelmed the border, there was no
choice but to merge quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The costs to South Korea in unifying with the North, which is in
dire financial straits, are estimated at between several hundred
billion dollars and a few trillion, depending on the method of
calculation. But all estimates suggest that reunification by
absorption would greatly damage South Korea's rebounding economy
and would pose a far heavier financial burden than the one West
Germany bore from its union with East Germany in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Park, one of the main negotiators behind last month's Korean
summit meeting, said that there would be no quick reconciliation on
the Korean peninsula and that the heavily fortified border dividing
North and South would not suddenly come crashing down. On the
contrary, the minister said, North and South Korea would proceed
very slowly, taking a series of measured steps in the coming months
and perhaps years to break down the ideological and economic
barriers that have divided them for more than a half century.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing military tensions, rebuilding the North's shattered
economy and increasing cultural ties are chief among the measures.
</P>
<P>
   Through these efforts, Park said, Koreans from the North and
South, who have long been socialized to regard each other as
enemies, would begin to view themselves as one people, setting the
stage for a formal union.
</P>
<P>
   But unforeseen events in North Korea could spoil South Korea's
plans for an orderly reconciliation. Little is known about the true
state of affairs in North Korea. There appears to be no meaningful
political opposition to the Stalinist regime of leader Kim Jong Il,
who has kept his deeply impoverished country in a state of physical
and ideological isolation. But selected members of the Communist
elite have been allowed narrow windows on the outside world, and
there is no saying what effect even gradual contact with South
Korea would have.
</P>
<P>
   Park said it was still too early to say exactly what type of
political system a united Korean peninsula could have, and nearly
impossible to set a timetable for reunification. Considering the
political strength of both governments, Park talked of the
possibility of what he called a ``co-federation.''
</P>
<P>
   If relations between the two Koreas advance, some senior
government officials envision a day when Koreans would travel
freely between the two countries, the North's factories, now idle,
would manufacture consumer electronics and other products for South
Korean conglomerates, and Korea would send a unified team to the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials acknowledged that much work lies ahead. They
said they had not anticipated the overwhelming success of the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of the agreement struck between President Kim
Dae-jung of South Korea and the North Korean leader have said that
it is very short on substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``To achieve a peaceful coexistence on the Korean peninsula, we
must link aid and economic development with North Korea's military
and political issues,'' said Kim Young-ho, a professor of political
science at Sungshin Women's University in Seoul. ``And so far Kim
Dae Jung's government has not done that. Just pouring money into
North Korea accomplishes nothing, because Kim Jung Il will readily
accept it and put it to good use.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, South Korean officials said they are well on their way to
realizing one of their first goals: reducing tension on the
peninsula. Already, both North and South have stopped their
propaganda broadcasts in the demilitarized zone and no longer refer
to each another in disparaging terms.
</P>
<P>
   And planning is already under way for a wide variety of cultural
exchanges in sports, the arts, religion, and journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean government is also encouraging South Korean and
foreign companies to form consortiums to develop North Korea's
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   During the summit meeting, officials said, the Korean leaders
discussed using some of the more than 1 million North and South
Korean troops stationed in the demilitarized zone to finish
building the remaining 10 miles of railway that would connect the
entire peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim Jong Il realizes that it's better to use the soldiers for
peaceful purposes rather than having them staring at each other all
day and building up hostilities,'' Park said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
