u i BC-LEBANON-BORDER-NYT &LR;      07-01 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-BORDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEBANON'S REACTION TO ISRAELI INCURSIONS MAY JEOPARDIZE U.N.
DEPLOYMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BORDER POST 34, Lebanon _ The quick deployment of U.N.
peacekeepers and Lebanese forces into the stretch of southern
Lebanon that Israel abandoned in May after 22 years of occupation
has been thrown into doubt with the controversy over a series of
apparent Israeli incursions across a borderline drawn in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   When the U.N. Security Council voted two weeks ago to endorse
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's certification that Israel had indeed
pulled out its troops, opening the way for an additional force of
peacekeepers to fill the security vacuum along the border, Lebanon
protested the findings. But Annan brushed aside Lebanese
objections, saying there were only a couple of border violations by
Israel and they would be cleared up swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   But then there were more transgressions, and U.N. relations with
both Lebanon and Israel became strained. Newspapers in the region
have reported an angry exchange, including curses, between Annan
and Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel, as well as a lengthy,
middle-of-the-night telephone call in which Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright reportedly shouted at President Emile Lahoud of
Lebanon to send his army into the south to replace the Hezbollah
guerrillas who are now the only force of local order.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has sent officers from the peacekeeping force
that has patrolled the south for more than 20 years to survey and
map the border, with orders to report back to New York headquarters
daily.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the surveyors found nine violations by Israel, U.N.
officials said at their headquarters in Naqura.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the violations, they said, were minor. One, for
instance, involved a lone Israeli soldier at an observation post on
a hill a few dozen yards over the nominal line, although the next
day he was joined by two armored personnel carriers.
</P>
<P>
   But the violations have become a political issue, jumped on by
both Lebanon and Israel, and drawing a threat from the leader of
the Hezbollah militia to take unspecified action if the United
Nations does not resolve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Here along a lonely stretch of road through the stony hills
where the border marches sharply north to swing around the Israeli
settlement of Metulla are several problems that have evolved during
the two decades Israel maintained what it called a ``security
zone'' in southern Lebanon with its proxy Lebanese militias and its
own forces.
</P>
<P>
   Border Post 33 _ a cement stake marking a point along the line _
is atop Sheik Abad Hill, a little way south. It had been a South
Lebanese Army and Israeli gun position. BP 34 is in a creek bed
below a cliff where a Lebanese family serves thick coffee in a
makeshift cafe of a truck and awning. BP 35 is on another hill
running north.
</P>
<P>
   Across the creek bed is the Israeli hilltop settlement of
Misgavan. Over the course of the occupation, the Israelis moved
their security fences forward, and the settlement spread over the
old border. Thus, if the original border were followed, the
settlement would be cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   To the north in Addaiseh, the borderline drawn in 1923, which
runs down a hill and then turns alongside the main road would, if
strictly followed, put about 10 Lebanese houses in Israel. Just to
the south, the border runs so close to a road alongside the Israeli
settlement of Manara that it would be impossible to build a
security fence.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the problems of the modern Middle East, this one
dates back to the way the Western powers divided up the defeated
Ottoman Empire after World War I. Two lieutenant colonels, one
French, one British, trudged up and down the hills from the coast
to below Mount Hermon, marking what was to be the border of Syria
and Palestine with piles of whitewashed rocks. Over the years, it
shifted here and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a border on wheels,'' a U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lebanese government, which takes its cues from Syria,
has declared every inch sacred. Israel, for its part, wants to
retain high ground, which in much of the area provides a commanding
position overlooking its north.
</P>
<P>
   Beirut newspapers quoted Lahoud as saying that Annan had
promised him in a telephone call on Tuesday that the Israeli
encroachments would be cleared up by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annan promised me to end the violations in three days and to
send radar systems and helicopters to monitor any future Israeli
violations of Lebanon's airspace or territorial waters,'' Lahoud
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Hezbollah leader, Sheik Hassan Nasrallah, said that ``time
is running out fast for U.N. efforts to get the Israelis totally
out. The resistance cannot wait too long for the border corrections
to come about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
