<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOMMUNICATIONS-POLITICS-ART-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCITEMENT AT THE CONVENTIONS? TRY TELECOM SIDESHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Calif., Mich., Texas, Va.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ When the Republicans gather here this month for
their national convention, to some it might be hard to tell the
difference: is this a political convention or a telecommunications
trade show?
</P>
<P>
   While the main event at the convention here _ and the Democratic
convention to be held in August in Los Angeles _ is, of course,
nominating a presidential candidate, a big corporate sideshow is
being planned as well. And in that effort, no single industry is
better represented than telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are writing seven-figure checks to local civic
host committees. They are spending millions more laying hundreds of
miles of telephone, cable, fiber-optic and high-speed Internet
lines at the conventions. They are handing out hundreds of
telephones, pagers and walkie-talkies to important politicians. And
they are doing this to promote their products to a captive audience
of power brokers _ along with their views on how Washington should
decide a number of issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues facing the industry are huge,'' said Reed Hundt,
former chairman of the Federal Communications Commission. ``Whether
it is Bush or Gore, there will be a whole new crop of decision
makers in government in 2001, and these new people will shape the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   More than most industries, telecommunications companies are
affected by Washington. Since the landmark 1996 Telecommunications
Act deregulated the industry, telecommunications has been
transformed from a stodgy industry to one of the fastest-growing
segments of the economy. Among the issues before the government: A
debate over open access to high-speed Internet networks, the fight
over local telephone companies' entering the $80 billion
long-distance market, the future ability of huge telecommunications
companies to pursue still more acquisitions and the rules governing
which companies can compete for the wireless spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the political conventions give telecommunications
companies a chance to showcase their latest technologies and wares,
in real time and in real life, to lawmakers and journalists. From a
marketing perspective alone, it hardly gets better than this: In
Philadelphia, there will be 30 governors, the congressional
leadership, local elected officials, fellow business leaders and
15,000 national and international journalists _ all chatting on
phones, using computers and transmitting information.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of this dazzling technology is not an option.
Telecom companies have built extensive redundancy and backup to
prevent any embarrassing technological troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every four years, we have the opportunity to showcase our
technological prowess before an important audience,'' said Tony
Cellucci, AT&AMP;T's director for the Republican convention. ``To do
that with such a large captive audience in one location is quite an
engineering feat.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has given more than $1 million to the Philadelphia 2000
host committee and a similar amount to the Los Angeles committee.
AT&AMP;T is also spending $8 million to $10 million to build new
cellular towers at the Philadelphia convention site.
</P>
<P>
   The company will also provide 500 cell phones _ with Republican
Party logos _ to GOP officials.
</P>
<P>
   A front-burner issue for AT&AMP;T is its $58 billion acquisition of
MediaOne Co., just approved by federal regulators, making AT&AMP;T the
nation's largest provider of cable, long-distance and high-speed
Internet access. In coming months, regulators will take actions
affecting how these companies unite.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, telecommunications companies are not the only ones
jumping on the promotional bandwagon. Companies like US Airways,
McDonald's, Microsoft and Pepsico provided the bulk of the $40
million in goods and services raised by Philadelphia's host
committee _ all tax deductible.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, General Motors, as it has for every convention
since 1978, will lend 400 cars _ full-size models and sport utility
vehicles _ to shuttle around the powerful. ``These are
thought-leaders and opinion shakers,'' said Bill Noack, GM
spokesman. ``We turn our vehicles over to them because it's a good
way to expose our products to a diverse and influential audience.''
</P>
<P>
   For telecoms, however, all this is more than mere promotion.
Conventions are a way to make money, too. With so many people
talking on phones and using computer modems, telecom companies plan
to turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's some combination of civic pride and economic
self-interest,'' David Cohen, co-chairman of Philadelphia 2000,
said of the telecom companies. ``We give them a direct opportunity
to make money. That makes it easier for them to be a significant
contributor.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Telecom participation in these conventions comes on top of
campaign contributions the industry has already made to the two
parties _ a total of $16.9 million in contributions to federal
candidates and the two parties in this election cycle, according to
the Center for Responsive Politics, a nonprofit group in
Washington. Two of the biggest corporate players at these
conventions are the biggest soft-dollar donors as well: AT&AMP;T ranks
No. 1 with $2.2 million to both parties, SBC Communications comes
in sixth with $1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Civic pride, too, plays a role since telecom companies tend to
be prominent players on their local scenes. In Philadelphia,
Comcast and Bell Atlantic-Pennsylvania, both with headquarters
here, have given $1 million each to the host committee, and so has
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   In Bell Atlantic's case, the company is spending another $4.5
million to create a telecommunications network at the convention
site that equals that of a small city: 8,000 traditional phone
lines and a variety of transmission and Internet-access lines with
names like DSL, DS-1 and ISDN. An additional $200,000 is going for
promotional materials, including banners around Independence Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exposure of Bell Atlantic to the media has tremendous
value as we become a national and international presence,'' said
Daniel J. Whelan, chief executive of the company. Just last
December, federal regulators allowed Bell Atlantic to sell
long-distance services to its New York customers. Moreover, Whelan
added, Bell Atlantic ``expects to turn a profit'' from
convention-related telephone use.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, host city for the Democrats, the local phone
company is SBC Communications, which is seeking federal approval to
enter the lucrative long-distance market and sell long-distance
calling to 15 million of its Texas customers.
</P>
<P>
   SBC, the parent company of Pacific Bell, is a convention
veteran. It used the 1996 Republican convention in San Diego to
kick off its wireless phones. This time, the word is ``band-width''
_ the new telephone and Internet connections being laid around Los
Angeles' Staples Center, where the convention is being held, to
allow for high-speed data transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fat pipes,'' said Steve Getzug, spokesman for SBC,
referring to the high-speed connections, ``will be a pretty
incredible application. We want to show some amazing gee-whiz
technology to capture the fancy of the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, no company _ telecom or not _ is making a bigger splash
in Philadelphia than Comcast, the nation's third-largest cable
company. Brian Roberts, president of Comcast, is co-chairman of the
Philadelphia 2000 Host Committee. And Comcast owns the First Union
Center in South Philadelphia, where the convention will be held,
and which is being renamed the ``Comcast-Spectacor Center'' for the
duration of event. (Among Comcast's other corporate ventures are
its ownership of QVC, the television-based retailer, the 76ers
basketball team, and the E! Entertainment, Golf and Food cable
channels.)
</P>
<P>
   Comcast has its card full of activities: Its regional cable
network, CN8, will broadcast five hours of live convention
programming daily using the $10 million studio Comcast built at the
convention site for sports games. And it is dedicating 200
employees to this effort, which will be offered free to cable
operators across the country, potentially reaching 68.5 million
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast will be sponsoring a fund-raising reception for 400
people honoring retiring Rep. Thomas Bliley Jr., R-Va., who helped
steer the Telecommunications Act through Congress. The company is
footing the bill for a 100-page media and delegate guide for the
100,000 people expected at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   It will also install Comcast kiosks there to demonstrate its
high-speed Internet service and is thinking about selling political
memorabilia on QVC.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who have to make important decisions, and
they are coming to our house,'' said Roberts, president of Comcast.
``This exposure may enhance our own credibility when we are
explaining new technologies, and it's a unique onetime opportunity
for elected officials to see Comcast. Policy makers can meet us
first and remember our names, our faces and our products. And, for
Philadelphia, it's our Super Bowl, our Olympics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
