<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NOW THERE'S A SOUND TO THE RIVALRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: To be subbed after the game) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ C RA-A-A-CK!
</P>
<P>
   No noise in the major leagues compares to the impact of Mike
Piazza's bat with a thrown baseball. Not McGwire. Not Sosa. Not
Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   The collision carries to the far corners of a crowded ballpark,
and also crashes through the speakers of a television set or a
radio. That impact makes you pick up your head to see where the
ball is heading, the way Piazza's savagely clubbed three-run homer
thudded against the left-field facade Friday night. The wallop
stunned the Braves at the end of an improbable and by now historic
10-run rally in the eighth inning that allowed the New York Mets to
shock the Atlanta Braves, 11-8, at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams would go back at it again Saturday afternoon,
after barely enough time for the concussion to die down, along with
the cheers and the holiday fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Now that resonance is part of the deepening relationship between
two ball clubs, the Mets and the Braves, perhaps just in time for
the geniuses of baseball to realign it out of significance.
</P>
<P>
   Thrown together in the National League's East Division, the Mets
and the Braves have created their own little duel, still lopsided
in favor of Atlanta, but at least starting to take on some depth
and equality.
</P>
<P>
   Rivalries make the games mean something, give them a context.
Otherwise, they are just contests between fine athletes. When the
Giants take on the Washington Redskins on a grim autumnal
afternoon, fans reminisce about how Lawrence Taylor waved urgently
for the medics after breaking Joe Thiesmann's leg at midfield.
There is a history.
</P>
<P>
   When the faded Boston Celtics meet the resurgent Los Angeles
Lakers, there are memories of ancient series in late spring,
Russell and West, McHale and Abdul-Jabbar. There is a history.
</P>
<P>
   When Italy plays France in the finals of the European soccer
championships Sunday in Rotterdam, there will be memories of the 31
times these nations have played, starting in 1910. France has won
the last two World Cup encounters, 2-0, in Mexico City in 1986 and
then the quarterfinals in St. Denis in 1996, on the dreaded penalty
kicks. My wife and I watched in a French cafe in Aix-en-Provence,
and she kicked me under the table to stop me from twitching every
time Roberto Baggio made a move. There is a history.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Mets and the Braves are just getting interesting, but in
fact the two teams go back a ways. The Braves have their roots in a
damp and seedy little nook called Braves Field in the Back Bay
section of Boston, when they used to play the Brooklyn Dodgers and
New York Giants 11 times each, home and away.
</P>
<P>
   After the Braves moved to Milwaukee in 1954 the Mets were
founded from the dregs of other rosters in 1962 and Spahn and Aaron
visited the rusted, rickety Polo Grounds. They were swept in a
doubleheader by the dismal Mets, after which Bobby Bragan, the
manager of the Braves, said he was glad to escape this ``chamber of
horrors'' _ surely a description Bobby Cox might have revived for
Shea on Friday night. The Braves and Mets have had their
differences. On May 4, 1964, in County Stadium (you could look it
up, but I was there), the clubs staged an old-fashioned dust-up at
home plate, after Ed Bailey of the Braves resented a characteristic
hard slide by Ron Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   In the confusion, the Mets' 73-year-old manager wound up
underneath 23-year-old Denis Menke of the Braves, who had this
horrible thought: ``Oh, my God, I've killed Casey Stengel.''
</P>
<P>
   Hah. Fat chance. Writers went out drinking with Casey long after
midnight. The old boy looked a little creaky but totally denied
ever being on the field during the fray. He was still going strong
at last call, as I vaguely remember. There is a history.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets beat the Braves in the 1969 National League
Championship Series. The Mets beat the Braves regularly when they
were good in the '80s. The Braves beat the Mets pretty regularly
since they got good in the '90s. There is a history.
</P>
<P>
   Fans can surely remember how the Braves killed the Mets'
wild-card hopes on the final lost weekend of 1998. They certainly
can recall how the Braves put the Mets into a tailspin last
September, but then how the Mets roared back from a three-game
deficit to throw the fear of Melvin Mora into the Braves before
finally succumbing in the 11th inning of the sixth game.
</P>
<P>
   Counting the playoffs last year, the Mets had won only 9 of 32
games from the Braves in the past two seasons, going into Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good rivalry,'' said Stan Kasten, the president of the
Braves, being gallant. ``The Mets are one of the two or three best
teams in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   There are even latter-day Hunt-Bailey traces in Piazza's being
upended by Brian Jordan in the playoffs last year, but nobody duked
anybody this time around. Then there is the matter of John Rocker,
who took it personally when verbal assassins shouted ugly things at
him from the stands. Rocker's diatribe against New York (actually
against the diversity of America itself) was the reason for the
heightened police presence at Shea this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Braves will take a while to shake the memory of all
those bases on balls, the sizzle of the fuse cord leading to the
terminal explosion of Piazza's brute home run. The history grows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 1408EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
