<SLUG> BC-BOATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERBOATS CHANGE PACE FOR SOME SAILBOAT OWNERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Maine., N.J., Fla., R.I.)   Herb McCormick is the editor of Cruising World magazine. 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to boating, Ken Weg is an equal-opportunity
enthusiast. In the waters by his summer place in Southwest Harbor,
Me., Weg keeps a pair of boats _ one power, one sail _ created
nearby at the legendary Hinckley Co. boat yard.
</P>
<P>
   When the breeze is up, the pharmaceutical executive from
Princeton, N.J., indulges his love of sailing aboard his classic
43-foot Sou'wester, Afterglow. But on calm mornings or when he
feels like a spin through the shallows with his young, twin
granddaughters, Weg opts for the joystick of his 36-foot Picnic
Boat, Promise, a handsome, highly maneuverable powerboat propelled
by water jets that can skim over a mere 18 inches of aqua.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never going to give up sailing,'' Weg said, ``but this is
the first powerboat I've ever had, and it's a nice change of
pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Weg is not the only one embracing what have often been viewed as
diametrically opposed designs: the proverbial stinkpot versus the
blow boat. In the last decade, in what appears to be an
irreversible trend, boat builders whose names have been synonymous
with quality sailing vessels _ from semicustom yards including
Hinckley, Morris, Sabre, Little Harbor and Alden, to more
mainstream-production manufacturers like Freedom and Pacific
Seacraft _ have added a string of interesting, successful
powerboats to their lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love boats, period,'' said Bob Johnson, the president of
Florida's Island Packet Yachts, whose company is fitting out its
first powerboat, a versatile 36-foot cruiser called the 360
Express. ``From a corporate philosophy, it gives us a broader
market base and the potential for more growth.''
</P>
<P>
   With its twin diesel engines and standard propellers, the Island
Packet offering is a different creature from the Hinckley Picnic
Boat, whose jet-drive propulsion system allows it to carve
spray-tossed turns like a water skier and then literally stop on a
dime. But even with a price tag of more than $400,000, the Picnic
Boat has been something of a phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started developing the boat around 1992, we thought we
might eventually sell 50 or 75,'' said Marnie Wright, Hinckley's
marketing director. ``But we've already sold well over 100. We just
hit it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Weg, many Hinckley Picnic Boat owners will continue to
pursue both types of boating. But Paul Petronello, the president of
Rhode Island's Freedom Yachts, focused on his more single-minded
customers when he made the decision to introduce his company's
Legacy line of powerboats.
</P>
<P>
   ``About five years ago we looked at our owner base and realized
that many of them were starting to leave sailing and switching to
power,'' Petronello said. ``And we had no product for them. So we
began to make the transition. It costs 10 times more to find a new
customer than to keep a loyal one and move them through the brand.
We had a couple of sailboat owners interested in changing, so we
used them as our spearhead to make the move.''
</P>
<P>
   An aging demographic of sailors who still wish to be active on
the water but who are no longer as interested in spinning winches
and yanking halyards is sometimes cited as the impetus behind some
yachtsmen's willingness to make the change. But to Bentley Collins,
the marketing manager at Sabre Yachts _ who said his company's
production this year would be an even 50-50 split between sailboats
and Sabreline powerboats _ that observation oversimplifies matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory is that a boater is a boater,'' he said. ``When
their kids are small, it might make sense to have a powerboat. When
they get to have teen-agers, sailing is a great way to enjoy a
family activity where you can also teach responsibility. Over the
years, I see a lot of boaters who go back and forth between sail
and power.''
</P>
<P>
   One boater who switched from sail to power _ but who shows no
clear signs of returning to his roots _ is Bill Parlatore, the
editor of Passage Maker magazine, whose publication caters to the
growing realm of long-range powerboat voyaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been a singlehanded sailor forever, but I went through
what's a typical pattern of evolution for a lot of sailors whose
wives want a more comfortable alternative,'' Parlatore said. ``We
started looking at bigger sailboats and multihulls, and it dawned
on us that what we were after was a motorboat.''
</P>
<P>
   For some sailors, such statements will amount to heresy. But
Weg, who never spent a day afloat he did not like, is not one of
them. ``There's nothing like the sensation of wind in your face
like you get on a sailboat,'' he said. ``But that Picnic Boat will
get you there pretty fast.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
