u s BC-TEN-ZIMBABWE-FAMILY-7     07-01 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ZIMBABWE-FAMILY-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BLACKS ARE DEDICATED TO WIMBLEDON, BUT WORRY ABOUT THEIR
HOMELAND
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ They grew up well below the equator and
still reside in and represent the divided African nation of
Zimbabwe, and yet for the three members of the Black family to play
at Wimbledon is, in many ways, to play at home.
</P>
<P>
   They were raised with four grass courts of their own on the
family's 22-acre avocado farm in the suburbs of Harare, the
Zimbabwean capital. The courts were made slowly one by one, like
statues, by their father, Don Black, who played at Wimbledon in the
1950s and wanted to re-create what he termed his ``own little
Wimbledon'' and nurture future champions in a very unlikely spot.
</P>
<P>
   Don even borrowed and posted the same epigram from Rudyard
Kipling near his courts: ``If you can meet with triumph and
disaster and treat those two impostors just the same.'' At the All
England Club, those words are written above the players' entrance
to Center Court, and Don's dearest _ and rather unlikely _ dream is
that one of his children will some day walk through that entrance
on Wimbledon's final weekend and march back through it with a
singles trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extra comforting to be here,'' said Cara Black, Don's
only daughter.
</P>
<P>
   It is comforting, too, because Cara's two brothers, Byron and
Wayne, together own a pied-a-terre within a long walk of Wimbledon.
Although Wayne lost in the first round and Cara lost in the second
round in singles, Byron advanced to the fourth round on Friday with
a straight-set victory over Spain's Albert Portas, and could go
quite a bit further.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the familiar signs and the reassuring surface, this
has hardly been a comforting season for the Blacks. Their country
has been in the midst of upheaval, with its president of 22 years,
Robert Mugabe, contributing. With Mugabe's approval, hundreds of
white-owned commercial farms, some of them owned by acquaintances
of Don Black's family, have been taken over by armed black
squatters.
</P>
<P>
   There were also reports of electoral intimidation and violence
in the run-up to last weekend's parliamentary election, won by a
narrow margin by Mugabe's ruling party, the Zimbabwe African
National Union-Patriotic Front, over the opposition party, the
Movement for Democratic Change. But the closeness of the election
was still a seminal change in a country that has never had a
legitimate opposition party in its 22-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still a little unclear as what's going to happen to the
land, but I feel like it's been a very closely run election, and I
just hope things calm down,'' Byron said. ``I think at this point
you have to accept the result. There is no going back now. If there
is intimidation, what do you do? I just hope the country can come
back and come together again. It's a bit torn up right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been feeling a bit down the last couple months, obviously
with all this trouble going at home and people that you know
through other people who are getting killed and this is quite a
serious situation. And I know first hand all of my family and
friends are farmers and the troubles they are having: some of this
intimidation and people coming on to their farm and forcing them to
sign over the deeds of their farms, just forcing them to.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's disturbing and has had a real effect on our morale. For
me, maybe just because I'm older and have been around a bit longer
and think a lot more these days. It's really had an effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron, 30, and his siblings have deliberately steered clear of
any political comments in recent months, opting _ as white members
of a society that is overwhelmingly black _ to let the electoral
process run its course. But it has been an emotional, difficult
period, said Cara, a 21-year-old with a promising all-court game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't directly affected our tennis, but always
subconsciously it's in the back of our minds,'' she said. ``It's
been a bit unsure the last couple months and having our parents
back home, every time you pick up the phone and call you have that
hold on you in your heart and you're just like, `I hope everything
is OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   Don and his wife, Velia, who have remained in Zimbabwe, are in
no danger, according to Byron and Cara, and there has been little
violence in urban areas of the country like Harare.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no plans to move whatsoever, no matter what
happens,'' Cara said. ``My dad is so set in his ways there. It's
where they grew up, as well. I don't think anything could move
them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Byron and his wife, Fiona, feel a similarly strong attachment,
but with Fiona expecting their first child in six weeks, she has
come to London to give birth, opting for a more tranquil
environment, although only for the short term.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's been going on at home has been on my mind the whole
time lately,'' Byron said. ``I just feel like I may go home and may
not have a home to go home to. My heart is back home, and I wish I
could be there. I struggle to put it into words. I feel so
patriotic about the country. We've played for our country and feel
so strongly about it and yet we can't do much about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron, 30, and Wayne, 26, the pillars of their country's Davis
Cup team, which nearly beat Andre Agassi and the United States in
the first round in Harare in April, will play for Zimbabwe again
one week after Wimbledon. They are scheduled to be host to Romania
in a World Group qualifying round in the same arena in which they
played the Americans, and though the Romanians and their best
player, Andrei Pavel, have asked for a change of site because of
the political troubles in Zimbabwe, the match has not been moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pavel keeps coming up to me and joking, saying, `I hear we're
playing in Romania,''' Byron said. ``It's a ploy of theirs,
obviously. They are going to use anything to try to change the
venue of the tie. Davis Cup is all about home advantage, and if we
lose that home advantage I'll be very upset.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
