<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HABITAT-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COST-CONSCIOUS YOUTH SAY OUTER BOROUGHS BEAT MANHATTAN FOR
AFFORDABLE SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By TRISH HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Jill Kerr and Chris Ytuarte decided to live
together, they considered moving to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But they never actually got around to looking, because whenever
they would think of people they knew _ people in their early 20s
squashed into small, expensive apartments, say, in the East 90s _
they knew they didn't want to live like that.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a new place together seemed like a good idea, but in the
end, the couple decided to live in the spacious one-bedroom,
$950-a-month apartment Kerr has been renting for two years, on 72nd
Road in Forest Hills, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr and Ytuarte each has a commute to Manhattan of about 25
minutes. Kerr manages the library at an investment firm and is
about to start a job writing reports for institutional clients in
global communications. Ytuarte (pronounced EE-to-it) is a reporter
covering fresh food for the trade publication Supermarket News.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr grew up in Floral Park, in Nassau County, right across the
border from Bellerose, Queens, where Ytuarte was raised. Both still
know a lot of friends living at home with their parents, in large
part because moving out in New York is expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Ytuarte, who worked at a newspaper last summer in New Hampshire,
returned to New York in September feeling he had no choice but to
go out on his own. ``I was sleeping on my dad's futon,'' he said.
He could have lived with his mother, also in Queens, but she, too,
has a one-bedroom apartment. It was a choice of futons, he said,
and ``I wanted a real bed; I wanted to be out on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   He looked for studio apartments through the fall and winter, but
found that he was spending most of his time with Kerr, whom he had
recently starting seeing, years after they had met in their first
year of high school.
</P>
<P>
   They are both 24, and people their age who live in Manhattan,
Kerr said, often seem to live in tiny spaces subsidized by their
parents. ``I don't know why people do it,'' she said. When she
began looking for an apartment, she wanted space, and light, and
air. If that meant forgoing Manhattan, she didn't mind, she said,
although Queens ``is considered out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   They think they're the youngest people in their apartment
building, and they have no friends in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Both said they like it there, though, particularly the charming
Austin Street, which has a Banana Republic, a Benetton and several
good restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Their apartment, in a rent-stabilized building where apartments
that come on the market these days would probably rent for $1,200
or so, has high ceilings, beautiful wood floors and about 900
square feet, which gives them plenty of room.
</P>
<P>
   ``My cousin and her boyfriend lived in a studio in Manhattan,''
Ytuarte said. ``I don't understand how anybody can do that. I can
sit out here, and Jill can be in the bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   They have a pleasing, leafy view. It used to be more sweeping,
encompassing the lake in Flushing Meadow, but in the spring a
10-story apartment building began rising nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great view,'' said Kerr. ``It just had a very open
feel. That's one of the best things about Queens, that you don't
feel claustrophobic.''
</P>
<P>
   They're upset by the change, but not so seriously that they want
to move. Besides, Ytuarte said, he can still see Shea Stadium,
where he goes 15 or 20 times every summer, for Mets games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have the view I care about,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
