<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-01 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Some, Coattails Are Less Helpful
</P>
<P>
   Richard Vinroot, the Republican nominee in this year's
governor's race in North Carolina, seldom misses an opportunity to
link his candidacy to that of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. Bush is
running ahead of Vice President Al Gore in most Tarheel State
presidential preference polls, and Vinroot, a former mayor of
Charlotte, knows a coattail when he sees it.
</P>
<P>
   In polls, Vinroot is running behind his Democratic opponent,
state Attorney General Mike Easley.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Bush goes, so go we,'' Vinroot likes to say. And where Bush
goes when he shows up in North Carolina, Vinroot tries to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Easley has a different take on coattails. What he knows is this:
While Democrats may be dominant generally in North Carolina, only
one Democratic presidential candidate has managed to carry the
state in the last eight elections _ Jimmy Carter in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   What to do, then, when Al Gore shows up?
</P>
<P>
   It happened the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Gore flew in to give a morning commencement speech at Tarboro
High School, a few miles from Easley's hometown, Rocky Mount.
Easley did not show.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, Gore appeared in Raleigh at North Carolina State
University, a jog down the road from Easley's office.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Easley did not show.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly ...
</P>
<P>
   He did show, but not until the speech was over and the crowd had
drifted off. Then the men had a talk.
</P>
<P>
   Easley says he is a good Democrat. There is no serious dispute
about that in his party. The thing to keep in mind, he says, is
that some races ``take on a life of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far in his travels about the country, Gore has not run into
many races like that.
</P>
<P>
   A Losing Candidate Helps the Other Side
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago in Arkansas, state Sen. Mike Ross defeated
Dewayne Graham, a former television reporter, in a race for the
Democratic nomination in the 4th Congressional District. So when
might the party expect Graham to fall in line and endorse Ross,
considered by state and national Democratic leaders to be the best
hope to oust the four-term Republican incumbent, Rep. Jay Dickey?
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   The party leaders were so taken with Ross and the help he might
give them in recapturing control of the House of Representatives
that they took the unusual step of choosing sides and endorsing him
before the primary vote. Graham was left fuming.
</P>
<P>
   And last Wednesday he went for revenge.
</P>
<P>
   He endorsed Dickey, saying somewhat enigmatically, ``He's one of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who once was a Republican and whose loss to Ross left
him $50,000 in debt, also said he might end up doing some campaign
consulting for Dickey _ on a contract basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be available,'' he said. But he insisted there was no
quid pro quo with Dickey.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats did not let that one pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have someone in effect who's broke and looking for a
job,'' said Vaughn McQuary, the state Democratic chairman. ``People
have to weigh how sincere his support for Jay Dickey is as opposed
to paying off his debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Making a Point in Cold Cash
</P>
<P>
   Ed Bernstein had a point to make.
</P>
<P>
   The price of prescription drugs had become an issue in the U.S.
Senate race in Nevada, as in many congressional races elsewhere.
Bernstein, the probable Democratic nominee, wanted to drive home
his assertion that former Rep. John Ensign, the Republican nominee
and the leader in the polls, was beholden to drug companies because
over the years he had accepted almost $100,000 in campaign cash
from them.
</P>
<P>
   So last Thursday in Las Vegas, when 20 elderly people came to
hear Bernstein commiserate about the price of pills and shots, he
opened up the dialogue by dumping $100,000 on the table. In cold,
hard cash.
</P>
<P>
   Ensign's acceptance of $100,000 in drug company money, Bernstein
declared, ``stands against working families, against seniors,
against Americans getting affordable prescription drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not stand on the side of the drug companies,'' he
added. ``I'll stand on the side of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Bernstein, who readily acknowledged that he had withdrawn
the money from his bank only a few hours earlier and would
forthwith return it, make his point?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he's for real,'' said Trish Barrios, who was in the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Ensign accused Bernstein of using ``a bad political stunt'' to
launch ``an ugly personal attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Bernstein, a trial lawyer, ever accept any campaign money
from special interests, such as trial lawyers?
</P>
<P>
   There is ``good'' special interest money and ``bad'' special
interest money, he replied, arguing that lawyers seek only to help,
whereas drug companies seek only to gouge.
</P>
<P>
   Bush Still Ahead, New Polls Show
</P>
<P>
   The Hotline, the popular Internet political tip sheet, keeps a
running tab of presidential preference polls in various states as
they become available. Last week, six new polls were added. Here is
how things stood over all when everything had been toted up:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush led in 24 states, worth 263 electoral votes.
Vice President Al Gore led in nine states, worth 157 electoral
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Needed to win: 270 electoral votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
