<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESBYTERIAN-LEADER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESBYTERIAN LEADER'S RENEWED FOCUS: RECONCILING DIFFERENCES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., Ill.)   (Eds.: See also PRESBYTERIANS-GAY-UNIONS)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ If an anniversary offers a convenient way
by which a person can measure life's progress, then June 24 was a
remarkable date for the Rev. Syngman Rhee. On that day, he was
elected moderator of the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.), the highest
office in the nation's largest Presbyterian denomination.
</P>
<P>
   The election occurred exactly half a century after Rhee had been
violently uprooted from his childhood home. ``Fifty years ago on
this very day, the Korean War broke out,'' he said, ``and I became
a refugee fleeing North Korea to the south. I was 19.'' He fled
with a younger brother, leaving his parents, an older brother and
four sisters, about whom he would hear nothing for 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   A well-known figure in ecumenical circles, Rhee (who is not
related to the former South Korean president of the same name) is
the first Asian-American to hold the moderator's job in the 211
years that American Presbyterians have maintained the office, the
occupant of which serves a one-year term. He says he is excited
that he was elected in the same month that the leaders of North and
South Korea held their first summit, offering hope for
reconciliation between the two nations. That is a goal for which
Rhee has worked, as an official within the Presbyterian Church and,
in the early 1990s, as president of the National Council of
Churches, which represents 35 Protestant and Eastern Orthodox
churches.
</P>
<P>
   Rhee will soon embark on 12 months of nearly nonstop travel,
meeting and preaching among the denomination's churches and
seminaries. As moderator, he will have a national platform from
which to expound a message of reconciliation, not only for Korea
but also for the church, which has suffered a serious internal
rift, primarily over how its members should respond to gay men and
lesbians within their congregations. Three years ago, Presbyterians
amended their constitution to forbid ordination of noncelibate gays
as ministers, elders and deacons _ a decision that remains bitterly
opposed by a substantial minority within the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, reconciliation is like building a bridge,'' Rhee said
in an interview in a hotel here, across the street from the
convention center where the Presbyterians' General Assembly, the
policy-making body that elected him, was having its annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But trying to bring together opposing sides can be very
difficult, even personally painful. In describing his experiences
as an advocate of reconciliation between the Koreas, Rhee said, ``I
was called all kinds of names _ pro-Communist, North Korean
sympathizer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhee, married and the father of three children, came to the
United States in 1956 and was ordained a minister four years later.
He received a master's from Yale Divinity School and a doctorate
from Chicago Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   Until a merger in 1983, Presbyterians were divided into Northern
and Southern churches, the legacy of a split in the Civil War. In
the 1970s, Rhee worked for the Northern church, in a department
that dealt with Christians in the Middle East. In his travels, he
found that North and South Korea maintained embassies in the same
nations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, at a friend's urging, he decided to contact the North
Korean Embassy in Egypt to try to obtain information about members
of his family who had remained in Pyongyang, the North Korean
capital, at the war's outbreak. Rhee learned that his father _ a
Presbyterian minister who was imprisoned and died in the war _ had
been friendly with a man who later became a very high official in
the Communist government. Within days of the meeting, Rhee said, he
received an invitation from his father's former friend for a
private visit to North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   He hesitated, he said, out of concern that if word of the trip
got out, it could endanger his younger brother, a businessman in
South Korea, where the government was hostile to the North. But
after much prayer, he decided to go. ``Life depends on God, and God
must have a purpose in providing this unexpected opportunity,''
Rhee said.
</P>
<P>
   In Pyongyang, he was reunited with his sisters. He learned his
mother had died eight years earlier and his older brother had been
killed in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on his theme of reconciliation, Rhee said that as a
young minister involved in the civil rights movement, he had
learned from the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. that in a
situation in which people are oppressed, they ultimately have the
initiative, rather than the oppressor. King told him, he said, that
the oppressed have a choice: to seek revenge for their hurts or to
forgive and seek a new relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Forgiveness is fundamental to Christianity, Rhee said. ``Anyone
who is in Christ is a new creation,'' he said. ``We should not be
enslaved by the past, if we are looking for the possibility of a
new day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
