<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE FIGHT FOR CLEAN ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, July 2:
</P>
<P>
   Now that Congress has passed the first campaign finance reform
in 21 years, Washington is filled with an air of
self-congratulation. That is understandable. But the best way to
celebrate is for principled lawmakers to press for broader
disclosure requirements and a ban on ``soft money'' to political
parties this year. The bill approved last week would force certain
tax-exempt slush funds that run campaign ads to reveal their
spending and financing sources. By the time it was approved, many
opponents had jumped on board and were actually trying to claim
credit for its passage. Their belated eagerness to get right on
this issue should now be exploited to make more progress on purging
American campaigns of special-interest money.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation restricting secret fund-raising was a
significant step forward, but its impact should not be exaggerated.
Some of the shadowy tax-exempt groups affected by the bill are now
expected to transform themselves into for-profit shell corporations
and continue their practices. Other nonprofit groups may also run
ads. It is still legal for groups without tax exemptions to raise
money and run sham campaign ads like the ones attacking Sen. John
McCain that were organized by donors to Gov. George W. Bush last
March.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to clean up the system is embodied in the
McCain-Feingold bill, which has been blocked by Trent Lott, the
Republican Senate leader. It would outlaw soft money to political
parties and prevent the use of corporate and union money for sham
issue ads close to an election. Individuals financing such ads
would be subject to disclosure requirements. Most senators support
this approach, but not enough for the 60 votes needed to break the
usual filibusterengineered by Lott and his fund-raiser in chief,
Mitch McConnell.
</P>
<P>
   Once Lott dropped his opposition to the disclosure bill last
week, it sailed through the Senate by a vote of 92-6. But earlier,
when Lott was pressing Republicans to oppose it, eight Republicans
not normally in favor of campaign reform voted for it. All are
running for re-election this year, some in tough races, suggesting
their sensitivity to voters on the issue. They should not now be
allowed to go home and claim they are for clean campaigns unless
they line up for more effective legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the holiday weekend, voters encountering Sens. William Roth
of Delaware, Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania and Spencer Abraham of
Michigan can make this point.
</P>
<P>
   As for the constitutional arguments on reform, a darkly comic
moment in the Senate last week should long be remembered for the
way it revealed the hypocrisy involved. McConnell, a self-described
expert on the Constitution, lectured his colleagues on the
purported violations of the document in the slush-fund disclosure
bill. Then, defying his own logic, he urged Republicans in tough
re-election fights to vote for a bill he had just declared
unconstitutional so they could avoid being tarred as anti-reform.
Clearly, McConnell will say anything to hold onto power and also
preserve the right of big money to buy influence in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The other important lesson last week lay in the shattering of
conventional wisdom. As usual, the politicians and Sunday talk-show
pundits had assured one another that the disclosure bill had no
chance this year. When will these so-called ``experts'' realize
what a disservice they do by parroting the cynical spin control of
those who live off the corrupt status quo? Again and again,
Americans are lectured by these people that campaign reform is not
a salient issue, even though McCain ignited the voters with it
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Americans do care about campaign reform. Their desire for
financially clean campaigns is one reason for the widespread
cynicism among voters in recent years. If lawmakers want to push
some of that cynicism back, they have only to listen to the people
who sent them to office in the first place. Then we will see even
more retreating by Lott and McConnell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
