u f BC-MASS-RENTS-REAL-690(2     07-01 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-RENTS-REAL-690(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOSTON AREA ADJUSTS TO RENT DEREGULATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Five years after Massachusetts voters ended rent
regulation _ or, more precisely, ended it in Boston, Brookline and
Cambridge, the three cities that still had some form of rent
control _ rents have taken sizable jumps, the cities are spiffier
and less pockmarked by deteriorating neighborhoods and many poorer
people have been forced to move to communities farther from the
urban core.
</P>
<P>
   While no overall study of the effects of the end of controls on
rents has been made, a survey by a leading landlord in Cambridge
found that rents for his company's formerly controlled apartments
had doubled.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy of the Boston area booming, landlord and tenant
advocates, politicians and academics who study housing all agree
that the degree to which rent deregulation itself produced those
effects is impossible to determine. Yet, for good or ill, they all
see deregulation as a factor in the changing faces of the three
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we enjoy an especially strong rental market,'' said
Edwin J. Shanahan, the executive director of the Greater Boston
Real Estate Board. ``Demand continues to outpace supply.'' That is
caused by several factors, Shanahan said, ``not the least of which
was the 25 years when we had rent control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Over those decades nobody would come into Boston, Brookline or
Cambridge to build rental housing,'' he said. ``So we essentially
ended up with 25 years of no measurable increase in supply.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of rent regulation, Shanahan said, ``we've seen
substantial rehabilitation of our housing stock in those three
communities, and a tremendous increase in the number of developers
looking to develop'' _ although so far there has been a lot more
interest than actual development, he conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Dreier, Boston's housing director from 1984 to 1992
and now a professor of public policy at Occidental College in Los
Angeles, is not so sanguine. ``What Boston shows is that a rising
tide does not lift all boats,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor and working-class families are squeezed,'' Dreier said.
``If you're a waiter, a chambermaid, even a schoolteacher or a
nurse, you have to pay half your income or more to put a roof over
your head. And if you're really poor, you're going to be doubling
and tripling up.''
</P>
<P>
   Or moving out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Dian Weaver, 31, a divorced mother of three, used to live in a
six-unit building in a poorer section of Cambridge. She was paying
$300 a month when rent control ended in 1995. By 1998, the rent was
$600, and she had to move.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver, who refuses to go on welfare, kept her jobs at two
restaurants in Cambridge, earning about $500 a week. She moved to
Attleboro, Mass., and now commutes to work by train, an hour each
way. The rent for her old apartment, ``last I heard,'' she said:
``$850.''
</P>
<P>
   In a referendum on Nov. 8, 1994, residents of Massachusetts _
though lacking a majority in each of the three affected cities _
ended rent regulation by a vote of 1,034,594 to 980,723, or 51 to
49 percent. The referendum had been spurred, particularly, by a
coalition of small-property owners in Cambridge, which had the most
stringent form of rent control covering most of the apartments in a
city dominated by renters. The impact of rent regulation in Boston
and Brookline had been muted in recent years by vacancy decontrol.
In all, about 100,000 units were decontrolled on Jan. 1, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   No comprehensive study of the effects of deregulation in the
three cities has since been conducted. But in Boston, according to
Elizabeth Sullivan, a spokeswoman for Mayor Thomas Menino, the
average rent for two-bedroom apartments hit $1,550 in 1999, up 75.1
percent from $882 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best available barometer is a study by Alex
Steinbergh, a principal of Resource Capital Group, a large landlord
in Cambridge, which used as a sample the 242 deregulated units in
the 15 buildings the company owns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sample showed that as of November 1999, the average rent
for all of the previously rent-controlled units essentially
doubled, from $510 to $1,016,'' Steinbergh said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The survey also showed that 89 of the 242 formerly
rent-controlled units, or 37 percent, had the same tenant as in
January 1995. ``Now the rents of those tenants, on average, went up
from $577 to $967,'' Steinbergh said, a 68 percent increase. ``So
those tenants' rents weren't going up as much as new tenants'.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Steinbergh's apartments were already on the open market
at the time of deregulation, ``and the average increase on those
market-rate units was 31 percent, from $1,025 to $1,343,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent meandering drive through Cambridge, Steinbergh
pointed out that, ``if you pick streets at random, you'll find
rehab work on virtually every one.'' And, indeed, like rainbow
sprinkles on a sundae, bright pastel shingles in an array of shades
adorned the sides of grand old buildings _ many with turret-like
bay windows and stately porticos _ on block after block.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exteriors have been fixed up, and inside there are new
heating systems, electrical, plumbing,'' Steinbergh said. ``We
think about a third of the 15,000 formerly controlled units have
done some rehab.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar patterns of housing rehabilitation were evident in
Boston. And while Menino was proud of the facelifting and economic
rejuvenation of many neighborhoods, he was unequivocal in his
assessment of rent deregulation: ``A disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the City address on Jan. 11, the mayor declared
affordable housing one of his highest priorities. ``We have an
obligation to make sure that prosperity doesn't price people out,''
he said. ``A stable economy needs workers at every level. And a
stable city needs a variety of housing for a variety of incomes.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Menino said: ``We're losing the middle class. I
know a situation in South Boston where this young couple has gone
up in the last year over $600 a month in rent. And there's no way
to combat that; they are at the mercy of the landlord. The affluent
are moving to our city in record numbers. But our homeless family
numbers have gone up 10 percent over the last year.'' The city's
vacancy rate is 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Menino said, ``is that there aren't any rental
housing proposals out there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rent control came off and the housing industry said they will
help us build new housing,'' the mayor said. ``Well, it's five
years later and I'm still waiting for the industry to come forward
with new housing proposals; any kind, but affordable housing for
the most part.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Million-dollar luxury homes; there are some of those being
built in our city,'' the mayor continued, ``obviously not for the
working person.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan of the real estate board said that the lack of
development of affordable housing ``essentially has to do with the
inordinate delays one encounters in trying to work through the maze
of permits and approvals that are required in a city as old as
Boston and with as much neighborhood activism as Boston enjoys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly,'' he said, ``when you are looking at a 2{-year
process to find out whether you are even going to be able to play,
the game requires a significant amount of capital to be put at
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   To which the mayor responded: ``I don't believe that. If you
come up with a good proposal for rental housing in our city, we
will expedite it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
