<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-LIBRARY-FELLOWS-2T     07-01 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LIBRARY-FELLOWS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GIFT OF CONTEMPLATIVE DAYS FOR LIBRARY CENTER'S FELLOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LYNDA RICHARDSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a year hidden away at the New York Public
Library, Paul Berman, a journalist and cultural critic, was finally
ready to meet his public, with an impressionistic lecture that
touched on religion, sex and Spanish imperialism.
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong talk by Berman, one of the first 15 fellows at the
library's new Center for Scholars and Writers, focused on two Latin
American poets, Sor Juana Ines de la Cruz and Ruben Dario. He
recited long quotations of poetry in Spanish, sometimes
passionately, then offered his own English translations. He did not
use notes. It was almost like performance art.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, no one in the small audience asked any
questions. At earlier lectures by library fellows _ one about the
letters of Arturo Toscanini, the Italian conductor, another about
the children's books of William Godwin, an anarchist political
philosopher _ there had been excited chatter and raised hands.
</P>
<P>
   Berman, 50, the author of ``A Tale of Two Utopias: The Political
Journey of the Generation of 1968,'' could not explain the
reaction, just his lecture. ``It was presented as a work of art,''
he said. ``It was presented as an adventure in poetry. It was not a
polemic. People were puzzled. What can I say?''
</P>
<P>
   The awkward moment was an extreme example of the difficulties
faced by the library's new center as it tries to find a public
face. In a somewhat utopian effort to create an intellectual
community, 15 fellows were thrown together in a renovated suite of
offices on the northeastern corner of the landmark Humanities and
Social Sciences Library at 42nd Street and Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The one-year residency, one of the more generously endowed
humanities fellowships in the country, comes with a stipend of
$50,000 and a housing allowance for out-of-towners. The fellows
included novelists, historians, journalists, university-based
scholars, a doctor and a musician.
</P>
<P>
   The public had only a few opportunities to learn what the
library fellows were up to. Aside from the series of five free
lectures, including Berman's in early May, the fellows mostly kept
to themselves, though early on they did ask one another, how would
the center make use of its prominent address? What would be its
public face?
</P>
<P>
   Other humanities institutes have faced the same question. ``It's
a paradox,'' said Jocelyn Carlson Baltzell, former associate
director of the New York Institute for the Humanities, a sort of
lunch club for intellectuals in Greenwich Village, and now the
associate director of the Los Angeles Institute for the Humanities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's mixing two irreconcilable aspects of intellectual
life,'' she said. ``In medieval terms, there is a life of action
and a life of contemplation, two separate lives. How could you
possibly blend them? You get a hybrid.''
</P>
<P>
   The library fellows devoted their days to contemplating, reading
and writing in glass- and oak-paneled offices equipped with
computers and louvered hardwood blinds that snapped shut for
privacy. They shared a communal telephone and met over a buffet
lunch in the lecture room every day. Offerings from the library's
vast collections were delivered at least twice daily on a rolling
cart.
</P>
<P>
   The time seemed to melt away. On the last official day of the
program on May 26, they swapped practical advice on how to download
documents onto computer disks. They packed their books and boxes
and traded e-mail addresses. One of the more important memos
circulating was a list of the best pastry and coffee shops in
Vienna, compiled by Christian Fleck, a sociologist from Austria.
Some leftover Champagne materialized at lunch. There was a tinge of
sadness.
</P>
<P>
   Francine Prose, a novelist who is writing a book on the lives of
women known principally for having been muses to well-known
artists, said the intellectual dividends of the program will become
apparent from work produced by the fellows. ``For me, the great
beauty of it was the ability to do my work,'' she said. ``Sure,
it's nice if all that other stuff happens. But every moment I got
to be in my office working is a real blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   D. Graham Burnett, a historian, found that having the time to
read in solitude was precious indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of scholarship is really reading,'' said Burnett,
who had a futon delivered to his office because he does not read
well sitting up.
</P>
<P>
   The center's leading donors, Dorothy Cullman, and her husband,
Lewis B. Cullman, insisted that writers be included in the mixture
of fellows to spice things up. They gave $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve fellows were named by an anonymous selection committee
after a rigorous application process. Three were chosen by the
center's director, Peter Gay, the Yale historian. The applicants
had to demonstrate that their work would benefit directly from
access to the library's collections.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the first class of fellows last year, the
library's president, Paul LeClerc, had said that he envisioned the
center ``as becoming a great intellectual spark plug in the life of
New York.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, LeClerc said that he would not abandon
the spark plug metaphor. ``A certain amount of sparks happened this
year, and we'll see more in the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was shared by Gay, 77, the author of more than 20
books on subjects including the Enlightenment, Sigmund Freud and
bourgeois culture. ``We'd like New York to notice that we're here,
but they will,'' he said. ``I'm very optimistic about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some similar programs are more ambitious in their public
outreach, like the National Humanities Center in Research Triangle
Park, North Carolina, which holds monthly lectures, concerts,
exhibitions and an occasional large public conference. But the
library fellowship's low profile is not a surprise to some in the
intellectual world. Stanley N. Katz, president emeritus of the
American Council of Learned Societies, said LeClerc and Gay were
``traditional and cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a fellowship program faces a delicate balancing act
when it tries to engage the public, Katz said, because fellows
``will only come to this sort of thing if they will have time
primarily to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   And Baltzell said she believes such centers are elitist by their
nature. ``The idea of evangelical intellectuals is an oxymoron,''
she said. ``To go out with a missionary purpose is antithetical to
the contemplative life.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the library's 15 fellows, Andrew Delbanco, a Columbia
University professor, said he expects the center's relationship
with the public to evolve. ``In its first few months, it's finding
its way,'' he said. ``I would like to see the engagement of the
center with the larger life of the city deepened and developed for
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in private, the library fellows found that their best
intentions sometimes fell short. Earlier this year, two of them,
Anthony Holden, a British journalist and biographer, and Dr. Howard
Markel, a pediatrician and medical historian, started weekly
discussions of Dickens' ``Bleak House'' with three other fellows.
(Holden is researching a book on Leigh Hunt, the English poet,
critic and essayist, who is caricatured in the novel, and Markel
has written five scholarly papers on Dickens and medicine.)
</P>
<P>
   Another fellow, Pamela Clemit, a specialist in British Romantic
literature, had taught the novel at the University of Durham in
England. But she said she was told only belatedly about the
discussions. By then, the discussions had collapsed because of
conflicting schedules.
</P>
<P>
   The fellows often exchanged ideas over lunch. At one informal
lunch talk, Sven Beckert, a history professor at Harvard, told the
other fellows that he had decided to write a book about cotton to
get at issues of global business.
</P>
<P>
   The hands of fellows shot up. Ada Louise Huxtable, the
architectural historian and critic, offered that labor relations in
the early mill villages were coercive, that workers were virtually
indentured servants. Kathleen Neal Cleaver, a professor who was the
first woman on the Black Panthers' central committee and the former
wife of Eldridge Cleaver, noted that land was available for cotton
farming only because the Army had cleared it of Indians. The
pediatrician made a point about cotton and disease. One of the
novelists suggested a narrative about how a bale of cotton came to
be distributed. The Latin America specialist suggested a comparison
with coffee. Delbanco wondered whether coercion was too broad a
term to encompass both factory wage labor and slave labor.
</P>
<P>
   Gay, wondered about the role of the state, observing, ``It's
more complicated than you make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckert nodded politely. Later, he said: ``That was the great
thing about the center. It brought people from very different
perspectives together.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the departing fellows had no complaints. After all,
the program had given them handsome stipends and nice offices for a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver, for one, said she felt part of a special group because
it was the first, and she said that the group could be quite
different five years from now.
</P>
<P>
   But she could not help noting that in its first year, it was not
particularly diverse, either by gender or race. ``How could it not
strike you?'' she said. ``This is New York City. It is a raucously
diverse city, and that's not the way you would describe the
collection of scholars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 1505EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
