<HEADER>
A0723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TEACHING-FELLOWS-2     07-01 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHING-FELLOWS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADS COURT BRIGHT, BORED PROFESSIONALS TO TEACH IN TROUBLED NYC
SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The advertisements, in stark black and white, began
appearing in newspapers and on Web sites in June. ``Four out of
five fourth graders in our city's most challenged schools fail to
meet state standards in reading and writing,'' they said. ``Are you
willing to do something about it?''
</P>
<P>
   With that blunt appeal, Schools Chancellor Harold Levy hopes to
persuade dozens of New Yorkers to drop whatever jobs they are doing
and teach in New York City's most troubled schools this fall. All
college graduates with at least 3.0 grade point averages can apply,
no matter how sparse their teaching experience and credentials.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Levy will choose 250 of the applicants _ who so far
include bankers, lawyers, social workers, a speech writer, an
acupuncturist, a zoo keeper and a judge _ to join a new program
called New York City Teaching Fellows. The new teachers will work
in failing schools starting this fall, earning the starting salary
of $31,910, and the city will pay for them to get master's degrees
and will provide other support.
</P>
<P>
   Though the program is similar to Teach for America, the national
organization that places recent college graduates in urban schools,
it is aimed at slightly older people who have been working for at
least several years. Most of the applicants have already tried at
least one career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aiming for people who may have decided the job they are
doing is not spiritually satisfying,'' Levy said. ``We are drawing
in some extraordinarily gifted applicants, and it will be a great
challenge to see whether we can keep them in the system and get
their enthusiasm to be infectious.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 400 people have applied so far, a number that board
officials say is promising considering that they began publicizing
the program only two weeks ago. The board is hoping to select the
250 fellows by the end of July and to put them through a rigorous
one-month training session (board officials call it ``boot camp'')
in August.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate goal is to help the city meet a new state
requirement that only certified teachers work in failing schools,
known as ``schools under registration review.'' Last year, New York
City violated the requirement by hiring nearly 600 uncertified
teachers to work in its 99 failing schools when it could not find
enough certified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the teaching fellows would be uncertified at first,
they would complete the required course work at the City University
of New York over the next two years, a plan that Levy hopes will be
acceptable to the state Board of Regents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The program is also a test of sorts for a larger effort to
recruit people from other fields to teach in all 1,100 city
schools. The regents are to vote in August on whether to allow such
programs in school districts statewide.
</P>
<P>
   If the teaching fellows program works, it might be the model for
a permanent ``alternate route'' program for New York City teachers.
But the board is also considering other possibilities, like
training prospective teachers itself instead of having them take
courses at City University.
</P>
<P>
   Levy said in an interview that he wanted to lure teachers from
other professions mostly because the state's education schools were
not turning out nearly enough teachers to meet the city's needs.
This year alone, the Board of Education hired 9,000 new teachers,
60 percent of whom were uncertified.
</P>
<P>
   But Levy also said he believed that ambitious, talented people
from other fields could be an asset to the school system and bring
fresh ideas. ``The challenge,'' he said, ``will be getting our act
together enough to support these people once they're in the system
instead of leaving them out in the cold.''
</P>
<P>
   The board plans to spend about $4 million on the program in the
coming school year, most of which will cover the cost of graduate
courses for the new teachers. The board has also hired the New
Teacher Project, a consulting group affiliated with Teach for
America, to help advertise the program, select the fellows and give
them adequate support during the school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These folks know how to bring in talented people, how to keep
them enthusiastic, how to train them to do a good job in the
classroom,'' Levy said. ``We need their help because, with the best
intentions, the system currently does every conceivable thing to
make it difficult for them to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the 99 failing schools where the teaching fellows will
be working _ mostly in Brooklyn and the Bronx _ have the highest
teacher turnover rates in the city. Young, inexperienced teachers
are the most likely to leave, frustrated by the lack of resources
and guidance, the intense pressure to improve student performance
and the daunting array of problems that their students bring to
school.
</P>
<P>
   Levy said the teaching fellows' situation would be different
because they would have constant support. Taking a cue from Teach
for America, the program will provide each teaching fellow with a
mentor _ possibly a senior teacher, although such arrangements have
had only limited success in the past. Teachers from City University
will periodically observe each fellow on the job. And all 250
fellows will meet every few months to discuss their experiences and
offer advice.
</P>
<P>
   The New Teacher Project was responsible for the eye-catching
advertisements for the Teaching Fellows program and made sure they
appeared in places where young professionals were likely to see
them: in The New York Times and The Village Voice, for example, and
in Time Out, the weekly entertainment magazine. In the coming
weeks, the ads will also appear on popular Web sites like
Citysearch.com and Zagat.com. In addition, the New Teacher Project
is sending mass e-mail messages to college alumni organizations and
volunteer groups.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At an informational session on Wednesday night, about 150
would-be teachers, most in their 20s and 30s, packed into a
conference room at McKinsey &AMP; Co., a consulting firm on East 53rd
Street that donated space for the event. Were the neighborhoods
where they would be teaching safe, they wanted to know. Would their
classrooms have computers? Would applicants who attended New York
City schools have an advantage?
</P>
<P>
   Robbyn Hasberry, a corporate recruiter, said she had recently
realized that the business world ``is not my calling.'' Hasberry,
who is black and majored in education at the State University of
New York at Stony Brook, said part of the reason she wanted to
teach in New York City was to help make the the city's teaching
force more racially diverse.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman, who spoke on the condition of anonymity because
she did not want her employer, a financial services company, to
know that she was applying to the program, said she was earning a
lot of money _ about three times the $31,900 starting salary for
city teachers _ but that her job was unfulfilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to an office every day and do these projects and they
all start to blur,'' said the woman, who is 35 and lives in
Greenwich Village. ``And you start looking for something with more
value. I saw the ad and it answered the question, `What can I do to
make the world a better place?' I would be completely remiss to not
at least check it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Several people conceded that they did not know whether they
could get by in the city on a teacher's salary, and that it might
prevent them from joining the program. But Levy _ who until
recently made more than $500,000 a year as a corporate lawyer and
now makes $245,000 as chancellor _ said he believed that the lower
pay would not be a major deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more people want a sense of satisfaction that what
they are doing is important to the larger social order,'' he said.
``This is an opportunity for people with dedication and social
conscience and drive to make good on their altruistic impulses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
