</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-HOOLIGANS-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE GERMANS KEPT THEIR TROUBLES AT HOME DURING EURO 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN MAIMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ While mourning their country's early exit from the
European championships on June 20, Germans also had reason to heave
a sigh of relief. It was a victory of sorts that the poor play of
the German team and not the rowdy behavior of German hooligans had
been the dominant topic of conversation during the first round of
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that our team did not perform well at Euro 2000,''
said Rainer Lingenthal, spokesman for the German Interior Ministry.
``But off the field, our security measures to keep hooligans away
from the tournament proved very effective.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a sign of how success at major soccer events is gauged
these days. The indelible memory left by Germans at the 1998 World
Cup was that of the brutal attack on a French gendarme by four
hooligans. Determined to avoid a repeat of this type of incident at
the European championships, the German government enacted drastic
measures to keep hooligans out of the co-host countries, Belgium
and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   A month before the start of the tournament, the German
parliament amended a law that forbids foreign travel to citizens
who pose a ``significant threat to national interests and image''
to expressly include soccer hooligans.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of local police departments, the Interior Ministry
created a list of 3,000 hooligans whom it felt were likely to
travel to the tournament merely to engage in violent behavior. The
police visited these hooligans, labeled Category C, at home and
told them their presence at the games was not welcome.
</P>
<P>
   More controversially, 508 of the Category C hooligans were
informed by mail that they were legally barred from traveling to
Belgium and the Netherlands. The letter stated that failure to
comply with this ban could result in a one-year jail sentence. The
German government says it feels validated in the measures it took
to keep the tournament as hooligan free as possible. While there
were still instances of hooliganism by Germans, they were far fewer
than had been feared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to keep known troublemakers away from the
tournament,'' Lingenthal said. ``We feel we did that effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the fans cited by authorities was Dirk Wunram, 30, a
native of Berlin. He wanted nothing more than to attend the
tournament, but instead was one of 215 people forced to sign in at
his local police precinct on days Germany had a game.
</P>
<P>
   Wunram is clean-cut and does not give off any signal of being a
dangerous man. But a six-page police document chronicling his
activities on the German hooligan scene tells of dozens of acts of
violence at and around soccer matches in Germany and abroad since
1993. After his most recent arrest for his involvement in a bloody
brawl after a soccer match in Berlin in May 1999, Wunram was given
a two-year ban from all German soccer stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Far from making apologies for his violent past, Wunram, an
unemployed carpenter, considers himself a victim of circumstances.
He fails to understand why people find his ``hobby'' so distasteful
and calls the times he spent as a soccer hooligan ``the best of his
life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hooliganism is a sport,'' Wunram said recently, speaking
openly for the first time about his decadelong experiences on the
scene. ``There's a lot of strategy and tactical planning involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to keep people like Wunram in Germany, security was
tightened at border crossings into Belgium, the Netherlands and
France. Thorough searches of vehicles meant milelong traffic jams
but yielded 158 potential hooligans who were sent back to Germany.
Hans-Juergen Goldmann of the German border police said these
searches succeeded in keeping ``most of the bad ones'' from leaving
the country.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The English government, in contrast, chose not to increase its
powers to keep hooligans at home during the tournament and
experienced a public relations disaster.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures released by the Belgian police, more than
half of the 503 people arrested before the Germany-England match in
Charleroi, Belgium, on June 17 were English, about 140 were German
and 80 were from Belgium. Before a loss on June 20 eliminated
England from the tournament, UEFA, the governing body of soccer in
Europe, had considered removing it from the competition as a result
of the problems caused by British hooligans.
</P>
<P>
   According to the German Interior Ministry, its strategy for
maintaining order at the tournament was created on a
person-by-person basis in close consultation with state police
units specializing in sports-related violence.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Friedrich Loesel, a German hooligan expert, helped his
government create psychological profiles of hooligans. He said
Wunram was typical of the older and more sinister type of hooligan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older ones like him are particularly dangerous because
they assume a leadership role,'' Loesel said. ``They tend to be
more intelligent and demand that their young recruits go to lengths
to prove how violent they can be. That is how things spin out of
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Wunram casually narrates his evolution from soccer fan to soccer
hooligan, fondly recalling the spine-tingling sensation of seeing
his first game at the Berlin Olympic Stadium when he was 11. The
pure joy of sitting in a sold-out soccer stadium, cheering on the
home team, did not last long, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, the game just became secondary,'' Wunram said.
``The things going on around the game were much more interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Those things were fights between rival hooligan factions,
sometimes involving battles between hooligans with allegiances to a
particular team and sometimes involving alliances of hooligans
representing a geographic region of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think of these people as fans of the game is ridiculous,''
Loesel said. ``Although some may start that way, they all end up as
fans of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Wunram's actions at a German national team exhibition match in
1996 in Poland cemented his reputation as one of the country's more
infamous hooligans. The report on Wunram by the Berlin police
identifies him as a member of the drunken mob that chanted, ``We've
marched into Poland to thrash the Jews again,'' one of many taunts
that precipitated a postgame brawl. According to the report, this
incident tarnished Germany's image and was grounds enough to keep
Wunram away from the European championships.
</P>
<P>
   With a strange sense of moral relativism, Wunram adamantly
defends his hooliganism. He even hopes to return to it once his
stadium ban ends, regretting only that government restrictions are
making it hard for older hooligans to groom ``young talent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can tell me that what I did was wrong,'' Wunram said.
``Nobody can say that I didn't live my life to the absolute fullest
during these years.''
</P>
<P>
   Loesel, concerned about sports-related violence in all its
manifestations, has a different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our psychological profiles indicate that about 25 percent of
hooligans are clinically psychopathic,'' Loesel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a higher percentage than one finds among inmates in
German prisons.''
</P>
<P>
   When Germany was eliminated from the European championships,
Wunram woke up the next morning thinking he was a free man. Then he
found another letter in his mailbox informing him that the police
are maintaining the travel ban on him until the tournament
concludes on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Germany is leaving nothing to chance. It and South Africa have
emerged as front-runners to play host to the 2006 World Cup. The
winner will be chosen on Thursday in Zurich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
