<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-APPLE-TOURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK APPLE TOURS BUSES RETURN TO MANHATTAN STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York Apple Tours' red double-decker buses
returned to the streets of Manhattan this weekend for the first
time in four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the company's 63 buses were out by 6 a.m. Saturday in
the second day of operation since a panel of state court judges on
Monday rebuffed efforts by the city and state to sideline the buses
while regulators tried to shut the company down permanently.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has been cited for hundreds of regulatory and
safety violations in its nine years of carrying tourists around the
city, became a target of city and state authorities after an
accident on May 22 when an Apple bus struck and killed a
71-year-old actor at 45th Street and Ninth Avenue in Hell's
Kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki issued an order pulling the registration of
the company's 63 buses pending the outcome of an administrative
hearing that the city had started before the accident in an attempt
to shut down New York Apple Tours. The city was acting on
complaints that many New York Apple drivers did not have a
commercial driver's license, that the buses were not
environmentally certified and that they were being driven illegally
along cross streets.
</P>
<P>
   New York Apple challenged the order, saying it violated the
company's rights to due process, and on June 14 a state Supreme
Court judge in Manhattan agreed, reversing the governor's order and
appointing a former city official to monitor the company.
</P>
<P>
   But the city and state appealed, keeping the buses off the
streets _ and hundreds of New York Apple employees out of work _
until the appellate court ruling on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Square Business Improvement District and New York City
&AMP; Co., the convention and visitors bureau, had removed New York
Apple brochures from their offices and from information packets
given to tourists. Community advocates in Hell's Kitchen said they
were planning to post flyers to warn tourists about New York
Apple's problems in the West 40s and 50s between Avenue of the
Americas and Ninth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   By late morning Saturday, the buses _ packed with foreign
tourists and others from across the country _ were winding along
crowded streets in neighborhoods like Greenwich Village and the
Rockefeller Center area.
</P>
<P>
   Many passengers did not know _ or even care _ about New York
Apple's troubles with the authorities. They were just there for the
ride, snapping pictures and looking up at skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   John Avery, 62, a tourist from Birmingham, England, got on a
tour bus at West 57th Street and was dropped off downtown on West
Fourth Street. His only complaint was about the bumpy Manhattan
streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be able to see everything,'' he said. ``And you
can't do that from the subway.''
</P>
<P>
   John Fisher, a Hell's Kitchen community advocate who lives on
45th Street and Ninth Avenue, said he was disheartened as he woke
up Saturday morning to see a New York Apple bus on his block.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not happy, as can be expected,'' he said. ``The one
thing that people need to understand is that this operation has not
been given a clean bill of health. So, we'll see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
