u a BC-NY-CANADIAN-DEVELOP-N     07-01 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CANADIAN-DEVELOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON COVETED MANHATTAN SITE, CANADIAN DEVELOPER PLANS SKYSCRAPER 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After more than two years of rumors, squabbling and
legal wrangling, a Canadian developer has finally bought one of the
most sought-after corporate corners in Manhattan, and plans to
build a 35-story skyscraper there.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, the planned 1.2 million-square-foot tower
near Grand Central Terminal, at the southwest corner of Madison
Avenue and 42nd Street, will become the new home of the Canadian
Imperial Bank of Commerce, according to real estate executives. It
would be the latest headquarters project among a handful of major
office towers under construction or in the planning stages.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Clark, the president of Brookfield Properties Corp.'s
operations in the United States, confirmed that the company closed
the deal with Credit Suisse First Boston on Friday. He said it was
a complicated process that required the signing of 190 documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited,'' Clark said. ``This gets us going again. It'll
be a great addition to the 42nd Street corridor.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he was in negotiations with a major financial
institution, although he would not identify it. But real estate
executives who know of the plans said that the Canadian Imperial
Bank of Commerce, the largest bank in Canada, was expected to take
at least two-thirds of the space in the tower. In what has become a
routine demand by the city's most profitable corporations, the bank
has asked the administration of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for millions
of dollars in tax breaks for the project.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, CIBC was planning to move into 7 World Trade
Center when the current tenant, Salomon Smith Barney, suddenly
decided to stay put. The bank, which owns a stake in Brookfield,
looked at other possible locations before focusing on Madison
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few blocks north of the Brookfield site, Bear Stearns &AMP;
Co. is building a tower at Madison Avenue and 46th Street, while to
the west, workers are digging the foundation for the Ernst &AMP; Young
Building at 42nd Street and Seventh Avenue. Morgan Stanley is
building its third tower in the Times Square area on Seventh Avenue
between 49th and 50th streets.
</P>
<P>
   Demolition has already begun on the world headquarters for AOL
Time Warner Inc. in the twin-towered Columbus Center project at
Columbus Circle. And The New York Times recently signed a
nonbinding letter of intent with state and city officials to pay
about $85 million for control of a site on Eighth Avenue between
40th and 41st Streets, for a new headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Brookfield's proposed tower at Madison Avenue and 42nd Street
has been a long time coming. The complex $150 million deal involved
buying the 22-story, 87-year-old building at 300-310 Madison Ave.
and two town houses, as well as air rights from three adjacent town
houses, the Rogers Peet building and nearby Grand Central Terminal.
Demolition of the office building, which is largely vacant, is
expected to begin soon, according to Brookfield. Clark said
construction should begin early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The project would be the first of several new office towers
planned by Brookfield, which owns a large development site on Ninth
Avenue at 31st Street and is one of several developers vying to
build the New York Stock Exchange project in Lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But if the 42nd Street deal is a new beginning for Brookfield,
it is an exit ramp for another developer, Harry Macklowe. Macklowe
had put the site together for his own comeback project, a large
office tower. But he ran into trouble with his lenders, Credit
Suisse First Boston. After a long tug of war, First Boston took
over the site and hired Macklowe to buy several adjacent parcels.
Brookfield was supposed to buy the site last fall, but a new battle
erupted between Macklowe and First Boston, delaying the sale for
months.
</P>
<P>
   Brookfield now has control and is using Macklowe's old
architect, Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill, if not his designs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000701.0124 </DOCNO>
