<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0730 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-LAORETTI-NYT &LR;      07-01 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LAORETTI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAORETTI READY TO CALL IT QUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By MICHAEL ARKUSH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, Pa. _ The ovation at the final green Friday afternoon
was subdued and short, a dramatic contrast to the summer of 1992,
the last time the former club professional Larry Laoretti completed
a U.S. Senior Open at Saucon Valley County Club. Laoretti was the
winner that day, outdueling such prominent golfers as Jim Colbert,
Dave Stockton, Gary Player and Al Geiberger. He had made quite an
impression. Friday, the only thing he made was an early exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way it goes sometimes,'' said Laoretti, who
recorded a 9-over 80 to miss the cut by five shots and finish 19
behind the second-round leader, Bruce Fleisher, who held a one-shot
advantage over Jim Thorpe and two-shot edge on Hubert Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept trying,'' Laoretti said. ``I didn't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   That much is evident. Laoretti, in fact, seemed a good bet for
the weekend until he started to hack away on the back nine,
recording seven bogeys, one double bogey and only one par en route
to an abysmal 44.
</P>
<P>
   The par-5 12th symbolized his failure. One shot after another
ended up in the rough. A double bogey put him at 5-over for the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky to make a seven,'' said Laoretti, who had
registered a respectable opening-round 72. ``I had to make an
8-footer.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Laoretti, 60, who was an all-star athlete during
his high school days in Mahopac, N.Y., seemed in decent spirits on
Friday after he concluded his round. The Open, after all, was only
his fourth start of the season. He lost his exempt status this year
after dropping out of the top 70 on the career money list, and
failed to qualify last fall. He won't try again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm done; I'm going to go home and relax,'' said Laoretti, who
resides in Palm City, Fla. ``I'm not going to go to school anymore.
What am I going to prove? I've got my retirement coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, how could Laoretti, making his first trip back to the
scene of his glorious triumph, ever duplicate what happened in July
1992? Though he wasn't a total unknown _ he had recorded nine top
10 finishes in 1991, placing 15th on the money list _ his victory,
he admitted, ``shocked everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, perhaps, except for Laoretti, who had been playing
well heading into the week.
</P>
<P>
   On that Sunday, he played better than well, hitting 11 of 14
fairways and 17 of 18 greens in a 68 that propelled him to a
four-stroke victory over Colbert. Others applied pressure on the
untested Laoretti. It didn't make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had all the chances in the world to fold and he didn't,''
Stockton said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, however, did not make Laoretti a consistent
contender on the senior tour. In fact, he has never won again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd play a lot better,'' he said Friday. ``It wasn't
meant to be, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The same goes with his disappointing finish this week, though,
as a fellow competitor Joe Inman points out, it shouldn't diminish
what Laoretti accomplished eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made his senior tour career,'' Inman said. ``That's
something he'll have the rest of his life. Whether he did well this
time or not is not the point. He won the Senior Open and you can
never take that away from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Laoretti, of course, also has wonderful memories from 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that I remember the most was when I made the putt on
18, my wife Susan came running across the green,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ran across the green this time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
