<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS, IN PAIN, MANAGES A VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ A parade of past champions glided across a
red carpet during an uplifting ceremony on Center Court Saturday
while the missing Pete Sampras sat in a training room with his left
shin tethered to an electric stimulator.
</P>
<P>
   It was 20 minutes before his match, and Sampras was squeezing
each second out of his treatment time for tendinitis before facing
the dangerous windmill motions of the 6-foot-5-inch Justin
Gimelstob. Almost an hour later, a distressed Sampras took a peek
at two of the lingering legends perched as spectators in the Royal
Box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up and saw Bjorn and the Rocket,'' said Sampras with
a tinge of awe when he referred to Bjorn Borg and Rod Laver. ``In
that first set, I wasn't too proud that they were watching. They're
my idols. So you know who is there. At one point, I wanted to throw
my racket up there; and they could play for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been two days since the tendinitis sneaked into his shin,
two days since he had felt the court beneath his feet and the
racket handle in his hand. For one shaky 24-minute first set, it
was as if Sampras was trapped in an awkward meeting with a former
flame. He was uncomfortable, disconcerted and timid in his approach
to the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Then the ice was broken. Once he understood how much pain there
would be, once he found his old rhythm again, Sampras was able to
prop himself up with his serve and steady his attack with a series
of delicate half-volleys in a 2-6, 6-4, 6-2, 6-2 display of
third-round resiliency.
</P>
<P>
   With the reality of Sampras' march onward in front of him, the
animated Gimelstob gamely kept trying. Early in the third set, as
he furiously charged forward for a delicate shot by Sampras, it
looked as if Gimelstob jackknifed as he skidded to a stop and
tumbled over the net. By the end of the set, he had slipped on the
grass, slammed his hand on the lawn, and watched Sampras scamper
for a lunging half-volley that cut a perfect angle across the net
for a winner.
</P>
<P>
   All Gimelstob could do was smile in the absurdity of it all. If
Sampras did not undo Gimelstob with his touch, he was blowing holes
in his confidence with a serve that reached a high of 131 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came out of his mother's womb, God spent a little
extra time on his right shoulder,'' said Gimelstob, a native of
Morristown, N.J., who actually served more aces (12) than Sampras
(11). ``He just touched it. So that helps. He's got a beautifully
smooth action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever seen him lose when he steps on the court? If you
have to think about it, that's pretty good. Doesn't really matter
if he's injured. He's a great player. He seems to thrive on playing
injured.''
</P>
<P>
   While Andre Agassi eased by with a straight sets victory,
another of Sampras' challengers, Gustavo Kuerten, did not hold up
as well on the sixth day of Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   In need of a shot of Nyquil, a stuffy and achy Kuerten did not
have the energy to produce an encore to his French Open title.
Kuerten, seeded fourth, was upset by 114th-ranked Alexander Popp,
7-6 (6), 6-2, 6-1, on Court 2, known as the graveyard for elite
players at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   The seeded women remained on track Saturday. Lindsay Davenport,
Venus Williams and Monica Seles all held up to advance to the round
of 16. There was little uncertainty along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere around Sampras was different. He was playing a
hard server with great net coverage, but normally Sampras' match
against the 99th-ranked player on the tour wouldn't drum up such
intrigue. But with Sampras chasing Roy Emerson's Grand Slam record,
with a quirky back that has put him face to face with his tennis
mortality, the addition of tendinitis to his list of ailments was
unsettling. The first set only added to the drama, albeit
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``My racket felt like a foreign object,'' Sampras said. ``It
doesn't happen that often.''
</P>
<P>
   Without practice time for two days, Sampras was testing his pain
threshold throughout the first set. Slowly, his reaction time
improved. Eventually, he got his footing for some clever returns of
serve to break Gimelstob.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sore, and it will continue to be sore,'' said Sampras,
who will play Jonas Bjorkman in the fourth round on Monday. ``I
just need to find a way to play on it.''
</P>
<P>
   To escape one match did not firm up Sampras' belief in his
endurance. A week ago, his confidence was in much better shape than
it was even after his victory today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in the tournament,'' Sampras said. ``I have a day
off, and then I play Bjorkman. I'm here to complete the tournament,
win or lose. It is what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   He seemed dispirited more than re-energized. But sometimes with
the hangdog Sampras, it is hard to decipher his real mood. There is
a sense of determination, though. After all, Kobe Bryant managed.
Bryant's ability to play with a sprained ankle in the NBA finals
did not escape the notice of Sampras, a Lakers season ticket
holder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing hurt is something I've learned to deal with,'' Sampras
said. ``Everyone, at times in their career, whether it's Kobe
Bryant in the finals, plays hurt. I use him as my inspiration. This
is Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where his place in history is greatest. So as Sampras
stayed alive in his attempt to break Emerson's record and to tie
William Renshaw's mark for most men's titles at Wimbledon (seven),
it was fitting that Borg and Laver were witnesses to his chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have loved to have been part of it,'' Sampras said of
the parade of champions. ``I was doing whatever I had to in order
to play. It would have been an honor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
