<SLUG> BC-CAR-GORDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO GORDON, BEING BOOED MEANS HE IS AT THE TOP AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE CALDWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ More than a thousand race fans gathered in
the rain and mud Friday to try to snag T-shirts thrown by a man on
stilts and to catch a precious glimpse of a young driver buried
deep in the NASCAR Winston Cup standings.
</P>
<P>
   A mother with kids in tow stood behind a barricade and patiently
waved a piece of cardboard with a hand-lettered message for Jeff
Gordon: We drove 1,600 miles to see you.
</P>
<P>
   It is quite clear that Gordon is still adored by half of all
stock-car racing fans. The big difference is that Gordon is not as
hated as he used to be by the other half. As he headed into
Saturday night's Pepsi 400, a race with many subplots, Gordon has
been working harder than ever to change that.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to be the old Jeff Gordon. He wants to be the Jeff
Gordon who other drivers eyed jealously, who was booed for
sometimes making it all look so easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not booing near as much,'' he said, smiling. ``I want
them to boo.''
</P>
<P>
   Being booed, at least to Gordon, means that he is the class of
the field again. Gordon was booed as much as Dale Earnhardt, the
official Winston Cup bad guy, during a magnificent four-season
stretch in which he won three championships.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is in 10th place in the Winston Cup standings entering
Saturday night's race. He has finished lower than eighth in only
one season in his seven-year NASCAR career, and that was in 1993,
his first full season.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, other drivers have zoomed to the front. With a
points system every bit as mystifying as that used by college
football's Bowl Championship Series, NASCAR rewards drivers who are
consistently good more than it rewards drivers who win a lot.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Bobby Labonte, who has won one race this year,
leads the standings. Earnhardt, 49, who has not won at all, trails
Labonte by just 67 points. Gordon's team owner, John Hendrick, and
first-year crew chief, Robbie Loomis, said they have abandoned
hopes of winning another championship and simply hope to finish in
the top five. This represents quite a comedown for Gordon, who does
not turn 29 until August.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he could get on a roll right now, and who knows what will
happen?'' Hendrick said. ``This team is coming together. It just
takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Gordon's mantra. When the crew chief, Ray Evernham, left
the team last year to start his own team, Gordon was expected to
struggle, just not this much. He considers this season to have been
his most challenging, but he also conceded that struggling has been
good for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people want to see you be challenged,'' he said. ``It
looked like it came so easy, so fast. It's been a year where I've
really learned a lot about myself. But I think it's brought me
closer together with the team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
