<SLUG> BC-NY-DEAF-SCHOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TEACHERS UNION BLOCKS REPLACEMENTS AT SCHOOL FOR THE
DEAF 
</HEADLINE>
   By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City teachers union thwarted a plan last
week by the principal of the city's School for the Deaf to replace
35 teachers who are not proficient in American Sign Language with
those who are, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Florsheim, the principal, created a firestorm among union
leaders on Tuesday when he told 35 teachers that they would be
working at new schools in the fall, said Randi Weingarten,
president of the United Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Union representatives quickly intervened, tentatively
negotiating the number down to about 10, said Weingarten, who
complained that principals did not have the authority to remove
tenured teachers. Margie Feinberg, a spokeswoman for the New York
City Board of Education, said officials were investigating the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Florsheim's efforts are representative of a larger debate about
the education of deaf students.
</P>
<P>
   The average deaf 18-year-old American cannot read above the
fourth-grade level, according to some statistics. Some advocates
for the deaf say that the literacy problem lies in the fact that
American Sign Language, called signing, bears no relationship to
English in syntax, grammar or spelling. Weingarten said last week
that methods other than sign language to teach deaf students should
be explored. But proponents of sign language, like Florsheim, who
is deaf, say the problem is not with sign language, but with the
people teaching it.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Board of Education made American Sign
Language, or ASL, the primary language of the deaf school in 1998,
after complaints from some parents about the quality of teaching
there. The school, also known as Junior High School 47, teaches
students in pre-kindergarten through grade 12.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Fass, a deaf mother of two deaf daughters, Esther, 7,
and Adele Idy, 4, was one of the complaining parents. Both children
attend the school. Fass said on Friday that she was disappointed
that Weingarten had prevented Florsheim from replacing the
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I completely disagree with Randi Weingarten's comment that
there are other methods of teaching,'' Fass wrote in response to a
question. ``ASL is a language, and how is that possible for her to
say that there are other methods? Is she fluent in ASL, and if not,
what right does she have?''
</P>
<P>
   Terri Thomson, the Queens representative on the board,
spearheaded the effort to make sign language the primary language
at the school. She said on Friday that, though she was not familiar
with what happened on Tuesday, she was aware of on-going staffing
changes to ensure that students were well educated.
</P>
<P>
   ``At each of our public agenda meetings, a group of parents
would come to testify because their children were getting poor
educations,'' Thomson said. ``Some were being taught through sign
language interpreters who were not teachers, and the quality was
poor. We heard from students, who told of failing tests. Many said
they felt isolated going to school, walking around with sign
language interpreters. What they cried out for was a program where
they could be taught in their home language _ ASL.''
</P>
<P>
   Florsheim, the first deaf principal of the school, has mostly
hired teachers fluent in sign language to his staff of 87 since
becoming principal in 1996. The school has about 300 students.
</P>
<P>
   American Sign Language had been banned from schools for more
than a century. In the late-1960s, William Stokoe Jr., a linguist
at Gallaudet University, a university in Washington, D.C., for
students with hearing loss, worked for it to become recognized as a
language.
</P>
<P>
   But now, as the number of technology jobs grows, and as medical
technology is making it possible more often for deaf children to
gain partial hearing through surgical implants, some parents and
educators are pushing for broader forms of communication.
</P>
<P>
   Anther method of communication for people with hear loss is cued
speech, which can supplement sign language. It breaks words into
syllables and conveys them with hand signals and lip reading, so
that a deaf person can link visual signs and sounds to the language
as it is written and spoken. Other methods of communication include
oral-auralism, which essentially is lip reading with the help of
hearing aids; signing exact English, which is using a type of sign
language to depict English just as it is spoken; and auditory
verbal therapy, which teaches the maximum use of hearing aids
without the lip reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm exasperated by this situation,'' Weingarten said of the
incident at the school. ``Here's a school designed to help kids who
are deaf or hard of hearing, and one of the approaches is supposed
to be ASL. Florsheim believes that ASL is the only way. It's a good
method, but it is not an exclusive method. There are some kids who
will benefit from others. That is not something he understands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
