<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEROT-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEROT TAKES HIMSELF OUT OF THE RUNNING BUT WANTS NO ONE TO TAKE HIS
PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By notifying the Reform Party that he does not intend to run for
president this year, Ross Perot has apparently ended an improbable
political career that has sparked widespread interest in
third-party alternatives to Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Perot's letter to the chairman of the Reform presidential
nominations committee, which was delivered Friday night, suggested
that even from behind the curtain, he was still trying to exert a
degree of influence over the primary process of the party he
founded, largely at the expense of its leading contender for the
nomination, the former Republican presidential candidate and
television commentator Patrick Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Perot proposed that in place of having his name on the ballot,
which he earned through petition signatures collected on his
behalf, a line would read ``No Endorsement,'' giving primary voters
the chance to express dissatisfaction with other candidates, as he
said, who ``do not represent the principles of the Reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Farris, chairman of the president nominations committee,
said Saturday that he did not know how the three-member panel would
decide the issue. The party constitution recognizes the possibility
of making no endorsement but does not discuss how that decision may
be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it seemed abundantly clear to many party leaders that
Perot's request was directed at Buchanan as a rebuke of his agenda
as antithetical to the party platform and as a serious effort to
undermine his support on the eve of primary voting.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform candidate is selected by mail and Internet voting,
starting on Wednesday and concluding on Aug. 9. The winner will be
announced at the party convention that week in Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extremely cynical approach,'' Bay Buchanan, chief
campaign strategist for her brother, said of Perot's request,
asserting that he and his supporters were using the request ``to
protest Pat Buchanan, and the appeal is the way they are going to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she added, ``We will dominate the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Verney, a spokesman for Perot, said the request was not
specifically aimed at Buchanan, but rather as a way for voters to
reject anyone who would draw the party away from its traditional
roots. They include silence on otherwise divisive issues like
abortion rights and homosexuality, which Buchanan addresses often
on the stump.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're reading more into it than they should,'' Verney said
of Buchanan supporters who feel disturbed by the request. ``This
was not to support or oppose any one candidate. It was to allow
members to clearly express their opinion, and a lot of them told
Ross it was better to have no person as a candidate than the wrong
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Verney said he did not know if the nominating rules permitted
the party to accept Perot's request. But if they did not, he said
Perot would not change his mind and run.
</P>
<P>
   The Buchanan campaign has asked the nominations committee to
insist that the other candidate in the race, John Hagelin, not be
placed on the ballot unless he promises not to seek the nomination
from another party if he fails to win the Reform endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin, a physicist, has run for president before as the
nominee of the Natural Law Party, winning less than 1 percent of
the vote in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider him a major threat,'' Bay Buchanan said.
``But our argument is that if you put him on our ballot, he gains
lots of prestige and national attention. Then if he loses and goes
to another party, he uses the prestige of the Reform Party against
us. That's a rule or ruin approach.''
</P>
<P>
   In responding to the Buchanan challenge, Hagelin sidestepped the
issue and charged that Buchanan was raising concerns only because
he felt his lead slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   Perot ran for president in 1992 and 1996 under the banner of the
Reform Party, which he formed out of growing disenchantment with
the political mainstream and brought new focus to old issues like
trade and campaign finance reform that some voters continue to find
troubling.
</P>
</TEXT>
