<HEADER>
A0751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT &LR;      07-01 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 TOUR RIDERS BANNED AS ARMSTRONG BEGINS TITLE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUTUROSCOPE, France _ Four hours before its start Saturday, the
87th Tour de France was rocked by an announcement that three of its
180 riders had been disqualified for failing to pass a blood test
that indicates the use of illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   With no immediate right of appeal, the riders were suspended
from the sport for 15 days. About a half-dozen riders have been
similarly punished each year since the blood tests were introduced
in 1997, but this was a first in the Tour de France, the world's
most prestigious bicycle race.
</P>
<P>
   The news of the suspensions overshadowed an exhilarating
performance by unsung British rider David Millar, who won the first
stage, a 16.5-kilometer (10.3 miles) time trial, Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Malta-born 23-year-old Millar, who burst into tears after
realizing that he had finished just ahead of last year's Tour
champion Lance Armstrong in the time trial, will wear the overall
leader's yellow jersey in Sunday's second stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dream. I can't even talk,'' he cried as soon as
Armstrong had crossed the line.
</P>
<P>
   Millar, who lives in the surfing resort of Biarritz, France,
beat Armstrong by just two seconds while Frenchman Laurent Jalabert
was third 13 seconds behind, and 1997 winner Jan Ullrich was fourth
a further second back.
</P>
<P>
   After having recovered and put on several different colored
jerseys for different category leaders, Millar reflected on his
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still fairly incredible. I'm going to sleep in the jersey
tonight, and, in fact, I'm not going to take it off for years!''
said the son of a Royal Air Force pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest,'' he said, ``I don't know what nationality I am
because I was born in Malta, my family is Scottish and I was
brought up in Hong Kong, which is where my father still lives as
well as most of my friends _ and my mother is in London,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, officials made no immediate public comment about the
drug suspensions. A drug inspector reported that Jean-Marie
Leblanc, who directs the race, had been shocked by the news and
then said, ``I'm glad the cheaters were caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, officials were dispersed across the plains of
Futuroscope, a technology theme park, as they prepared for the
start of the three-week, 3,660-kilometer (2,274-mile) Tour. The
race was disrupted and nearly collapsed in 1998 when a drug scandal
resulted in the expulsion of one team and the withdrawal of five
others to protest police searches for illegal performance-enhancing
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The riders disqualified Saturday were Sergei Ivanov, 25, who won
the Russian national championship last Sunday for the second
consecutive year; Rossano Brasi, 28, an Italian, and Andrei
Hauptman, 25, a Slovak. Ivanov rides for the Farm Frites team from
the Netherlands, Brasi for the Polti team from Italy and Hauptman
for the Vini Caldirola team from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did everything we could to avoid this,'' said Hendrik
Redant, a sporting director of Ivanov's team. `'And still it
happened. I can't explain it.'' Under another sponsor, TVM, the
Farm Frites team was heavily involved in the 1998 scandal and some
of its previous officials still face trial in France on charges of
transporting illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the three disqualifications followed by a
day a public warning by Leblanc that any rider tempted to use drugs
in the Tour was ``playing with fire and risking his reputation.''
Although blood tests can be administered at any time during the
race, the one Saturday was part of the official schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test was no surprise, no secret,'' said Martin Bruin, a
Dutchman who heads the drug inspection team sent by the
International Cycling Union, which governs the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors, whom the riders always refer to as ``the vampires,''
arrived at each of the 20 teams' hotels between 7 and 8:45 a.m.
Saturday to draw drops of blood. They are tested to determine the
hematocrit level _ the number of red corpuscles. A level higher
than 50 percent sends a rider home for two weeks ``to regain his
health,'' as the rules put it since the international union insists
that the inspection is a health test, not one for drugs.
Nevertheless, in the public mind, a hematocrit level above 50
percent indicates the use of EPO, an artificial hormone that
increases red corpuscles, which carry oxygen to muscles and thus
increase performance in endurance sports.
</P>
<P>
   No reliable blood test exists to confirm the presence of EPO,
which closely resembles a natural hormone. Although a urine test
for EPO is under development at the French national drug-testing
laboratory, it has not been deemed foolproof and was not approved
for use in the Tour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
