<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, July 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few days, summery heat will expand from the Plains
into most of the Eastern states. Disturbances in a vigorous jet
stream at the northern periphery of the hot air mass will set the
stage for recurrent thunderstorms from the northern Plains to the
interior Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Humidity will begin to increase in the Northeast Sunday as
breezes from the southwest develop. Sunshine will be dimmed
occasionally by high clouds, especially from the eastern Great
Lakes to New England.
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms will erupt where a surge of sultry air
intersects a front in the northern Mississippi Valley and Great
Lakes states. Areas of heavy rain will heighten the risk of local
flooding, especially where the ground is saturated from recent
rain.
</P>
<P>
   Some strong thunderstorms will occur near a front in the
northern Rockies. The Pacific Northwest will stay rather cool.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TEMPERATURE ERROR
</P>
<P>
   Measuring the correct air temperature can be difficult. Last
week after studying readings from nearby instruments, technicians
determined that the official thermometer at St. Paul was reading
consistently high. Most erroneous thermometer readings are too
warm. Thermometers must be carefully placed five feet above the
ground and must remain always in the shade. In addition, the
instrument must be properly ventilated and situated away from
surrounding objects that might radiate additional warmth.
</P>
</TEXT>
