<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0754 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-NEWCOMERS-REAL-3TA     07-01 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NEWCOMERS-REAL-3TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE CLASS OF 2000, RENTING 101 
</HEADLINE>
   By NADINE BROZAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The annual migration to New York of new college
graduates, degrees in hand, entry-level jobs on the horizon, seems
as inevitable as the changing of the seasons. Just as predictable
is the sticker shock they face when they plunge into the hunt for
an apartment, when they realize that what they might pay for an
entire house in Birmingham or Boise is barely enough for a studio
here.
</P>
<P>
   That of course has been true, to one degree or another, for
years, but the price tags presented to the class of 2000 seem
particularly breathtaking, even compared to those of last year when
the market was already torrid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cycle of soaring rents has to break somewhere, but we've
been saying that for years and years and it only gets more
incredible and more shocking every year,'' said Michael Shapot, an
associate broker with Coldwell Banker/Hunt Kennedy in Manhattan who
has many young people among his clients. ``It is a landlords'
market. They are demanding, demanding, demanding _ and getting,
getting, getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Supply and demand, with a New York twist, are part of the
reason.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the booming economy in general and the demand for
co-op apartments in particular, ``co-op owners who once rented
their apartments are now selling them because they are getting top
dollar and are choosing not to rent any longer,'' Shapot said.
``There are some new buildings, but they are selling out or renting
out incredibly quickly at prices that the class of 2000 is
unwilling or unable to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   So unless the graduates have trust funds or six-figure salaries,
they are finding themselves scaling down the visions they brought
to the city: trading in elevators for walkups, banding together
with more roommates than they had planned on, putting up temporary
walls to carve bedrooms out of living rooms or relinquishing the
idea of Manhattan altogether and finding haven in Brooklyn, Queens,
the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, they are making further compromises, like giving up a
quick walk to a subway stop. Some, defeated altogether by the size
of their paychecks relative to the going rents, return to the nest
and parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wealthy city, and it is starting to shape up that
only kids with silver spoons can be here,'' said Andrew Heiberger,
president and owner of Citi Habitats, a residential brokerage
company that rented 5,400 apartments in Manhattan last year and
caters to what he described as ``upwardly mobile professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But even a silver spoon, inherited or earned, may not be
sufficient. Consider the case of Chip Krotee of Minneapolis, who is
about to begin a job as a trader with Merrill Lynch, and Arjay
Jensen of St. Louis, who will work for Goldman Sachs. Roommates at
Duke University's Fuqua School of Business, where they received
their masters of business administration degrees in May, they
figured they would find a place to live with relative ease. The
moving allowances their companies gave them included payment of
brokers' fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brokers we called suggested we come to New York three or
four weeks before we were ready to move and bring lots of cash,''
Krotee said the other day from his home in Minneapolis, where he
was packing. ``We came up on May 24 figuring we'd be safe if we
brought two months' rent. We were hoping to find a two-bedroom
apartment somewhere on the West Side below 90th Street for $3,500 a
month for the two of us.''
</P>
<P>
   They were shown six or seven apartments, two of which they
deemed ``tenable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were willing to take them outright, but we were rejected,''
Krotee said. ``We were told we needed assets of $1 million, and
even with those assets landlords wouldn't look at us unless we had
worked in New York City for two years. We also needed a guarantor
in the tristate region with income 100 times our rent.''
</P>
<P>
   They did find a two-bedroom apartment in a prewar building on
West 73rd Street. ``There the management was fine,'' Krotee said,
``but because we had no New York City guarantor, we had to put six
months' rent, or $24,000, in a security deposit and had to take out
loans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we have MBAs, six-figure salaries, perfect
credit ratings and fixed assets that are not too shabby didn't
matter,'' he said, looking back on the painful search.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Blase Boyd of Kearny, N.J., felt much the same way after
he began looking for an apartment to share with three friends from
Georgetown University: Benjamin Meyer of Kansas City, Kan., Nathan
Swem of Shellbourne Falls, Mass., and Nicolina Kuh of Arlington,
Texas They all graduated last month and have jobs at investment
banking firms like ING Barings and Warburg Dillon Read.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found a place on East 57th Street that was a steal at
$4,900, a 35th-floor penthouse with three bedrooms and two
terraces, and our four salaries covered the rent,'' Boyd said.
``But they only wanted two people signing the lease and there were
no two of us whose salaries covered 40 times the rent.'' (The
annual income _ including salary, dividends and interest _ that
landlords require of tenants can vary, Heiberger said; 40 to 52
times the monthly rent is usual.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Boyd said, they were limited to one guarantor, and
they had no one individual who could fill that role.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Boyd grew so frustrated by endless red tape that,
he said, ``even though I love the three people I'll be living with,
friends since freshman year, I seriously contemplated dropping out
and going to Hoboken or Jersey City by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Pondering what it takes to make landlords become almost as picky
as co-op boards, he said: ``We have gone to a better school where
we've all graduated with honors. I was only cum laude, the other
three were magnas. We are financially responsible. I paid for a
year of Georgetown out of my own pocket and we all have well-paying
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they have signed a lease on a sublet on West 106th Street
between Broadway and Amsterdam Avenue for $4,100 a month. No
guarantor was required, but they are awaiting approval from the
board of the co-op building. ``If they turn us down, I don't know
who they want in that apartment,'' Boyd said.
</P>
<P>
   The rents being paid by Krotee, Boyd and their roommates do not
seem out of line with current prices in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the income requirement of nine out of 10 buildings, a
salary of 50 times one months' rent, someone earning $60,000 would
barely qualify for a $1,200 studio,'' Heiberger said. ``And a
$1,200 studio is the bottom of the barrel in the city. It would be
a fifth-floor walkup or on the first floor facing an alley with a
view of the trash.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The minimum for most studios is $1,500 and they go up to
$2,200,'' he continued. ``One-bedrooms that you can convert to two
are $2,400, and two-bedrooms that you convert to three are around
$3,600. Once you get into three bedrooms, the prices jump greatly
to $6,000 and you're competing with couples with families who are
raising kids in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, landlords, who tend to prefer older and presumably
more settled tenants, are raising the bar higher in other ways. For
example, the requirements for guarantors, without whom many
landlords will not consider a renter right out of school, are
tightening up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guarantors are required to make 75 times the monthly rent,''
Heiberger said. ``They must submit their own financial information
that is more onerous than a mortgage application to prove that they
are able to support their own obligations plus the obligations of
the tenant. Six out of 10 landlords require the guarantor to be
from New York State, eight of 10 that they be from the tristate
area and 10 out of 10 that they be from the United States. Kids and
their parents are being forced to pay more than their tuition for
their senior year of college in advance just to get the key.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, the fact that their nest may be empty no longer
automatically ends parental financial obligation. Ryu Suzuki, who
will start as an associate for UBS Warburg on July 5, came to New
York in May right after graduating from Oberlin College. He would
not have been able to move into the apartment he found _ a
$2,000-a-month condo studio in Murray Hill _ had his parents, who
flew here from Tokyo to make sure that he found a safe place, not
been willing to put up a year's rent, $24,000, in advance. ``Having
recently purchased a new house in Tokyo, they were not shocked
about the prices,'' Suzuki said.
</P>
<P>
   Even a medical degree does not ensure safe passage through the
roiling rental waters. ``It seems to me that if someone is starting
out as a physician in New York and has the credentials, landlords
would bend a little,'' said John Lemery of Saratoga, whose son, Dr.
John M. Lemery, just graduated from Dartmouth Medical School and
started work last week as an intern in emergency medicine at the
Bellevue Hospital Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needed something reasonably close to Bellevue because he
will work 12-hour shifts and undergo all that goes with being an
intern,'' Lemery said. Lemery found a 300-square-foot studio in a
doorman building on East 47th Street for $1,675 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to pay the first and last month's rent on a two-year
lease, security deposit and brokerage fees which came to more than
$8,300,'' Lemery said. ``It all had to be deposited in certified
funds with the broker. They wouldn't take a personal check, and I
had to guarantee the lease, provide them with a copy of selected
information on my income tax return and get a letter from my bank
saying that we are creditworthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides providing advance payments, bank records, tax forms,
references and guarantors, apartment seekers must be prepared to
make snap decisions or almost inevitably forfeit opportunities even
in less desirable apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Bercovici, a new graduate of the New School for Social
Research in Manhattan, is moving to Williamsburg in Brooklyn
because the apartment he occupied for two years in Park Slope has
been sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told there was a new building in Williamsburg, and when
I called, a woman told me there were eight apartments left,'' he
said. ``When I went to see it, there were only two left. So many
apartments had been pulled out from under my feet that I was ready
to take it on the spot. It was close enough to what I was looking
for and I didn't feel like going crazy. There was a guy in line
behind me, and once I said I would take it, the broker turned to
him and said, `Now there is only one left,' so he took it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bercovici, a painter who is looking for a teaching job, was
scheduled to move in with a roommate July 1, and together they will
pay $1,775 a month for a 1,400-square-foot loft. ``Everything else
in the neighborhood was at least $500 more,'' he said. ``There is
no gas in the building yet, which is why it is so cheap.'' The
building is being converted from commercial to residential status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, $2,000 a month is a steal,'' said Annie Livingston of
Portland, Ore., who graduated from Yale last year, is now the
assistant public relations director at Swann Galleries in Manhattan
and has been renting a room in a friend's co-op.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She and her Yale roommate, Sarah Karnasiewicz of Southbury,
Conn., an operations design assistant at the Whitney Museum of
American Art, spent their lunch hours and evenings since the
beginning of May pursuing an apartment, and said they had probably
tramped through 30 of them.
</P>
<P>
   They made every effort to avoid using the services of a broker,
Livingston said, because brokers ``charge 15 percent of the year's
rent and don't do much,'' but in the end, they found their new home
last Tuesday through an agent, Adam Feingold of New York City
Apartments.
</P>
<P>
   They said it was love at first sight when they saw the apartment
_ which has two bedrooms, two baths, a living room and an eat-in
kitchen _ in a newly renovated four-story town house on 78th Street
east of Second Avenue. Especially because the rent is $2,200 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   The search was an education for the women, who just last weekend
were told by a broker that it was unlikely they would find a decent
two-bedroom apartment for less than $4,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started out, I thought that paying $1,000 a month was
ridiculous,'' said Karnasiewicz, who has been camping out with
friends, ``moving from floor to floor depending on the kindness of
strangers'' since the start of the search. ``Now I think we are
getting a great deal for the money. To get anything halfway decent
or clean for less than $2,500 seems like a bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I would be in a palace, but I expected to find
something small, clean and comfortable and would go where the
prices took me, anywhere where I would feel safe,'' she said.
``Then when we started looking, I realized we are definitely not in
a position of power. No matter what state an apartment is in, it
will be rented, probably to people making twice as much money as we
are.''
</P>
<P>
   They got their apartment by getting to it first _ after they had
begun to consider leaving Manhattan. ``We had been looking for
weeks,'' she said. ``On Tuesdays at 1 p.m., when the new Village
Voice listings come online, the day before the paper is printed, I
go through them and make calls. I was the first person to call _ 20
minutes after the listing was posted_ and we raced over there right
from work. We knew within minutes that this was it.''
Karnasiewicz's father is the guarantor.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the draw of communities outside Manhattan was
directly proportional to their proximity to subway or PATH commuter
train stations, but even that is changing with rising demand.
``People are not so insistent any more on being right at the No. 7
subway stop,'' said Scott Cooper, a broker with Cooper Real Estate
in Woodside, Queens. ``Since apartments here are in such great
demand, people who used to want to be no farther than four blocks
from a subway now consider 10 blocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what locales were the most popular alternatives to
Manhattan, Heiberger listed Hoboken, Jersey City and Fort Lee in
New Jersey, Astoria in Queens, Long Beach on Long Island, and
Williamsburg, Park Slope and Brooklyn Heights.
</P>
<P>
   But what is considered reasonable one year can become pricey the
next. As rents rise in Park Slope, which once got the spillover
from Brooklyn Heights, Windsor Terrace is becoming more popular.
Rents there are 10 to 15 percent lower than in Park Slope, said
John P. Burke Jr., a broker with John P. Burke Realty. A
two-bedroom apartment in Windsor Terrace would be $1,650, compared
to $2,200 in Park Slope, he said. ``There has been more demand for
two-bedrooms this year over last,'' he said, ``mainly because few
people can afford to live alone and must share to get by.''
</P>
<P>
   Rents in Astoria have been escalating as well. A one-bedroom
apartment there that would have averaged $750 to $800 a month a
year or so ago is now $900 to $1,000, Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Which communities are considered likely to be the next magnets
for the young? The graduates are not as willing as suburban
homeowners to travel more than a half hour to reach the city,
brokers say, but migration east in Queens to Bayside seems to be
starting, and boundaries are beginning to stretch to Staten Island
and Great Neck on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Great Neck, that affluent North Shore community? ``Yes,''
Heiberger said. ``you can still get a one-bedroom apartment there
for $1,200.''
</P>
<P>
   Tufts University class of '99 graduates Sarah Rosen, an
assistant producer at Dateline NBC, and Chelsea Switzer, an events
coordinator at Chelsea Piers, barely considered Manhattan, even
though that was where they wanted to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it would be impossible,'' Rosen said. ``We wanted to
find something for $1,500 a month and with one bedroom that we
could subdivide. We each wanted our own room and were not willing
to have someone living in the living room.''
</P>
<P>
   They registered with an apartment listing service that provided
them with addresses of places in their price range. ``Nothing they
sent us to was in Manhattan,'' Rosen said. They also responded to
newspaper ads, through which they found a two-bedroom third-floor
walkup in Park Slope that was $450 above their budget. ``We saw it
and said, `We will kick ourselves if we don't take this,' and then
the rent went up another $50 a month because we had them build a
wall,'' she said. ``We immediately decided we needed a third
roommate.''
</P>
<P>
   Through an ad they put on the Tufts alumni Web page, they
recruited Stefan Kimball, a new graduate of Penn State, who has a
job as a paralegal with Latham &AMP; Watkins and who was scheduled to
move in July 1. The fact that the apartment is not in Manhattan
doesn't seem to matter to Kimball, whose family lives in Finland.
``I like the idea of living in New York, not New Jersey,'' he said.
``Park Slope is pretty cool, and we have a nice view of Manhattan
from the window. I'm paying $800, and for someplace like Park
Slope, that seems like a bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   For those unshakable in their resolve to be in Manhattan, Gus
Perry of Stein-Perry Real Estate in Washington Heights said, ``We
are absolutely seeing more young people up here, and in Inwood and
the north Harlem areas. This is the only place you can find a large
one-bedroom for under $1,500 on the island of Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichole Argyres, a book editor who graduated from the University
of Michigan four years ago, and David Gordon, who graduated from
its school of music in April, are moving to Inwood in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to choose whether we wanted a good location and a
really small apartment or live in Brooklyn or the Bronx,'' Argyres
said from Ann Arbor. ``We knew that David would be studying at the
Manhattan School of Music, which is near Columbia, so we wanted to
try to be in Manhattan. To live elsewhere would be a huge
commute.''
</P>
<P>
   They found what is termed a ``junior four'' (one large bedroom
and one small) for $1,300 a month. ``It's spacious in a great
location 20 minutes from downtown on the express and there is lots
of green,'' Argyres said happily.
</P>
<P>
   How much farther young people will be willing to commute to work
and play in Manhattan remains to be seen. And what current trends
portend for the post-college generation of the future is an open
question.
</P>
<P>
   As Lucy Martin Gianino, an actress who is also a real estate
broker with Coldwell Banker/Hunt Kennedy, put it: ``If I could give
my children one gift, it would be a co-op.'' Gianino has three
children, Gemina, 30, a teacher who is about to enter the Harvard
Graduate School of Education, Antonia, 27, a stage manager for the
play ``Rent,'' and Gian-Murray, 22, a new graduate of Wesleyan
University who will be an intern for a year with the Actors Theater
of Louisville in Kentucky. ``It is my big concern as the parent of
three children who are all in the arts or education,'' Gianino
said. ``Will they be driven out of the city as everyone here
becomes an investment banker? Will they have to leave professions
they love to earn a buck so they can put a roof over their heads?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
