<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0757 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CELLPHONES0702-COX     07-01 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLPHONES0702-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Digital-age phones bring out stone-age manners in some users
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Ruby Owens has a bumper sticker that says ``If we
were meant to be talking on the phone while driving, we'd be
driving phone booths.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens is one of the growing horde of people who have had
unpleasant encounters with people who have turned on their mobile
phones and clicked off their brains.
</P>
<P>
   In her case it was a guy in a dark blue Mercedes ``with a
Budweiser in one hand and a cell phone in the other, driving with
his knees'' on northbound Interstate 75 approaching a dangerous
interchange.
</P>
<P>
   Owens said the man was carrying on a lively conversation as he
swerved from side to side, nearly forcing her and her van full of
children off the road. ``I was saying 'Oh my God! I'm dead and my
children are dead.' He only missed us by a couple inches,'' Owens
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got where I was going in Tipp City, I was still shaking
all over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association estimates
there are about 94 million Americans with wireless telephones right
now, and another 46,000 people sign up for new mobile phone service
every day.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, within a pool that large, there will be a few jerks
like the guy in the dark blue Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Schafer said he recently had a head-on encounter with a car
driven by a young woman who laughed and talked merrily on her phone
as she exited Interstate 70 using the entrance ramp from Ohio 48.
She apparently never realized her mistake even after Schafer
screeched to a halt and blared his horn at her.
</P>
<P>
   Don McGee said he recently saw what appeared to be a businessman
in a shiny black sport utility vehicle turn left with the thumb and
index finger of his left hand holding a sheet of paper against the
steering wheel while using his other hand to hold a phone to his
ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he thought he was
productive/efficient/chic/connected/cool,'' McGee said. `` . . .
but, to those of us who watched him make that turn, he will always
be just a self-absorbed moron.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving while talking on a mobile phone is illegal in England,
Israel and a few other countries. The Cleveland suburb of Brooklyn
last year became the first American city to start ticketing
motorists for using a handheld phone while driving, and other
cities have followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   State legislatures across the country have debated the issue,
but none have banned mobile phone use in cars.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Journal of Medicine published a study in 1997
that said a driver using a cell phone was four times more likely to
be in an accident than drivers who were not talking.
</P>
<P>
   And the study indicated that phones that a driver could use with
both hands free were no less dangerous than phones that had to be
held. Apparently it's the distraction of holding a conversation
while driving and not the problem of having one hand occupied that
causes problems.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Keller is a waitress at a restaurant that serves breakfast
and she said, ``People get so wrapped up in their cell phone
conversation, they don't even realize you're standing in front of
them trying to take their orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller said she had her worst restaurant mobile phone experience
as a customer at a restaurant three years ago. ``There weren't many
people there, but there was one guy talking on his cell phone like
he was the only person in the building,'' she said. ``We had to ask
to move to a different table further away from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really sad is when the business you're in makes you so
busy that you can't even interact with the people around you.''
</P>
<P>
   David Hume, owner of the Pine Club in Dayton, said his staff has
had to quiet people who were disturbing others at his restaurant
with their mobile phones, but it happens rarely. Hume said he
personally is known for using his cell phone frequently while
running his business, and he understands the need for some people
to stay in touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody has a phone that rang loudly or he was talking,
we're really tuned into that sort of thing, and we would talk to
him about it,'' Hume said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But really the bigger issue is common courtesy. Some people
have cell phones that instead of ringing they play Beethoven's
``Fifth Symphony'' or something. Having that go off in a restaurant
is inappropriate and unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``But by the same token, if somebody is at a table using loud,
aggressive language that, too, is inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   TALKING TASTEFULLY
</P>
<P>
   ``Cell phones in restaurants are rude,'' said Sue Fox, an author
and consultant on business etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``The essence of courtesy is making people feel comfortable, and
when you're sitting at a table talking on the phone, you're putting
everybody around you in an awkward position,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said she worked for Apple Computers for more than 10 years
and says she got firsthand exposure to every business etiquette
mistake possible. She still works in Silicon Valley, but now she
runs Etiquette Survival Inc. in Los Gatos, Calif., and conducts
seminars in business etiquette and international protocol.
</P>
<P>
   She said mobile phone use became a status symbol years ago in
Southern California, and restaurants and other public businesses
have had to ban mobile phone use to curb inconsiderate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said mobile phones, e-mail and other technologies became
popular so quickly that there wasn't time for rules of etiquette to
be established for their use. But she said common sense and
consideration for others dictate how wireless phones should be
used.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some courtesy rules for mobile phone use:
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't take a mobile phone to dinner with you if you can avoid
it. If you are a doctor or someone else who must be reachable in an
emergency, use a phone that vibrates instead of ringing.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you are expecting a call that can't be postponed until
after dinner, tell your dining companions ahead of time. When the
call comes in, excuse yourself and answer the call in a place where
you will have some privacy. ``You can't help but overhear if
someone nearby is talking on a cell phone,'' Fox said. ``Remember
that nobody wants to hear your conversation, so talk where no one
will be forced to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   _ If you know you're going to have to be on the phone a lot,
stay at home. It's unfair to others to interrupt a meal, a meeting,
a sermon or other public event with constant phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you receive a call while driving, pull off the road if you
have to answer it. If you have to initiate a call while driving,
park first.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never talk on a mobile phone while in a social setting with
others. You put your companions in the awkward position of not
being able to talk freely among themselves for fear of disturbing
you. If you're dining with only one other person, that person has
no one to talk to at all while you're on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep your voice down. Occasionally you may be forced to take
an emergency call in a public place such as in a store. Move to a
secluded area if possible and talk quietly. Under no circumstances
should you shout, curse or otherwise display anger during a public
phone call. Save your histrionics for a time when you have privacy
and won't embarrass or offend others.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
