u s BC-CARP-OUTDOORS-NYT &LR;      07-01 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARP-OUTDOORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARYLAND OFFICIALS BLAME BACTERIA FOR DEATH OF CHESAPEAKE CARP 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS BRANDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 1960s, President Lyndon B. Johnson signed into law the
Clean Water Act, which in just a few years made the Potomac River
one of the nation's top largemouth bass fisheries and returned the
ospreys, bald eagles, great blue herons and other elegant birds to
this beautiful, sprawling river.
</P>
<P>
   But, since May, thousands of adult carp, a bottom-feeding fish,
have died in the Chesapeake Bay and the Potomac River, and in the
many tributaries that flow into the two. In some places along the
Potomac, in just 100 feet of shoreline, 25 or more dead carp, from
18 inches to 4 feet long, have been found dead.
</P>
<P>
   Dead and diseased carp have been found in virtually every tidal
and freshwater tributary of the Chesapeake Bay, as well as
reservoirs, since the second week of May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We advise against eating diseased or dead carp,'' said Charles
Poukish, an environmental specialist with the Maryland Department
of the Environment, who is involved in researching the deaths.
``Look at the gill tissue and if they are not their normal pinkish
red, don't eat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Internationally, carp are one of the most popular eating fish,
though in the United States their culinary popularity is still
evolving. Carp were first extensively stocked in the United States
in the 1830s, when Europeans coming here wanted them to be part of
their diet.
</P>
<P>
   The carp deaths are caused by a bacterial gill disease thought
by environmental officials to be induced by flavobacterium.
Although bacteria are common in freshwater habitats around the
world, and there have been carp deaths in other parts of the world,
there have never before been deaths of this magnitude in the United
States. Usually the bacteria have little effect on fish unless
their resistance is lowered by other factors. Other fish besides
carp can be affected, and some catfish have died as well.
</P>
<P>
   Poukish said he believed that one factor was a sudden increase
in air temperature that quickly raised the water temperature from
the 50s to the 70s, which then triggered aggressive spawning among
the carp. The first occurrences of carp deaths were in the
Chesapeake, then moved into the Potomac and other waterways. The
spreading of bacteria from one fish to another occurs primarily
during spawning, which also lowers their disease resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spawning stress, population density and weather conditions _
particularly the sudden hot spell during the second week of May _
seem to be the most plausible factors involved with reducing
tolerance to this ubiquitous pathogen,'' Poukish said.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no formal carp population count, and some
researchers said they suspected that the carp population had
reached a critically high density. Some fishermen have said they
believe the deaths may be helpful to the overgrown carp population
and give other species better access to food.
</P>
<P>
   Poukish also suggested that the carp might have been more
vulnerable because of reduced dissolved oxygen levels and organic
pollution, particularly high nitrites.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the carp deaths, most other fish throughout the bay
region seem to be healthy. But there is still concern by
environment officials that other fish could become vulnerable to
bacterial stress factors, so testing continues, including testing
for viruses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a natural part of the environment, and a natural
thinning process _ maybe,'' said Ana Baya, a fish disease expert at
the University of Maryland researching the carp deaths. ``The
catfish are also affected to a lesser extent and, like the carp,
are also bottom-feeders.''
</P>
<P>
   All freshwater fish species can be affected, or killed, by the
bacteria suspected, environment officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those who live relatively close to the waterways,
pollution is a significant factor, so don't fertilize your lawn,
which can reduce oxygen levels and increase organic pollution,''
Baya said.
</P>
<P>
   Baya and Poukish said they believed the ospreys, bald eagles and
the great blue heron _ all fish-eating birds _ were not affected by
the carp deaths at this point. Part of the birds' protection is
that the bacteria that kills the fish are soon consumed by other
bacteria. Still, because all freshwater fish species can be
affected by the bacteria, ``this is raising a red flag to us,''
Poukish said. Moreover, carp breed all summer, so transmission may
continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
