<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-WIMBLEDON-OFFTHECOURT     07-01 1636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-OFFTHECOURTS0702-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wimbledon off the courts
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ We could call this story Martina's World.
</P>
<P>
   Martina Hingis is young and pretty and the No. 1-ranked women's
tennis player in the land. She earns millions a year, owns homes in
Florida and Switzerland, travels to glamorous cities every week and
strikes seductive poses for international magazines regularly.
</P>
<P>
   She's dated a handful of tennis players, a Tampa Bay hockey
player and recently declared her newest squeeze _ second-ranked
men's player Magnus Norman _ ``very shaggable'' in a London
tabloid. He called her ``my rock.''
</P>
<P>
   But when professional tennis arrives on its biggest stage of the
year at the All England Club, Hingis is looking over her shoulder.
Fellow inhabitants of this world are trying hard to unseat her from
every aspect of her dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Wise Lindsay Davenport wants Hingis' ranking; tease Anna
Kournikova wants her endorsements; newcomers Venus and Serena
Williams want her Grand Slam titles; ingenue Alexandra Stevenson
wants her spotlight; tell-all author Nathalie Tauziat wants it all
to end, all but the tennis talk, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Romance, jealousy, intrigue, beautiful women, hunky men and
outrageous parents. Add in charges of hazing, racism, arrogance and
even hetero-sexism, plus a few racy newspapers, and suddenly the
sport of tennis turns into a maze of intertwining and neverending
storylines more fit for ``The Young and the Restless'' than the
sports pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soap opera's certainly the right word for it,'' said veteran
tennis writer and NBC commentator Bud Collins. ``We don't have
anything like it in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   ROMANCES
</P>
<P>
   It begins when 128 men and 128 women come together for a
tournament _ each with their egos, coaches, parents, friends and
families.
</P>
<P>
   It becomes the grandest Grand Slam for many reasons: royal
traditions, agonizing rain delays, questionable food, limited
practice facilities, less than ideal lodgings and, most
importantly, tabloid journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unlike any other tournament,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Photographers trail players. Reporters aren't far behind,
sniffing for ``background'' stories because readers will already
know the match winners by morning, said longtime tennis writer John
Roberts, who works for The Independent, a regular daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than just a sporting event,'' Roberts said. ``It's
the one time of the year that women who stay at home, their
husbands' shirts don't get ironed. It becomes like a serial. The
players become the characters for a fortnight. And the scores are
the least of it.''
</P>
<P>
   If all this doesn't lead to fights, it might lead to love.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis and Norman, the highest-ranking couple on the tour,
aren't the only ones finding romance and making headlines in
England. Pete Sampras recently got engaged to actress Bridgette
Wilson, and she's been besieged by photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi doesn't talk much about girlfriend Steffi Graf, but
they've been on practice courts together and she watches his
matches from the stands. Kournikova coldly disallows any discussion
of her love life, even though she's wearing a big diamond on her
left hand and has been photographed waltzing around London
hand-in-hand with NHL player Sergei Fedorov.
</P>
<P>
   Younger players involved in relationships haven't yet mastered
interview evasion skills. Belgian Kim Clijsters fretted about
missing her beloved Lleyton Hewitt's first-round ejection. Jennifer
Capriati admitted her Belgian love, Xavier Malisse, has helped her
serve and her off-court mentality.
</P>
<P>
   But even love can divide in this competitive world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I see things and my eyes light up. 'Whoa, I didn't
know,'' Serena Williams said, laughing but adding that it probably
won't happen for her. ``I'm really focusing on my career, trying to
keep that No. 1 in life. It's really hard if you get involved in a
relationship. Next thing you know, your game goes down.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis took exception to that, although it wasn't aimed
specifically at her. She zinged back that Williams isn't any sort
of an expert on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think my game went down so far,'' the top seed said.
``I'm happy with my relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Uniting men and women at Grand Slam tournaments makes tennis
player love affairs easier. Playing in a city with such devoted
reporters makes public knowledge unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's guided by tabloid journalism,'' Collins said. ``We all
like a good romance, and there have been some good ones here: the
lovebird double with Chrissie (Evert) and Jimmy (Connors) in 1974.
There used to be a lot of romances because it was a co-educational
circuit until about 1972 so you didn't have to stray far for
romance.''
</P>
<P>
   REVELATIONS
</P>
<P>
   But you also don't have to stray far for bad blood, either.
</P>
<P>
   Nathalie Tauziat published a book earlier this year _ in French
only so far _ criticizing the Women's Tennis Association for its
role in promoting Anna Kournikova for her beauty more than its
higher-ranked players for her ability. A few players got upset,
Tauziat said, but others appreciated what she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Kournikova. I think she's a nice girl,'' she said.
``But what I don't like is the whole system about people talking
only about her because she's sexy. There are other girls who are as
good or better players and they don't talk about them as much as
about her.''
</P>
<P>
   She named Davenport, Mary Pierce and Conchita Martinez as
examples.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova, however, has not changed her approach. An
advertisement featuring picture of her in a sports bra beside the
words ``Only the ball should bounce'' has been plastered all of
London for the past month. She contends her promotional work
doesn't distract her from her tennis career, although she remains
titleless in 68 career tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it must somehow take away something from me
being a tennis player,'' she said. ``I think I can help a lot of
people by doing that. I think it's very important for young women
to get the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport politely questioned Kournikova's motives, however, and
how much it helps her tennis to dominate the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really sure what her goals are. I would think it is
being a better tennis player,'' she said. ``Obviously she likes the
attention but I think she would want to win a Grand Slam title
before all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova _ who lost in the second round and woke up to
headlines like ``Kournikover! Anna said she was more than just a
bimbo, but oops she's out again'' _ insists tennis takes
precedence. She avoids reading about herself and focuses on
practicing instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to have thick skin,'' the Russian said. ``You guys are
all making everything around, not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport is the only top women's player truly absent from the
tabloids this year. She doesn't read them and doesn't care that
she's left out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those papers aren't exactly the type of publications I'm dying
to be in,'' she said, smiling. ``I can let that go.''
</P>
<P>
   Martina Navratilova, back this year in doubles, didn't want to
comment specifically on Tauziat's book because she hasn't been on
tour recently enough. But she thought the WTA ``was pushing
hetero-sexism a little bit,'' although they've backed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see the guys posing with just a flag in front of the
important parts,'' the nine-time singles champion said. ``There is
a double standard, always has been. We play a damn good game,
period. If we're sexy on top of that, fine. It should not be the
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Of greater concern were the situations involving Damir Dokic,
father of 17-year-old rising star Jelena, and American Alexandra
Stevenson's charges of racism and hazing in your first year on
tour. Dokic was taken away by police after berating reporters and
smashing a cell phone. Observers said he appeared drunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Pierce was pretty bad,'' Collins said, referring to Mary
Pierce's father. ``But this guy Dokic is a menace, it seems. He
needs help, which is sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson, meanwhile, marred her second trip to the All England
Club, a second-round loss, with her comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt badly for Alexandra Stevenson,'' Collins said. ``I
think the mother said, 'Well, let's give them something to write
about.' ``
</P>
<P>
   It worked, and while Venus and Serena Williams agree the tour
isn't immune from racism, they won't discuss names or details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here can't think in the new millennium mind,'' Serena
said. ``There is still something out there.''
</P>
<P>
   EGOS UNCHECKED
</P>
<P>
   Just plain jealousies crop up too, though, and garden-variety
disagreements _ like the argument about a practice court that led
Anne-Gaelle Sidot to tap Samantha Stevenson's cap a few weeks ago
or when John McEnroe told British TV viewers some of the women
could use a bit of humility.
</P>
<P>
   The targets, again Venus and Serena Williams, handled the
criticism well, although Venus used a bit of bravado when
discussing her reaction to McEnroe's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that Serena and I are very polite,'' she said. ``But
I believe also most of the time when Serena and I lose a match,
it's because we beat ourselves, not because the other player beat
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, meanwhile, again sounds like a pal down the street
more than a member of ``Martina's World'' on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some players need a little bit of arrogance and some players
don't,'' she said. ``I've never believed that I need to tell people
that I'm a great tennis player. But some people like to do that or
need to do that and need to feel that recognition. Everybody's
different. I see things differently from a lot of players.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
