u i BC-CONCERT-DENMARK-BOS &LR;      07-01 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCERT-DENMARK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERT TURNS TO HORROR AS EIGHT ARE CRUSHED TO DEATH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSKILDE, Denmark _ Just 10 hours after she had watched eight
people get crushed to death at a rock festival here on muddy
farmland, Tina Rasmussen was still shaking Saturday, her eyes red
from tears and lack of sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing another human being die is the worst thing in the
world,'' said the 19-year-old Danish student, shivering under a
relentlessly overcast sky, tugging gently at the stud that is
pierced through her lower lip.
</P>
<P>
   It had rained all day on the 50,000 mostly young people who
gathered Friday on this farm about 25 miles west of the Danish
capital Copenhagen, on the second day of the four-day annual rock
festival. But the rain only added to the festive atmosphere at
this, one of Europe's longest-running and biggest music shows,
which drew 170 performers and the likes of Willie Nelson, Lou Reed,
and Iron Maiden.
</P>
<P>
   Just before midnight, the carnival mood turned to horror after
the Seattle band Pearl Jam took the stage. Thousands of fans surged
forward. Eddie Vedder, the band's charismatic lead singer,
recognized the danger immediately, urging the crowd to back off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was screaming, he was scared,'' Rasmussen said. ``There was
just a panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Rasmussen said people began slipping and falling on the muddy
ground in front of the stage. But while the crowd screamed and the
band screamed, the human tide surged forward inexorably.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the crush of bodies left eight young men dead, three
fans seriously injured, and 26 more requiring hospital treatment.
Among the dead were Danish, German, Swedish, and Dutch victims,
police said. They were all in their teens or 20s. The
identification and notification process was going slowly.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy _ one of rock 'n' roll's deadliest _ cast a pall
over Denmark on what was supposed to be the biggest celebration
here in years. Saturday, the Queen of Denmark and the King of
Sweden formally opened a new $2.7 billion bridge that links their
countries for the first time and links Sweden to mainland Europe.
</P>
<P>
   With its high standard of living and low crime rate, Denmark is
an unlikely place for a tragedy of Friday's proportions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like this don't happen in Denmark,'' said Lise
Christiansen, a hotel receptionist. ``People are walking around,
just stunned. It is hard to comprehend the horror of it. As a
parent, you see your children go off to these concerts all the time
and you think nothing of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Danish prime minister, Poul Nyrup Rasmussen, told Danish TV
that ``it was a terrible and tragic accident. It is very difficult
to put words on the fact that so many young people have lost their
lives in such sinister circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival here was first held in 1971, modeled on the 1969
Woodstock concert, and it is widely known as one of the most
enjoyable of its kind in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Carsten Iversen, the festival's security chief, said the
promoters ``always have said that they wanted it to be the safest
festival, and that is very visible.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Jam canceled its Sunday show in Belgium, the last leg of
its 10-week European tour that had taken them to 26 cities in 18
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Herman Schueremans, promoter of the Werchter rock concert near
Brussels, said Pearl Jam's members were too upset to perform.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the band had issued a statement on its Web site saying
it was devastated by the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so painful,'' the band said. ``We are all waiting for
someone to wake us and say it was just a horrible nightmare. There
are absolutely no words to express our anguish in regard to the
parents and loved ones of those precious lives that were lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Festival spokesman Leif Skov said the show by the British band
The Cure, which was to follow Pearl Jam, was canceled ``out of
respect for the dead.'' But Skov said music continued on the
festival's six other stages and that the festival would go on and
conclude Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is stronger than death,'' said Skov.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Rasmussen and her friends, meanwhile, were torn over
whether to stay here or go home. Saturday, they lighted candles for
the dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what shows more respect, staying here or going
home,'' the Copenhagen teenager said, tears welling up in her raw
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, a friend she hadn't seen since the disaster
struck approached her tentatively and the two teenage girls hugged
each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're alive!'' Rasmussen cried through her sobs. ``You're
alive!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
