<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRACLE 2: METS MAUL MADDUX IN SECOND INNING
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Mets have had to be creative to beat the
Atlanta Braves. Whether it is a 15th-inning, bases-loaded single
over the outfield wall or nine two-out runs to complete a huge
comeback, the Mets are only just a little better when they win.
Everything they get is a struggle, and that is a pattern of the
Braves, the National League's reigning superpower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever team I've been with,'' said Mets pitcher Mike
Hampton, ``the Braves have been a contest _ always close games.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday the Mets did something different, grabbing a lead and
continuing to pile on. This time, it was a Mets starter who was
masterful, and a Mets offense that did all the pounding. The Mets
prevailed, 9-1, and they can move into a first-place tie with the
Braves with a victory Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter outdueled Greg Maddux, and there wasn't much
competition. Leiter worked seven innings, allowing six hits and
striking out 12, a season-high. Derek Bell had four hits, including
two doubles and a home run, and for the second game in a row, a
home run by Mike Piazza punctuated a decisive two-out rally.
</P>
<P>
   A hit batsman, passed ball and bases-loaded walk helped Atlanta
score the game's first run on Friday, and the first run Saturday
was also unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux showed off his agility, leaping to snare a check-swing
grounder from the leadoff batter Melvin Mora. Derek Bell bounced a
double over third base, and after a ground out, Mike Piazza fanned
on a sinker in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   But the pitch was wild, getting away from catcher Ferando Lunar,
and Bell raced home, sliding in headfirst as Piazza beat Lunar's
throw to first. The Mets led, 1-0, and they had only just begun.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter had boasted during spring training that after so many
seasons, he had finally found his swing. A .103 career hitter,
Leiter declared that this was the season he would belt his first
home run. He has not done that yet, and in fact he has been awful,
with just two singles in 31 at-bats (.065) before Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But after Benny Agbayani smoked a two-out bases-empty home run
into the left-field bullpen, giving the Mets a 2-0 lead in the
second, Leiter flared a single to left. Maddux had failed to retire
the pitcher, and by the time he got another out, the Mets had
scored five more runs.
</P>
<P>
   Mora lashed a double into the left-field corner, and Leiter
stopped at third. Then Bell doubled to the same spot, two runs
scored to put the Mets ahead by 4-0, and Bell clapped his hands at
second base. The right fielder has been streaky this season, but he
is officially hot again, with a 12-game hitting streak and 11 games
in a row with a run scored _ the latter a Mets record.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo came up next, and the second baseman _ who has
overtaken Houston's Craig Biggio as the leading All-Star
vote-getter at his position _ delivered. Down in the count by 0-2,
Alfonzo roped a single to left to score Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Backing up for a play at the plate, Maddux wiped his brow as he
slowly walked back to the mound. His pitches were high and he
seemed exhausted, perhaps because of the virus that had caused him
to miss Thursday's start.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching coach Leo Mazzone visited the mound, but he did not
tell Maddux to do what happened next. Maddux's first pitch to
Piazza wound up clanging off the pavilion for the center-field TV
cameras, a two-run homer that made it 7-0 Mets.
</P>
<P>
   For Piazza, the home run was his 23rd of the season, and the
runs batted in gave him 70. He now has driven in runs in his last
14 games, three games shy of the major league record held by Ray
Grimes of the 1922 Chicago Cubs. Piazza also has a 19-game hitting
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux would bat in the third, but he was through on the mound.
Maddux is having another fine season, and in a few days he will
most likely be named to his eighth All-Star team. But this was his
shortest outing in four years, as he allowed seven runs on seven
hits in his two innings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
