<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-SCREENING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 RETESTED AFTER QUESTIONABLE SCREENINGS SHOW SIGNS OF CANCER
</HEADLINE>
  By SHERRI DAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Five women who are believed to have received
second-rate mammograms from two radiologists whose licenses have
been suspended showed signs of breast cancer after being retested,
state health officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The women are among more than 11,000 patients who were examined
in the last five years by the doctors, Steven J. Bier and Mario
DiBlasio, who provided government-financed breast cancer screenings
to poor women in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The New York state health commissioner, Dr. Antonia Novello,
suspended their licenses in May, accusing them of conducting
inaccurate diagnostic tests and billing for services they did not
provide.
</P>
<P>
   After the suspensions, the State Health Department said it would
try to find the doctors' patients and retest them at state expense.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 2,100 of the 11,000 patients have been screened.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, 400 need additional testing, including the five who
showed strong indications of breast cancer, officials said. Those
five women must now have biopsies to determine if they actually do
have cancer, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Bier's lawyer, Barry Berke, said that his client had ``always
had the health and welfare of his patients as his highest
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Dr. Bier is concerned with the best interest of his
patients, he has been assisting and locating patient records to
review and has been conducting his own review of the actual
facts,'' Berke said. ``He is confident that after a full
examination of the facts as opposed to ambiguous and unreliable
statistical inferences he will be completely vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   DiBlasio, when reached by telephone Saturday, said that he had
been unaware of the findings involving the five women _ which were
reported Saturday in The Daily News and The New York Post _ but
would not comment further.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier interviews he said that he was being unfairly
maligned by the state.
</P>
<P>
   John Signor, a spokesman for the Health Department, said it was
not clear if the five women whose tests displayed indications of
breast cancer developed their conditions before or after the two
doctors screened them. But, he said, the poor quality of Bier's
mammograms was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through law enforcement we received about 300 mammograms done
by Dr. Biers' office, and our experts have reviewed those and
basically found them to be totally inadequate, which raises other
concerns,'' Signor said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
