<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUARDIAN-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUARDIAN ANGELS SHIFT FOCUS TO CHILDREN AND INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Guardian Angels, once known for patrolling the
New York subways and making citizen arrests, are entering their
third decade with several updated programs, including a patrol that
monitors the Internet, crime prevention for young children and a
squad that wears, instead of the trademark red beret, crimson
bicycle helmets.
</P>
<P>
   Angels are even available in the in-line skater version, in
Central Park on weekends, according to group organizers.
</P>
<P>
   When the Guardian Angels began patrolling the ``Muggers
Express,'' also know as New York's No. 4 subway train, in 1979,
they drew the animosity of the transit police and of public
officials, who called them vigilantes. Their credibility was hurt
when Curtis Sliwa, head of the group, said that they had faked
several of their crime-fighting exploits.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, calls from the public have centered more on keeping
children out of trouble with gangs or drug dealers, Sliwa said, so
the Angels' 150 patrollers are no longer the group's main focus.
</P>
<P>
   Cyberangels, the group's Web site, fields ``a group of highly
skilled and highly motivated volunteers over the age of 18, who
virtually patrol the Internet looking for child pornography,
stalkers, child predators, groups advocating child abuse and
pedophilia, hate and bigotry sites and scam artists,'' according to
the site, www.cyberangels.org. In all, 5,000 volunteers work on the
site, Sliwa said.
</P>
<P>
   Through its Urban Angels program, the group mentors children
ages 8 to 15 teaching them character development and communication
skills, and arranging for them to do volunteer work in their
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem is no longer teens, but kids ages 8 to 15, and
what to do to keep them from becoming troublemakers,'' Sliwa said.
``We could continue with the patrols, but that's not where the need
was.''
</P>
<P>
   The Guardian Angels have branched out, with chapters in Japan,
Sweden, England _ where an all-woman contingent patrols the London
subway system _ and 28 cities in the United States, Sliwa said.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, Angel recruits are still trained in self-defense
and physical conditioning, legal issues, and first aid, including
CPR. No alcohol, drugs or weapons are allowed, and a young man in
an Angels T-shirt routinely frisks Sliwa, and others, when they go
in to the group's headquarters on Eighth Avenue near 46th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still focus on the adversarial reaction people had to
us earlier, and say, `Are you still vigilantes?''' Sliwa said.
``Clearly, we're not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
