A0771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FIREWORKS-TOXIC-NYT &LR;      07-01 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREWORKS-TOXIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCH OUT FOR THE ROCKET'S RED GLARE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM LUBELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those patriotic fireworks displays of light, color and noise may
also be explosions of toxic particulates, an environmental magazine
reports.
</P>
<P>
   The Earth Island Journal, a quarterly magazine published by the
San Francisco-based Earth Island Institute, says in an article in
its summer issue that aerial displays can generate increased levels
of airborne arsenic, cadmium, mercury, lead, copper, zinc and
chromium. Citing a Swedish technical journal, the article links
airborne chemical particulates to lung cancer and heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the most noted study of the effects of
fireworks displays on public health was conducted by the
Environmental Protection Agency on July 4, 1976, in St. Louis.
Taking atmospheric samples near the site where a large fireworks
display was held that night, the EPA found the total concentration
of fine particulate matter in the air after fireworks was about
twice that of the morning's measurement. The level of arsenic was
found to be more than 28 times the level detected 12 hours before,
and the level of the toxic element antimony about 200 times the
previous level.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists differ on how to interpret such data.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a threat,'' said Philip K. Hopke, chairman of the
chemistry department at Clarkson University and a member of the
EPA's Strategies Advisory Committee. ``For those susceptible, it
could be another insult that could really hurt them. It's a real
possibility.'' Those susceptible include people with
cardiopulmonary illnesses or asthma, and children, whose immune
systems may not be able to fight off the effects of short-term
exposure to airborne particulates.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, says Jonathan M. Samet, co-author of a report
by the Health Effects Institute in Cambridge, Mass., which studied
the correlation between microscopic air pollutants and
cardiopulmonary-related deaths in 90 American cities, ``We don't
really know what the effects are of short-term exposure for these
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks makers strongly object to charges about their
products' safety. John Steinberg, president of the Pyrotechnics
Guild International, said that the industry is ``very highly
regulated'' and that ``fireworks made in or imported into the
U.S.A. must exclude harmful chemicals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
