<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0777 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-1STLD-     07-01 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 TOUR RIDERS BANNED AS ARMSTRONG BEGINS TITLE DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS for updating thruout) 
By SAMUEL ABT  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUTUROSCOPE, France _ With a strong but not dominating ride,
Lance Armstrong opened the defense of his championship Saturday in
a Tour de France that was shaken just hours before the start by the
ouster of three riders for failing a blood test that hints at the
use of illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of all three time trials in the last Tour, Armstrong
finished second Saturday. The man ahead of him, by two seconds over
a 16.5-kilometer (10-mile) flat course, was David Millar, 23, a
Scot riding in his first Tour de France. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Millar, who rides for the Cofidis team in France, was both
thrilled and overwhelmed by his victory, bursting into tears when
Armstrong, the U.S. leader of the U.S. Postal Service team and the
last man to start, crossed the line. ``I don't believe it,'' Millar
said, looking sincere in his disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot not to believe as the 87th Tour began its
three-week, 3,660-kilometer (2,274-mile) journey counterclockwise
around France. The three disqualifications and the shadow they cast
over the Tour ranked atop the list.
</P>
<P>
   With no immediate right of appeal, the riders were suspended
from the sport for 15 days by the International Cycling Union,
which governs the sport. About a half-dozen riders have been
similarly punished each year since the blood tests were introduced
in 1997, but this was a first in the Tour de France, the world's
most prestigious bicycle race.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Marie Leblanc, who directs the race, said: ``I'm glad the
cheaters were caught. This shows that the rules are working.''
Similar views were expressed by other officials, who seemed
determined not to have the case blight opening day.
</P>
<P>
   The race was disrupted and nearly collapsed in 1998 when a drug
scandal resulted in the expulsion of one team and the withdrawal of
five others to protest police searches for illegal
performance-enhancing drugs. Since then, the Tour and the sport
itself have attempted to regain public confidence by developing new
tests to detect drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The riders disqualified Saturday are Sergei Ivanov, 25, who won
the Russian national championship last Sunday for the second
consecutive year; Rossano Brasi, 28, an Italian, and Andrei
Hauptman, 25, a Slovene. Ivanov rides for the Farm Frites team from
the Netherlands, Brasi for the Polti team from Italy and Hauptman
for the Vini Caldirola team from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the disqualifications followed by a day a
public warning by Leblanc that any rider tempted to use drugs in
the Tour was ``playing with fire and risking his reputation.''
Although blood tests can be administered at any time during the
race, the one Saturday was part of the official schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test was no surprise, no secret,'' said Martin Bruin, a
Dutchman who heads the drug inspection team sent to the Tour by the
International Cycling Union, which governs the sport. ``The test
was scheduled and everybody knew we were coming to test them.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors, whom the riders always refer to as ``the vampires,''
arrived at each of the 20 teams' hotels between 7 and 8:45 saturday
morning to draw blood from the crook of each rider's arm.
</P>
<P>
   The blood is tested to determine the hematocrit level _ the
number of red corpuscles. A level higher than 50 percent sends a
rider home for two weeks ``to regain his health,'' as the rules put
it since the International Cycling Union insists that the
inspection is a health test, not one for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a hematocrit level above 50 percent indicates the
use of EPO, an artificial hormone developed for patients on kidney
dialysis to increase their red-blood corpuscles. These carry oxygen
to muscles and thus increase performance in such endurance sports
as bicycle racing, rowing, marathon running and long-distance
skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 180 riders tested Saturday morning was, of course,
Millar, who is an outspoken advocate of clean racing. He is also a
fine time-trialer and was among a handful of favorites for this
first of 21 daily stages since he won a similar race against the
clock _ flat and nearly the same distance _ two weeks ago in the
Route du Sud, his final preparation race.
</P>
<P>
   Just Friday night, having a beer with some friends, he was
marveling at the size and scope of the Tour de France, which he was
seeing for the first time. ``I can't believe it,'' he said,
unknowingly rehearsing his speech before he donned the leader's
yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The Scot, who was born on Malta and reared in Hong Kong because
his father is a commercial airline pilot, said afterward that he
hoped to stay in that jersey at least through the team time trial
on Tuesday. ``And we've got a strong team, so we should do well
there, too,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   He finished the stage in 19 minutes 3 seconds and said he was
hoping to break 18 minutes over the straightforward course in cool
and overcast weather. Armstrong was two seconds slower, with
Laurent Jalabert, a Frenchman with ONCE, third, 13 seconds behind
the winner, and Jan Ullrich, a German with Telekom who won the Tour
in 1997, fourth, 14 seconds late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed,'' Armstrong said, ``but I'm happy
that David won. He's a good friend of mine and a good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the favorites who lost more than a minute were Franck
Vandenbroucke, a Belgian with Cofidis; Bobby Julich, an American
with Credit Agricole; Michael Boogerd, a Dutchman with Rabobank,
and Richard Virenque, a Frenchman with Polti. Marco Pantani, an
Italian with Mercatone Uno and the winner of the 1998 Tour, lost
more than two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Two familiar faces were missing from the race. Chris Boardman,
an Englishman with Credit Agricole and the winner of three opening
races, was not entered by his team because of illness. And Mario
Cipollini, an Italian with Saeco and the king of the sprinters, did
not show up either, enabling his replacement, Daniel Atienza, a
Spaniard, to finish in 158th place among the 177 starters.
</P>
</TEXT>
