towns of the West that turned to shells once they were stripped of
their gold, new ghost towns are sprouting over much of the Great
Plains. Despite an economic boom throughout much of the U.S., all
that remains for Warsaw, North Dakota's 40 or 50 citizens,
descendants of Polish immigrants, is the one bar, Tork's Polski
Dom, and at the corner of two county roads, the surreal
100-year-old St. Stanislaus Roman Catholic Church. Irene Durey has
been taking care of the sacristy in Saint Stanislaus since 1984.
(Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
