   (NYT6) ARDOCH, N.D. -- July 1, 2000 -- DYING-TOWNS-4 -- In North
Dakota and well beyond, across thousands of old rural towns in the
broad belly of the Plains from Eastern Montana and Western
Minnesota and the Canadian border down through Nebraska into Kansas
and Oklahoma, the nation's long run of growth and prosperity has
blown right by. In Ardoch, N.D., population 49, the city hall is
padlocked, its windows boarded, its electricity meter still, its
clapboard facade unpainted for decades. Ardoch is among the
withering rural communities in the northeastern corner of North
Dakota. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MOUNTAIN, N.D. -- July 1, 2000 -- DYING-TOWNS-3 -- In
Mountain, N.D., the forces of decline have chased away the
optimistic spirit of America. Buffeted by debt, the lowest wheat
prices in 30 years and seven years of ruinous drought and floods,
the inertia of decline has begun to intrude on small town life
throughout much of the Great Plains. Leslie Geir, 47, with two of
his three children, Chris, 15, left, and Laura, 10, on their farm
in Mountain, N.D., established by his great-grandfather. To make
ends meet, Geir's wife Delores is an aide in the home for the
elderly, and daughter Diane works there part time. All the Geirs
still have hope. Chris intends to be a farmer, and Diane hopes to
settle on a farm. ``There is no better place to raise a family,''
says Leslie Geir. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
