<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME MATCHES TURN INTO MARATHONS; CAPRIATI CAN STOP THE MUSIC;
SELES HAS BEEN THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ The witnesses to two epic matches Saturday
left the All England Club with their tennis appetites sufficiently
stuffed. Just after Mark Philippoussis broke the tension on Court 2
by winning with a near record 20-18 fifth set, Martina Navratilova
exited the grounds after losing the final set of her wrenching
mixed doubles match, 18-16.
</P>
<P>
   Each match dripped with drama. The end to Philippoussis' day
finally arrived when the backhand return by Sjeng Schalken died
into the net to end a 5 hour 1 minute match that was over after a
fifth set that lasted 2:15.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was the longest match in memory to be played on one
day, the finish fell short of the 46 total games for a set that
Nicola Pietrangeli and Nikki Pilic needed to end a second-round
match in 1962. The epic third-round victory by Philippoussis ended
with this mind-boggling score: 4-6, 6-3, 6-7 (7), 7-6 (4), 20-18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hung in there, and stayed mentally tough,'' said
Philippoussis, who served 44 aces in the match. Afterward, Tim
Henman, who won in straight sets Saturday, smiled as he asked
Philippoussis, ``What took you so long?''
</P>
<P>
   The length of the day was far more than Navratilova bargained
for when she decided to return to Wimbledon after a five-year
absence to play doubles. Earlier in the afternoon, she and her
doubles partner, Mariaan de Swardt, won a three-set match. As
darkness fell, Navratilova and her mixed doubles partner, Mahesh
Bhupathi, were locked into a three-hour drama against Jan Siemerink
and Miriam Oremans. On match point, Bhupathi sent a backhand into
the net to finish off the evening 6-4, 6-7 (5), 18-16.
</P>
<P>
   The break for Philippoussis came at 18-18 when he converted on a
triple break point with an inside-outside forehand down the line.
He then served out for the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always considered myself a fighter,'' said Philippoussis
who will play Henman in the next round. ``That was a good match for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   CAPRIATI CAN STOP THE MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   As a band played during a nearby Center Court ceremony, an
irritated Jennifer Capriati was morphing into the parent of a teen
on Court 3: Hey, turn it down. She could not concentrate on Yayuk
Basuki.
</P>
<P>
   Down by 5-2 in the first set of her third round match, Capriati
called for a referee and asked that someone cut off the band that
was escorting in the past champions during a parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, `What's going on? Can they turn off the
music?,''' Capriati said. ``He said they were pretty much done in
10 minutes. I said, `Well, in 10 minutes, I could be down a set and
a half already. I don't have 10 minutes to spare.' He just said
that he'd do his best.'''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the music stopped, and Capriati began to play.
She staged a blistering rally to take over the match and barge past
Basuki 7-6 (4), 6-0. Basuki told reporters from Indonesia that she
was displeased when Capriati interrupted play to call a referee,
and believe she showed disrespect by breaking her momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fair,'' Capriati said. ``I have every right to call the
referee. It was on a changeover. It's as important as calling for
an injury timeout to me. It stopped the music, so I'm not concerned
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati is concentrating on recouping her game after her
first-round exit at the French Open. Her next step will be
difficult. In the round of 16, she will face second-seeded Lindsay
Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The previous time I played her, I came close,'' said Capriati,
who lost to Davenport 6-3, 2-6, 6-3 in February.
</P>
<P>
   SELES HAS BEEN THERE
</P>
<P>
   Although she is considered one of the best-liked players on the
Tour now, Monica Seles can somewhat relate to the hazing
experiences Alexandra Stevenson said she encountered during her
rookie year on the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my first year, there were two players on the Tour, and
for whatever reason, they didn't like me,'' Seles said without
naming names. ``They were the players who talked a lot on the Tour
to other players. I was 14 or 15, really in my own shell. I just
said, `Hi,' and `Bye,' and looked down at the floor. I was very
shy. I think that's how people perceived me in the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I was 18, they realized I was different. I changed
probably as a person, too. I was much more open. I wasn't as shy as
I was when I was 14.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
