first in the country Saturday to legally take on all the rights and
responsibilities of marriage, in the first state to let them.
Margaret Picard, left, the city clerk, issued a civil union license
on Saturday to Lois Farnham, center, and Holly Puterbaugh in South
Burlington, Vt. (Paul O. Boisvert/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WARSAW, N.D. -- July 1, 2000 -- DYING-TOWNS-5 -- Like
towns of the West that turned to shells once they were stripped of
their gold, new ghost towns are sprouting over much of the Great
Plains. Despite an economic boom throughout much of the U.S., all
that remains for Warsaw, North Dakota's 40 or 50 citizens,
descendants of Polish immigrants, is the one bar, Tork's Polski
Dom, and at the corner of two county roads, the surreal
100-year-old St. Stanislaus Roman Catholic Church. Irene Durey has
been taking care of the sacristy in Saint Stanislaus since 1984.
(Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ARDOCH, N.D. -- July 1, 2000 -- DYING-TOWNS-4 -- In North
Dakota and well beyond, across thousands of old rural towns in the
broad belly of the Plains from Eastern Montana and Western
Minnesota and the Canadian border down through Nebraska into Kansas
and Oklahoma, the nation's long run of growth and prosperity has
blown right by. In Ardoch, N.D., population 49, the city hall is
padlocked, its windows boarded, its electricity meter still, its
clapboard facade unpainted for decades. Ardoch is among the
withering rural communities in the northeastern corner of North
Dakota. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MOUNTAIN, N.D. -- July 1, 2000 -- DYING-TOWNS-3 -- In
Mountain, N.D., the forces of decline have chased away the
optimistic spirit of America. Buffeted by debt, the lowest wheat
prices in 30 years and seven years of ruinous drought and floods,
the inertia of decline has begun to intrude on small town life
throughout much of the Great Plains. Leslie Geir, 47, with two of
his three children, Chris, 15, left, and Laura, 10, on their farm
in Mountain, N.D., established by his great-grandfather. To make
ends meet, Geir's wife Delores is an aide in the home for the
elderly, and daughter Diane works there part time. All the Geirs
still have hope. Chris intends to be a farmer, and Diane hopes to
settle on a farm. ``There is no better place to raise a family,''
says Leslie Geir. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MOUNTAIN, N.D. -- July 1, 2000 -- DYING-TOWNS-2 -- Like
towns of the West that turned to shells once they were stripped of
their gold, new ghost towns are sprouting over much of the Great
Plains. In North Dakota and well beyond, across thousands of old
rural towns in the broad belly of the Plains from Eastern Montana
and Western Minnesota and the Canadian border down through Nebraska
into Kansas and Oklahoma, the nation's long run of growth and
prosperity has blown right by. In Mountain, N.D., a rural community
of people of Icelandic descent, farming is the primary way of life,
but the farmers are struggling. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WHITMAN, N.D. -- July 1, 2000 -- DYING-TOWNS-1 -- In
North Dakota and well beyond, across thousands of old rural towns
in the broad belly of the Plains from Eastern Montana and Western
Minnesota and the Canadian border down through Nebraska into Kansas
and Oklahoma, the nation's long run of growth and prosperity has
blown right by. Like towns of the West that turned to shells once
they were stripped of their gold, new ghost towns are sprouting
over much of the Great Plains. In Whitman, N.D., small-town way of
life is faltering with shuttered buildings on Main Street. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) YOUNSTOWN, Ohio -- July 1, 2000 -- PRISON-EXPERIMENT-2 --
Five prisons operate in Youngstown, Ohio, with about 40,000
inmates. Many of the prisoners are young fathers with plenty of
time to ponder long lists of regrets, with their children, often
little known and less seen, at the top of those lists. At the
Northeastern Ohio Correctional Center, a new social experiment is
underway. Sharing thoughts and meals, prison officials and inmates
tested a program, as merciful as it is experimental, to let 11
children and their imprisoned fathers directly repair family ties.
Byron Gant working on a poster with his daughter, Daterria. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) YOUNSTOWN, Ohio -- July 1, 2000 -- PRISON-EXPERIMENT-1 --
Five prisons operate in Youngstown, Ohio, with about 40,000
inmates. Many of the prisoners are young fathers with plenty of
time to ponder long lists of regrets, with their children, often
little known and less seen, at the top of those lists. At the
Northeastern Ohio Correctional Center, a new social experiment is
underway. Sharing thoughts and meals, prison officials and inmates
tested a program, as merciful as it is experimental, to let 11
children and their imprisoned fathers directly repair family ties.
DeWayne Mixon, a 32-year-old convict in his sixth year of a
nine-year assault sentence, playing with his son Diamond. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
