A0788 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-ERDOS-NYT &LR;      07-01 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ERDOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUL ERDOS, AUTHORITY ON MAIL SURVEYS DEAD AT 86 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC PACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paul Erdos, a long-time market research executive who
was an authority on mail surveys, died on Wednesday at his home in
Manhattan. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Erdos and Arthur Morgan founded Erdos &AMP; Morgan, a
Manhattan-based market research firm, in 1947. It was the first
marketing research organization to specialize in mail surveys. In
1988, Advertising Age called it ``one of the best-known names in
print audience research.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling Erdos, Don Dillman, the Thomas S. Foley Distinguished
Professor of Government and Public Policy at Washington State
University, said, ``I was always impressed with how `people
oriented' he seemed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Dillman, who is also the president-elect of the American
Association for Public Opinion Research, said Erdos seemed to be
``treating each recipient of his mail questionnaires as someone
from whom he needed help, rather than using the utilitarian
approach of `How can I get them to do what I want them to do?'''
</P>
<P>
   With assistance from Morgan, Erdos wrote a book, ``Professional
Mail Surveys.'' It was first published in 1970, when Erdos &AMP;
Morgan's long-standing clients included The National Geographic
Society, Time Inc., Dow Jones and U.S. Steel. In 1988, Advertising
Age called it ``the best-selling, most authoritative text on mail
survey research.''
</P>
<P>
   On Page 1 of the book, Erdos wrote: ``The basic distinction
between mail and other types of surveys is the fact that in
surveying by mail there is no person to ask the questions and guide
the respondent. This gives rise to important differences in survey
design, questionnaire construction, and various other aspects of
the survey. These differences result in some advantages and some
shortcomings.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Erdos and Morgan won the Charles Coolidge Parlin Award,
a market research honor awarded by the Philadelphia chapter of the
American Marketing Association and the Wharton School of the
University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, an article in a publication of the Philadelphia
chapter said the two men had done ``pioneering work in mail survey
methodology.'' ``Erdos and Morgan were selected for the Parlin
Award on the basis of their techniques which have made mail survey
data gathering effective, establishing new standards for response
rates,'' the article added. ``On their mailings, they average a 60
percent response rate, and in some instances have received over 80
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Morgan resigned as executive vice president of Erdos &AMP;
Morgan, and it was acquired in 1988 by Jerome Kossoff, owner and
president of Beta Research Corp. of Syosset, N.Y. Erdos stayed with
the firm and retired several years later.
</P>
<P>
   Erdos was born in Budapest and grew up there. He studied at the
University of Heidelberg, Germany _ where he met Morgan _ and at
universities in Switzerland, France and Britain. In 1937 he
received a doctorate in philosophy from the University of Pecs,
Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Fleeing Hitler's army in World War II, Erdos moved to New York
in 1939 after working in publishing in Hungary and Italy. In New
York he held jobs as a literary agent, in market research,
publishing and data processing and was with Fact Finders Inc., a
market research firm, from 1942 to 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Erdos and Helen Mero were married in 1950, and she died in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Erdos is survived by a stepdaughter, Kathleen Mero Mogul of
Newton, Mass.; and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 1826EDT &QL; 
