<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0789 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-WIMBLEDON-MEN0702-COX     07-01 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-MEN0702-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Philippoussis survives, Sampras and Agassi advance
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ When Tim Henman took the court for his
third-round match Saturday afternoon at Wimbledon, Mark
Philippoussis and Sjeng Schalken were just beginning the fifth set
of their match.
</P>
<P>
   When Henman walked off the court a 6-3, 6-3, 6-3 winner against
Hicham Arazi, Philippoussis and Schalken still were playing that
fifth set.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, five hours and one minute after they'd started, 10th
seed Philippoussis emerged the victor of the second-longest men's
singles match on record. He won 4-6, 6-3, 6-7 (7-9), 7-6 (7-4),
20-18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came off at 16-all,'' Henman said after his one-hour,
47-minute win. ``I just said to Philippoussis, `What took you so
long? I played my match in one set of yours.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Australian chuckled as he recounted the story later, but
when it happened, he wasn't laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was bleeding, had blood on my shorts, felt like I'd just
been punched to death for five hours,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Philippoussis survived the closest call of the day, as top seed
Pete Sampras, second seed Andre Agassi, eighth seed Tim Henman and
12th seed Patrick Rafter all advanced into the fourth round. Fourth
seed Gustavo Kuerten was the only player upset.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras entered his match with Justin Gimelstob amid questions
about his health but afterward remained the favorite to win the
title. He had limped through his second round because of an
inflamed left shin tendon, then spent two straight days icing and
treating the injury.
</P>
<P>
   When he took Centre Court, it showed that he also hadn't been
near a court in two days. He started with four straight
doublefaults and lost the set 6-2 in 24 minutes before surging back
to win 6-4, 6-2, 6-2 in two hours, seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I was really out of sorts in the beginning,'' Sampras
said. ``I looked up and saw (Bjorn) Borg and the Rocket (Rod
Laver). At one point I wanted to throw my racket up there; they
could play for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Borg and Laver, heroes of Sampras as a child, had attended
an earlier Champions' Parade celebrating the 2000 championships;
Sampras had skipped it because he needed to ice his leg. He joined
a briefer ceremony later with other players who had been on the
court for the main program.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi also won easily, defeating Jerome Golmard 6-3, 6-3, 6-4.
He next meets David Prinosil. Sampras plays Jonas Bjorkman in the
fourth round. While Sampras expects to struggle with the leg injury
for the rest of the fortnight, Agassi said he's playing more
purposefully this year than he was a year ago, when he lost the
final to Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I was riding momentum,'' the 1999 French Open winner
said. ``This year I'm building a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   Philippoussis, on the other hand, next plays Henman, the great
British hope. He isn't concerned about recovering physically from
his five-hour match and isn't haunted by the injury he sustained
last year on Centre Court.
</P>
<P>
   Philippoussis had won the first set from Sampras in a
quarterfinal match and looked on course to win the match, when he
tore knee cartilage in a freak injury. He's forgotten that this
year, he said, and instead relies on the knowledge of his increased
devotion to practice and his career overall as motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the training I've done paid off,'' he said in relief.
``That got me through the match. It's simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
