<HEADER>
A0795 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BRIDGE-SCANDANAVIA-BO     07-01 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGE-SCANDANAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BRIDGE LINKS SWEDEN, DENMARK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN _ When Queen Margrethe of Denmark and King Carl
Gustaf of Sweden met Saturday in the middle of a new $2.7 billion
bridge and tunnel complex, it marked the first time since the Ice
Age some 7,000 years ago that their two countries have been linked.
</P>
<P>
   The Danish prime minister, Poul Nyrup Rasmussen, and his Swedish
counterpart, Goeran Persson, looked like long-separated brothers
when they greeted each other on a man-made island called Peberholm
in the 10-mile stretch of water that divides the countries.
</P>
<P>
   But while the royals and the politicians are literally embracing
each other as the last piece of Europe becomes linked to the
mainland, getting ordinary Danes and Swedes to enthusiastically
embrace the concept of Nordic and European unity is a little
harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that bridge will bring us is more drunken Swedes,'' said
Jens Olesen, a street sweeper in Copenhagen, as he sat in a bar
here Thursday night, watching Italy defeat Holland to gain a spot
in Sunday's European soccer championship final against France.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, the Danes and Swedes fought each other, feeding
ancient animosities that seem anachronistic today when both
countries are affluent, influential members of the 15-nation
European Union. Scania, the southwest region of Sweden that is now
linked by the bridge, was part of Denmark for 800 years until 1658.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedes and Danes share a skepticism about the single
European currency that led them to join Britain as the only
European Union members purposely to stay out of its launch last
year. But Scandinavians love to tell you how different they are
from each other.
</P>
<P>
   Lotte Vandel, an ethnologist who studies the differences between
ethnic groups in Scandinavia, said Swedes and Danes are equally
prejudiced against each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stereotypes are well worn,'' she said. ``Swedes are
boring, stiff and always drunk. The Danes are happy, funny and
informal. We make an excellent couple because we embrace the
stereotypes of each other so enthusiastically. This is a very
impressive bridge, but a bridge can't eliminate stereotypes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, by any measure, the bridge they call Oeresund after the
strait of water that both separates and unites Denmark and Sweden
is a remarkable achievement. It took seven years to build and is
the 10th longest bridge in the world, linking the Danish capital
with Malmoe, Sweden's third largest city. The bridge has created a
new European region, called Oeresund, which with 3.5 million people
ranks in size with the Hamburg, Barcelona, and Amsterdam regions.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge is the central part of an ambitious physical and
psychological effort to bridge the last gap between continental
Europe and Scandinavia, an experiment in how far the European
Union's determination to mix and blur national identities of its
members can go without stirring up resentment that could doom the
goal of European integration.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the magnificent mock-Renaissance city hall called
Radhus, Copenhagen Mayor Jens Kramer Mikkelsen predicted the bridge
will be a success. He said that while Danes and Swedes have a
tendency to dwell on what divides them, they are more like each
other than they might care to admit. Both descend from Viking
stock, and from a culture that regarded men and women as equals
long before others. Both have a generous social welfare system, and
high taxes to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Mikkelsen said those who live in the Copenhagen and Malmoe areas
speak different languages, but in a dialect that they both
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We speak the same language, really,'' he said. ``We read each
other's newspapers. What we have to do now is to build mental
bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   Ilmar Reepalu, chairman of Malmoe's city council, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a poll and found that 85 percent of Swedes and 74
percent of Danes think this bridge is a positive development. We
have to exploit this optimism. People here have got to see
themselves as residents of the Oeresund region, not just of
Copenhagen and Malmoe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But while the bridge could bring an economic windfall to the
region, its steep toll prices are seen by some as prohibitive. It
costs about $33 for cars one-way and about $100 for trucks,
although a train ride costs about $8.
</P>
<P>
   Mette Kirk, a Danish ethnologist who interviewed hundreds of
people on both sides of the bridge, said the politicians are overly
optimistic about the bridge's ability to bring ordinary Danes and
Swedes together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict a majority of the population will not visit the
other side, simply because it is too expensive to cross the
bridge,'' said Kirk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crucial that the politicians recognize the cultural
differences. Ignoring them would be one sure way to fail this
integration effort,'' she said. ``Swedes think that eating from a
plate in Denmark is dangerous because Danes don't rinse the dish
soap away. In Sweden, you don't forget to take your shoes off when
entering a Swedish home, and you don't ever ask for an ashtray at a
dining table. In Denmark, you don't say hello to a cashier. And you
must enjoy a beer at work on Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   While Danes frequently dismiss Swedes as drunks, Kirk said
European Union figures show that the Danes drink more and die more
from alcohol abuse than Swedes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most stereotypes, the ones we hold about each other are
frequently not backed up by facts,'' said Kirk. ``But it
underscores that we have been socialized differently. You can't
expect this to be an easy integration because we are different.''
</P>
<P>
   On the ferry, Swedes profess a nostalgia for the old days. Petra
Glimiker, a photographer, said many Swedes, who pay among the
highest prices for alcohol in the world, love the ferry because
alcohol is half-price on the seas. ``Touring'' is a euphemism for
drinking on the ferry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have taken touring away from us,'' Glimiker said. ``It's
terrible. My uncle is so depressed. He loved to go touring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
