<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
  
 MEXICANS VOTE  Sunday IN WHAT COULD UPSET 71-YEAR PRI RULE
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ For months, 60 million voters in this country have
been told repeatedly that this year's presidential election will be
the cleanest and fairest in Mexico's corruption-riddled history.
</P>
<P>
   Now they'll know the truth.
</P>
<P>
   As Mexicans go to the polls Sunday to decide their closest
presidential race in a century, they know there is more than just
political pride at stake. The vote will also be a testament of how
far Mexico has come as an open democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my candidate and I'll vote for him,'' said Rosa
Munguia, 28, a marketing assistant who chose to keep her preference
a secret. ``But the most important thing is that the process be
clean, and I think it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Many share Munguia's hopes for a relatively fraud-free vote,
mostly because of the confidence they have in a new electoral
agency and tribunal that are independent from the government and
responsible for keeping things clean Sunday. Both the agency and
tribunal have assured voters they will be impartial.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there will be more than 4,000 national and
international observers and thousands more domestic and foreign
journalists who will be closely monitoring the balloting process.
</P>
<P>
   But there continued to be some lingering doubt, even in the
final days leading up to Sunday's vote, over whether Mexico's
political machines were trying to coerce voters.
</P>
<P>
   Alianza Civica, the nation's largest watchdog group, said in a
report released Friday that its observers had received 288
complaints of pressure tactics by Mexico's three largest parties.
More than three-quarters of the complaints were against the
governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   A separate report issued last week by the Atlanta-based Carter
Center concluded that the chances for widespread fraud were slight.
</P>
<P>
   But, the study added, episodes of small-scale fraud could affect
Sunday's vote by one or two percentage points, a significant amount
given that recent opinion polls have shown the race a statistical
tie between PRI candidate Francisco Labastida Ochoa and Vicente
Quesada Fox, the leading opposition candidate of a center-right
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Another leading candidate, former Mexico City mayor Cuahtemoc
Cardenas, of the center-left coalition, is expected to place a
distant third, followed by two less prominent candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike past presidential races in Mexico, which seemed more like
well-choreographed charades to keep the PRI in office, this year's
campaign has been unusually competitive and nasty, due mostly to
the battle between Labastida, a former interior minister, and Fox,
a former Coca-Cola executive and governor of Guanajuato state, who
has the best chance of breaking the PRI's 71-year grip on the
National Palace.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates themselves have been nearly invisible since
Wednesday, when Mexican electoral law required them to end their
campaigns, including all print, radio and television advertising.
Media outlets have also been prohibited from showing images of the
candidates, so that they do not appear to show favoritism for one
party over the others.
</P>
<P>
   But the corruption drama continued. Saturday, the Mexico City
daily Reforma reported that a PRI governor, Victor Tinoco Rubi of
Michoacan state, ordered $80 million in public funds to buy votes
in his state. The newspaper published parts of what it said were
transcripts of telephone conversations between Tinoco and a leading
national party official.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deny that completely,'' Tinoco told a group of foreign
correspondents via telephone during a press conference Saturday
morning. ``Reforma is only interested in tarnishing the electoral
process.''
</P>
<P>
   A prospective voter, Jesus Nunez, was preparing a batch of pork
tacos in the southern part of the capital Saturday. He shook his
head slowly in disgust when asked his reaction to the latest
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised, but I am sad,'' he said, wiping his hands
on a stained white apron. ``I think it shows how desperate the PRI
is, but it also shows how some things haven't changed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
