<HEADER>
A0798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TOUR-SIDE0702-COX     07-01 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-SIDE0702-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three riders suspended for suspected drug dopingBy Suzanne
Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUTUROSCOPE, France _ Last year's Tour de France was dubbed the
Tour of redemption by director Jean Marie LeBlanc, who wanted to
distance this popular international event from a drug scandal that
almost ruined it the summer before.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's Tour still got off to a poor start Saturday
morning when three riders were suspended for two weeks because of
suspected blood doping.
</P>
<P>
   The riders suspended were Sergei Ivanov, a week removed from his
Russian championship; Italy's Brasi Rossano and Slovakia's Andrey
Hauptman.
</P>
<P>
   Officials tested all 180 riders Saturday morning. The three who
failed the test weren't notified until six hours before the start
of the first stage, a 9.9-mile prologue through Futuroscope.
</P>
<P>
   The tests of the three showed abnormally high levels of
hematocrit, meaning that their percentage of red blood cells was
more than 50. This percentage usually indicates the use of the
banned hormone and blood booster EPO.
</P>
<P>
   All cyclists provided a urine sample last week. The samples are
now frozen and will be examined by a new method that supposedly can
detect the unquestioned use of EPO. These tests will get underway
in three weeks, after the Tour concludes. Officials had hoped that
the new test would be available for the start of the Tour, but knew
that the test, even scheduled now after the end of the event, would
keep cyclists from using illegal substances.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov's positive test was especially troubling to those in
cycling circles. He rides for Farm Frites, a team that was not
invited to last year's Tour as a result of doping allegations in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   TOUR BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   2:05: the margin in minutes that defending champion Lance
Armstrong owns over 1998 Tour victor Marco Pantani.
</P>
<P>
   12: the number of seconds that Armstrong's U.S. Postal Service
Team collectively owns over ONCE after the first day. USPS, which
currently has the best collective time over the rest of the 19-team
field, will be the final squad in competition in Tuesday's team
time trial if it holds its lead.
</P>
<P>
   13: the number of consecutive stages in which Armstrong owned
the overall lead, dating back to July 11, 1999. It was snapped
Saturday when Armstrong, the defending Tour champion and Austin
resident, finished second to Britain's David Millar.
</P>
<P>
   SCOUTING THE FIELD
</P>
<P>
   The local newspaper, Centre Presse, polled a variety of experts
on who they thought would be on ``the podium final'' on the last
day. Armstrong was the overwhelming favorite, garnering 16 of the
21 first-place votes. He was named second or third on five others.
Johan Bruyneel, the USPS director sportiff, declined to put his
three choices in order, but included Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Ullrich, who won the 1997 Tour and finished second in 1996
and 1998, was the predicted winner on four ballots with Pantani
receiving the other first-place vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bernald Hinault, a five-time Tour winner or ``vainqueur,''
predicted an Armstrong victory.
</P>
<P>
   TOUR TRAVELOGUE
</P>
<P>
   Futuroscope is an amusement park with a scientific theme. The
relatively new park, which was the site of last year's final time
trial, attracts about 3 million people a year.
</P>
<P>
   But the park is surrounded by history. Nearby Poitiers,
population 85,000, is the ancient capital of Poitou. Famous figures
who have passed through Poitiers include Joan of Arc and Richard
the Lion-Hearted. Because the city is on a hilltop overlooking the
Clain and Boivre rivers, it proved to be valuable strategic spot in
so many wars. Charles Martel won a battle for the Christians when
he chased away the Muslims here in 732. Edward the Black Prince of
England and King John of France battled here in 1356 as part of the
Hundred Years War. England won, with its archers using longbows to
vanquish the French.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
