<DOCNO> NYT20000701.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR-MAIN0702-COX     07-01 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-MAIN0702-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TBy Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUTUROSCOPE, France _ Lance Armstrong seemed in such a hurry
late Saturday afternoon. He tucked in his chin and willed his legs
to pump out one final sprint so he could whip past the
balloon-festooned finish line and end his 9.9-mile performance to
kick off the first stage of the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   But the defending Tour champion kept riding as a cluster of
European photographers buzzed toward him, much like a swarm of
mosquitos spotting a new victim.
</P>
<P>
   He talked to no one as he successfully dodged the crush of
cameras and sped to an awaiting gray bus painted with the stars and
bars logo of his U.S. Postal Service Team. From that point,
Armstrong could enjoy his privacy, get a much-needed massage and
eat a quiet dinner before heading to bed so he can start it all
again this afternoon with a 120 mile trek to Loudun.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 14 stages, dating back to a time trial in
Metz, a city in eastern France, another rider stepped on the podium
to accept the famed Tour leader's yellow jersey and all the
pressure that comes with wearing it.
</P>
<P>
   While Armstrong rode away to his hotel, a fresh-faced Brit
received the customary bouquet of yellow zinnias and daffodils to
commemorate his winning of stage one.
</P>
<P>
   David Millar, a 23-year-old Tour rookie, became the toast of
Great Britain after his performance in the near 10-mile time trial.
Millar, the lone English rider in the Tour who represents the
French team Cofidis, won the event in a time of 19 minutes, three
seconds. He negotiated through Futuroscope, a scientific-themed
amusement park, at nearly 32 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was in a hurry to get away from the chaos, Armstrong
was hardly disappointed with his performance.
</P>
<P>
   He was in second place, only two seconds behind Millar with a
nice cushion over his main rivals, including past Tour champions
Marco Pantani and Jan Ullrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to have won,'' Armstrong said about two
hours after the race. ``But it's a big responsibility to have the
yellow jersey. Between now and the team time trial, it's probably
better that I don't have the jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for Millar, I like him,'' he said. ``But I'm happier
that I beat the ones who are my main threats.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong had the fastest opening split and was ahead of
Millar's time until the last gentle stretch of pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Only 25 riders in the field of 177 (three riders were suspended
before the race) broke the 20-minute barrier, with Millar and
Armstrong the only two who threatened to eclipse 19 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Jalabert, the French rider who publicly said that
Armstrong had peaked too early in his training, was third, 11
seconds behind Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich, the defending world time trial champion, was fourth, 12
seconds behind Armstrong. Alex Zulle, another Tour contender, was
sixth at 19:22.
</P>
<P>
   This year's traditional prologue was lengthened by almost four
miles to give it more bite. Winning the prologue does not guarantee
a victory stroll in Paris on July 23, but it can gut a rider's
chances if he performs poorly.
</P>
<P>
   That's what seem to happen to Pantani, who won the Tour in 1998.
Pantani finished in 21:19, 2:04 behind Armstrong. He'll hope to
make up the gap once he gets to the mountain stages.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani's rust was clearly evident Saturday. He left cycling
last summer after flunking a blood doping drug test on the next to
last day of the Giro d' Italia. He had a hefty lead at the time of
his suspension. He did not start competing again until May at the
Giro after receiving a private audience with Pope John Paul II .
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service, nicknamed the Posties, fared extremely
well Saturday. Vjatceslav Ekimov's time of 19:24 held up for about
one third of the race. He finished seventh. Tyler Hamilton was
ninth at 19:36.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's Kevin Livingston was 24th at 19:59 Benoit Joachim was
34th at 20:08.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
