<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP WANTED: LAKERS LOOKING FOR POWER FORWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ The NBA ungagged its general managers,
players and agents at 12:01 a.m. Saturday, but instead of a
cacophony of wheeling and dealing, the public hears only the sound
of silence. And it will be that way, more or less, for the next 30
days.
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent season opened just after midnight Friday, but the
league has designated July a dead month for signing players, so the
results won't be known for some time _ until contracts can be
signed Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there will be no shortage of deals reportedly
reached, not necessarily with the facts to support them. And the
defending-champion Lakers will again be at the center of much
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, last July one media outlet had them supposedly signing
Charles Oakley and later Lorenzen Wright. Done deals, both of them.
Yet come August, neither player was wearing the purple and gold.
</P>
<P>
   So it will go again this month, with Glen Rice probably heading
elsewhere, and the Lakers again seeking a starting power forward
and/or backup center.
</P>
<P>
   All Laker decisions will eventually come back to Rice, who was
an awkward fit in coach Phil Jackson's system. Before the Lakers
can decide what to spend and what to seek in the free-agent market,
they'll need to decide on one of three options with Rice: re-sign
him (unlikely), let him walk away as a free agent (possible) or
sign him and trade him (most likely), perhaps for another small
forward, such as Philadelphia's Toni Kukoc, or a power forward,
such as Miami's P.J. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   By now, talks with Rice and agent Jeff Wechsler are under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the first thing we'd like to address,'' Lakers
general manager Mitch Kupchak said. ``However, we'll address other
issues at the same time. ... We're going to make a bunch of phone
calls, and we'll have to juggle as best as we can and keep two or
three other things going at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, the Lakers enter the free-agent season largely
intact. Eight players are under contract, and the team holds an
option on Ron Harper, who they expect to return. It's almost a
given that Brian Shaw will be re-signed as well. Add recent
draftees Mark Madsen and Cory Hightower, and the Lakers will have
12 players committed for next season.
</P>
<P>
   But the work won't end there. They still need a starting power
forward to replace A.C. Green, ideally someone who can also play
some center.
</P>
<P>
   The top free agents who fill the bill _ San Antonio's Tim
Duncan, Portland's Brian Grant, the Clippers' Maurice Taylor _ are
virtually unattainable because the Lakers are far over the salary
cap and will have only the $2.25-million cap exception to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian Grant's a wish list,'' Jackson said. ``I mean, that's
Santa Claus coming and visiting, if there's a possibility for Brian
Grant to be here. But Brian Grant turned down $41 million that's
left on his contract, and I'm sure that he's not planning on coming
here for $2.5 or whatever the exception is. Maybe he is. Maybe we
can work that out, some deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a nice golden retriever that he can have, he can
drive a car that I have that's an extra car. I might even encourage
him to meet my daughter, who I think is a terrific gal,'' Jackson
said with a laugh. ``We have to be realistic about what we can do
and the reality of what our needs are and what we have as far as
the salary structure.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Lakers will look to the second tier of free-agent big
men. Among the potential bargains, they have shown previous
interest in Golden State's Adonal Foyle, and they also have an eye
on Toronto's John Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Others who could sign for the exception include New York's Kurt
Thomas, Boston's Danny Fortson and Orlando's Bo Outlaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have a very attractive team to come and play
for,'' Lakers executive Jerry West said. ``I think somebody can
look, that there's playing time here available at that position,
and again we're hopeful something like that will happen. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to build around Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant.
That's our task. To say it's going to be easy, that's not the
case.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
