<SLUG> BC-BBO-DOHN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER IS ALL THE RAGE IN NATIONAL LEAGUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ All-Star games aren't about turning double
plays, making diving catches, laying down bunts or moving runners
over.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star games are about homers off the light towers, homers out
of stadiums, and more homers and more homers and more homers.
(There's also some great pitching thrown in, but that just makes it
tougher to hit homers, so let's not worry about that.) Therefore,
here's the National League All-Stars as they should be:
</P>
<P>
   FIRST BASE: Mark McGwire, St. Louis. While McGwire continues to
pound baseballs farther than anyone, many folks think Colorado's
Todd Helton deserves the nod. But Helton must be judged in two
categories, home and away. He's played one more game at Coors Field
than on the road, and the altitude pays off huge. At home, he's
hitting .459 with 14 homers and 43 RBI. On the road, he's hitting
.305 with seven homers and 25 RBI. McGwire is hitting .300 with 29
homers and 62 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND BASE: Jeff Kent, San Francisco. There's plenty to chose
from in Jose Vidro, Eric Young, Luis Castillo and Kent, but none
are better than Kent. He's a fixture in the middle of the lineup,
and without his .355 average, 21 homers and league-leading 78 RBI,
Barry Bonds doesn't have 28 homers batting ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   SHORTSTOP: Barry Larkin, Cincinnati Reds. He missed time with a
hand injury and is involved in a contract squabble that certainly
has his days with the Reds numbered as they look to perhaps go with
youth at shortstop. But Larkin is still one of the premier
shortstops. It's not a deep position this season, but Larkin's .313
average with eight homers and 28 RBI means something despite
missing three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   THIRD BASE: Chipper Jones, Atlanta Braves. He's having a down
year hitting in the clutch, which, of course, doesn't explain why
he's still batting .322 with 19 homers, 60 RBI and playing his
usual defense. Jones is doing at third for the Braves what every
other club would like to see from its third baseman. That's why the
bidding will be out of control if he tests the free-agent market
after the season.
</P>
<P>
   CATCHER: Mike Piazza, New York Mets. Maybe the Dodgers' Todd
Hundley would have given Piazza a good run if he didn't miss four
weeks with an injury. But Hundley did, Piazza didn't. And just
think of it this way: All those folks still bitter about Piazza
getting run from the Dodgers over Chase Carey's hurt pride can take
solace in knowing the change of environment had no affect on
Piazza. He's still the game's best offensive catcher, hitting .361
with 23 homers and 70 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   LEFT FIELD: Gary Sheffield, Dodgers. He wanted the left-handed
bat behind him in the lineup, and now everyone knows why. Sheffield
is hitting .337 with 27 homers and 70 RBI and certainly is among
the early candidates for the MVP. He's third in the league in
homers, second in RBI, eighth in runs scored (62) and fourth in
total bases (188). Bonds is good, but he's no Sheffield to this
point.
</P>
<P>
   CENTER FIELD: Jim Edmonds, St. Louis. The Angels couldn't sign
him to along-term deal so they moved him to the Midwest. Now, he's
the best center fielder in the league, and that includes the guy in
Cincinnati. Edmonds has scored 72 runs and is hitting .341 with 22
homers and 50 RBI. He also is on base seemingly every time McGwire
bats.
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT FIELD: Vladimir Guerrero, Montreal Expos. Good thing the
Dodgers didn't think he had enough talent to sign him when he was a
kid (presumably above the age of 16). Now, he's the best right
fielder playing in obscurity. Guerrero is hitting .365 with 22
homers and 67 RBI, though someone should explain his existence to
the people in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   STARTING PITCHER: Randy Johnson, Arizona. Let's see. He's 12-2,
has a 1.57 ERA, 177 strikeouts in 131 innings and has allowed 88
hits. Any other questions?
</P>
<P>
   RELIEF PITCHER: Byung-Hyun Kim, Arizona. He's 21, but he's
emerged as the toughest closer. His awkward submarine style has
baffled hitters, who have just 20 hits in 37 innings. Kim is 2-2
with 14 saves and a 1.91 ERA. He also has 67 strikeouts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
