<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GWYNN NOT READY TO GIVE UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Tony Gwynn opted to have knee surgery and thus all but end
his 2000 season _ he could return in September when San Diego
figures to be well out of the playoff hunt _ his focus was on
getting better for next season. And maybe the following one.
</P>
<P>
   And Gwynn also made it clear he would like to continue playing
with the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I plan to keep playing for at least the next couple of
years, this is what I have to do,'' Gwynn said before the surgery.
``I want to be an everyday player. And this is where I want to
play. So to put myself in position to be an everyday player again,
I'm having the surgery now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I thought my only option was to be a designated hitter in
the American League, I could go do that now. But that's not what I
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres orthopedist Jan Fronek said loose material was cleaned
from Gwynn's knee and surfaces where the femur and tibia meet were
smoothed over. Gwynn also had bone-to-bone rubbing in his knee, and
floating pieces of broken cartilage were removed.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of a season for Gwynn, who had the knee drained
seven times and received injections of a cartilage-enhancer on
other occasions. Even so, Gwynn, 40, was hitting .323 before
undergoing surgery.
</P>
<P>
   THE A-ROD CHASE: The Mets signed shortstop Rey Ordonez to a
four-year, $19 million deal in the offseason, but the key was not
giving in to a no-trade clause. Now, with Ordonez out for the
season and the club playing fine without him, they're prepared to
dump him in the offseason if they can sign free agent-to-be Alex
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets are prepared to pay anything for him, which it
might take since $150 million contract numbers are being talked
about throughout the industry.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING ON OBJECTIVITY: For years, opponents have complained
about Atlanta's pitchers getting the outside corner of the plate
from umpires, and when a TBS camera showed the catcher's box at
Turner Field wider than the rules allow, it created quite a stir.
</P>
<P>
   Braves president Stan Kasten, upset about it, banned TBS
announcers Skip Caray, Don Sutton, Pete Van Wieren and Joe Simpson
from the team's charter flight to Montreal. Kasten and Turner
Sports president Mark Lazarus discussed the situation, and the
announcers were allowed on the charter from Montreal to New York
later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother said, `Birds in their little nest agree, 'tis a
shameful sight when children of one family bite and chide and
fight,''' Caray said.
</P>
<P>
   The wonderful irony is that the Braves and TBS are both owned by
Ted Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: The pinch-hit home run by Arizona rookie first
baseman Alex Cabrera, 28, made him the 78th player to homer in his
first major-league at-bat. ... Atlanta's Andruw Jones has 21 homers
and Chipper Jones and Andres Galarraga have 19 apiece. The last
time the Braves had three players with 20 homers at the all-star
break was 1973 when Hank Aaron (27), Darrel Evans (27) and Davey
Johnson (23) did it. They're the only three teammates to hit 40 in
the same season. ... Houston right-hander Jose Lima, who went 21-10
last season, set a franchise record with his 12th straight loss.
Lima's 1-12. ``It has been a year I'd rather forget,'' Lima said.
``Everything has gone wrong.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
