<HEADER>
A0808 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-MAGNANTE-A'S-LADN     07-01 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MAGNANTE-A'S-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGNANTE HAPPY WITH HOME AWAY FROM HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Oakland Athletics pitcher Mike Magnante had to let go
of one dream in order to achieve another.
</P>
<P>
   Magnante, a former standout at Burroughs High in Burbank,
Calif., and UCLA, missed the chance to continue pitching in his
hometown, as he did last year with the Angels, but offset his
disappointment by signing the first multiyear contract of his
10-year major-league career during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland signed the 35-year-old left-handed middle reliever to a
two-year deal, with a team option for a third year, and even though
Magnante recently suffered through a 32-day stint on the disabled
list, the Burbank resident feels right at home with the Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife gets to come home (to Burbank) when I'm on the road,''
Magnante said. ``It's an hour flight, it's nothing, and my parents
can come up to see me and see a game whenever they want, so it's a
very good situation for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was obviously the ideal situation, but if it can't
be ideal, this is about as close as I can get to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Magnante, who broke in with the Kansas City Royals in 1991 and
spent two years with the Houston Astros, had a successful season
with the Angels in 1999, when he appeared in a career-high 53 games
and had a 3.38 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   When Magnante's contract expired at the end of the year, the
Angels were without a general manager, and although he wanted to
stay in Anaheim, Magnante was impressed by the Athletics and their
two-year offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come back to Anaheim, and I didn't hide it, that's
for sure,'' Magnante said. ``Before I even filed for free agency,
we faxed a letter to the Angels basically saying, 'I want to come
back, but since there's nobody in place I have to protect myself
and file. As soon as you get a GM, please call,' and stuff like
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oakland had been calling since the day I filed, and I know the
Angels were in a tough situation, but I felt I couldn't wait. I'd
never had a two-year deal in my whole career, and there I was,
looking at it dead in the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit of security, it's close to home, it's a
great organization, a great group of guys and a team that had a
good chance to win, so I knew I had to jump on it.''
</P>
<P>
   This season has been a mixed bag so far for Magnante, who has
appeared in 22 games with a 4.96 ERA. The A's entered Saturday's
game against the Angels one-half game behind Seattle in the
American League West, but Magnante missed all but one game in June
because of an extraordinary run of bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really three injuries,'' Magnante said. ``I started out
with a sprained ankle and did not go on the DL, and I believe that
by changing my mechanics because of the ankle, I caused the pulled
hamstring. I knew it was a risk not going on the DL, but I always
worry about my arm, not my legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, just as Magnante prepared to return to Oakland, he pulled
a muscle in his forearm during a rehab assignment with Triple-A
Sacramento, which kept him out of action another two weeks.
Magnante finally returned Tuesday and allowed one run in two
innings to help preserve an Oakland victory over Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very frustrating,'' Magnante said, ``because before I
signed, we talked about how one of my advantages was that I've
always been healthy. Sure enough, you come in, and the next thing
you know, you're down with an injury and you're out for 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily it didn't hurt the team, but at the same time, you
want them to get what they're paying you for. My brother tells me
that bad things happen in threes, so hopefully I've used up all my
bad luck for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Magnante, now 100 percent healthy, will leave Anaheim tonight as
Oakland travels to Texas, but the pitcher doesn't harbor any
regrets about his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of tough, because I still have a lot of friends over
there,'' Magnante said as he gestured toward the Angels' clubhouse.
``I got to stay in my own house and commute during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still sad that it didn't work out, but I'm not unhappy
with the results. I had two great options, and in either place I
would have been extremely happy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
