<SLUG> BC-BBA-AL-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL WEST IS LOOKING GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The AL West was supposed to be a mediocre division
with no clear-cut winner. And while there is still no clear-cut
winner, it is far from mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the combined record of every team in the division, the
AL West is the best division in the majors at 25 games over .500
(through Friday). The Mariners and A's both established themselves
as contenders in June, the Mariners going 20-7, and the A's going
18-7. The Angels are lurking close behind and figure to have a say
in who wins the division, and even the Rangers are starting to get
hot again.
</P>
<P>
   So who's the favorite?
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia was asked which team was better,
Seattle or Oakland. And Scioscia, who has become quite good at
answering questions without actually answering them, was
diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle has a better bullpen, Oakland has a better everyday
lineup,'' Scioscia said. ``Seattle has more ways to manufacture
runs, Oakland likes to get guys on base for the big guys to slam.
They're two different clubs, but they both have good pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   As is custom for managers, A's manager Art Howe won't admit to
scoreboard watching at this point in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not this early, it's not even the second half of the season
yet,'' Howe said. ``I'd say August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you're talking about the Yankees of old when they were
up 20 games by the All-Star break, then it might be over. That's
why when I was a kid I wasn't an American League fan. There was
never a pennant race.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has been a contender in recent years, winning the
division in 1995 and '97. But Oakland hasn't won the division since
the end of their dynasty years in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been in a building process the last eight or nine
years,'' said former Athletic and current Angel Scott Spiezio.
``They've got some good young talent added with some good veterans.
They've brought in pitching, which has solidified the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I was there they had hitting. Now they've added
pitching with guys like (Mark) Mulder and (Tim) Hudson and (Jason)
Isringhausen. They've done a good job. ... Us, we're trying to hang
on and get a hot streak going. We're starting to get some injured
guys back, so when the rest of us get hot, we'll be right there.''
</P>
<P>
   NO JUSTICE: Cleveland's trade of David Justice to the Yankees
might have seemed a bit strange, considering the rivalry between
the two teams. But the Indians were looking beyond the surface of
the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Justice is making $7 million this season, and Ricky Ledee, whom
the Indians acquired, is making $240,000. By trading Justice, the
Indians cleared room on their payroll to acquire much-needed
pitching help.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors are circulating the Indians are interested in the
Phillies' Curt Schilling, but general manager John Hart says he
isn't planning to rebuild the team. Hart talked about injuries that
have hurt the club, but he won't get any sympathy from Angels fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying the injuries are the only reason we are where
we are,'' Hart said, ``... but what would happen to the White Sox
if you took Bob Howry and Keith Foulke out of the bullpen, and
James Baldwin and Mike Sirotka or Jim Parque out of the rotation,
and Frank Thomas out of their lineup?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's essentially what's happened to us. We've got nine
people on the DL. No one seems to realize what that means.''
</P>
<P>
   PASS THE BUCK: Orioles owner Peter Angelos certainly would be
the one to hoist a championship trophy and take the credit if his
club won anything. But with the Orioles struggling and on their way
to their third consecutive losing season, Angelos passed the buck
in an interview with The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `once-proud Orioles' never won a damn thing from 1983
until we got here,'' Angelos said. ``We almost got to the World
Series twice in '96 and '97.''
</P>
<P>
   About the makeup of the team, Angelos said, ``These are not my
decisions.'' And the only blame he accepts is hiring ``the people
who picked the teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelos also said he might become more involved in the
day-to-day operation of the club. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
