<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GHO-CALCAVECCHIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALCAVECCHIA SETS GHO PACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ As opposed to Tiger Woods, who reportedly
raised the bar in professional golf, Mark Calcavecchia &AMP; Co. have
lowered it at the Greater Hartford Open, turning this week's PGA
Tour stop into a limbo contest.
</P>
<P>
   How low can you go?
</P>
<P>
   Try a course-record 9-under 61, said Kirk Triplett, whose
scorching third-round performance at TPC River Highlands enabled
him to hurdle 26 players into a share of third place at 13-under
197, tied with Edward Fryatt (66).
</P>
<P>
   Quite impressive, said Calcavecchia, who had very little problem
slipping beneath the bar himself. He shot his second straight 64,
opened a three-shot lead, and was able to match Triplett's record
with one of his own: a 54-hole, 17-under total that smashed the
previous best by two.
</P>
<P>
   Bright red numbers, to be sure, the sort that left poor Notah
Begay wondering if he were holding the correct end of the club.
After all, he made five birdies, shot 67 _ and fell from a share of
first to solo second, three back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess my only major concern is I'm glad I just didn't get
blown out of the tournament today,'' said Begay, who is coming off
a stirring victory at last week's FedEx St. Jude Classic. ``I mean,
Mark came out of the gates just overwhelmingly strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Begay is not exaggerating because Calcavecchia, tied with Begay
at 11 under to start the day, ripped a 9-iron to 12 feet at the
first hole and drained that birdie to set the stage for another
brisk effort. When he made a ``miraculous birdie'' at the second, a
40-footer after driving into the rough, Calcavecchia was two shots
clear of Begay and in a rush to go even deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to stay aggressive because these guys are good,''
said Calcavecchia, who has won nine times on Tour, though it's been
more than two years since his most recent one.
</P>
<P>
   He certainly had it pushed to overdrive as he got to the turn
with birdies at the par-5 sixth, par-4 seventh, and par-3 eighth,
the second time in three days he has ripped off three straight
birdies at the stretch. He was 16 under, four in front of Begay,
with Triplett rushing in from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep waiting for (the greens) to get hard,'' said Triplett,
``but they're receptive. The fairways are firm. No wind, low
scores.''
</P>
<P>
   How low? Consider that more than half the field (47 of 82)
posted subpar rounds and that the scoring average was 69.157, a
shockingly low figure on what they call ``moving day'' out here on
the PGA Tour. Indeed, it was a day to move, though it resembled
more of a rush to the front.
</P>
<P>
   Triplett's birdie fest was most noticeable _ three straight
starting at the second, three more beginning at the 15th, nine in
all _ as he rifled past all those players he had fallen behind
because of a second-round 72.
</P>
<P>
   A 72? Triplett conceded the Friday score had really gotten him
steamed. ``I was very discouraged after the second round,'' he
said, knowing 72 is like 82 on a course that has been defenseless
all week.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a 61 can help you forget that 72, though even
Triplett's effort was overshadowed later in the day when
Calcavecchia kept up the pressure with birdies at the par-3 11th
and par-5 13th to get to 18 under.
</P>
<P>
   By now, Begay had joined in the fun, having shaken off some
early mental mistakes that were ``uncharacteristic of me.'' He was
referring to a missed par attempt from inside 3 feet at the par-4
second and a three-putt bogey at the par-3 fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They happen once in a while, but you hate to see it when
you're trying to make up some ground,'' said Begay, who made the
turn four shots behind Calcavecchia, then fell five back when the
leader made birdie at the par-3 11th.
</P>
<P>
   But Begay, who played his final 13 holes bogey-free, drove the
296-yard, par-4 15th, two-putted for birdie, and picked up a shot
against Calcavecchia's par-saving putt from 6 feet after his drive
came up short right and his second shot went through the green into
a swale.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he was losing control, but Calcavecchia did make his
only bogey of the day, electing to hit an ``easy 7-iron'' instead
of a ``hard 8-iron'' into the 17th green. It went long and he could
not get it up-and-down, a situation that allowed Begay to get
within three shots thanks to a solid par.
</P>
<P>
   All of which put these two gentlemen together again, in Sunday's
final pairing, and the philosophy hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just after birdies again,'' said Calcavecchia, who knows
there are lots of them out there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
