<HEADER>
A0814 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-REDSKINS     07-01 2514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-REDSKINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNYDER'S CASH, REDSKINS' FUTURE ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington Redskins owner Daniel Snyder is spending more than
$100 million on player salaries, leaving many to wonder how this
record-breaking figure can be tucked and stuffed into the $62.5
million salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins are doing it by giving out big signing bonuses and
prorating them over a long term, which is basically the way every
team does it. Snyder is just doing more of it.
</P>
<P>
   If you know your Salary Cap 101, you know the first year of any
huge contract is normally the least expensive. In fact, the
Redskins have crafted this so well, they have even budgeted $10
million signing bonuses for No. 1 draft picks Chris Samuels and
LaVar Arrington and figure on $5 million or so for running back
Stephen Davis, a franchise player who will likely have a new deal
in place by the time the Redskins begin charging $10 a head at
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   According to someone close to the Redskins' salary cap
situation, ``Everybody thinks they're going to be in trouble if
they don't win it all, but they've done this pretty well. The
salary cap is going to expand quite a bit over the next few years''
_ it will be as high as $80 million in about three years _ ``and
much of that increase will absorb the salaries. They won't have
major cap worries for the first two years at least.''
</P>
<P>
   However, if older players like Bruce Smith, Darrell Green, and
Deion Sanders play only one or two years of their very large
contracts, Snyder will be in big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Former Pittsburgh Steelers director of football operations Tom
Donahoe, who ran a team that didn't have deep pockets and that had
to build through the draft, thinks it's a great risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's aggressive,'' said Donahoe. ``It's a bit shortsighted,
particularly in relation to the salary cap. It's a decision you
have to make. You take a shot now or build a couple of years down
the road. If it's the right approach, time will tell. One thing to
consider, when you put together high-priced veteran players,
there's always an issue of chemistry. Nobody can determine what
that will be until you get out there on the field. It'll be
interesting to watch. They'll certainly have a bull's-eye on their
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Paying big money to older players goes against the grain of most
NFL teams, and that's why Snyder is being criticized by other
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder also has been influenced by his new personnel man, Vinny
Cerrato, formerly of the 49ers, who has been accused of
overspending to the point that the 49ers had to get rid of almost
$50 million in payroll the past two years, leaving the once great
franchise in a hole. The 49ers did win a championship during their
free-spending years, so their predicament may have been worth it.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the 49ers and Redskins is that the salary
cap wasn't climbing as quickly when the 49ers were spending.
</P>
<P>
   If things do work out and the Redskins win a Super Bowl, then
the strategy worked.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins, who last won a Super Bowl in 1991, have an
incredible blend of young and veteran players. The NFL public
thought it insane when Washington signed the 40-year-old Green to a
five-year, $10-million deal, but the feeling is Green is in such
great shape (he ran a team-best 4.24 40-yard dash in late May), he
can play three years as a nickel back. Anyway, Snyder, a lifelong
Redskins fan, said he gave Green the money as a ``lifetime
achievement'' contract. Along with Irving Fryar, 39, and Smith, 37,
there are players the rest of the team looks up to. But there is
also a growing corps of young superstars like Champ Bailey, and
Arrington and Samuels, both of whom will start barring prolonged
holdouts, and Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a big-name team, and now we have to produce big-name
results,'' said Fryar. ``It's going to be fun out there playing
alongside great players, but fans want to see results. I think it's
going to make us hungry to show the fans that we are a great
football team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins certainly have excellent clubhouse leadership in
fullback Larry Centers, quarterback Brad Johnson, Green, Smith,
Sanders, and Marco Coleman, and they've even made allowance for the
injury-prone Johnson going down. They signed Jeff George.
</P>
<P>
   Too many leaders? Too many egos? We shall see.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, when talent and future Hall of Fame players are
handed to you on a silver platter, the coach must produce. Norv
Turner's future has certainly been in doubt the past two years, but
a poor start now will mean that he is gone, especially with Ray
Rhodes around as the defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The thought on Turner is that he must at least make it to the
Super Bowl. Anything less wouldn't sit well with Snyder, who is
spending more time in the Redskins' front offices now that he has
sold his Internet empire. Last year, Snyder was a coach's
nightmare, often calling Turner in the middle of the night to
criticize the play-calling.
</P>
<P>
   Defense was a huge problem the past few years, and Rhodes was
brought in along with Foge Fazio, the former defensive coordinator
of the Minnesota Vikings. Rhodes can't help but look better than
his predecessors. He is already afforded the luxury of Smith as a
pass rusher and Arrington, who may be one of the best pass rushers
to come out of college in years. Chasing the quarterback should
help Sanders and Bailey make plays in the secondary, and Mark
Carrier is one of the hardest-hitting safeties in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes's biggest job may be to get the most out of the
high-priced interior line of Dana Stubblefield and Dan Wilkinson,
who have not lived up to their billing. Still, it's not a bad way
for Rhodes, who was fired following an 8-8 season at Green Bay, to
take a step back as a defensive coordinator before he returns to
the head coaching ranks.
</P>
<P>
   What has made the resurgence of the Redskins possible is
Snyder's deep pockets and the huge revenue stream resulting from
the new stadium. Once the two high-profile rookies and Davis are
signed, Snyder will have shelled out about $50 million in signing
bonuses. Smith got $4.25 million; Sanders, $8 million; George, $2
million; Carrier, $3 million. Arrington and Samuels will be
collecting around $10 million each, and Davis close to or exceeding
$5 million. In addition, the Redskins will retain their vital free
agents, issuing a $1.6 million signing bonus to Centers, $3 million
to Coleman, $2 million to Green, $750,000 to guard Keith Sims, and
a few other sub-million bonuses issued to players such as center
Jay Leeuwenburg, tackle Andy Heck, center Cory Raymer, and safety
Matt Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   The signings of the major free agents and the rookies should
affect the cap by about $7 million in 2000 and much higher than
that as the contracts get into their second and third years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have about a two-year window to win it all before their
situation becomes horrendous,'' said one NFL source.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins will score points. When healthy, Johnson is one of
the most efficient passers in the league and can get the ball to
speedy receivers Albert Connell, Michael Westbrook, and Fryar, who
never seems to age and should be an even bigger part of the team
this year. The Redskins signed veteran Adrian Murrell just in case
Davis holds out, which nobody really anticipates, and they also
have Skip Hicks around.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins are confident their depth will get them through
times of injuries, and they also anticipate being very strong on
third downs, offensively and defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Redskins are putting themselves out on a limb.
Snyder isn't afraid of the consequences, or he wouldn't have
attempted to put together an all-star team. Down the road in
Baltimore, Orioles owner Peter Angelos has taken the same approach
with little results. To Washington observers, Snyder's philosophy
is similar to Angelos's and to that of Yankees owner George
Steinbrenner, who has been hugely successful after spending
lavishly.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder especially feels in competition with the Baltimore
Ravens. Despite the fact the Ravens don't have quite the on-paper
talent, some believe they may be the better team. That would
irritate Snyder to no end.
</P>
<P>
   Most owners are hoping the Redskins fail miserably.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're probably saying their prayers,'' said Donahoe. ``If it
works, you'll have coaches fighting with owners all over the
league, but the strong owners have a philosophy and they have an
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say if it's right or wrong. It can work, or it can
blow up in your face. I don't know if there's a right way or a
wrong way. What we did in the '90s worked. We just lost too many
players. The one negative is you're almost penalized in this league
for having too many good players. You should be rewarded for good
drafts. That doesn't seem to be the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins have drafted future All-Pro players in Bailey,
tackle Jon Jansen, Arrington, and Samuels.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime talent scout said of Arrington, ``If he's not the
best player in the league since Lawrence Taylor, I don't know
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Snyder doesn't know anything, either. But what if he does?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Powerful words
</P>
<P>
   NFL spokesman Greg Aiello confirmed it was commissioner Paul
Tagliabue who suggested that Ray Lewis speak to 250 players at the
annual rookie symposium in San Diego sponsored by the league. Every
year, the league runs the four-day event in hopes it can advise
young players how to conduct themselves on and off the field. The
messages usually go in one ear and out the other, but the feeling
is if Lewis's words don't sink in, none will. Lewis, who was
acquitted of double-murder charges, came to the symposium
unannounced, spoke briefly, and, according to one league official,
``stunned everyone who was there. Nobody made a sound when he
walked into the room.'' The players hung on Lewis's every word,
just what Tagliabue hoped for. Last year, a panel of NFL rookies
spoke to the incoming players. One of them was Jets offensive
lineman Jason Fabini, who just days later was arrested for his role
in a barroom brawl. Fabini was later fined by Tagliabue. Lewis's
message centered around the dangers of hanging around with the
wrong people and of being in places you don't belong. Let's watch
for the outcome . . . The first of the preseason football
publications is in. Athlon Sports picks the Patriots second in the
AFC East to the Indianapolis Colts and has New England making the
playoffs as a wild-card team. Athlon picks the rest of the
division: Miami, Buffalo, then the Jets. The publication picks
Washington, Tampa Bay, St. Louis, Jacksonville, and Denver as the
other divisional winners. It also predicts Jacksonville over Tampa
Bay in the Super Bowl . . . The Patriots are going to wait and see
how things work with Bill Belichick's enormous workload, which
includes responsibilities as defensive coordinator, head coach, and
personnel director. Belichick has gone by the title of just head
coach for a reason. If things work out on the personnel side and
the combination of Belichick and Scott Pioli produce results, then
you may see more titles. If not, a personnel guy may be brought on
board . . . With a shortage of defensive linemen, some of the NFL
Europe players are getting attention. Agent Mike Clohisy reportedly
fielded several calls on defensive tackle Chartric Darby, who
played at South Carolina State and who had 8 1/2 sacks for
Barcelona, before settling on Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vital information
</P>
<P>
   The reason Patriots national scout Lionel Vital left the Jets to
come to New England is because his voice will be heard by
Belichick. In New York, Bill Parcells didn't pay him much heed. In
next year's draft, Vital, who scouted the Southwest for the Jets,
should have a huge role in setting up the draft board with
Belichick and Pioli . . . Despite needing a player of his size, the
Patriots are out of the bidding for Gilbert Brown, the often beefy
defensive lineman who is a free agent and has so far eaten his way
out of the NFL. The Packers still have an interest in re-signing
Brown at a minimum contract, as do the Seattle Seahawks, but other
teams have shied away based on Brown's ongoing battle with weight
problems . . . Standing together chatting at a USA soccer game at
Foxboro Stadium last week: Belichick and Doug Flutie . . . One
intriguing possibility for Ben Coates is teaming with Shannon
Sharpe in Baltimore. The Ravens are said to be interested in making
this happen, but so far Coates hasn't found any deal or situation
to his liking, though there are still several teams in need of
another tight end . . . Former Boston College coach Jack Bicknell,
who coaches the Barcelona Dragons of NFL Europe, is back in his New
Hampshire environs and appears duly impressed with three Patriots
who played for him. On nose tackle Garrett Johnson: ``He just keeps
his mouth shut and plays. He'll give you everything he has on every
play. He's a football player.'' On wide receiver Sean Morey: ``I
think the kid is going to be a star. This kid wants to play all the
time, and he'll do anything to get out there. Honestly, he was hurt
the entire year with an ankle problem, but he always wanted to play
even though he wasn't 100 percent. The only game he was OK, he
caught nine passes. We had to hold him out the last game because
the doctors feared his ankle would swell so much we wouldn't be
able to get him home.'' On Fall River linebacker Marc Megna:
``Tremendous strides. He basically came out of nowhere because he
used to be a nose tackle in college (Richmond). For Marc, it was
like sitting in algebra class. He had a lot to learn about playing
outside linebacker. I really like him. I don't know if he'll be
able to come as far as the Patriots want him to come in a short
time, but Marc, like most of the kids here, will be a very good
special teams player.'' . . . Bicknell (we really miss this guy)
would obviously be the natural choice to coach the Boston franchise
of the XFL, if that gets off the ground in two years. ``I keep
hearing I would be in consideration, but I haven't spoken to anyone
from that league. It would certainly be flattering, but I'm not out
there looking,'' said Bicknell . . . Interesting that back in the
early '90s, Cleveland Browns owner Art Modell had whittled his
selection of head coaches to two: Belichick and Bill Cowher. He
went with Belichick, who struggled with peaks and valleys, while
Cowher went on to great success in Pittsburgh . . . We are often
reminded of Bob Kraft's incredible charitable side. Columbia
University now will benefit from his $5 million gift of the Robert
F. Kraft Family Center for Jewish Student Life . . . Our
condolences to Pete Carroll and his family on the passing of his
mother . . . Fullback Rob Konrad ran a 4.49 40-yard dash recently
in Miami. Konrad, the former Syracuse star from North Andover, is
expected to become a bigger part of the Dolphins' offense this
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
