<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0815 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-SAMPRAS     07-01 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-SAMPRAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS IN FINE FORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Pete Sampras declined to tread upon the red carpet
rolled out at the All England Lawn Tennis &AMP; Croquet Club Saturday
for 65 surviving champions and finalists from Wimbledon's first 113
years. He was trying to make sure that the hallowed green carpet of
Centre Court wouldn't be rolled over him. Meanwhile, the man
considered one of his main challengers, Gustavo Kuerten, was on
nearby Court 2 being rendered ineligible for future honor rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras's absence was excused for medical reasons, and he proved
they were legitimate. He looked as if he might become a Wimbledon
relic, too, as he stumbled early in the first test of the
tendinitis in his lower left leg that has afflicted him since
Wednesday. But after spotting feisty fellow American Justin
Gimelstob the first set, during which, he recalled, his racket
``felt like a foreign object,'' he gradually regained his familiar
form and ground out a 2-6, 6-4, 6-2, 6-2 third-round victory.
</P>
<P>
   That keeps the top seed and defending champion on course to
achieve more of the pomp and circumstance of which he was unable to
partake on this occasion. He's advanced to the second week in his
march toward a record-tying seventh Wimbledon crown and
record-setting 13th Grand Slam title.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras insisted he meant no disrespect, and in fact, he headed
directly from his postmatch press conference to the royal box at
Centre Court, where he was belatedly honored with a commemorative
plate and took his place in the pantheon-for-a-day that included
Rod Laver, Bjorn Borg, Margaret Court Smith, Billie Jean King, and
John Newcombe.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't join them for the initial march, Sampras explained,
because he wasn't in much shape to walk, bow, or do anything except
receive treatment for the injury he suffered while warming up for a
draining four-set victory over Karol Kucera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have loved to have been part of it,'' Sampras said.
``For the hour before I played, I was doing whatever I could to
play. Getting treatment, warming it up, taping it, do whatever I
can, making sure I'm as comfortable as possible out there.''
</P>
<P>
   As comfortable as possible meant not very. Even though he'd been
given an extra day to rehabilitate because his match had been
postponed by rain and darkness, he summed up his condition in one
word: ``Sore.''
</P>
<P>
   His first-set performance also could be summed up in one word:
Sour.
</P>
<P>
   Looking like a man who hadn't touched a racket for 2 1/2 days,
which he hadn't, Sampras double faulted three times in losing his
first service game and double-faulted again on set point. Looking
up at the royal box, which for this one day was filled with
tennis's royal family, Sampras felt unworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Borg and the Rocket (Laver),'' he said. ``When I was
playing the first set, I wasn't too proud that they were
watching.''
</P>
<P>
   He wished they could have been helping.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, I wanted to throw my racket up there,'' Sampras
said. ``They could play for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Sampras shook off the cobwebs and the pain, and
Gimelstob was cooked. On this celestial day, he offered a fitting
assessment of Sampras's superiority: ``Probably when he came out of
his mother's womb, God spent a little extra time on his right
shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other members of the constellation who had business on their
agenda _ matching No. 2 seeds Lindsay Davenport and Andre Agassi _
found time to join the parade.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, the women's defender, strolled past Paola Suarez,
6-4, 6-2. World No. 1 Agassi, who had avoided extinction against
Todd Martin only 24 hours earlier, was moved up to the head of the
walk of fame to give him time to prepare for his 6-3, 6-3, 6-4
victory over Jerome Golmard.
</P>
<P>
   On the snake pit that is Court 2, Kuerten became the latest
entry on a dishonor roll of prominent casualties including, among
many others, John McEnroe, Jimmy Connors, Agassi, Boris Becker,
Conchita Martinez, Michael Stich, Virginia Wade, and Richard
Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
   Kuerten took the court with a terrible cold, and that was the
best he felt all afternoon in a feeble 7-6 (8-6), 6-2, 6-1 sweep by
114th-ranked Alexander Popp.
</P>
<P>
   Kuerten requested an injury timeout while trailing, 3-2, in the
second set. The trainer came to his chair and massaged his left
calf and lower back.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I was) just sore a little bit,'' said Kuerten. ``I have a bad
cold for a few days. I didn't feel enough power to see myself with
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about panaceas: Kuerten won one game the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get some help there, but wasn't too helpful,'' he
observed with grim accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Kuerten thus completed a dubious double for French champions,
joining Mary Pierce, who like him ruled Stade Roland Garros three
weeks ago _ on the sidelines here.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-7-inch Popp, 23, is a German whom the British press
continually tries to recruit for the local Davis Cup team because
his mother is an English native.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the nicest day of my life up to now,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But not nice enough to persuade him to stay here after this
tournament. Popp steadfastly professed loyalty to his native land.
Like Sampras, he resisted the British red carpet treatment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
