<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0816 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKL-WOLTERS-WNBA-BOS &LR;      07-01 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-WOLTERS-WNBA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOLTERS CATCHES UCONN FEVER IN WNBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The woman who calls herself ``Big Girl'' is back,
front and center, where she wants to be. It might be difficult to
imagine Kara Wolters not being anywhere but front and center, given
her 6-foot-7-inch frame and outgoing personality.
</P>
<P>
   Wolters was the center on that fabulous University of
Connecticut team and then . . . and then what? After a brief stint
playing in Hartford for the now defunct ABL, what happened? Wolters
often pondered that same question.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Wolters, who turns 25 next month, saw the best and
worst of pro basketball: She had a reserved seat on the bench of
the WNBA champion Houston Comets and soon she will even get a ring
to commemorate her limited time and minimal contributions there.
</P>
<P>
   When she receives that ring, however, it will only serve as a
reminder of her days as a bench warmer for the Comets. Wolters is
now back to doing what she does best, playing like a real,
honest-to-goodness center, as she stars for the Indiana Fever, one
of four WNBA expansion teams. The Fever selected her in the
expansion draft last December and gave Wolters a chance to play
regularly again. She is Indiana's second-leading scorer and
rebounder while averaging more than 26 minutes a game. She's among
the league leaders in field goal percentage, free throw percentage,
and blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, she feels she has arrived at UConn, The
Sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if I'd ever get that feeling again,'' she said
after a recent practice at Conseco Fieldhouse, where the Fever play
their home games. ``I feel like I'm in college again, which is
exactly what I wanted to feel like, to relive those glory days of
UConn. The people here have confidence in me as being a go-to
player again. That's a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, she wondered if she ever would get that feeling
again, but it's her nature not to think she wouldn't. The only
questions in her mind were when and where? She had left UConn in
1997, part of a four-year run highlighted by that 35-0 NCAA title
team in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities in women's basketball were there in 1997, which
did not exist even a year before. The WNBA was starting up. The ABL
was entering its second season. Wolters decided to join the ABL's
New England Blizzard, and stay close to her Holliston, Mass., home.
In her first season, she led the league in blocked shots and was
named to the first All-ABL team.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one problem: She wasn't progressing as a player.
K.C. Jones was the Blizzard's coach, and, well, after four years of
Geno Auriemma at UConn, this was a little different. Auriemma once
threw her out of practice and when she tried to come back, he threw
a basketball at her. The laid-back, cruise-control Jones was the
anti-Auriemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really coached in New England,'' Wolters said. ``K.C.
Jones wasn't at the point of his career where he was coaching
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in her second season, the ABL folded. In May 1999, Wolters
was selected in the WNBA draft by the Comets, who were preparing
for what would be their third straight title. It was a marriage
that never worked.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets run a system based on their three terrific perimeter
players _ Sheryl Swoopes, Cynthia Cooper, and Tina Thompson.
Centers, such as Wolters, are deemed excess baggage. As she put it,
``Their idea of post play is, screen for me, get me the ball, and
then get the heck out of my way. I'm a scorer. That's not the
situation for me. Then I hurt my knee. It was one thing after
another. It was a very down time in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   She appeared in 10 games, averaging 4.1 minutes. She got into
two playoff games for a total of five minutes. She then went to
Comets coach Van Chancellor, who had no use for her as a player,
and asked to be put in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, 15 players were selected before her, including one
Houston teammate. She was still seen as a questionable performer.
We won't even get into her pregame routine (very loud Van Halen) or
her superstitions (rubbing a gold basketball around her neck 52
times) or her inherent skepticism (Elvis is alive). This was a
woman who needed to be seen, not heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just wasn't a proven pro at the time,'' said Kelly
Krauskopf, the Fever's CEO. ``It had been awhile since the ABL
folded, and our league is mostly one of guards and perimeter
players. That's what teams were looking for. But Kara is still
young, and centers are hard to find. We thought she had a lot of
upside.''
</P>
<P>
   And has it worked out?
</P>
<P>
   ``Even better than we thought,'' Krauskopf said. ``When I tell
people what Kara is doing, it's almost like they act surprised. It
had been so long since Kara had been on a team where she could be
that kind of player. This can be her team.''
</P>
<P>
   As for now, Wolters has two main goals: continue improving and
stay healthy. Easier said than done. In the last 10 days, she has
injured her back during practice and was knocked unconscious for a
minute last Sunday when she was the recipient of an accidental
uppercut to the nose. She had hoped to return to action Saturday
night at home against Miami, but sat out after being suspended
without pay for one game and fined $500 by the WNBA for leaving the
bench when a teammate was flagrantly fouled Friday. She went on the
court after Rita Williams was fouled by Liberty guard Jessica Bibby
during New York's 72-70 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Before those travails, however, she was on her way to
establishing herself as one of the league's true inside presences.
In one five-game stretch, she averaged 16 points and 7 rebounds.
The Fever, however, lost four of them; they are an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   But their coach, Anne Donovan, is 6-8, a Hall of Famer, and
knows what she has and what she wants. The Fever want Wolters to be
an integral part of their system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kara has a lot of ability and talent, but she was never on a
team that utilized it,'' Donovan says. ``Her game is improving and
evolving as teams try to attack her now. I will say this: Kara is
one of the most motivated athletes I've ever been around. This is a
girl who has the will not just to play, but to improve and be the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan and Wolters are a mutual admiration society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anne Donovan is a post coach. She can totally relate,''
Wolters said. ``She's a two-time Olympian, a Hall of Famer, I feel
like a sponge. There's so much I can learn from her.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a big person, you can be either totally useful or
totally useless. There's no middle ground there. You have to get in
the right system when you're big. You're very dependent on your
guards and your system when you're a post player. It was just a
matter of fitting into the right system. I never for once doubted
myself. I think I lost a little confidence along the way, and I
definitely went through an emotional roller coaster the last year
and a half. But it never got to the point where I wanted to give it
up and go work at 7-Eleven.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been another perk for Wolters. Last December, after
months of practicing and traveling with the 2000 Olympic team on a
no-guarantee basis, she was formally added to the Sydney squad. Of
course, it doesn't hurt that the Olympic coach, Nell Fortner, will
take over as the Fever's head coach next season. Or that Auriemma
is an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Wolters was told of the decision a week before it was made
public, but also was told to keep it a secret. She told her parents
by giving them a pair of gift-wrapped plane tickets to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics was my dream even before there was a WNBA,''
Wolters said. ``People told me I was crazy to go through this long,
tryout process when they're not committing to you. Well, I told
them, `When you have a dream, you'll do anything.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I never missed a trip with them. That was a good sign. They
always called me back. That was a great sign. But yet they would
never commit to me. So I said, `OK, I have to make them realize
they need me.' It's a lot of work. It still is. For the last seven
months, I've been playing with the best players in the world every
day. I think I've gotten better every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Girl is big _ and back _ again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
