u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-FORTSON-B     07-01 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-FORTSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORTSON HOLDING DOWN FORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the free agency recruitment period began Saturday, Danny
Fortson was feeling ``kind of nervous and scared.'' Fortson and his
agent, Raymond Brothers, cautiously answered questions about the
process that started at 12:01 a.m. Although he would not divulge
the names of any teams interested in his client, Brothers received
10 calls from organizations in both conferences during the first
day of the free agency period, most coming just minutes after
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most gratifying thing about this is that so many teams
called right after midnight trying to get a jump on Danny Fortson
because a lot of them believe that Danny may be the best power
forward out there,'' said Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   But the news that several teams expressed interest did little to
diminish the anxiety Fortson felt. He knows cap room is scarce and
he desperately wants to join a team that will give him playing
time. Fortson believes the right fit with an organization will
allow him to be the top rebounder in the NBA and a real
contributor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never gotten a chance to play in the NBA yet,'' said
Fortson, still disappointed about the not-so-significant minutes he
got as a Celtics forward last season. ``I've got all the ability
locked inside of me ready to go out there and play. I've been
playing behind Antoine Walker and Antonio McDyess for my whole
career. If I get to the right place, I'll be just fine. I need a
chance to play myself. I could be just as good as those guys. You
never know, and nobody's given me a chance yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of depression because I got hurt and didn't get
into the lineup right when I thought I should've gotten into the
lineup. I felt I was more than ready to play and produce. I could
have helped the team. You never know what could have happened if I
was in there playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Fortson doesn't re-sign with Boston, he still prefers
East Coast living. Given a choice, he would like to play in
Philadelphia (where he was born), New York (a favorite team from
childhood), or somewhere close to Pittsburgh (where he went to high
school).
</P>
<P>
   After learning a few lessons about criticizing the Celtics when
he was nearly traded to Toronto last season, Fortson praised the
efforts of associate coach Jim O'Brien and spoke affectionately
about his teammates and the organization's support staff. He
understands that the decisions Boston makes could greatly affect
his future, that part of the process is some of what makes him
nervous about free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not dead,'' said general manager Chris Wallace of
working something out with Fortson. ``We're looking at Danny on all
fronts now. We're looking at signing him. We're looking at who's
interested out there. Is there any way we could do a deal with
them? Because we drafted Jerome (Moiso), I wouldn't rule him out
and I wouldn't rule him in either. We want to get something there
that works for the Celtics; who knows how that fits in with his
timetable?''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics are keeping all options open with respect to Fortson
and the other free agents available as they search for a veteran
backup point guard, someone who can play out on the perimeter at
second guard or small forward, and an athletic defender. The Boston
brass spent Saturday making calls, but it's still early in the
process for the home team. The decisions of Orlando and Chicago
will dictate the market to a large extent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the majority of the league, we're there with exceptions
and sign-and-trades,'' said Wallace. ``That doesn't usually go
right out of the box. But we've had some chats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people we have pegged as possibilities to be at the
exception. Right now, it takes them a little while to come to the
exception. They just can't be there the first day. Then, because
there are more players than there is cap room, somebody of
significance could get stuck with the exception and fall down to
that level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
