<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION LEARN FROM THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ A year ago, the Revolution had momentum and
optimism as they traveled to a midseason game in Dallas. Their
commitment and physical style threatened to overwhelm the Burn in
the blazing Texas sun.
</P>
<P>
   But Dallas regrouped. Leonel Alvarez, then the Burn's midfield
leader, calmed the tempo and encouraged his team to maintain
possession. The Revolution soon spent most of their energy, and
Dallas took a 2-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution will be in a similar situation when they visit
Miami Tuesday. This time, though, Alvarez is on their side. And,
the Revolution have evolved to the point where they understand the
importance of a possession game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to understand how to manage the rhythm of the game,''
Alvarez said Saturday. ``The important thing is to have the
mentality of a winner. We have to play this game like it is a
championship game, the final game, like Juventus against Lazio. We
have to take responsibility for our errors and learn from them. We
can make mistakes but not like the ones we have made in the past.
And, we have to keep improving.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez joined the Revolution last August, after the team's fate
was nearly sealed and morale was sinking fast. Now, the Revolution
are rejuvenated, tied for first place in the Eastern Division under
coach Fernando Clavijo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are playing with more joyfulness and we are playing
together,'' Alvarez said. ``We are all in this together with the
goal of making the playoffs. The coach gets the credit _ he has
bonded us together.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez was recruited to the MLS to bring guidance to a
fledgling league. Alvarez has been an excellent example this year
by maintaining a physical condition that has enabled him to become
one of the Revolution's most durable players. He also has emerged
in an outspoken leadership role. After the Revolution were
defeated, 3-1, in Columbus, Ohio, last week, Alvarez called a
meeting in the locker room in an attempt to regroup the team. The
Revolution concluded that game with six players age 24 or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young players here all like to work and they are very good
players,'' Alvarez said. ``They play with a lot of heart, they are
in good condition, and they are hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have not played since the Columbus game and will
not have a home match until they meet the MetroStars July 15.
Clavijo has appealed to Alvarez, John Harkes, and Mauricio Wright
to provide direction.
</P>
<P>
   This is usually slump time for the Revolution. Last year, they
went from May 23 until the June 25 loss at Dallas without a
regulation-time defeat. But after a 3-2 win over the MetroStars on
Independence Day, they went on a seven-game losing streak and never
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution are attempting to add a forward, but Alvarez is
not in favor of Spanish striker Jose Luis Morales, who trained with
the Revolution last week, mostly because of Morales's lack of
physical conditioning. Morales has not played for a month, since
the end of the Spanish Liga.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo is expected to return from Uruguay and meet the
Revolution in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., Monday. He said his mother,
Irma, 77, is near death in their hometown of Maldonado.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
