<DOCNO> NYT20000701.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0821 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     07-01 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS HE THE PROBLEM? HE DIDN'T HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Gritty. Hard-nosed. Overachieving. Those have been the
trademarks of the Sons of Jimy Williams these last two years. You
could outscore the Red Sox with your talent, but you could not beat
the soul out of them. The Sox played blood-and-thunder baseball for
nine innings and they did it every day.
</P>
<P>
   Not Saturday. The sight of the inimitable Izzy Alcantara
quitting in the middle of an eighth-inning rundown will stand as
the defining moment of a slide that has seen the ``This is the
Year'' Red Sox reduced to a .500 club as midseason nears.
</P>
<P>
   When the 7-2 beating (three more errors) was over, Williams
called a team meeting, then refused to take questions on the game,
stating only, ``U-G-L-Y, that's it on the game. Ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   The room was quiet after that. Food went untouched as players
dressed and left. Jeff Frye called it ``embarrassing,'' Carl
Everett stated ``We sucked,'' and Jason Varitek said ``Maybe we
need, as a team, the appearance we're playing harder. Despite
what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   They can start by finding a new home for one Israel Cristostomo
Alcantara.
</P>
<P>
   Joggin' Izzy. Izzy is as Izzy Does. Everybody do the Izzy
Shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   Five games into his big-league career, he's already a Red Sox
legend, right there alongside Dwayne Hosey, Bobby Sprowl, and Bob
``Beetle'' Bailey. Izzy only knows one speed and it's half-speed.
He plays defense like Sam Horn and styles like Chris Canty.
Saturday it looked like he quit like Tony Eason. Why do I suspect
he's one of those secret Statman Projects brought to general
manager Dan Duquette by meter reader Mike Gimbel?
</P>
<P>
   It would be unfair to blame everything that's happening to this
ball club on a 27-year-old Dominican who worked 10 long years to
get to the majors and has a limited grasp of English. But Alcantara
plays a game that is foreign to the Red Sox of the last two
seasons. His presence in the everyday lineup tells us how low the
Sox have sunk.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night he hit his first major league homer and styled
around the bases even though the Sox were trailing, 4-1. He also
stayed back in right field and let a ball drop for a hit when it
could have been caught.
</P>
<P>
   The clever White Sox know a good thing when they see it and went
at Izzy with a vengeance Saturday. They took advantage of a
mismatch in right.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is generally not conducive to such strategy. In
football you try to isolate Randy Moss when he's guarded by Tebucky
Jones. In hoops you pound the ball inside to Shaquille O'Neal when
he's posting up Mark Jackson. Baseball doesn't allow such
exploitation, but the White Sox figured out how to go at Izzy.
</P>
<P>
   Sox rookie righthander Paxton Crawford (wearing Heath Irwin's
old No. 63 jersey) retired the first eight batters he faced and we
were thinking about Billy Rohr at Yankee Stadium in April of 1967.
Then he walked No. 9 batter Mark Johnson. You know what all those
coaches say: The walks will kill you.
</P>
<P>
   After the walk, Ray Durham drilled a single to right. Because
the count was full, Johnson was running. Because Alcantara was in
right, Johnson scored. That's right. The catcher scored from first
on a single to right. Shades of Enos Slaughter in the 1946 World
Series (Slaughter actually scored from first on a double, but Harry
Walker's hit became a single in decades of retellings _ sort of
like ``Play it again, Sam,'' which is never actually uttered in
``Casablanca'').
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to cut the ball and get to the cutoff,'' said
Alcantara. ``I think I did my job.''
</P>
<P>
   No. He should have gotten to the ball quicker and made a
stronger throw to Frye. Neither mistake was of the forgivable,
physical variety.
</P>
<P>
   Next batter. Same problem. Jose Valentin hit a looping single to
right-center, but again it became a double because of the Izzy
Shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Alcantara committed a routine error, juggling a
ball hit to right-center. In the eighth, he singled to lead off the
inning, then found himself at second with Frye at first and two
out. When a pitch got away from Johnson, Frye broke from first and
had second, but Alcantara froze off second and was dead meat. He
didn't put up any kind of a fight. Like an Iraqi soldier in the
Gulf War, he threw down his weapon and surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He only had one way to go,'' said Frye. ``He said it was his
fault. But I don't see anybody not hustling.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it took a while for Everett to bring Alcantara's hat and
glove to the outfield for the start of the next inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for me to discuss with you guys what I feel about the
effort,'' said Everett. ``It's not the media's business. It's gonna
happen. He has to pick himself up and don't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that it appeared Alcantara wasn't trying very hard, Everett
said, ``That's what they used to say about me.''
</P>
<P>
   No one ever said it about Williams's Red Sox. Not until
Saturday. That's why there was a meeting. That's why Jimy wouldn't
talk about his team. This was not a day when Williams could recite
the mantra about ``kids playing hard.'' This was an unprofessional
effort by a professional ball club.
</P>
<P>
   And the players knew it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
