<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0822 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-HOWELL-     07-01 1975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-HOWELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROS OUTWEIGHED CONS FOR NEWCOMER HOWELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was easy to lose count, considering the number of people from
whom he accepted congratulations, but the word ``sir'' was used
many times Thursday as Charles Howell stepped away from the final
green after his first round as a professional golfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, sir,'' he said to a reporter at the Greater
Hartford Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' he said to a young fan who had requested an
autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir, I appreciate it,'' he said to a volunteer who had
followed his group.
</P>
<P>
   A mere 48 hours had passed since the 21-year-old Howell had
announced his decision to change his life forever, and though he
had shot a 1-over-par 71 and was seven strokes behind, he stood
amid a crowd of folks wanting to know even the slightest of
details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir'' he said. ``It was nerve-wracking. A little
uncomfortable, though I had more butterflies last night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir,'' he said. ``It hasn't sunk in yet. It hasn't hit me
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the thought occurred that in the days and weeks and
months and years to come, Howell may well grow tired of all the
attention, all the tugs at his time, all the requests, all the
questions. Then what?
</P>
<P>
   Too difficult to predict, said Debbie Howell, though she knew
one thing: ``He'd better always be nice or he's gonna have his
mother after him.'' Good round, bad round _ it didn't matter, she
said. ``He'd better always be polite.''
</P>
<P>
   The proud, but somewhat overwhelmed mother stood to the side
Thursday as her son made his way through the crowd that had
gathered. Debbie Howell knows ``a birdie from a bogey,'' but not
much else about golf, except that her son has been captivated by
the sport since he was 7 and watched a neighbor hit plastic golf
balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came into the house and asked, `Can I take golf lessons?'
'' said Debbie Howell.
</P>
<P>
   Golf? The parents were not sure. Debbie has never played and
will never play, she said. ``I don't have the temperament for it.''
Her husband, Charlie, a pediatric surgeon, started playing when his
son showed an interest, but he soon quit because he doesn't have
the time, she said. Brother Ben, 17, is a wrestler and a boxer and
has no interest in slapping around a little, dimpled white ball.
</P>
<P>
   But if young Charles wanted to, they figured, why not?
</P>
<P>
   The rest, as they say, is history. Within five years, Howell was
a junior golfer of great promise, a student of famed instructor
David Leadbetter, and fairly determined that golf would be his
life. Cross-country junior golf trips, a scholarship to Oklahoma
State, and an amateur career culminating with last month's
record-smashing NCAA championship victory put even more polish on
the star.
</P>
<P>
   A summer of marquee amateur events, starting with the Northeast
Amateur at Wannamoisett CC in Rumford, R.I., was on the horizon.
Then came a detour when he least expected it _ a sponsor's
exemption to play in a BUY.com Tour stop in Greensboro, N.C.
Instead of battling collegiate archrival Luke Donald in Rhode
Island, Howell nearly caught Kent Jones in North Carolina. He twice
shot 63 and finished second, which would have been worth $43,200
had he been a pro.
</P>
<P>
   On the trip from North Carolina to Hartford, where he was to
play in the GHO as an amateur on a sponsor's exemption, Howell was
left to ponder even more evidence that his pro stock was at its
highest, so when he got to Connecticut he called home. ``He was
talking about it,'' said Debbie. ``We were saying, `Charles,
wouldn't you rather have your mom and dad there with you for this,'
but he said, `No, I want to do this by myself.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So Charles Howell went to bed an amateur, woke up a
professional, and walked in to TPC River Highlands with a check for
the entry fee. There was, however, a dead giveaway that he was a
novice at this procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lady told him it was the first time anybody had paid their
entry fee with a check signed by a mother,'' said Debbie Howell,
author of that check. She was laughing, but when asked her feelings
about her son forgoing his final year in college, she was adamant:
``If he's happy, we're happy.''
</P>
<P>
   At 21, he is fearless, possesses a swing that can whip a 2-iron
250 yards, and drives well over 300 yards, so why shouldn't Howell
be happy? He's not silly enough, however, to think that this is the
same type of golf he played in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every shot is important out here,'' said Howell. ``That pretty
much is the biggest difference.'' He learned that the hard way
Thursday, when he made a double bogey at the par-4 first hole (his
10th). His drive found the rough and his second shot came up short,
leaving him a long putt over a mound on a sloping green. Howell
putted it off the green, chipped back on, and took two more with
the flat stick.
</P>
<P>
   Not a pleasant memory, but he was kidded that he could not have
possibly thought he'd go his entire pro career without a double.
``No, sir, so it's good to get that out of the way,'' he said,
laughing. Howell, however, shot a 3-under-par 67 Friday to make the
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsor's exemptions have come forward from the B.C. Open, the
John Deere Classic, and The International, events with
million-dollar purses, courtesy cars, exquisite golf courses,
premier treatment, and the chance for TV exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Life certainly has changed for this youngster who grew up in the
shadows of Augusta National, the most hallowed ground in golf. He
has played there with members, but you could say that he has taken
one step closer to a dream _ teeing it up in the Masters. A
heartwarming, almost incomprehensible thought, said Debbie Howell,
who didn't want to get ahead of herself. There was, after all, a
more pressing problem, she said after watching Round 1 of the GHO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so used to seeing him in his orange (Oklahoma State)
hat,'' she said, turning her attention to Charles, who stood nearby
wearing a blue Ping hat, signing an autograph for a marshal.
</P>
<P>
   The marshal thanked Howell, who, in turn, said, ``You're
welcome, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surprise endings
</P>
<P>
   Two tales from the world of amateur golf that demonstrate the
fragile nature of this great sport. In Florida, Justin Biggs
started the final round of the state's amateur championship 10
shots off the lead and was looking to move up a notch or two on the
leaderboard. When he posted a 6-under 66_287 at Pine Tree GC in
Boynton Beach, things got interesting, particularly since the
54-hole leader, Kevin Mock, made two double bogeys going out, then
completed his round with three straight bogeys to shoot 78_289. The
player two shots behind Mock at the start of the round, Brendan
Takacs, also made a pair of double bogeys and shot 76_289, and on
it went until Biggs's 1-under 287 proved good enough to win. In
Arizona, there was a comedown, not a comeback as Mark Johnson was
disqualified from the state's mid-amateur championship at a point
in the competition when he held an 11-shot lead with nine holes
left. It seems Johnson's son, Seth, was working as caddie,
accompanied by his friend, Derek, and a rules official spotted
Derek reaching into Johnson's bag and removing the player's putter.
Derek reportedly handed the putter to Johnson, while Seth carried
the bag to the green. A violation of Rule 6-4, said the official,
who cited Johnson for using more than one caddie. ``The toughest
call I ever had to make in my 25 years,'' said the rules official,
whose decision was made even worse by two twists _ the DQ took
place on Father's Day and on Seth's 14th birthday, and the decision
to caddie was his idea of a gift to his father . . . John Daly, to
the crowd at Monday's charity golf event hosted by Tom Lehman at
Minneapolis GC: ``I think it's time you guys get a PGA Tour event.
I'm sure the US Open's probably coming to (nearby) Hazeltine,
although I probably won't be playing in that one.'' At least right
now, Hazeltine is not on the list as US Open sites, but it is down
for a future Ryder Cup, though that, too, is an event Daly
shouldn't count on . . . Overseas this weekend, the Murphy's Irish
Open will be decided Sunday, though the easy winner of the event is
Ballybunion, which is arguably one of the world's greatest golf
courses. Surprisingly, Irishman Padraig Harrington had never played
Ballybunion before this week, and Seve Ballesteros was seeing it
for the first time, too. ``It made me feel the same way as when I
first saw St. Andrews,'' said Ballesteros. Told that he was the
overwhelming 6-1 favorite to win, Darren Clarke of Northern Ireland
scoffed: ``I wouldn't put a penny on myself at that and I wouldn't
put anything on at 60-1, either.'' . . . Brad Faxon has a
scheduling conflict that he says is unsettling and given his loyal
nature, you can understand why. After being sidelined with a broken
hand last year, Faxon returned in style to Endicott, N.Y., by
winning the B.C. Open in September and he very much wants to defend
that title. But the PGA Tour schedule-makers pushed that event up
to July this year, where it is opposite the British Open. After his
CVS Charity Classic at Rhode Island CC July 9-11, Faxon will head
to Great Britain to try to qualify for the British Open, ``but if I
miss, I'll come back for the B.C. Open,'' he said, adding that the
overlap was unfortunate . . . Mark Calcavecchia has missed just one
GHO since 1981, that being in 1985 when, after four years on Tour,
his career had still not taken off. He earned just $15,957 that
year and ranked 162d on the money list, yet he still found that he
was wanted at the GHO. ``(Tournament director) Ted May gave me an
exemption that year, and I always remember the people who were good
to me.'' Calcavecchia pointed to his tie for 12th in 1986 as a
springboard to a season that saw him jump to 58th on the money list
and he hasn't been outside the top 60 since. ``Ted can ask me and
I'll do anything he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The right call
</P>
<P>
   So, how exactly did Wendy Ward know her ball moved ever so
slightly last Sunday as she lined up a key putt in the final round
of the McDonald's LPGA Championship? Simple. Like many golfers, she
puts the ball down an exact way each time she lines up a putt, in
her case with the ``RULE 35'' on her Callaway looking directly at
her. Why? ``It's reminding me to enjoy the game, as their
philosophy goes.'' Of course, by calling the one-shot penalty on
herself (the ball rolled slightly after she soled her putter), it
was a little harder to enjoy the game, but she deserves a great
deal of credit for the way in which she handled the situation. Yes,
she missed a playoff spot by one shot . . . Heather Daly-Donofrio,
who recently resigned as golf coach at her alma mater, Yale, shot
an even-par 71 at Inniscrone GC in Avondale, Pa., to qualify for
next month's US Women's Open. Among those who also advanced were
LGPA Tour regulars Kathryn Marshall and Joan Pitcock, while 1997 US
Women's Amateur champ Silvia Cavalleri also made it. Pam Kerrigan
of Franklin, a rookie on the LPGA Tour, fell short, as did Kelly
Robb of Concord . . . The brightest picture at last weekend's
McDonald's LPGA Championship? The bright, flamboyant red, white,
and blue golf bag of Pat Bradley, the US captain for October's
Solheim Cup matches . . . A familiar name was tied for 14th at the
Northeast Amateur: Billy Haas, son of longtime PGA Tour star Jay
Haas. ``He loved it,'' said Jay, who played in the event when he
was a collegian. Billy Haas will also follow his father's footsteps
and enter Wake Forest this fall, giving dad two programs to follow
come September because Jay Haas Jr. plays golf at Augusta State.
Jay Haas, a nine-time winner on Tour, will be paired with Peter
Jacobsen at the CVS Charity Classic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
