<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS WINGING IT ON DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no mystery that the Bruins are coming off a lousy season.
It's also no mystery that their No. 1 need is on defense.
</P>
<P>
   With the strong possibility that veteran Don Sweeney, an
unrestricted free agent, will land somewhere else, the only
experienced blue liners sure to be back this fall are Hal Gill,
Kyle McLaren, and Darren Van Impe.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much out there among free agents _ the pickings on
defense are ultra slim _ and that is a cause for worry among Bruins
management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned,'' said president/general manager Harry Sinden.
``I think it falls short of what we need both in depth and in depth
of quality. McLaren, Gill, and Van Impe are fine, but we need three
more. If we had three more like them, we'd be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing Sweeney would be a big blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming through the year we had, there were very, very few
players, if any, who performed,'' said Sinden. ``He may be the only
one who did. He's only so good, he's not a great player. He's only
so good and he performed right up to his expectations and his
level.''
</P>
<P>
   That is to say the others didn't. McLaren was hurt for much of
year and Gill often looked confused and out of synch. Van Impe was
inconsistent and because of the injuries, was asked to do more than
he could.
</P>
<P>
   The upside for Gill is how well he played for Team USA in the
World Championships, but Sinden said that didn't make any
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gill was just one member of a team that played well below what
we thought they could do,'' he said. ``He's no different _ no worse
or no better _ than almost every other player on the team except,
perhaps, Sweeney.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for the Bruins to go out and grab a big-ticket
defenseman, it isn't going to happen. Sinden said they're looking
to make less dramatic changes through free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of them could help us, but there isn't anything
out there that is going to make a huge difference to this team,''
he said. ``They could make a slight difference, though, and we
should be looking to make slight differences.''
</P>
<P>
   An unknown is whether the young players in the system can make
that difference. One is Jonathan Girard, who is offensive-minded,
and the other is Martin Grenier, who came in the deal for Ray
Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Girard) is an enigma,'' said Sinden. ``He's like (Scott)
Niedermayer in New Jersey. I think he's going to come close this
year to really making it. He's just way out of his league (in
juniors). Under the rules, he went back, but he would have been
much better off if we could have sent him to Providence.''
</P>
<P>
   Grenier has not signed with Boston, but the club could use his
6-foot-5-inch, 231-pound frame and hard-nosed approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably like Girard, he's a totally different type of
player, but he probably could come close to making it,'' said
Sinden. ``He brings something we need, just like Girard brings
something else. Whether he's ready or not, that's a big step.''
</P>
<P>
   The team had high expectations for defenseman Nick Boynton, last
year's first-round pick. However, a diabetes diagnosis followed by
family problems and a serious shoulder injury hindered his
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through nobody's fault, I don't think he had anywhere near the
development he should have had in his first year,'' said Sinden.
``Next year, he likely won't be faced with a couple of crises.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said he and his staff are optimistic that two of their
draft picks, both defensemen, taken last weekend, could make
contributions in the same way forward Mikko Eloranta did last year.
</P>
<P>
   One is Jarmo Kultanen, taken at No. 174. He is 6-2, 198 pounds,
27 years old, and considered a late bloomer. He has been playing in
the Finnish Elite League the last several seasons. In the ninth
round, at No. 268, the Bruins took a chance on Pavel Kolarik, a
27-year-old native of the Czech Republic. He played last year with
Slavia Praha of the Czech Elite League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think they could come close to making the team,''
Sinden said. ``Whether they improve it or not is another question.
Whether they do enough to improve you or whether they're a little
too old to bother is another question. We have two there and both
come highly recommended. I would imagine they're as good as
Boynton, Girard or Brandon Smith or Mattias Timander. They're in
that class, but does that improve our team? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said if they make as much of a contribution as Eloranta
did in his first season, the club would be happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as I didn't count on Eloranta doing anything more than
hanging on to the team, I'm not counting on these guys at this
point either,'' said Sinden. ``The fact they've had experience over
there and they've both been substantial members of their teams is
kind of an indication they've got a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A painful decision
</P>
<P>
   Rough-and-tumble forward Wendel Clark called it a career
Thursday after 15 seasons. His spirit was still willing but his
body, ravaged by injuries, had had enough. Clark, who has the heart
of a lion, began his career as a Maple Leaf (his first of three
stints in Toronto) when he was taken first overall in the 1985
entry draft. After many stops, he ended his journey in the same
place it began. ``The timing right now just seems right,'' said
Clark, who reached the 30-goal plateau five times. ``I started as a
Leaf and now I can end as a Leaf. No matter where I played, this
has always felt like home.'' It was an emotional decision for
Clark, who tearfully made the announcement. ``He cried more here
than at our wedding,'' said Clark's wife, Denise . . . Nice to see
that sometimes there is justice. When the ruling came down in the
Ottawa Senators' favor, saying that bratty forward Alexei Yashin
owes the club one year of service before becoming a free agent
(hooray for common sense), the Senators announced they'd be happy
to welcome him back. It had to be hard for general manager Marshall
Johnston and majority owner Rod Bryden, both of whom showed a lot
of guts in waiting out Yashin, to keep from grinning ear to ear.
Yashin, who sat out an entire year because he thought $3.6 million
was too paltry for his services, has lost all leverage. Now, if the
Senators elect to trade him (a likely scenario), they're going to
have more options. Had the ruling gone in Yashin's favor, he would
have become a restricted free agent. Yashin has maintained he won't
play for any team for $3.6 million, so the saga continues. It
doesn't seem possible, despite the Senators' welcome mat, that
Yashin will play for the Senators, and at least one of his
teammates says good riddance. ``They've got to decide what's best
for the team, but he did refuse to play for us,'' said center
Vaclav Prospal. ``It's going to be difficult if he ends up here. I
think we were a better group without him.'' Reportedly, Yashin
recently received a speeding ticket for going 93 miles per hour in
a 62-m.p.h. zone. If Yashin wants to explore his options, slowing
down and growing up would seem appropriate . . . Former Bruins
assistant coach and all-around good guy Cap Raeder will be back
behind the bench this fall. He was hired as an assistant by the San
Jose Sharks, for whom he had been a scout . . . When the Columbus
Blue Jackets took defenseman Lyle Odelein in the expansion draft,
it was considered a risk because he was scheduled to become a
sought-after unrestricted free agent. However, the Blue Jackets
came to terms with the tough blue liner on a multiyear deal.
``Signing Lyle Odelein was a major priority for us coming out of
the expansion draft,'' said Columbus president and general manager
Doug MacLean. ``A lot of people thought we took him simply to get a
compensatory draft pick, but we took him to sign him. He will be an
anchor on our blue line and a real leader for our team. He is one
of the fiercest competitors in the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Low, will he go?
</P>
<P>
   Rumors abound that former Edmonton coach Ron Low might be
heading behind the Rangers' bench, which would reunite him with
former Oilers president Glen Sather, now in charge of cleaning up
the mess in Gotham. Low walked away from the Oilers last year after
Sather offered him a new contract for the same money he had made
the year before. Viewing that as a no-confidence vote, Low stepped
down. ``We're in the middle of talking, but that's all there is to
it right now,'' said Low. ``There's nothing there yet. So, take
everything you hear with a grain of salt and then add some
pepper.'' . . . Pretty shocking, isn't it, to see that the Montreal
Canadiens are for sale? Molson has decided to get out of the
business and has put the Habs on the block. Once again, the
financial strain of the Canadian dollar against the US dollar has
caused another north of the border franchise to decide it is tired
of losing money. Some reported to be interested in purchasing the
club are a group headed by former GM Serge Savard and
communications giant BCE . . . For a while it looked as if it were
a fait accompli that GM Lou Lamoriello, whose contract was up,
would be leaving the Devils. Because of the change in ownership, it
was rumored that Lamoriello was going to the Rangers, Phoenix,
Edmonton, and even Boston. But when the franchise is officially
turned over to YankeeNets July 12, Lamoriello will be at the helm.
That also means that coach Larry Robinson, who helped lead New
Jersey to the Stanley Cup, will be back . . . It took Mark Parrish
a while, but the former Florida Panther has warmed up to the idea
of playing for the New York Islanders. Parrish was part of the
multiplayer swap that set the stage for Islanders GM Mike Milbury
to select former Boston University goalie Rick DiPietro with the
No. 1 pick overall in draft. ``I wasn't exactly told I was on the
trading block,'' said Parrish, who is 23 and was traded for the
first time after two years in South Florida. ``I'll get a chance to
play a bigger role on an up-and-coming organization and I'm very
excited about it now. The way I described it to a friend of mine,
it's almost like you're breaking up with your first girlfriend. You
don't know how to react.'' Parrish said he might actually be a
better fit with Islanders coach Butch Goring, as opposed to
Florida's Terry Murray. ``Terry Murray is a good coach and he's
been known to make the playoffs a lot, but he's also not a young
players' coach,'' said Parrish. ``He likes his older guys. I've
heard nothing but great things about Butch and how he brings along
young guys and lets them just play.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snow removal?
</P>
<P>
   Wrentham native Garth Snow won't be staying in Vancouver. Snow,
an unrestricted free agent, wants to go to a team where he can play
more. ``(Canucks GM) Brian Burke and (assistant GM) Dave Nonis have
treated him great, but it's time to move on,'' said Snow's agent,
Steve Mountain. ``It's time to see if he can be a starter somewhere
else.'' Snow made $1.4 million US last season and was due to make
$1.9 million US this year, had the Canucks picked up the option on
his contract. Vancouver reportedly offered Snow a two-year deal
worth $1 million a season, but the goalie declined . . . Remember
Wes Walz, the former Bruins draft choice who signed the first
one-way contract Sinden ever agreed to? Well, he's back. Last week,
Walz signed with the Minnesota Wild. The 30-year-old, who was
drafted in the third round in 1989, played six games with Long
Beach of the IHL last year with an eye toward making an NHL
comeback, but decided to return to the Swiss Elite League, where he
had been the last several seasons. He helped Lugano win that
league's regular-season title with 10 goals and 15 assists in 18
games. Walz played 73 games for Boston in 1989-90 and '90-91,
notching 21 points, including nine goals. He also played for
Philadelphia, Detroit, and Calgary before heading overseas.
Calgary's GM when Walz was there was Doug Risebrough, now the
Wild's GM . . . Sixty-seven days to training camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
