<SLUG> BC-SAIL-SAILING-AMERICASCUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUP HAS ALTERED ITS COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the briefest of moments, oh somewhere around the early 1980s
and the dawning of the Dennis Conner era, people actually discussed
the America's Cup in terms of an ``Olympic-style'' sport.
</P>
<P>
   That was code for ``equal opportunity,'' and it rested on the
uncomplicated faith that the America's Cup _ symbol of supremacy of
yacht design, building, and the seamanship to sail such creations
better than anyone else _ was open to all nations on a roughly
egalitarian basis.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if this ideal were ever even worth applying to the
nation's oldest sporting trophy, it disappeared entirely when in
mid-May, the world's modern high-tech barrons began plundering Team
New Zealand and dividing up the spoils of _ no, not a victory on
the water _ but of another game called: ``Who wants to be a sailing
millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, we all know Team New Zealand was not as squeaky clean and
pristine as it seemed on that March day when Russell Coutts turned
the helm over to the fair-faced understudy, Dean Barker, and said,
in effect: ``You take it from here, kid. Win one for the
motherland.''
</P>
<P>
   And Barker did. And Team New Zealand, by virtue of its virtue,
it seemed, had crushed all the high-rollers in the world in
embarrassing fashion. And since no potential competitors even had a
clue how to get to where TNZ was in the year 2000, how would they
possibly figure out how to get to where it would be in 2003?
</P>
<P>
   It certainly seemed as if a dynasty was at hand for at least a
couple of Cup cycles, especially when the Team New Zealand
leadership made, as a final gesture, something like a blood oath
that filthy lucre would never break up the very solidity from
whence TNZ's magic powers seemed to flow.
</P>
<P>
   By now even casual Cup observers know what this spring has
wrought on New Zealand. A posse of the world's billionaires, which
descended on the island largely as spectators last fall and has not
only plundered Team New Zealand but has reset the entire landscape
for the next Cup backward.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday in Monaco, an unofficial meeting took place of the
challengers of 2003 to swap some informalities about the next Cup,
sponsored by The Louis Vuitton Cup Challenger Series. The Louis
Vuitton Cup is the four-month series of races among all the Cup
challengers to determine which team will challenge the Cup
defender. Last time, Prada won the Louis Vuitton Cup and got waxed,
5-0, by New Zealand for the America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Since no one has officially challenged (deadline is next March),
the meeting in Monaco was not an official Challenger of Record
Management committee meeting, and yet many of the alignments
already are clear. Even owing to the inevitable attrition that
takes place as we get closer to Cup deadlines, here is a rundown of
those participating in the Monaco non-meeting:
</P>
<P>
   New York Yacht Club/Team Dennis Conner; Seattle Yacht
Club/OneWorld Challenge, backed by Craig McCaw; the Corinthian
Yacht Club/Seattle Challenge, backed by Russell Belden; Australian
Challenge, backed by Syd Fischer; Le Defi Francais, returning; FAST
2000 from Switzerland, returning; Ernesto Bertarelli from
Switzerland, with New Zealand's Coutts and Brad Butterworth.
</P>
<P>
   Missing in action because of the French airline strike were Dawn
Riley's America True and Japan's Nippon Challenge, both returnees.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda of the meeting, according to Louis Vuitton's Bruno
Trouble, was a discussion of the world audience and the events
leading up to the next Cup, one to sail in the Med, another in New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the old Olympic hey-everyone-jump-in spirit _ a look
at the lineup makes it pretty clear that the great divide will come
between those groups that have to beat the bushes for corporate
funds and civic bake sales and those with unlimited funding who can
hit the ground at full speed. This is no five-year waiting period,
as was the last Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly absent from the Monaco list is Prada boss and
owner Patrizio Bertelli _ perhaps not in the billionaire's club at
$650 million, but he won't get snubbed. Bertelli bought the hard
goods developed by Young America. The intellectual properties
remain a question.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the takeover of the Cup by billionaires is really a step
backward, and is perhaps traceable to Bill Koch in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest Cup was fought for world sailing supremacy by
bitter rivals whose grandfathers had fired cannons at each other in
the War of 1812. So, for the captains of the industrial revolution
with names like Astor, Morgan, and Vanderbilt, to take on the
British sea supremacy _ even in the hour of the Empire's decline _
was far more serious than a summer regatta among friendly nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Cup did go through its clubby period as the post-war racing
started up in 1958. Conner, and his two-boat,
leave-no-stone-unturned approach to enlisting corporate backing
took the Cup in a very new direction, the outward appearance of
which has been rued to this day by purists: all that damn
advertising on the hull, the sails, the racing suits.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the effort to keep the corporate logos in some sort of
good taste, clearly a corner had been turned.
</P>
<P>
   And now, if the richest men in the world turn the entire sailing
pool into a free agency draft for a very finite supply of top
players (witness the NBA and Major League Baseball to see the same
effect), the Cup will very surely have turned another corner.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever loses, it will not be the sport of sailing _ 2003
promises to be great stuff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
