<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-USBASEBALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOGGS BALKS AT TRYOUT OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No stars and stripes for Boggsie in Sydney after all.
</P>
<P>
   Though former Red Sox third baseman Wade Boggs is headed for the
Hall of Fame, US Olympic baseball officials wanted him to spend a
couple of weeks with an independent minor league team to make sure
he could still put his bat on the ball. No thanks, said the
41-year-old Boggs, who said he didn't want to spend a fortnight in
the bushes with no guarantee of making the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun for a while to actually think about playing in the
Olympics,'' said Boggs, now a special assistant in the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays front office, in a St. Petersburg (Fla.) Times report
last week. Though retired major leaguers are eligible for the
Games, only a handful _ like Terry Steinbach _ are both willing and
able to play. Most of the squad, which will be chosen in late
August, will be minor leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Political backflips
</P>
<P>
   Team coordinator Bela Karolyi has his doubts about the
four-person committee that will choose half of the six-member US
Olympic women's gymnastics team at next month's trials at the
FleetCenter. ``I am the only one who watches them since January,''
said Karolyi, who has convened the top contenders for monthly boot
camps at his Houston ranch. The rest of the committee _ 1984
Olympian Tracee Talavera, judge Marilyn Cross, and gymnast Chari
Knight _ will have to see them in competition this month. Not that
anybody expects that all votes will carry equal weight at selection
time, even though they're supposed to. Karolyi, who has been to
every Games since 1976, is the sport's all-time backroom politician
. . . Rough reentry for gymnast Shannon Miller, who's trying to
make her third Olympic team at 23. After an encouraging camp
performance in May, she had a dreadful outing at a recent meet in
Ontario, falling twice from the beam (where she won gold in
Atlanta) and once from the bars. ``Different ballgame,'' said
Karolyi, who chalked up Miller's miscues to adjusting her 1996
skills to 2000 realities. ``She knows now where she is at.''
There's good news on the men's side where Jason Gatson, who tore
his ACL last year, is rounding into form. ``His knee is not quite
100 percent, but we think he'll be ready to go,'' said coach Peter
Kormann. ``He's tumbling and he's vaulting and he looks like he's
on track to be a major contender.'' . . . New Zealand sculler Rob
Waddell suffered his first loss in two years at the recent World
Cup rowing event in Vienna. Waddell, the two-time world champ, was
beaten in the semis by defending Olympic gold medalist (and former
Brown oarsman) Xeno Mueller of Switzerland, who hadn't won a race
in two years. ``It's a long way to the Olympics, and I haven't
peaked yet,'' said Waddell, who's odds-on to win in Sydney. The
sample-sized US flotilla had a promising showing _ a silver medal
from the men's lightweight four and bronzes by the men's quad and
the women's double of Ruth Davidon and Norwood's Carol Skricki. The
Yanks will send virtually all hands (except for the eights and
possibly sculler Don Smith) to this month's event in Lucerne,
Switzerland, which follows the last-chance Olympic qualifier there
. . . There'll be no return ticket for all three US Greco-Roman
wrestlers who won Olympic silvers last time. Matt Ghaffari, Brandon
Paulson, and Dennis Hall were all beaten at last weekend's trials
in Dallas. So all eight team members will be rookies. The freestyle
team returns only Melvin Douglas (and injured Les Gutches, if he
beats Charles Burton in their challenge), but has two former world
champs in Terry Brands and Sammie Henson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Family first
</P>
<P>
   Why wasn't Sheryl Swoopes, named last week as the final member
of the US Olympic women's basketball team, one of the first 11
picked? She had taken herself out of the running because family
commitments kept her from participating on the team's lengthy
exhibition tour. Swoopes, who was the third-leading scorer in
Atlanta and has sparked the Houston Comets to three straight WNBA
titles, is leading the league in scoring . . . Ticklish choice
upcoming for US Olympic women's tennis coach Billie Jean King, who
has to name her squad a week from Monday. Does she pick doubles
specialist Corina Morariu to go with Lindsay Davenport and hope
they regain their championship form? That would mean leaving off
Serena Williams, which might provoke sister Venus into staying
home. Or does she use the Williamses as her doubles unit?
``Somebody is going to be left behind,'' said King. ``It is not
fun.'' If she could name five players, as the men can, she wouldn't
have a problem. But since the Women's Tennis Association has chosen
not to have Olympic results count toward its rankings (as the men's
ATP does), it gets one less player per country . . . It was a
double dip for diver Mark Ruiz. He qualified for the US Olympic
team on both springboard and platform last week. The 21-year-old
Ruiz could have had a walk-on if he'd chosen to compete for his
native Puerto Rico, but he has lived in Florida since he was 12.
David Pichler could also have doubled, but he splattered his final
springboard dive and ended up fourth. Also on the team are 1996
veteran Jenny Keim, Troy Dumais, Michelle Davison, Laura Wilkinson,
and Sara Reiling. The Americans, who didn't make the podium at the
last world championships, have won a medal at every Olympics since
1912 _ 127 in all . . . Life begins at 40 for the US Olympic
dressage team, which will average 42 at Sydney. On the squad for
the fourth time is Robert Dover (44), who will be joined by
Christine Traurig (43), Sue Blinks (42), and Guenter Seidel (39) .
. . Back within Olympic medal range is the US men's volleyball
team, which breezed unbeaten through its World League qualifying
group on the way to next week's finals in the Netherlands. The
squad, ranked fifth in the world, plays its final Olympic tuneup at
the Springfield Civic Center July 22 against the Bulgarians, who
knocked them out of medal contention four years ago in Atlanta . .
. A complicating factor in US Olympic men's soccer goalkeeper Adin
Brown's return from last week's second knee arthroscopy is that
he's a Christian Scientist, which limits his treatment options and
may delay his rehab. Brown, who plays for the Colorado Rapids, is
expected to be sidelined for up to three weeks . . . Why will the
Edmonton organizers end next year's world outdoor track and field
championships with the men's 4 x 100 relay instead of the 4 x 400?
To set the stage for a last hurrah for Olympic gold medalist
Donovan Bailey and his mates, who'll be ending their careers on
home soil . . . Washington outbid Vienna and Hamar, Norway, for the
2003 world figure skating championships, which will be held at the
MCI Center. It'll be the 11th time a US city has hosted the event
and the first time since 1998, when the site was Minneapolis.
Vancouver will stage next year's championships, with Nagano hosting
in 2002 . . . After an eight-year absence, the World Cup luge
circuit finally returns to the States next February for not one but
two events. They'll not only be sliding on the Olympic track in
Salt Lake City, they'll finish the season on Lake Placid's new run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
