<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-YOUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMS CHECK IN WITH YOUTH INFUSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 2000 NBA draft is history. The courtship of free agents has
begun. It's time to take a look at the teams, see how they did, see
what they need, and see where they're staying over this Fourth of
July weekend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ritz
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO: ``We're loaded and ready to go,'' coach Doc Rivers said
on draft night. Boy, is he right. The Magic were the undisputed
winners, getting one of the top prospects (Mike Miller) and trading
their other two picks, along with two players, for future
first-round picks. Those deals, say Orlando executives, enable the
team to make not only a hard run at the big free agents, but also
to keep valuable free agents Bo Outlaw and Ben Wallace. They have a
plan, that's for sure. Tim Duncan is the key. If he can be
convinced to sign with the Magic, it will trigger a second wave of
interest among the other desirables. Who wouldn't want to play with
Duncan and for Rivers? They'll still do well, but the whole plan
revolves around Duncan. If they can't get him, no one can. He'll
stay in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Four Seasons
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS: We all should know by now that owner Mark Cuban isn't
afraid to do anything. He opened a drawer in his foyer and took out
$3 million to send to the Magic. The Mavs upgraded in the
department that needed the most upgrading: rebounding. They drafted
Etan Thomas (a poor man's Buck Williams) and added Donnell Harvey
via a trade with New York. Harvey is ready to rebound now. They
also got a scorer in Courtney Alexander, although he plays the same
position as Ironman Michael Finley. The Mavericks finished the
season strong. They still need a center, but who doesn't? And wait
until they get into the serious free agent market once they unload
millstone Shawn Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: They had reservations at the Ritz, but when they got
there, it was booked. They basically took Marcus Fizer to thwart a
Clippers-Magic trade that would have given Orlando Darius Miles.
How Fizer fits with Elton Brand will be interesting. Then they
drafted a center (Chris Mihm), but traded him to division rival
Cleveland for a point guard with 17 games of college experience
(Jamal Crawford). Then they drafted another center (Dalibor
Bagaric) who likely will stay overseas. They had better hit the
free agent jackpot, and we don't mean Pervis Ellison.
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY: New honcho Rod Thorn resisted inquiries and took the
best player in the draft. Was Kenyon Martin crying because he was
happy or because he is going to play for the Exit 16Ws? But Jersey
is staying here only on a weekend rate because it lost Jayson
Williams (retirement) and may lose Kerry Kittles. Martin fills a
huge hole _ we can't see him taking any, er, stuff, from Stephon
Marbury _ and if Kittles can make it back, the Nets could move up a
notch. New coach Byron Scott apparently has all the right stuff,
which he's going to need.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: How did Olumide Oyedeji slide into the second round?
Wasn't Dallas going to take him at 12? Didn't the Celtics bring him
back for a second look? There must have been some 11th-hour scare,
because no one pegged him there prior to the draft. But if he can
be cleared to play, the Sonics got two great athletes in Oyedeji
and Desmond Mason, a true senior. Either could be insurance if
Rashard Lewis bolts, which may happen because the Sonics are locked
into what they can pay. But what Seattle needs more than anything
is for Vin Baker to stop whatever he's been doing the last two-plus
years, lose the weight, and be the player he was in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Westin
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER: The Grizzlies may have gotten the best player in the
draft because Stromile Swift is two years younger than Martin. In
addition, he wants to be in Vancouver (which is, by the way, a
beautiful city, even if it is in what Kenny Anderson called a
foreign country). The Grizzlies have a nice, young nucleus, which
may mesh in a year or two. By that time they'll be in Nashville or
New Orleans and be good enough so that Dick Versace can take over
the coaching duties.
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX: Why do I think that if anyone is going to extract Jake
Tsakalidis from Greece, it will be Jerry Colangelo? It's a wonder
Tsakalidis lasted as long as he did (No. 25); surely he'll be in
the NBA sooner than later. He's young, he has an NBA body, and if
he can be half as good as Arvydas Sabonis, the Suns will be happy.
Surround him with good players, which Phoenix has, and he could be
even better.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: The Bucks released Tractor Traylor from George Karl's
doghouse and shipped him to Cleveland. They then got Joel Przybilla
via a draft-night trade with Houston, which, if he develops, could
be a coup. At worst, they got a shot-blocking center. They also got
Jason Caffey, who was a disappointment at Golden State. Their big
chore is re-signing Tim Thomas. The feeling is that Milwaukee,
already shelling out big bucks to Big Dog Glenn Robinson and Ray
Allen, won't go to the max for Thomas. But someone (Chicago?) will,
although he's not worth it.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Speedy Claxton would have helped the Sixers in the
playoffs after Eric Snow went down. They also got a serviceable
player in local favorite Mark Karcher (Temple) in the second round.
But the ongoing dilemma is the relationship between Larry Brown and
Allen Iverson. Do the Sixers really feel they can win with Iverson,
who was on time for one practice during the playoffs? And what will
they do with Toni Kukoc? We can't see Brown taking in Glen Rice,
because Brown likes guys who play (or try to play) defense. Then
again, Kukoc doesn't do much at that end of the floor, either.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: OK, we still don't get the Traylor trade, although it
mostly was about moving Bob Sura and his salary. But the Cavaliers
did get Mihm, which, given their interior woes, was a nice
addition. He may turn out to be Danny Schayes Part 2, but the soft
label seems more convenient than fair. Brad Daugherty was supposed
to be soft, too, remember? He turned out all right. We just wonder
if the Gund Arena practice floor can take Traylor guarding Shawn
Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Marriott
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: The Celtics would have been relegated to the Milner
Hotel had they traded three first-round picks for Jermaine O'Neal.
(The last time that happened, it was for Bob McAdoo.) But Portland
wouldn't bite and Jerome Moiso is now aboard. He speaks three
languages, which will come in handy when his legendary passivity
riles Rick Pitino. ``The questions for him are strength and
toughness,'' said his UCLA coach, Steve Lavin. ``But it's
refreshing to work with someone like him because he's not a prima
donna or have an overstated opinion of himself.'' He was a good
pick at 11 _ most had him gone before then _ and the Celtics did
need to get more athletic. But he also plays the same position as
Antoine Walker, who generally stays on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Holiday Inn
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Raptors still need a point guard, but they weren't
enthralled with what they saw in the draft. In Morris Peterson,
they got a ready-for-service wingman who can step in for the
soon-to-be-departing Tracy McGrady. Toronto has a Hall of Fame
coach in Lenny Wilkens, a superstar in the making in Vince Carter,
and one of the most attractive free agents in McGrady. It looked
for a while as if the Raptors were on to something.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: The Hawks said DerMarr Johnson was the guy they wanted
and he's an improvement over their last shooting guard, a guy named
Rider. Hanno Mottola was supposed to be a first-rounder, but he
fell into the second.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH: If kids can stay free, they'll get by with DeShawn
Stevenson. There isn't a more professional place he could have
landed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel California
</P>
<P>
   LA CLIPPERS: You can check out any time you like, but you can
never leave. Except if you're a free agent. Yes, they got all those
great young players. They always get them. Then they lose them or
abuse them. Charles Barkley is right. This is no place for young
Mr. Miles.
</P>
<P>
   LA LAKERS: Gee, do you think they'll survive the loss of A.C.
Green? Draftee Mark Madsen has probably already read all the books
Phil Jackson likes to distribute to the players.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Motel 6
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Just what the Knicks needed, another point guard. They
made a decent draft selection in Harvey and then traded him to
Dallas for Erick Strickland. Did they think it was Rod?
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: Let's hope the Pistons are as happy with Mateen Cleaves
as he is with them. Scouts didn't like his size, speed, or shot. He
should have showed them his NCAA championship ring. The Pistons
have bigger, more immediate concerns, in Grant Hill. If he leaves,
can you spell lottery?
</P>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE: What position don't they need? Power forward. What
position does Jamaal Magliore play? Yup. Now, if they can move
either Anthony Mason or Derrick Coleman, this pick might make a
little more sense.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Maybe there isn't much of a difference between
Przybilla and Jason Collier. The Rockets obviously didn't think so.
They also got a No. 1 out of the deal. But Collier is not an
interior-type guy and Przybilla is.
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO: The Kings like those Euros. Actually, their guy is a
Turk (Hidayet Turkoglu), but he supposedly can play a little. They
also got a backup center (Jabari Smith) in the second round, which
is better than getting one in the first.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Morrison Hotel
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI: Pat Riley got a couple of second-rounders (Eddie House,
Ernest Brown) who one day might play. But he also made a pre-draft
trade that brought back whipping boy Chris Gatling and gives the
Heat the possibility of free agent shopping next summer. Now all
they have to do is get Tim Hardaway's name on a one-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN STATE: The Warriors' pick was in February and it was
Larry Hughes. Not bad. They also got Sura and Vinny Del Negro in a
pre-draft, three-team deal.
</P>
<P>
   PORTLAND: The guess here is the Blazers could have had the first
10 picks in the draft and still won't recover from that monumental
meltdown in Game 7 against the Lakers. Then again, given the way
they played in March and April, no one figured them to get that
far. They have to find out what gives with Brian Grant and then
deal with the O'Neal situation. It's hard to believe they turned
down three No. 1s for O'Neal, who wasn't good enough to get off the
bench in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roach Motel
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON: The Wizards' only pick was in the second round.
Michael Jordan has a few more pressing engagements.
</P>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO: The Spurs' only pick was in the second round. Gregg
Popovich has another matter on his hands with only the future of
the franchise at stake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bates Motel
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA: Maybe Larry Bird knew the Pacers were planning on
drafting Primoz Brezec and decided to get out. (Bird has trouble
pronouncing Detlef; we can just see him with this guy.) Brezec was
a reserve on his club team and his numbers have gone down the last
three years. Why didn't they just pass?
</P>
<P>
   DENVER: The Nuggets actually made a trade to get a late
first-rounder (Mamadou N'diaye). What were they thinking?
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: The Timberwolves hosted the draft and didn't have a
first-round pick. But they made sure to reward all those who
persevered with their second-round selection of point guard Igor
Rakocevic from Red Star Belgrade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
