<HEADER>
A0828 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-GIANTS-LA     07-01 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-GIANTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEREZ NOT BAD, BUT NOT GOOD ENOUGH TO BEAT GIANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The better Carlos Perez pitches, the fewer
alleged prospects the Dodgers will be tempted to package in a deal
at the trade deadline to acquire the veteran starter Dodgers
general manager Kevin Malone talked of the day Orel Hershiser was
waived.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows? If Perez pitches well enough, maybe the Dodger
won't need to make a deal at all.
</P>
<P>
   According to those who matter, Perez threw two bad pitches
Saturday against San Francisco, and he's progressing nicely.
</P>
<P>
   According to what matters, though, those two pitches resulted in
four runs and a 4-1 Giants victory at Pac Bell Park. It's the first
time in five games the Giants have beaten the Dodgers this season.
</P>
<P>
   Giants lefty Kirk Rueter (6-4) won his fourth straight by
holding the Dodgers down for six innings. Four relievers, including
closer Rob Nen, pitched the final three innings. The once-vaunted
Dodgers lineup has turned sporadic and inconsistent, scoring three
runs or less in 11 of their last 28 games. They've lost all 11
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Perez) has been pitching better lately, but we didn't get him
any runs,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``He pitched out of
some jams, he competed. I felt like we would win that ballgame if
we just hang close.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez has spent the first three months of the season looking
over his shoulder at what's chasing him, be it Eric Gagne, Orel
Hershiser or the minor leagues. None of those are issues any more.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne's here, Hershiser's not, the minor leagues are out and
Perez said he had such stiffness in the right side of his neck that
he couldn't turn his head. Or look over his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough day; the problem with my neck, feeling sick the
last two days, fever and other kind of stuff, but I'm the kind of
guy that likes to play,'' Perez said. ``It was tough for me to
pitch inside. I tried to go inside twice and gave up a homer a
double. I was glad to have good command with my fastball, and I
used that to get ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a win for the Dodgers, but it wasn't an abomination.
And in Perez's case, not to mention the Dodgers', that's paramount.
</P>
<P>
   Perez was coming off a pair of strong relief appearances in
which he allowed one run in 8 innings. It was enough to place him
back in the rotation and Hershiser into limbo. Yet, Perez hasn't
won since May 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a good game for the way I feel right now,'' said
Perez, who pitched six innings. ``I didn't think I was going to go
six innings. When I woke up, I didn't think I was going to be
available to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   While Perez pointed to the two pitches that resulted in two-run
homers by Ramon Martinez in the third inning and Rich Aurilia in
the fourth, it's not as if he didn't make other mistakes that led
to his unnerving during those innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Calvin Murray grounded to Kevin Elster at
shortstop, but the Dodgers were slow in turning a double play and
Murray was safe. Perez then balked Murray to second before Martinez
hit an 0-2 split-finger fastball over the left-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos isn't going to shut many people out, but he kept us in
the ballgame. That's all you can ask,'' Dodgers first baseman Eric
Karros said. ``(The balk) hasn't been called all year. That may
have got him rattled. I think the fact we were unable to turn the
double play kind of got to him a little bit. It was a combination
of the two, and give any team opportunities like that, and
eventually you're going to get burned.''
</P>
<P>
   Aurilia's homer made it 4-0, and unlike the night before when
the Dodgers pounded Giants pitching for nine runs, they got little
going offensively.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the first three innings, the Dodgers grounded into
inning-ending double plays. Their only run came on F.P.
Santangelo's shallow sacrifice fly to right center in the seventh
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like to start the runners, but (Rueter) also has a great
move,'' Johnson said. ``The jumps we were getting, if we started
them it wouldn't have made any difference.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
