<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0829 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-WHITESOX-B     07-01 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-WHITESOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX LACK FIRE IN CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Hit bottom? Don't be so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it looks like we're in free fall and there's no end
in sight,'' Red Sox second baseman Jeff Frye said after a 7-2 loss
to the Chicago White Sox so unspeakable, manager Jimy Williams's
public postmortem was reduced to a single four-letter word.
</P>
<P>
   ``U-G-L-Y, that's it on the game. Ugly,'' Williams said, arms
crossed and face flushed with the same anger he showed his team
immediately after the game, when he kept the clubhouse door closed
while giving his players an earful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him upset, pretty fired up before,'' shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra said after a game in which the Sox were charged with
three errors, allowed four unearned runs, and committed other
blunders that did not show up in the box score but were seared onto
Williams's brain plate. ``He was upset today, and he has a right to
be. He's right, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox dropped to .500 (38-38) for the first time since April
14 after losing for the ninth time in their last dozen games, their
second straight loss to the White Sox assuring them of not winning
a series for the seventh straight time. Since May 19, when they
were 25-13 and 12 games above .500, the Sox have lost nine series,
won two, and split two, both against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Embarrassing,'' Frye said. ``We didn't pitch good, we didn't
hit good, we didn't field good. We made mental mistakes, we made
physical mistakes, anything we could do wrong we did wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard to watch? Imagine playing in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams didn't raise his voice, pitcher Bryce Florie said. He
didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was due,'' Florie said. ``We needed it. Some guys on the
team were already thinking of doing something, but he beat us to
the punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He basically said we were playing with our heads up our butts.
It's one thing when you're getting beat and putting everything on
the line. But when you're making mental mistake after mental
mistake, you can't put up with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at (the White Sox). They were making all the plays,
taking the extra base. That's what made this team what it is,
playing hard whether we're up by 10 runs or down by 10 runs.
Everybody knew that's what they got when they played the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then you get in a situation like this, everything gets
magnified. People start mentioning things, guys start saying, `Why
did you do this?' That's when the finger-pointing starts. I've been
on those kinds of teams. You start losing, the bad vibes get going.
That's why we have to nip this in the bud.''
</P>
<P>
   The one player spared Williams's wrath was rookie pitcher Paxton
Crawford, who did a credible job filling in for the best pitcher in
baseball, the injured Pedro Martinez, in a debut that was big
league in name only.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I didn't make him mad,'' said Crawford, a guileless
22-year-old from Plummerville, Ark., a hamlet of 500, some of whom
almost certainly could have played a better right field than Izzy
Alcantara did Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was intended or not, Alcantara displayed a maddening
nonchalance both in the field, where he allowed a catcher (!), Mark
Johnson, to score Chicago's first run from first base on a single,
and on the basepaths, where he was caught in a rundown between
second and third after coming to a halt for no discernible reason
on what should have been a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Alcantara, who also played Jose Valentin's single into a
run-scoring double for the second White Sox run, later was charged
with an error when he picked up Chris Singleton's leadoff single in
the sixth, then dropped it as he prepared to throw, allowing
Singleton to take second. New third baseman Ed Sprague, who somehow
was not charged with a throwing error on the first ball hit his
way, followed with a two-base error when Carlos Lee's ground ball
clanked off his glove. The White Sox went on to score four runs in
the inning, three on Valentin's bases-loaded triple off Rich
Garces.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the ugliest game I've been a part of since I've been
here,'' said catcher Jason Varitek, who threw wildly into right
field after bumping into plate umpire Mike Van Vleet, an error that
led to the third Chicago run, scored in the third inning. ``Any
manager would be upset. Guys are upset.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were held to four hits in eight innings by lefty
Mike Sirotka, all singles. Brian Daubach singled home Boston's only
run off Sirotka, but even that play wound up tainted, as
Garciaparra was erased at the plate trying to score from second on
a terrific throw by Singleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes to fail,'' Garciaparra said. ``We've always had a
club where everybody knew the demeanor of the club, how you've got
to play. Everybody picked each other up. We're not doing that now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's got to look in the mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   And what will they see? Varitek, whose ninth-inning RBI double
in the ninth was Boston's only extra-base hit of the game, is
hopeful they'll see the essence of what has made them winners in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough time for a lot of people,'' he said. ``We
really need to dig deep and trust in our abilities when we go out
there. If we play hard and concentrate, good things are going to
eventually happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't all of a sudden say, `Today's the day we're
going to make it happen.' You have to keep grinding, game after
game after game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
