</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOOD WON WITHOUT PLAYING A SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Suppose they gave a Wimbledon final _ and nobody showed
up.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen quite that way. But sort of, smiles 88-year-old
Sidney Wood, the most _ shall we say, mature? _ of the champions
who Saturday paraded across the fading lawn of Centre Court where
they had spent glorious afternoons of dashing and bashing and
making names for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs was a millennial reunion, an extraordinary celebration of
bygone (and present) prowess, a convention of sneakered gods,
dripping with auld lang syne. Some were decrepit, others as sleek
as Boris Becker and Stefan Edberg, fetching as Steffi Graf and
Evonne Goolagong.
</P>
<P>
   Henry ``Bunny'' Austin, the English humanitarian who liberated
the male knee by introducing shorts, arrived in a wheelchair.
Although he finished second to Americans Ellsworth Vines in 1932
and Don Budge in 1938, and is ``doing better'' with his walking at
home, Austin says that, despite the abysmal state of British
tennis, he's not contemplating a comeback. He will be 94 next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The Brits may have lost their Empire, but not their touch in
stylish presentations, laced with pomp and circumstance. They know
how to do these things, rolling out a red carpet, a scarlet-coated
brass band of the Scots Guards, and a spare duchess to preside.
She, the Duchess of Gloucester (not Gloucester, Mass., I'm told),
handed out mementos to the 65 champs and runners-up in a ceremony
that kept the packed-in audience of 13,812 applauding for almost an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the noise meter were the house record-holder Billie Jean
King (20 titles overall), double-Grand Slammer Rod Laver, Bjorn
Borg, Andre Agassi, John McEnroe, Chris Evert, Martina Navratilova,
Goolagong, Becker, Graf, and the last English champ, Virginia Wade
(23 years ago).
</P>
<P>
   Borg got an extra hurrah as he stooped to kiss a baseline where
he spent most of his time in winning five titles. But no one was
slighted in acclamation.
</P>
<P>
   While the band played ``God Save the Queen,'' as archaic as such
may seem, for a moment you felt touched, and removed to 1877, the
year the Big W commenced, when London was the center of the
universe and Victoria ruled a worldwide Empire. Ruling Wimbledon is
still tantamount to holding the world title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our most important tournament,'' says an American named
Pete Sampras, who missed the parade. Icing and other treatment for
his inflamed left foot and shin took precedence before he went onto
Centre Court to struggle for almost an hour against Justin
Gimelstob. Presently ``the adrenaline kicked in'' and the champ
joined the last 16, 2-6, 6-4, 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up at the royal box, and saw Borg and Laver,'' he
laughs, ``and I was embarrassed to play so bad in front of them. I
wanted to throw my racket up there and let them play.'' Sampras got
his commemorative platter from the Duchess later.
</P>
<P>
   Pauline Betz Addie, the doyenne of female champs as the 1946
victor, continues playing regularly in Washington at 80. The widow
of a baseball writer, Bob Addie, who covered the hapless Senators
(long since vanished from the American League) for the Washington
Post, she recalls his colleagues ribbing him. They said Pauline was
the only winning athlete he associated with.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Wood, a lively New Yorker, the champion of 1931, finally
got his Centre Court recognition _ a little late, but ``worth
waiting for.'' Friskily he approached the Duchess, properly bowed
his full head of ashen hair, and you thought he might be asking her
(about 45 years his junior) if she'd like to step out in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   You see, there was no presentation on his great day. No final,
in fact. Wood is the only major champ to win by default. It wasn't
that he appeared on court, looked around, and said, ``Where's
Frank?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I knew the day before that I was the champion. My pal,
Frank Shields _ you know, Brooke Shields's grandfather later in his
life _ was supposed to play me for the title. But he sprained his
ankle in the semis, beating Jean Borotra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevertheless, Frank wanted to play, and could have played. You
won't believe this, but the US Davis Cup committee wouldn't let
him. We were going to play the Brits the following weekend in the
semifinals at Paris. Sam Hardy, the captain, and the rest of the
committee, said the Davis Cup came first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine that happening today, expecting a guy to give
up a shot at the Wimbledon title just to be ready for a Cup match?
We lost anyway, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we were amateurs then, and the USTA (US Tennis
Association) had the power of life and death over us. Frank and I
thought it was a terrible affront to Wimbledon to leave them
without a men's final, but that's the way it was. We felt we were
co-champs. Wimbledon gave me the small trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   He grins, ``Here's what we did. I told Frank that the next time
we played a grass court final the winner would get the Wimbledon
trophy. That happened the following year here, at the Queen's Club
tourney. I beat him, 12-10, 6-0, and kept the trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood, a child prodigy with racket, first played Wimbledon as a
15-year-old (a male record for precocity). ``I wore white knickers
because they said I was too young for long pants. That was 1927. I
drew Rene Lacoste, the champ of 1925, in the first round. We were
on Centre Court, and I got four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Shields and I didn't feel too bad about that
non-final because we were so young. I was 19, he was 21, and at
that age you feel you'll have plenty more chances at the title.''
</P>
<P>
   They never came close. But Wood was on Centre Court again, where
he didn't win the title but got credit for it, anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
