<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-JUSTICETRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE TRADE OUT OF LEFT FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who says no one can keep a secret anymore?
</P>
<P>
   With virtually the entire baseball universe (outside of
Rockerville) focused on the Yankees' pending deal for Sammy Sosa,
the Cleveland Indians slipped in unnoticed and cut their own deal
with the Bombers. Sammy stayed home, where that other Chicago icon,
Jerry Springer, would just love to put the whole dysfunctional Cubs
family squabble on the air. David Justice, who thought he was just
minding his own business and quietly having a fine season for the
Tribe, suddenly found himself decked out in pinstripes, as swift a
costume change as any his ex-wife, Halle Berry, ever had to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came together so quickly,'' Indians assistant general
manager Mark Shapiro said, ``and we were all working so hard the
last couple of days that hardly anyone left their offices, and only
a few people were in the loop _ it caught the world by surprise.
That made it kind of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who already had failed to coax Juan Gonzalez to
come to the Apple on their terms, were never enchanted with the
idea of giving up five prospects for Sosa. Were they serious about
their pursuit of Sosa? Absolutely. Did their better judgment
override George Steinbrenner's enthusiasm for the Cubs slugger? It
appears so, especially after the Boss summoned all his lieutenants
to Tampa for a summit meeting last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, in the end, did not want to make a commitment to a
player who too many in their organization felt was too
one-dimensional to command the kind of ransom the Cubs were asking.
Great hitter, great box office? Without a doubt. But the answer to
all their prayers, when their pitching staff remains in shambles?
Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the same conclusions, of course, the Red Sox
apparently reached.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Indians received a phone call from the Bombers,
asking if they'd consider dealing slugger Manny Ramirez, the free
agent-to-be. ``They asked if Manny Ramirez was a guy we would talk
about,'' said Shapiro. ``That kind of led to where we ended up. We
just happened to match up very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, by trading Justice, lose a $7 million salary that
gives them extra cash to throw at Ramirez after the season. The
Yankees get a battle-tested veteran with a championship pedigree in
Justice, who won't flinch at the New York spotlight and will slide
gracefully into left field.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee gives the Indians another corner outfielder to add to an
already sizable collection that includes Richie Sexson, Alex
Ramirez, Russell Branyan, and Jacob Cruz. One or more of that group
can now be turned around and used by the Indians to go out and get
a pitcher by the trading deadline _ assuming they haven't been too
crippled already to make a run this season _ or reload for next
season.
</P>
<P>
   They'll also receive two minor league prospects to be named,
their talent level no doubt to be determined in part by how great a
contribution Justice makes to the Bombers.
</P>
<P>
   It has all the earmarks of a win-win deal. And Shapiro insists
that no one should regard the trade of Justice as a signal from
Cleveland that the Indians feel they're already out of contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal gives us a lot of flexibility, but in no way should
there be a perception that we're ready to blow this thing up and
running up the white flag,'' he said. ``There's no way we'll do
that. We're looking at whether we have to retool either this year
or next year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So-so interest
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, who now find themselves in the untenable position of
having a high-priced superstar they no longer want and who no
longer wants to be with them, were hoping for a phone call from Dan
Duquette. But the Sox have not jumped back into the Sosa
sweepstakes, and there was little indication that they would.
Arizona, which had expressed passing interest earlier, called
Friday, and the Cubs had the obligatory scout in place at Bank One
Ballpark that night. But while owner Jerry Colangelo has the
reputation of having deep pockets that rival only Steinbrenner's,
the D-backs are already top-heavy in investments in high-priced
veterans, and may only be trying to gauge how desperate the Cubs
are to rid themselves of Sosa. ``Nobody has a feel yet about how
strong their interest is,'' said one National League executive of
Arizona, ``but I think they're in it.'' With the emergence of
Korean Byung-Hyun Kim as closer, the D-backs may be disposed to
move arbitration-eligible Matt Mantei and perhaps Travis Lee, who
is playing out of position in right field . . . The atmosphere in
Chicago has been so poisoned, incidentally, that one of the game's
most charismatic players is now referred to as ``Sam-me-me-me'' by
one local columnist. ``This might be the time to find out if the
Cubs would take less to get a deal done,'' said one American League
executive. ``But I don't think Dan is trying at this moment.'' Any
deal with the Sox would still almost certainly include Trot Nixon.
``I think Sosa is on the Red Sox' wish list,'' said one party close
to the Sosa dealings, ``but I think there are some extenuating
circumstances that probably would not make Sammy a very good fit in
Boston.'' Hmmm. Is that a hint that the Sox' clubhouse wouldn't be
big enough for Sosa and the brothers Martinez? . . . The Sox are
still looking for hitting help. They've asked about Pittsburgh's
Kevin Young, the 31-year-old first baseman/outfielder who has
driven in 100 or more runs in each of the last two seasons and hit
26 and 27 home runs, respectively, and is on a similar pace this
season (11 home runs and 54 RBIs through 75 games). The Reds, who
could do no better than a split against NL Central-leading St.
Louis last week, are approaching the point where they'll be looking
to next year. They're rapidly approaching the position where they
may be willing to unload everyone on their roster outside of Junior
Griffey, Pokey Reese, Sean Casey, and closer Danny Graves. The Sox
have long had interest in switch-hitting outfielder Dmitri Young,
outfielder Michael Tucker also is available, and GM Jim Bowden can
expect loads of calls if he decides to move pitchers Denny Neagle
and Pete Harnisch. One of the huge questions facing the Reds is
whether icon Barry Larkin returns after this season. Larkin wants
Craig Biggio money to come back; the Reds are already beginning to
prepare for the possibility he may not return and are scouting
second basemen, with the idea that Reese would go to short . . .
Whatever dwindling interest the Red Sox had in Orioles righthander
Scott Erickson all but expired when the Sox bombed him Thursday
night in Fenway Park . . . Count Nixon among Ricky Ledee's
boosters. ``I played against him here and in the minors,'' Nixon
said, ``and he's a real good player. The Yankees' front office
didn't have much faith in him, but give him some security and I
guarantee he'll hit .300 with at least 20 home runs.'' . . .
Pawtucket pitcher Tomo Ohka was one of only two players in the Sox
system to be named to Baseball America's minor league all-star
teams. The other was Single A Augusta outfielder Lew Ford. Former
Northeastern star Carlos Pena was named to the Double A team. He's
playing first base for Tulsa in Texas's system and came into the
weekend batting .306 with 17 home runs and almost an RBI-a-game
pace (70 RBIs in 79 games) . . . One scout on the Brian
Daubach-Curtis Pride-Jeff Frye outfield the Sox used last week:
``Not exactly Ellis Valentine, Warren Cromartie, and Andre Dawson,
was it?'' . . . Next time you're in Asheville, N.C., to see the
Single A Asheville Tourists, the Colorado Rockies' affiliate, be
sure to check out the steaks at Il Paradiso. Tell owner Victor
Giancola that Gary Hughes sent you. Hughes is the longtime scout,
now working for the Reds, who recently signed Brett Gray, the
Frontier League phenom (that's the league that gave us Morgan
Burkhart), who last month struck out 25 batters in a game. Hughes
signed him the next morning. ``Jim Bowden called and said, `What do
you know about this guy?' '' Hughes said. ``I told him, `Nothing,
except he struck out 25 guys last night.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Radke off the market?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently there won't be an auction for Brad Radke after all.
Reports out of Minnesota are that new Twins CEO Chris Clouser may
strike a deal on a contract extension for the righthander that will
pay him $36 million over four years. Radke and his agent, Ron
Simon, apparently have made some concessions on their insistence
that Radke have the right to demand a trade after the 2001 season.
Initial indications are that he'll still be able to demand a trade,
but only under certain conditions . . . The Blue Jays were among
the teams that believed they were in a strong position to deal for
Radke. Toronto, by the way, already quietly is making plans to take
a run at free agent Chipper Jones after the season . . . How bad
has the atmosphere gotten around the Cubs during L'Affaire Sosa?
``With this circus going on, it's tough for me to think about
anything else,'' said veteran Mark Grace. ``I wish he would find
out whether he was staying or going. It's killing him and killing
the rest of us.'' . . . Justice's trade to the Yankees is historic
for a dubious reason. His $7 million salary puts the Yankees'
payroll at more than $100 million, making the Bombers the first
team to crack that barrier. Another year, and the Yankee payroll
could zoom over $120 million. Derek Jeter ($10 million) and Mariano
Rivera ($7.25 million) are up for new contracts, and you know the
Yankees will make at least one major free agent signing this winter
. . . The Yankees reportedly have Phillies pitcher Curt Schilling
on the top of their wish list for a deal before the trading
deadline. Schilling gave GM Ed Wade a list of teams to which he'd
accept a trade: the Yankees, Mets, Braves, Indians, Cardinals, and
Diamondbacks. Schilling is signed through next season, and at least
two baseball executives say Schilling just wants some attention . .
. Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. said he plans to begin talks with
agent Barry Axelrod after the All-Star break on a new contract for
Jeff Bagwell. McLane insists the club has no intention of trading
the native New Englander, who is eligible to become a free agent
after the 2001 season. ``Anyone who says we're trying to get rid of
Bagwell and (Craig) Biggio, that's absolutely untrue,'' McLane told
the Houston Chronicle last week. ``They are the cornerstones of our
franchise. The White Sox'' _ who have the best record in the majors
_ ``got rid of a lot of players, but they kept Frank Thomas because
he's their cornerstone. I'd take Jeff over Frank Thomas any day.
We're going to start talking about (Bagwell's contract), and we're
going to do everything we can to sign him. I still see Craig and
Jeff finishing their careers in Houston. We're totally committed to
those guys.'' That would kill any fantasies Red Sox fans have of
Bagwell coming home to finish his career. Bagwell has said he'd
like to remain in Houston, but only if the club has a chance to
contend . . . Want a reason why the Mariners were at the top of the
AL West beginning play Saturday? Manager Lou Piniella said he
hasn't had a bullpen like this since the days of the Nasty Boys
(Rob Dibble, Randy Myers, Norm Charlton) in Cincinnati. Kazuhiro
Sasaki had converted his last five save opportunities, Jose
Paniagua had allowed just one run in 17 games, lefthander Arthur
Rhodes had 12 straight scoreless appearances, and the much-maligned
Jose Mesa had an ERA of 1.78 for the month. New pitching coach
Bryan Price is winning kudos from the staff . . . With 128 hits
through 79 games, Angels outfielder Darin Erstad is on a pace for
262, which would break George Sisler's major league record of 257,
set in 1920. No player has had more than 240 hits in a season since
1930 . . . The Cubs, who already were forced to wait until 5 a.m.
for their charter flight from Pittsburgh to Milwaukee Thursday
night, had their night turn even longer when the team bus crashed
into a commuter plane near the runway. ``It shattered our
windshield and glass was flying everywhere,'' said infielder Jeff
Huson. ``Our driver didn't even hit the brakes. Glenallen (Hill)
was screaming. It was hilarious.'' . . . Phillies pitcher Andy
Ashby, subject of numerous trade rumors, didn't make any friends in
Philly after his last start, when he gave up six runs in six
innings, raising his ERA to 6.36. On his way to the dugout, Ashby
reportedly responded to the boos directed his way with a few
profanities. The headline in the Philadelphia Daily News the next
morning: ``Ashby makes an Ash of himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
