<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WATERPOLO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WINS, ADVANCES TO FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMITOS, Calif. _ Chris Oeding, who is the incoming men's
and women's water polo and swimming coach at Long Beach (Calif.)
City College, won't be able to be with his teams when school
begins.
</P>
<P>
   His excuse, though, is valid. When classes begin Aug. 14, Oeding
will be about a month away from concluding his chase for another
trip to the Olympic Games before he can ``hang up my suit and put
on my hat.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Oeding and his teammates continued their march
toward the Sydney Olympics in September by outlasting Italy 8-5 in
a physical game that concluded the team's round-robin play. The
victory propelled the Americans into the championship game in the
UPS International Cup at the U.S. National Aquatics Center.
</P>
<P>
   The physical play, most of which was generated by Italy, was
what the U.S. team (3-1-1) expected in a game that determined who
would play Yugoslavia (4-1-0) in today's 3 p.m. PDT championship
game of one of three pre-Olympic tune-ups for the Americans. The
U.S. had 13 man-advantage situations, converting on only four;
Italy's Alberto Angelini was kicked out of the game early in the
second period for a flagrant foul; Italian assistant coach
Ferdinando Pesci received a red card for arguing and two-meter man
Roberto Calcaterra didn't climb out of the pool afterward until he
was finished chirping at the American players.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens all the time with them, especially towards the
end of a tournament,'' said Wolf Wigo, who led the U.S. with three
goals. ``It was average. I didn't see anybody bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. was sluggish in the beginning, trailing 1-0 after one
period, but Wigo got things going with consecutive goals late in
the second period. Chi Kredell and Chris Humbert added
second-period goals to give the U.S. a 4-1 halftime lead and the
Italians never got any closer.
</P>
<P>
   Oeding's contribution to the victory didn't show up in a box
score that listed him with one shot attempt and no goals. The
28-year-old Cal graduate, who serves as the team captain, makes his
contributions as a playmaker, defender, tactical leader in the pool
and spiritual voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously you can see I'm not one of the biggest guys in the
pool,'' said the 6-foot-1, 185-pound driver, who played for U.S.
National team coach John Vargas at Corona del Mar (Calif.) High and
has scored two times in five UPS Cup games. ``(Vargas) taught me to
really learn and understand the game tactically. I let my
experience help me bring the guys together in the pool.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Oeding's role was just a little bit different as he
scored 11 goals as a member of the U.S. team at the Atlanta
Olympics. Only Humbert, who scored 14 times, had more goals for the
U.S.
</P>
<P>
   His trip to the Olympics came three years after his career
nearly ended. Oeding was fresh off finishing a sterling four-year
career at Cal, during which he was a three-time All-American and
three-time member of a NCAA champion. A year later, however, he
suffered rotator cuff damage to his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a career-ending injury,'' Oeding said. ``You could
literally put a pinkie (finger) on my hand and I couldn't push it.
It was a huge struggle for me both mentally and physically.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he wasn't ready to quit. After surgery and nearly a
year of rehab, he was back in the pool working his way to Atlanta.
The Olympic dream didn't end there, though, as a disappointing
seventh-place finish wasn't satisfying enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here because I want a medal,'' Oeding said. ``Sure there's
a risk involved by putting your life on hold for four, eight or
even 12 years before you can rejoin real life. It's also exciting
as hell.''
</P>
<P>
   It also takes a lot of understanding. Oeding credits support
from his wife, Eden, whom he married in 1999, and his family for
understanding the 7:30 a.m. workouts and world travel for
competitions.
</P>
<P>
   And he looks forward to jumping in full time at Long Beach as a
physical education instructor and aquatics coach after spending
last year as a part-time instructor and men's water polo coach at
Orange Coast College.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water polo has opened a lot of doors for me,'' Oeding said.
``I was able to attend Berkeley which I would never have been able
to do and have traveled around the world. It's been a fantastic
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   An Olympic medal would be a nice finish to the experience.
</P>
<P>
   In other games:
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA 6, YUGOSLAVIA 4: The game meant little for the
Yugoslavians (4-1-0) in the standings but, for obvious reasons, it
was still an emotional contest. However, it was Croatia (3-2-0)
scoring the game's first four goals and holding on for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA 10, TEAM UPS 6: Omar Amr had two goals and Chris
Aguilera 12 saves for Team UPS (0-5-0) but Australia (2-2-1) swam
away with the win. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
