<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE'S RETURN REMAINS UNCERTAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The pitching rotation, for better or worse, is
down to five pitchers for five spots. The middle of the order is
never-changing, and in another few weeks even talk of suspensions
should be gone.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. What else could there be?
</P>
<P>
   With time seemingly sorting everything out, Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson began talking about the return of leadoff hitter and
center fielder Devon White. Last week, White disclosed
season-ending surgery wasn't needed on his left shoulder, which
leaves Johnson looking forward to a return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping he can have the kind of effect on us as he did in
Florida,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The parallel for which Johnson is striving is in reference to
1997, when White returned from a calf-muscle pull in late July and
the Marlins went on to win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are hoping White returns before August, but he's
still not hitting live pitching, and he still has pain in his left
shoulder. Not only could he give the stagnant top of the lineup
life, but he remains the best center fielder on the roster, team
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With White in the lineup, that gives me more options,''
Johnson said. ``I have a problem resting guys like (Gary) Sheffield
and (Shawn) Green. With injuries and stuff, (Geronimo) Berroa and
White out, that's a lot of depth missing.''
</P>
<P>
   However, before the Dodgers get too gung-ho about White's
return, he's yet to face live pitching. White continues to hit off
a batting tee, and while he's progressing nicely from the left
side, he said he can only hit a few days a week right-handed
because of pain and discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   White suffered a partially torn left rotator cuff diving for a
ball May 2 against Atlanta and has been on the disabled list since.
In his place, Todd Hollandsworth and F.P. Santangelo have played in
a platoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my main focus is trying to get my shoulder strong and
ready, so when I do get back in there, it's not 80 percent or 90
percent,'' White said. ``There's no way I'm going to be 100
percent, but I'll be close. It's going to be like spring training
again for me. The main thing is me being back to help the team
close those four games (in which they trail Arizona).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm itching to come back, but they tell me I just can't come
back because I feel good. I have to come back and say I can play
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   AILING ADAMS: With right-hander Jeff Shaw already on the
disabled list, the last thing the Dodgers need is an injury to
another reliever. But right-handed set-up man Terry Adams continues
to experience stiffness in the back of his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   While Adams maintains it's not enough to land him on the
disabled list, the pain was sufficient enough to merit a cortisone
shot Friday in hopes of relieving the irritation. Johnson said he'd
like to give Adams a rest until Tuesday in San Diego, but Adams
could pitch today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time there's tightness in the shoulder, it's dangerous,''
Johnson said. ``It's tight for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Even though right-hander Gregg Olson reported no
problems in his Friday rehab stint, he'll be making a few more
before getting consideration for a return to the roster. ``I think
he needs to prove he can get up to two innings, no problem,''
Johnson said. ``I think we have to be that safe, that cautious.''
Olson is hoping to return after the All-Star break. ... Gene Orza,
general counsel for the players association, said decisions have
yet to be made on whether to appeal the suspensions of Sheffield,
Carlos Perez and Santangelo. The players association wants to
appeal Sheffield's five-game suspension, but the union and the
Dodgers hope to talk Perez out of his appeal. Santangelo said he'll
fight his ``all the way to the Supreme Court.'' ... Shortstop Kevin
Elster left in the seventh inning with a sore left hamstring, but
he said he plans on starting the series finale today. ... Johnson
said he'll probably sit struggling Green, which, with Monday's off
day, would give him a pair of days off. Green has started all 79
games, but the last time Johnson thought of sitting him, Green
talked him out of it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
