<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-USWOMEN-CANADA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WOMEN TOP CANADA AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ It doesn't matter where they play _ in Taipei,
in Port-au-Prince, in Sydney, in Winnipeg, in Worcester. When the
US women's soccer team meets Canada, it's a guaranteed KO.
</P>
<P>
   So it was again Saturday night in Muhammad Ali's hometown, as
the world champions got two first-half goals from Shannon MacMillan
and took out their northern neighbors, 4-1, at Papa John's Cardinal
Stadium for the 21st straight time.
</P>
<P>
   The victory earned the US a rematch in Tuesday night's Gold Cup
final in Foxborough with Brazil, which upset China, 3-2, in
overtime in Saturday's other semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans hadn't lost to Canada since 1986, back when their
makeshift national team played a year's worth of matches in three
July weeks. So they were hardly complaining when the toss of the
coin that decided their group allowed them to duck the Chinese
here.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians had been blown out twice by the US this spring,
losing, 4-0, in the US Cup and 9-1 in the Pacific Cup. ```We wanted
to prove that the 9-1 score wasn't indicative,'' said Canada keeper
Nicole Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Still, nobody was disputing that the Americans were by far the
better side. ``We are not at that quality,'' conceded coach Even
Pellerud, who'd coached Norway to the 1995 world title and was
brought in this year to resuscitate the Canadian program after the
team failed to qualify for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The US wasted no time affirming the point, storming the Canadian
end from the opening whistle and getting three corner kicks in the
first three minutes. Then, a dozen minutes in, midfielder Nikki
Serlenga lofted a long crossfield ball for MacMillan, who dribbled
across the box and blasted a goal into the upper corner.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans nearly had another in the 25th minute, when Mia
Hamm dribbled through the Canadian defense and found Tiffeny
Milbrett open at the penalty spot. But keeper Karina LeBlanc (who
alternates with Wright) gathered in Milbrett's bid.
</P>
<P>
   LeBlanc did the same to Kristine Lilly in the 35th minute, after
Serlenga had launched another cruise missile to MacMillan, who
served Lilly for a point-blank shot straight on.
</P>
<P>
   Next time, though, MacMillan took no chances. Three minutes
later, with three red-shirted defenders around her, she cocked and
fired from 25 yards and caught LeBlanc flatfooted. Then Milbrett,
denied earlier, took a deft through ball from Julie Foudy, sprinted
into the area and fired a 12-yarder past LeBlanc.
</P>
<P>
   So it was 3-0 at halftime, but US coach April Heinrichs wasn't
concerned about the score. What she'd wanted was for her side to
play with creative dominance, no matter who was in the lineup. No
issue there Saturday night. The only question was whether the
Americans, who hadn't allowed a goal in the tournament, would hang
up another clean sheet.
</P>
<P>
   That chance ended in the 58th minute, when defender Kate Sobrero
pushed Charmaine Hooper in the penalty area. Hooper, Canada's
all-time scorer, drilled her kick low and left past keeper Siri
Mullinix and the US scoreless skein was snapped at 486 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anything else changed. The US got the goal back within
seven minutes as Foudy set up Hamm for a top-of-the-box boomer.
Then it was time for curtain calls, as Foudy came out for Lorrie
Fair and Hamm came out for Susan Bush.
</P>
<P>
   So the US and Brazil, who tied, 0-0, Tuesday at Foxboro Stadium
when keeper Andreia blocked Lilly's last-minute penalty kick, get a
chance to pick up where they left off. And this time, there'll be
no coin flip.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Cidinha knocked in a penalty kick in the final minute
of the first overtime to push Brazil past the favored Chinese. The
Brazilians, who lost to China in the Olympic semifinals, had come
from behind to take the lead on Roseli's goal in the 60th minute.
And after the Chinese equalized on Qiu Haiyan's chip shot in the
75th, Brazil had a chance to win on Sissi's free kick in injury
time, which keeper Gao Hong stopped. ``We won the game on Brazilian
hustle,'' declared coach Jose Duarte.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese, playing without star forward Sun Wen, had struggled
earlier in the tournament, beating Canada only 3-2 and needing two
goals in the final five minutes to put away Mexico, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   They struck quickly though, as Shui Qingxia hooked in a free
kick from 20 yards in the 9th minute. But Brazil drew even two
minutes later when Katia da Silva, who scored six goals here
against Trinidad &AMP; Tobago, headed in Cidinha's free kick.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides squandered golden chances to take the lead. China's
Pu Wei, alone 10 yards from the goal, shot directly at Andreia in
the 22d minute. And in the 23d, Roseli hit the post on a breakaway
with keeper Gao Hong out.
</P>
<P>
   Roseli came storming back, though, to slam in a rebound after
Gao had blocked her breakaway. And she had another chance to win it
four minutes into overtime but Gao blocked her point-blank shot.
``Whoever has more luck wins the game,'' shrugged Chinese coach Ma
Yuanan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
