<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING THROUGH LAKERS WITHDRAWLS? TRY THESE ALTERNATIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ An avid reader (OK, my cousin) calls to complain
that the sports year seems to have ended when the Lakers'
championship parade chugged to a halt. He and a guy at the office
had chatted about the Lakers every morning of the regular season
and playoffs, with ``Groundhog Day'' regularity, until 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we do now?'' the guy said this week.
</P>
<P>
   What indeed? What's a sports fan to do around here all summer
before the Lakers begin their quest for a repeat?
</P>
<P>
   As you try to get on with life beyond the NBA Finals, it doesn't
help when you start to sink your teeth into Wimbledon, and you come
across this quote from Pete Sampras on the subject of playing
through a leg injury: ``I use Kobe Bryant in the NBA Finals as my
inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help when you go to a Dodgers game for the first time
in nearly a month, on the Tuesday that Orel Hershiser is released,
and there's Kobe throwing out the first ball.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't help when Kobe throws as if he could start for
the Dodgers right now.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime soon, we must give in to Lakers withdrawal. What do we
do then? Here are a few ideas:
</P>
<P>
   -- Ride your bicycle to San Diego as fast as you can. Next day,
ride your bicycle back from San Diego as fast as you can. Repeat
this, oh, 10 times. Then you'll know what the Tour de France
cyclists go through _ if they didn't have the Alps to contend with.
</P>
<P>
   Follow the Tour de France (on TV and on paper, not on a bike),
which turned into the world's greatest annual sports event as soon
as Americans became competitive. You want international flavor?
First-stage leader David Millar was born in Malta, lives in
Biarritz and considers Hong Kong home. But because he used to live
in Scotland, the Reuters news service dubbed him the ``Flying
Scot'' in a headline. Are we sure he didn't change planes in
Burbank once?
</P>
<P>
   -- Go to Dodger Stadium and cheer Kevin Brown ($15 million a
year) and Gary Sheffield ($10 million a year) for giving the
Dodgers their money's worth.
</P>
<P>
   -- Go to Edison Field, just so someday you can say you saw Darin
Erstad in that season when he couldn't miss.
</P>
<P>
   -- Tune out NBC during the Olympics to protest its decision to
cover the events on tape-delay. Otherwise, next time it'll be
worse: They'll show everything days or weeks later, and it'll be
like a car race on ESPN2, where you can't tell when it happened and
what it meant.
</P>
<P>
   -- Go to a movie. Recommended: ``The Life and Times of Hank
Greenberg,'' about the Detroit Tigers Hall of Famer who was a hero
to Jews in the 1930s and '40s. A timely revelation, though off the
topic of the documentary, is that when the Tigers clinched the 1934
pennant, people in Detroit celebrated by turning over streetcars.
</P>
<P>
   -- Read a book. Recommended: Bruce Jenkins' ``A Good Man: The
Pete Newell Story,'' about the great college basketball coach,
worthy rival of John Wooden, and one-time Lakers general manager.
</P>
<P>
   -- Be a conscientious All-Star voter. Study before punching your
ballot. Don't just vote for the local favorites. Don't
automatically vote for the hot first-half hitters either. Think
about who you'd really want at the plate in a big game.
</P>
<P>
   See if we can move the Toronto Blue Jays' Carlos Delgado, the
American League's most productive hitter of the past season and a
half, up from sixth in the voting at first base.
</P>
<P>
   -- Go to Del Mar for a weekend of racing in one of the prettiest
settings in sports. Bring $500. Bet $10. You'll need the rest for
dinner and a hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   -- Go to the local tennis tournaments (men at UCLA in July,
women in Manhattan Beach in August). Ask other spectators why they
show up for these things in tennis outfits. Perhaps they anticipate
an announcement from the chair ``Miss Sanchez Vicario has withdrawn
due to injury. Would Mrs. Herman Cavandish be kind enough to
replace her in tonight's featured match?''
</P>
<P>
   -- Read an encyclopedia so you'll be prepared for Dennis
Miller's allusions on ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Go to a minor-league game. Triple-A is the most entertaining
level, because you see familiar faces on the way down as well as
prospects on the way up. But the L.A. area's five Single-A teams
have attractive little ballparks where you might get as close to
the action as, well, Jack Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   -- Go to a Long Beach Summer League basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   -- Submit your application for the Clippers head-coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   -- Reserve your seats for the Lakers opener. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-00 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000701.0203 </DOCNO>
