<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-N     07-01 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT TAMPA BAY, 6-1 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Jorge Posada and Orlando Hernandez were
dressed in street clothes and waiting at the clubhouse door when
their teammates came through, in single file, after their emotional
victory Saturday. Roger Clemens saw Posada and playfully
shadowboxed, an allusion to the catcher's short but nasty brawl in
the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Way to go, Duque,'' other Yankees shouted to Hernandez, who
threw five and two-thirds innings after not knowing if his elbow
trouble would prevent him from pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees want to build on this 6-1 victory over Tampa Bay.
Hernandez hopes to wake up Sunday and feel no pain in his elbow,
and come back and pitch well again in five days. Perhaps Tino
Martinez, who had a three-run double to finish off the Devil Rays,
will put together more runs batted in in the days to come. Maybe
the passion that Posada's fight generated will fuel a rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are a team needing a spark and maybe this was it.
``We needed this,'' Posada said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager said, ``It was a lift for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner seethed over Friday's 6-4 loss to Tampa Bay
when he had lunch Saturday with Torre and General Manager Brian
Cashman. Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, asked
questions, demanded answers and said afterward that he was
accepting the assurances of Torre and Cashman that the team was
good enough to win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Translated: Those guys tell me we're good enough, and they had
better be right.
</P>
<P>
   They all agree that there is a need for pitching, the need for
Hernandez and Clemens to come back this weekend _ Clemens pitches
Sunday after coming off the disabled list _ and revitalize the
rotation that has been so inconsistent that it has placed a strain
on the bullpen. There were 13 instances in the Yankees' last 43
games that the starting pitcher did not finish the fifth inning.
Torre dug deep into his bullpen again Friday, and Saturday he held
back David Cone from his usual bullpen session, just in case
Hernandez's elbow trouble surfaced again.
</P>
<P>
   El Duque felt good warming up _ ``He felt strong,'' Posada said
_ and contentiousness yanked Hernandez back into the world of
pitching in the big leagues. After Tampa Bay's Russ Johnson stroked
a leadoff double in the third, Hernandez became annoyed when Randy
Winn called time out as Hernandez began to throw the ball.
Hernandez flipped the ball high into the air and shot a glance at
Winn, then fired a fastball inside, forcing him to jump out of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys started yelling at him'' from the Tampa Bay
dugout, Posada said. Hernandez looked over his left shoulder at the
Devil Rays' dugout and continued to stare, until Posada ran out and
nudged Hernandez in the lower back with his glove, turning him away
from the bench jockeys and back to the business at hand.
</P>
<P>
   The at-bat developed into a war of wills. Hernandez looked in
for the sign, then stepped away from the rubber. Winn called time
out. Hernandez shook off four signs and then stepped off the mound.
El Duque was determined to control the pace of the at-bat,
responding to every move Winn made, like a debater wanting to get
in the last word. Winn tried to check his swing on a 2-1 pitch, but
Umpire C.B. Bucknor called a strike, then ejected the third-base
coach, Billy Hatcher, igniting a long argument. Winn's at-bat took
about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When Winn was ready to hit, Hernandez shook off four signs
again, stepped away from the rubber, then threw a fastball and
prompted Winn to fly out to center field. In this way, Hernandez
and the Yankees gripped a 2-1 lead through six innings. Hernandez
(7-6) allowed one run on four hits over five and two-thirds
innings.
</P>
<P>
   With runners at second and third and one out in the Yankees
seventh, Tampa Bay Manager Larry Rothschild ordered an intentional
walk of Posada to get to Martinez, and the left-hander Mark Guthrie
moved ahead in the count, 1-2.
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie spun a low breaking ball over the plate and Martinez
pulled a soft liner into the right-field corner. All three runners
scored, padding the Yankees' lead to 5-1. After reaching second on
his double, Martinez hustled to third when a throw got away, and
Willie Randolph, the Yankees' third-base coach, patted Martinez on
the helmet. It was the second time this season that Martinez had
three RBI in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's Bobby Smith struck out to lead off the bottom of the
seventh, and when Posada stepped in front of home plate to whip the
ball to third, Smith pushed Posada discreetly with the barrel of
his bat. Posada turned and jabbed the ball into Smith's side, and
Smith and Posada immediately came together, wrestling each other to
the ground. Posada was quickly on his back, with Smith flailing
away with both hands.
</P>
<P>
   The benches cleared, and Posada and Smith were pulled apart.
Posada kept pushing his tongue into his cheek, as if to feel for a
cut. Both players were ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to throw the ball to third, and he just
shoved me with his forearm,'' said Posada, who said he was not
hurt. ``I didn't like that. I guess he can't strike out. So I
pushed him back.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said: ``I struck out and was walking away and I bumped
him. I don't know if he thought it was on purpose or whatever, and
he shoved me. Somebody pushes you _ are you just going to walk away
from it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any problem with anybody. I'm a nice guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Both face the possibility of suspension from Major League
Baseball's primary enforcement official, Frank Robinson. ``I have a
great deal of respect for Frank Robinson,'' Torre said. ``I would
certainly like him to remember how many fights he was in and not be
suspended.''
</P>
<P>
   But Torre seemed happy, pleased with the game; it was a good day
all the way around.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, the Yankees' second baseman, was scratched from
the starting lineup because of an ear infection. He might miss
Sunday's game as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
