<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1009 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-ABALONE-ENDANGERED-1s     07-01 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABALONE-ENDANGERED-1stLd-Writethru-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    WHITE ABALONE ON BRINK OF EXTINCTION
</HEADLINE>
 
(Removing unnecessary word in 16th paragraph) (With BC-ABALONE-RESCUE-LADN, both for use by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By CECILIA CHAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   VENTURA, Calif. _ In its heyday, white abalone dotted the ocean
floor in the prime fishing grounds off the Ventura County coast and
numbered in the millions from Point Conception to Baja.
</P>
<P>
   The sea snail was common fare on California's menus, offered
deep fried or in sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   But with fewer than 2,540 remaining, white abalone is nearly
extinct. The public has until Wednesday to comment on a National
Marine Fisheries Service plan to list the mollusk as an endangered
species, the first time a marine invertebrate would receive the
classification.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is listed, it's sort of a milestone in our thinking
about the ocean,'' said Ian Taniguchi, a marine biologist with the
California Department of Fish and Game. ``For the longest time,
probably throughout recorded history, there has been a sort of
mentality that things that come from the ocean are infinite, are
non-exhaustible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception we could ever fish an invertebrate species to
extinction is sort of being realized now with the white abalone.''
</P>
<P>
   The NMFS had already designated the white abalone as a candidate
for the endangered list in 1997. Last year, several environmental
groups - including the Channels Island Marine Resource Institute in
Port Hueneme - petitioned the agency to include it it under the
Endangered Species Act. And state Fish and Game currently is
working on listing the species under California's Endangered
Species Act, Taniguchi said.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental groups hope to bring more attention - and,
potentially, money for restoration and recovery - by classifying
the abalone as endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties also would be greater for those who illegally harvest
the species, with violators facing a $100,000 fine and a year in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   The white variety is among eight species of abalone that live
along the West Coast. It is the deepest dwelling, found on
low-relief rocks covered with algae at 80 to 200 feet, where the
water temperature is cooler.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, divers harvested thousands of pounds of the
melon-sized invertebrate - its shell lined with mother of pearl -
for the local and Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have always been a delicacy from Native Americans
onward,'' said Tom McCormick, director of the Channel Islands
Marine Resource Institute. ``They've always been perceived as
something exotic, very delicious and very California.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early 1950s after the war, when scuba diving becoming
available and expanding to new areas, you would hear reports of
hundreds of thousand of abalone from dives,'' he said. ``There are
pictures showing mountains of abalone as tall as two-story
buildings at processing plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people in the 1940s and 1950s, the $1.50 abalone sandwich
was very common. That memory is gone for younger people unless they
are out sport diving in Northern California to get the red
abalone.''
</P>
<P>
   The white abalone, favored for its tender meat, commanded a
higher price at market, up to 20 percent more than the red abalone,
which was the main staple of the fishing industry, Taniguchi said.
</P>
<P>
   From 1969 to 1977, more than 95 percent of the commercial white
abalone harvest took place, with a peak catch of 144,000 pounds in
1972, according to the National Marine Fisheries Service. A common
spot for catches was off the Ventura County coast - east of Santa
Cruz Island to Anacapa Island.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 30 years the white abalone population went from an
estimated high of 2.22 million to 4.24 million to 1,613 to 2,540 -
a 99 percent decline, the NMFS reported.
</P>
<P>
   That drop prompted state Fish and Game officials to close
fishing for white, pink and green abalone in 1996. A year later,
they imposed a moratorium on commercial and sport catches on all
abalone species found south of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Although harvesting was banned, the white abalone has not
rebounded, marine biologists say.
</P>
<P>
   Overfishing has reduced the density of the population, making
reproduction practically nil for the slow-growing gastropods, which
have a life span of 30 to 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Both male and female abalone are broadcast spawners, meaning
they release their eggs and sperm into the water to make contact by
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to be within a few yards of each other to have
successful fertilization,'' McCormick said. ``If they are spaced in
order of 1 to 1 miles apart, in most cases these animals won't
successfully reproduce because they are so far apart. So they will
die of old age.''
</P>
<P>
   Abalone move slowly on a single foot along the ocean bottom, and
adults have extremely limited movements. With its single, flattened
spiral shell, the species averages five to eight inches long.
</P>
<P>
   Research in the 1970s showed a potential of one white abalone
per square meter in its natural habitat - today it's maybe five
abalone per hectare or 10,000 square meters, Taniguchi said.
</P>
<P>
   Locations such as San Clemente, Catalina Island and Anacapa
Island, where the greatest number of white abalone was removed in
the 1970s, were surveyed last fall with disappointing results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found 157 in 10 days of looking,'' said Dan Richards, a
marine biologist at Channel Islands National Park. ``That is not
very good. Seventy hours of prime time searching over really good
habitat - and that was all we could find.''
</P>
<P>
   Although human consumption is largely to blame for the white
abalone's demise, some experts said a bacterial infection also
could have played a role.
</P>
<P>
   Withering syndrome, which shrivels the abalone in its shell, has
decimated 99 percent of the black abalone, McCormick said.
</P>
<P>
   First detected in the late 1980s in Southern California waters,
the syndrome is moving north and has reached Point Conception, in
Santa Barbara County, he said. The syndrome, which affects the
abalone's digestive glands, also has been found in pink, red, green
and white abalone.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
