<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-01 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1019 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     07-01 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 9)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BLIND EYE: The Terrifying Story of a Doctor Who Got Away With
Murder &LR;  By James B. Stewart. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14. A
journalist tells the story of a doctor suspected of killing at
least 35 hospital patients, and indicts the medical authorities who
failed to protect the public. Last year in The New York Times Book
Review, Lance Morrow called this a ``chillingly thorough and
superbly matter-of-fact ... reconstruction that has the fascination
of an acutely observed and troubling novel.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELEMENTALS: Stories of Fire and Ice &LR;  By A.S. Byatt. Vintage
International, $12. A British writer whose work explores the
intersection of aesthetics and morality spins tales in which
stolid, blinkered Europeans from the North become either imprisoned
or re-energized by the earthier South and the warmer-blooded people
(mostly artists) who live there. In Byatt's eyes, it is an
unforgivable crime not to be curious about a world ``full of light
and life.'' ``Byatt's prose is capacious yet exquisite,'' Fernanda
Eberstadt wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1999, and this
collection is infused with ``the throwaway gleams of a writer at
the height of her powers.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DISTANCE TO THE MOON: A Road Trip Into the American Dream &LR; 
By James Morgan. Riverhead, $12.95. The author explores America's
obsessive love affair with cars and car culture as he drives from
Miami to Portland, Ore., in a shiny new Porsche. ``The human case
for the automobile has never been more persuasively presented,''
Bruce McCall wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I'M A STRANGER HERE MYSELF: Notes on Returning to America After
Twenty Years Away &LR; , by Bill Bryson (Broadway, $14), is a collection
of humorous dispatches written for a British newspaper about the
author's bumpy re-entry into his native culture with his English
wife and four children. ``The best columns are those in which the
author discards his hapless persona and allows his natural
impatience and intelligence out of their cages,'' Elizabeth Gleick
wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRUE AT FIRST LIGHT &LR;  By Ernest Hemingway. Edited by Patrick
Hemingway. Scribner, $13. This fictional chronicle of an African
safari, which was abandoned by Hemingway and edited by one of his
sons, is a pale imitation of the writer's best work, James Wood
wrote last year. Nonetheless, ``there is a kind of mottled glamour,
made up of bullying integrity and nonsense, of truth and falsity,
which always makes the least of Hemingway's books compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1185 PARK AVENUE: A Memoir &LR;  By Anne Roiphe. Touchstone/Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $13. Avoiding sentimentality and self-pity in favor of an
emotionally mature distance, the author tells of growing up Jewish
in the 1940s and '50s with everything she could want except her
parents' affection. ``Roiphe gives her memoir the dramatic
vividness of a novel,'' Karen Lehrman wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; APPLES FROM THE DESERT: Selected Stories &LR;  By Savyon Liebrecht.
Feminist Press, $13.95. This collection of 12 stories originally
published in Israel focuses on the fault lines between secular and
Orthodox Jews, bereft parents and their torn children. ``At her
best, Liebrecht is the equal of far better-known Israeli authors
like Amos Oz,'' Suzanne Ruta wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOTHER OF PEARL &LR;  By Melinda Haynes. Washington Square/Pocket
Books, $13.95. This first novel revolves around a large cast of
characters in sleepy Petal, Miss., in the 1950s, including Even
Grade, a black orphan named for a road, and Valuable Korner, a
fatherless white girl named after a real estate sign. Last year the
reviewer Roy Hoffman admired the book's ``profuse and vigorous''
language.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GEORGE III: A Personal History &LR;  By Christopher Hibbert. Basic
Books, $18. As portrayed here, George III (1738-1820) was a
churchgoing, monogamous, mostly competent ruler before going
famously mad. His oldest son, however, George IV (1762-1830), the
subject of  &UR; PRINCE OF PLEASURE: The Prince of Wales and the Making
of the Regency &LR; , by Saul David (Grove, $15), led the field in
scandalous behavior at a time when London was the world's capital
for debauchery. ```George III' and `Prince of Pleasure' make a
simply unputdownable theater of the personal and political
absurd,'' Valentine Cunningham wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HOUDINI GIRL &LR;  By Martyn Bedford. Vintage Crime, $13. After
his Irish girlfriend dies in a mysterious train accident, a British
magician discovers that she led a double life and sets out to
unravel her carefully hidden past. Last year the reviewer Carey
Harrison called this ``a masterfully choreographed'' erotic
thriller.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POACHERS: Stories &LR;  By Tom Franklin. HarperPerennial, $12. Set
in lower Alabama, these mordant tales feature sympathetic good old
boys stuck in bad situations, frayed marriages and dead-end jobs.
``With this satisfying collection'' Franklin ``establishes himself
as one of the region's more interesting emerging voices,'' Bruce
Barcott wrote last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
